\tab Sally was coming down the lake road, so I waved to her and called her by \expndtw-7 name. I always liked to see Sally. I liked all of them, you understand, but \expndtw-6 Sally\rquote s the prettiest one of the lot. There just isn\rquote t any question about it.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-8 She moved a little faster when I waved to her. Nothing undignified. She was never that. She moved just enough faster to show that she was glad to \expndtw-10 see me, too.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-6 I turned to the man standing beside me. \ldblquote That\rquote s Sally,\rdblquote  I said.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-8 He smiled at me and nodded.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-7 Mrs. Hester had brought him in. She said, \ldblquote This is Mr. Gellhorn, Jake. \expndtw-8 You remember he sent you the letter asking for an appointment.\rdblquote\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-8 That was just talk, really. I have a million things to do around the Farm, \expndtw-9 and one thing I just can\rquote t waste my time on is mail. That\rquote s why I have Mrs. Hester around. She lives pretty close by, she\rquote s good at attending to foolish\-ness without running to me about it, and most of all, she likes Sally and the rest. Some people don\rquote t.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-7\ldblquote Glad to see you, Mr. Gellhorn,\rdblquote  I said.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-6\ldblquote Raymond F. Gellhorn,\rdblquote  he said, and gave me his hand, which I shook \expndtw-12 and gave back.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-8 He was a largish fellow, half a head taller than I and wider, too. He was \expndtw-9 about half my age, thirtyish. He had black hair, plastered down slick, with a part in the middle, and a thin mustache, very neatly trimmed. His jawbones \expndtw-2 got big under his ears and made him look as if he had a slight case of\cf0\expndtw0  \cf2\expndtw-4 mumps. On video he\rquote d be a natural to play the villain, so I assumed he was a \expndtw0 nice fellow. It goes to show that video can\rquote t be wrong all the time.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote I\rquote m Jacob Folkers,\rdblquote  I said. \ldblquote What can I do for you?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 He grinned. It was a big, wide, white-toothed grin. \ldblquote You can tell me a little about your Farm here, if you don\rquote t mind.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-2 I heard Sally coming up behind me and I put out my hand. She slid right \expndtw-3 into it and the feel of the hard, glossy enamel of her fender was warm in my \expndtw-10 palm.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-1\ldblquote A nice automatobile,\rdblquote  said Gellhorn.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-3 That\rquote s one way of putting it. Sally was a 2045 convertible with a Hennis-\expndtw-4 Carleton positronic motor and an Armat chassis. She had the cleanest, finest \expndtw-1 lines I\rquote ve ever seen on any model, bar none. For five years, she\rquote d been my favorite, and I\rquote d put everything into her I could dream up. In all that time, \expndtw0 there\rquote d never been a human being behind her wheel.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-1 Not once.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Sally,\rdblquote  I said, patting her gently, \ldblquote meet Mr. Gellhorn.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-5 Sally\rquote s cylinder-purr keyed up a little. I listened carefully for any knocking. \expndtw-4 Lately, I\rquote d been hearing motor-knock in almost all the cars and changing the \expndtw-3 gasoline hadn\rquote t done a bit of good. Sally was as smooth as her paint job this \expndtw-5 time, however.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-2\ldblquote Do you have names for all your cars?\rdblquote  asked Gellhorn.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2 He sounded amused, and Mrs. Hester doesn\rquote t like people to sound as though they were making fun of the Farm. She said, sharply, \ldblquote Certainly. \expndtw-3 The cars have real personalities, don\rquote t they, Jake? The sedans are all males \expndtw-1 and the convertibles are females.\rdblquote\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-3 Gellhorn was smiling again. \ldblquote And do you keep them in separate garages, \expndtw-5 ma\rquote am?\rdblquote\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2 Mrs. Hester glared at him.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-1 Gellhorn said to me, \ldblquote And now I wonder if I can talk to you alone, Mr. \expndtw-9 Folkers?\rdblquote\cf0\expndtw0\par
