\tab\cf2\expndtw-1 We take it for granted now, but I remember when the first laws came out forcing the old machines off the highways and limiting travel to automatics. \expndtw0 Lord, what a fuss. They called it everything from communism to fascism, but it emptied the highways and stopped the killing, and still more people get around more easily the new way.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-1 Of course, the automatics were ten to a hundred times as expensive as the \expndtw0 hand-driven ones, and there weren\rquote t many that could afford a private vehi\-\expndtw-2 cle. The industry specialized in turning out omnibus-automatics. You could always call a company and have one stop at your door in a matter of minutes \expndtw-1 and take you where you wanted to go. Usually, you had to drive with others \expndtw0 who were going your way, but what\rquote s wrong with that?\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 Samson Harridge had a private car though, and I went to him the minute \expndtw-1 it arrived. The car wasn\rquote t Matthew to me then. I didn\rquote t know it was going to \expndtw-8 be the dean of the Farm some day. I only knew it was taking my job away \expndtw-4 and I hated it.\cf0\expndtw0\par
\tab\cf2\expndtw-8 I said, \ldblquote You won\rquote t be needing me any more, Mr. Harridge?\rdblquote\cf0\expndtw0\par
