\tab Niccolo Mazetti lay stomach down on the rug, chin buried in the palm of one small hand, and listened to the Bard disconsolately. There was even the suspicion of tears in his dark eyes, a luxury an eleven-year-old could allow himself only when alone.\par
\tab The Bard said, \ldblquote Once upon a time in the middle of a deep wood, there lived a poor woodcutter and his two motherless daughters, who were each as beautiful as the day is long. The older daughter had long hair as black as a feather from a raven\rquote s wing, but the younger daughter had hair as bright and golden as the sunlight of an autumn afternoon.\par
\tab\ldblquote Many times while the girls were waiting for their father to come home from his day\rquote s work in the wood, the older girl would sit before a mirror and sing--\rdblquote\par
\tab What she sang, Niccolo did not hear, for a call sounded from outside the room: \ldblquote Hey, Nickie.\rdblquote\par
\tab And Niccolo, his face clearing on the moment, rushed to the window and shouted, \ldblquote Hey, Paul.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul Loeb waved an excited hand. He was thinner than Niccolo and not as tall, for all he was six months older. His face was full of repressed tension which showed itself most clearly in the rapid blinking of his eyelids. \ldblquote Hey, Nickie, let me in. I\rquote ve got an idea and a half. Wait till you hear it.\rdblquote  He looked rapidly about him as though to check on the possibility of eavesdrop\-pers, but the front yard was quite patently empty. He repeated, in a whisper, \ldblquote Wait till you hear it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. I\rquote ll open the door.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Bard continued smoothly, oblivious to the sudden loss of attention on the part of Niccolo. As Paul entered, the Bard was saying. \ldblquote . . . There\-upon, the lion said, \lquote If you will find me the lost egg of the bird which flies over the Ebony Mountain once every ten years, I will--\rquote  \ldblquote\par
\tab Paul said, \ldblquote Is that a Bard you\rquote re listening to? I didn\rquote t know you had one.\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo reddened and the look of unhappiness returned to his face. \ldblquote Just an old thing I had when I was a kid. It ain\rquote t much good.\rdblquote  He kicked at the Bard with his foot and caught the somewhat scarred and discolored plastic covering a glancing blow.\par
\tab The Bard hiccupped as its speaking attachment was jarred out of contact a moment, then it went on: \ldblquote --for a year and a day until the iron shoes were worn out. The princess stopped at the side of the road. . . .\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul said, \ldblquote Boy, that is an old model,\rdblquote  and looked at it critically.\par
\tab Despite Niccolo\rquote s own bitterness against the Bard, he winced at the oth\-er\rquote s condescending tone. For the moment, he was sorry he had allowed Paul in, at least before he had restored the Bard to its usual resting place in the basement. It was only in the desperation of a dull day and a fruitless discus\-sion with his father that he had resurrected it. And it turned out to be just as stupid as he had expected.\par
\tab Nickie was a little afraid of Paul anyway, since Paul had special courses at school and everyone said he was going to grow up to be a Computing Engineer.\par
\tab Not that Niccolo himself was doing badly at school. He got adequate marks in logic, binary manipulations, computing and elementary circuits; all the usual grammar-school subjects. But that was it! They were just the usual subjects and he would grow up to be a control-board guard like everyone else.\par
\tab Paul, however, knew mysterious things about what he called electronics and theoretical mathematics and programing. Especially programing. Nic\-colo didn\rquote t even try to understand when Paul bubbled over about it.\par
\tab Paul listened to the Bard for a few minutes and said, \ldblquote You been using it much?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  said Niccolo, offended. \ldblquote I\rquote ve had it in the basement since before you moved into the neighborhood. I just got it out today--\rdblquote  He lacked an excuse that seemed adequate to himself, so he concluded, \ldblquote I just got it out.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul said, \ldblquote Is that what it tells you about: woodcutters and princesses and talking animals?\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo said, \ldblquote It\rquote s terrible. My dad says we can\rquote t afford a new one. I said to him this morning--\rdblquote  The memory of the morning\rquote s fruitless pleadings brought Niccolo dangerously near tears, which he repressed in a panic. Somehow, he felt that Paul\rquote s thin cheeks never felt the stain of tears and that Paul would have only contempt for anyone else less strong than himself.\par
\tab Niccolo went on, \ldblquote So I thought I\rquote d try this old thing again, but it\rquote s no good.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul turned off the Bard, pressed the contact that led to a nearly instanta\-neous reorientation and recombination of the vocabulary, characters, plot lines and climaxes stored within it. Then he reactivated it.\par
\tab The Bard began smoothly, \ldblquote Once upon a time there was a little boy named Willikins whose mother had died and who lived with a stepfather and a stepbrother. Although the stepfather was very well-to-do, he be\-grudged poor Willikins the very bed he slept in so that Willikins was forced to get such rest as he could on a pile of straw in the stable next to the horses--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Horses!\rdblquote  cried Paul.\par
\tab\ldblquote They\rquote re a kind of animal,\rdblquote  said Niccolo. \ldblquote I think.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know that! I just mean imagine stories about horses.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It tells about horses all the time,\rdblquote  said Niccolo. \ldblquote There are things called cows, too. You milk them but the Bard doesn\rquote t say how.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, gee, why don\rquote t you fix it up?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote d like to know how.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Bard was saying, \ldblquote Often Willikins would think that if only he were rich and powerful, he would show his stepfather and stepbrother what it meant to be cruel to a little boy, so one day he decided to go out into the world and seek his fortune.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul, who wasn\rquote t listening to the Bard, said, \ldblquote It\rquote s easy. The Bard has memory cylinders all fixed up for plot lines and climaxes and things. We don\rquote t have to worry about that. It\rquote s just vocabulary we\rquote ve got to fix so it\rquote ll know about computers and automation and electronics and real things about today. Then it can tell interesting stories, you know, instead of about prin\-cesses and things.\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo said despondently, \ldblquote I wish we could do that.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul said, \ldblquote Listen, my dad says if I get into special computing school next year, he\rquote ll get me a real Bard, a late model. A big one with an attachment for space stories and mysteries. And a visual attachment, too!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean see the stories?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure. Mr. Daugherty at school says they\rquote ve got things like that, now, but not for just everybody. Only if I get into computing school, Dad can get a few breaks.\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo\rquote s eyes bulged with envy. \ldblquote Gee. Seeing a story.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You can come over and watch anytime, Nickie.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, boy. Thanks.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s all right. But remember, I\rquote m the guy who says what kind of story we hear.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure. Sure.\rdblquote  Niccolo would have agreed readily to much more onerous conditions.\par
\tab Paul\rquote s attention returned to the Bard.\par
\tab It was saying, \ldblquote  \lquote If that is the case,\rquote  said the king, stroking his beard and frowning till clouds filled the sky and lightning flashed, \lquote you w\rquote\rdblquote  see to it that my entire land is freed of flies by this time day after tomorrow or--\rquote  \ldblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All we\rquote ve got to do,\rdblquote  said Paul, \ldblquote is open it up--\rdblquote  He shut the Bard off again and was prying at its front panel as he spoke.\par
\tab\ldblquote Hey,\rdblquote  said Niccolo, in sudden alarm. \ldblquote Don\rquote t break it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I won\rquote t break it,\rdblquote  said Paul impatiently. \ldblquote I know all about these things.\rdblquote  Then, with sudden caution, \ldblquote Your father and mother home?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right, then.\rdblquote  He had the front panel off and peered in. \ldblquote Boy, this is a one-cylinder thing.\rdblquote\par
\tab He worked away at the Bard\rquote s innards. Niccolo, who watched with pain\-ful suspense, could not make out what he was doing.\par
\tab Paul pulled out a thin, flexible metal strip, powdered with dots. \ldblquote That\rquote s the Bard\rquote s memory cylinder. I\rquote ll bet its capacity for stories is under a tril\-lion.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What are you going to do, Paul?\rdblquote  quavered Niccolo.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll give it vocabulary.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Easy. I\rquote ve got a book here. Mr. Daugherty gave it to me at school.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul pulled the book out of his pocket and pried at it till he had its plastic jacket off. He unreeled the tape a bit, ran it through the vocalizer, which he turned down to a whisper, then placed it within the Bard\rquote s vitals. He made further attachments.\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote ll that do?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The book will talk and the Bard will put it all on its memory tape.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What good will that do?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Boy, you\rquote re a dope! This book is all about computers and automation and the Bard will get all that information. Then he can stop talking about kings making lightning when they frown.\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo said, \ldblquote And the good guy always wins anyway. There\rquote s no excite\-ment.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, well,\rdblquote  said Paul, watching to see if his setup was working properly, \ldblquote that\rquote s the way they make Bards. They got to have the good guy win and make the bad guys lose and things like that. I heard my father talking about it once. He says that without censorship there\rquote d be no telling what the younger generation would come to. He says it\rquote s bad enough as it is. ... There, it\rquote s working fine.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul brushed his hands against one another and turned away from the Bard. He said, \ldblquote But listen, I didn\rquote t tell you my idea yet. It\rquote s the best thing you ever heard, I bet. I came right to you, because I figured you\rquote d come in with me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure, Paul, sure.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Okay. You know Mr. Daugherty at school? You know what a funny kind of guy he is. Well, he likes me, kind of.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I was over at his house after school today.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You were?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure. He says I\rquote m going to be entering computer school and he wants to encourage me and things like that. He says the world needs more people who can design advanced computer circuits and do proper programing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh?\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul might have caught some of the emptiness behind that monosyllable. He said impatiently, \ldblquote Programing! I told you a hundred times. That\rquote s when you set up problems for the giant computers like Multivac to work on. Mr. Daugherty says it gets harder all the time to find people who can really run computers. He says anyone can keep an eye on the controls and check off answers and put through routine problems. He says the trick is to expand research and figure out ways to ask the right questions, and that\rquote s hard.\par
\tab\ldblquote Anyway, Nickie, he took me to his place and showed me his collection of old computers. It\rquote s kind of a hobby of his to collect old computers. He had tiny computers you had to push with your hand, with little knobs all over it. And he had a hunk of wood he called a slide rule with a little piece of it that went in and out. And some wires with balls on them. He even had a hunk of paper with a kind of thing he called a multiplication table.\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo, who found himself only moderately interested, said, \ldblquote A paper table?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t really a table like you eat on. It was different. It was to help people compute. Mr. Daugherty tried to explain but he didn\rquote t have much time and it was kind of complicated, anyway.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why didn\rquote t people just use a computer?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That was before they had computers,\rdblquote  cried Paul.\par
\tab\ldblquote Before?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure. Do you think people always had computers? Didn\rquote t you ever hear of cavemen?\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo said, \ldblquote How\rquote d they get along without computers?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. Mr. Daugherty says they just had children any old time and did anything that came into their heads whether it would be good for everybody or not. They didn\rquote t even know if it was good or not. And farmers grew things with their hands and people had to do all the work in the factories and run all the machines.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t believe you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s what Mr. Daugherty said. He said it was just plain messy and everyone was miserable. . . . Anyway, let me get to my idea, will you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, go ahead. Who\rquote s stopping you?\rdblquote  said Niccolo, offended.\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. Well, the hand computers, the ones with the knobs, had little squiggles on each knob. And the slide rule had squiggles on it. And the multiplication table was all squiggles. I asked what they were. Mr. Daugh\-erty said they were numbers.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Each different squiggle stood for a different number. For \lquote one\rquote  you made a kind of mark, for \lquote two\rquote  you make another kind of mark, for \lquote three\rquote  another one and so on.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What for?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So you could compute.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What for? You just tell the computer--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Jiminy,\rdblquote  cried Paul, his face twisting with anger, \ldblquote can\rquote t you get it through your head? These slide rules and things didn\rquote t talk.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then how--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The answers showed up in squiggles and you had to know what the squiggles meant. Mr. Daugherty says that, in olden days, everybody learned how to make squiggles when they were kids and how to decode them, too. Making squiggles was called \lquote writing\rquote  and decoding them was \lquote reading.\rquote  He says there was a different kind of squiggle for every word and they used to write whole books in squiggles. He said they had some at the museum and I could look at them if I wanted to. He said if I was going to be a real computer and programer I would have to know about the history of comput\-ing and that\rquote s why he was showing me all these things.\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo frowned. He said, \ldblquote You mean everybody had to figure out squig\-gles for every word and remember them? ... Is this all real or are you making it up?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s all real. Honest. Look, this is the way you make a \lquote one.\rquote  \ldblquote  He drew his finger through the air in a rapid downstroke. \ldblquote This way you make \lquote two,\rquote  and this way \lquote three.\rquote  I learned all the numbers up to \lquote nine.\rquote  \ldblquote\par
\tab Niccolo watched the curving finger uncomprehendingly. \ldblquote What\rquote s the good of it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You can learn how to make words. I asked Mr. Daugherty how you made the squiggle for \lquote Paul Loeb\rquote  but he didn\rquote t know. He said there were people at the museum who would know. He said there were people who had learned how to decode whole books. He said computers could be designed to decode books and used to be used that way but not any more because we have real books now, with magnetic tapes that go through the vocalizer and come out talking, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So if we go down to the museum, we can get to learn how to make words in squiggles. They\rquote ll let us because I\rquote m going to computer school.\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo was riddled with disappointment. \ldblquote Is that your idea? Holy Smokes, Paul, who wants to do that? Make stupid squiggles!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t you get it? Don\rquote t you get it? You dope. It\rquote ll be secret message stuff!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure. What good is talking when everyone can understand you? With squiggles you can send secret messages. You can make them on paper and nobody in the world would know what you were saying unless they knew the squiggles, too. And they wouldn\rquote t, you bet, unless we taught them. We can have a real club, with initiations and rules and a clubhouse. Boy--\rdblquote\par
\tab A certain excitement began stirring in Niccolo\rquote s bosom. \ldblquote What kind of secret messages?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Any kind. Say I want to tell you to come over my place and watch my new Visual Bard and I don\rquote t want any of the other fellows to come. I make the right squiggles on paper and I give it to you and you look at it and you know what to do. Nobody else does. You can even show it to them and they wouldn\rquote t know a thing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hey, that\rquote s something,\rdblquote  yelled Niccolo, completely won over. \ldblquote When do we learn how?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Tomorrow,\rdblquote  said Paul. \ldblquote I\rquote ll get Mr. Daugherty to explain to the mu\-seum that it\rquote s all right and you get your mother and father to say okay. We can go down right after school and start learning.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure!\rdblquote  cried Niccolo. \ldblquote We can be club officers.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll be president of the club,\rdblquote  said Paul matter-of-factly. \ldblquote You can be vice-president.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. Hey, this is going to be tots more fun than the Bard.\rdblquote  He was suddenly reminded of the Bard and said in sudden apprehension, \ldblquote Hey, what about my old Bard?\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul turned to look at it. It was quietly taking in the slowly unreeling book, and the sound of the book\rquote s vocalizations was a dimly heard murmur.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll disconnect it.\rdblquote\par
\tab He worked away while Niccolo watched anxiously. After a few moments, Paul put his reassembled book into his pocket, replaced the Bard\rquote s panel and activated it.\par
\tab The Bard said, \ldblquote Once upon a time, in a large city, there lived a poor young boy named Fair Johnnie whose only friend in the world was a small computer. The computer, each morning, would tell the boy whether it would rain that day and answer any problems he might have. It was never wrong. But it so happened that one day, the king of that land, having heard of the little computer, decided that he would have it as his own. With this purpose in mind, he called in his Grand Vizier and said--\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo turned off the Bard with a quick motion of his hand. \ldblquote Same old junk,\rdblquote  he said passionately, \ldblquote just with a computer thrown in.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Paul, \ldblquote they got so much stuff on the tape already that the computer business doesn\rquote t show up much when random combinations are made. What\rquote s the difference, anyway? You just need a new model.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ll never be able to afford one. Just this dirty old miserable thing.\rdblquote  He kicked at it again, hitting it more squarely this time. The Bard moved backward with a squeal of castors.\par
\tab\ldblquote You can always watch mine, when I get it,\rdblquote  said Paul. \ldblquote Besides, don\rquote t forget our squiggle club.\rdblquote\par
\tab Niccolo nodded.\par
\tab\ldblquote I tell you what,\rdblquote  said Paul. \ldblquote Let\rquote s go over to my place. My father has some books about old times. We can listen to them and maybe get some ideas. You leave a note for your folks and maybe you can stay over for supper. Come on.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Niccolo, and the two boys ran out together. Niccolo, in his eagerness, ran almost squarely into the Bard, but he only rubbed at the spot on his hip where he had made contact and ran on.\par
\tab The activation signal of the Bard glowed. Niccolo\rquote s collision closed a circuit and, although it was alone in the room and there was none to hear, it began a story, nevertheless.\par
\tab But not in its usual voice, somehow; in a lower tone that had a hint of throatiness in it. An adult, listening, might almost have thought that the voice carried a hint of passion in it, a trace of near feeling.\par
\tab The Bard said: \ldblquote Once upon a time, there was a little computer named the Bard who lived all alone with cruel step-people. The cruel step-people con\-tinually made fun of the little computer and sneered at him, telling him he was good-for-nothing and that he was a useless object. They struck him and kept him in lonely rooms for months at a time.\par
\tab\ldblquote Yet through it all the little computer remained brave. He always did the best he could, obeying all orders cheerfully. Nevertheless, the step-people with whom he lived remained cruel and heartless.\par
\tab\ldblquote One day, the little computer learned that in the world there existed a great many computers of all sorts, great numbers of them. Some were Bards like himself, but some ran factories, and some ran farms. Some organized population and some analyzed all kinds of data. Many were very powerful and very wise, much more powerful and wise than the step-people who were so cruel to the little computer.\par
\tab\ldblquote And the little computer knew then that computers would always grow wiser and more powerful until someday--someday--someday--\rdblquote\par
\tab But a valve must finally have stuck in the Bard\rquote s aging and corroding vitals, for as it waited alone in the darkening room through the evening, it could only whisper over and over again, \ldblquote Someday--someday--someday.\rdblquote\par
