\pard\keepn\s3\sb240\sa60\b\f2\fs26\page Point of View \par
\pard\b0\f0\fs20\par
\tab Roger came looking for his father, partly because it was Sunday, and by rights his father shouldn\rquote t have been at work, and Roger wanted to be sure that everything was all right. \par
\tab Roger\rquote s father wasn\rquote t hard to find, because all the people who worked with Multivac, the giant computer, lived with their families right on the grounds. They made up a little city by themselves, a city of people that solved all the world\rquote s problems. \par
\tab The Sunday receptionist knew Roger. \ldblquote If you\rquote re after your father,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote he\rquote s down Corridor L, but he may be too busy to see you. Roger tried anyway, poking his head past one of the doors where he heard the noise of men and women. The corridors were a lot emptier than on weekdays, so it was easy to find where the people were working. \par
\tab He saw his father at once, and his father saw him. His father didn\rquote t look happy and Roger decided at once that everything wasn\rquote t all right. \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, Roger,\rdblquote  said his father. \ldblquote I\rquote m busy, I\rquote m afraid.\rdblquote  Roger\rquote s father\rquote s boss was there, too, and he said, \ldblquote Come on, Atkins, take a break. You\rquote ve been at this thing for nine hours and you\rquote re not doing us any good anymore. Take the kid for a bite at the commissary. Take a nap and then come back.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Roger\rquote s father didn\rquote t look as if he wanted to. He had an instrument in his hand that Roger knew was a current-pattern analyzer, though he didn\rquote t know how it worked. Roger could hear Multivac chuckling and whirring all about. \par
\tab But then Roger\rquote s father put down the analyzer. \ldblquote Okay. Come on, Roger. I\rquote ll race you for a hamburger and we\rquote ll let these wise guys here try and find out what\rquote s wrong without me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He stopped a while to wash up and then they were in the commissary with big hamburgers in front of them and french fries and soda pop. \par
\tab Roger said, \ldblquote Is Multivac out of order still, Dad?\rdblquote  His father said gloomily, \ldblquote We\rquote re not getting anywhere, I\rquote ll tell you that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It seemed to be working. I mean, I could hear it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, sure, it\rquote s working. It just doesn\rquote t always give the right answers.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Roger was thirteen and he\rquote d been taking computer-programming since the fourth grade. He hated it sometimes and wished he lived back in the 20th Century, when kids didn\rquote t use to take it--but it was helpful sometimes in talking to his father. \par
\tab Roger said, \ldblquote How can you tell it doesn\rquote t always give the right answers, if only Multivac knows the answers?\rdblquote  \par
\tab His father shrugged and for a minute Roger was afraid he would just say it was too hard to explain and not talk about it--but he almost never did that. \par
\tab His father said, \ldblquote Son, Multivac may have a brain as large as a big factory, but it still isn\rquote t as complicated as the one we have here,\rdblquote  and he tapped his head. \ldblquote Sometimes, Multivac gives us an answer we couldn\rquote t calculate for ourselves in a thousand years, but just the same something clicks in our brains and we say, \lquote Whoa! Something\rquote s wrong here!\rquote  Then we ask Multivac again and we get a \i different \i0 answer. If Multivac were right, you see, we should always get the same answer to the same question. When we get different answers, one of them is wrong. \par
\tab\ldblquote  And the thing is, son, how do we know we always catch Multivac? How do we know that some of the wrong answers don\rquote t get past us? We may rely on some answer and do something that may turn out disastrously five years from now. Something\rquote s wrong inside Multivac and we can\rquote t find out what. And whatever is wrong is getting worse.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why should it be getting worse?\rdblquote\lquote  asked Roger. His father had finished his hamburger and was eating the french fries one by one. \ldblquote My feeling is. Son,\rquote  he said, thoughtfully, \ldblquote that we\rquote ve made Multivac the wrong smartness.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Huh?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You see, Roger, if Multivac were as smart as a man, we could talk to it and find out what was wrong no matter how complicated it was. If it were as dumb as a machine, it would go wrong in simple ways that we could catch easily. The trouble is, it\rquote s \i half-smart, \i0 like an idiot. It\rquote s smart enough to go wrong in very complicated ways, but not smart enough to help \i us \i0 find out what\rquote s wrong.--And that\rquote s the wrong smartness.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He looked very gloomy. \ldblquote But what can we do? We don\rquote t know how to make it smarter--not yet. And we don\rquote t dare make it dumber either, because the world\rquote s problems have become so serious and the questions we ask are so complicated that it takes all Multivac\rquote s smartness to answer them. It would be a disaster to have him dumber.\rquote\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If you shut down Multivac,\rdblquote  said Roger, \ldblquote and went over him really carefully--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We can\rquote t do that, son,\rdblquote  said his father. \ldblquote I\rquote m afraid Multivac must be in operation every minute of the day and night. We\rquote ve got a big back-log of problems.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But if Multivac continues to make mistakes. Dad, won\rquote t it \i have \i0 to be shut down? If you can\rquote t trust what it says--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  Roger\rquote s father ruffled Roger\rquote s hair, \ldblquote we\rquote ll find out what\rquote s wrong, old sport, don\rquote t worry.\rdblquote  But his eyes looked worried just the same. \ldblquote Come on, let\rquote s finish and we\rquote ll get out of here.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But Dad,\rdblquote  said Roger, \ldblquote listen. If Multivac is half-smart, why does that mean it\rquote s an idiot?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If you knew the way we have to give it directions, son, you wouldn\rquote t ask.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Just the same, Dad, maybe it\rquote s not the way to look at it. I\rquote m not as smart as you; I don\rquote t know as much; but \i I\rquote m \i0 not an idiot. Maybe Multivac isn\rquote t like an idiot, maybe it\rquote s like a kid.\rdblquote\par
\tab Roger\rquote s father laughed. \ldblquote That\rquote s an interesting point of view, but what difference does it make?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It could make a lot of difference,\rdblquote  said Roger. \ldblquote You\rquote re not an idiot, so you don\rquote t see how an idiot\rquote s mind would work; but I\rquote m a kid, and maybe I would know how a kid\rquote s mind would work.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh? And how would a kid\rquote s mind work?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, you say you\rquote ve got to keep Multivac busy day and night. A machine can do that. But if you give a kid homework and told him to do it for hours and hours, he\rquote d get pretty tired and feel rotten enough to make mistakes, maybe even on purpose.--So why not let Multivac take an hour or two off every day with no problem-solving--just letting it chuckle and whir by itself any way it wants to.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Roger\rquote s father looked as if he were thinking very hard. He took out his pocket-computer and tried some combinations on it. He tried some more combinations. Then he said, \ldblquote You know, Roger, if I take what you said and turn it into Platt-integrals, it makes a kind of sense. And twenty-two hours we can be sure of is better than twenty-four that might be all wrong.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He nodded his head, but then he looked up from his pocket-computer and suddenly asked, as though Roger were the expert, \ldblquote Roger, are you sure?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Roger was sure. He said, \ldblquote Dad, a kid\rquote s got to \i play\i0 , too.\rdblquote  \par
