\tab Genevieve Renshaw, M.D., had her hands deep in the pockets of her lab coat and fists were clearly outlined within, but she spoke calmly. \par
\tab\ldblquote The fact is,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote that I\rquote m almost ready, but I\rquote ll need help to keep it going long enough to \i be \i0 ready.\rdblquote  \par
\tab James Berkowitz, a physicist who tended to patronize mere physicians when they were too attractive to be despised, had a tendency to call her Jenny Wren when out of hearing. He was fond of saying that Jenny Wren had a classic profile and a brow surprisingly smooth and unlined considering that behind it so keen a brain ticked. He knew better than to express his admiration, however--of the classic profile, that is--since that would be male chauvinism. Admiring the brain was better, but on the whole he preferred not to do that out loud in her presence. \par
\tab He said, thumb rasping along the just-appearing stubble on his chin, \ldblquote I don\rquote t think the front-office is going to be patient for much longer. The impression I have is that they\rquote re going to have you on the carpet before the end of the week.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s why I need your help.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nothing I can do, I\rquote m afraid.\rdblquote  He caught an unexpected glimpse of his face in the mirror, and momentarily admired the set of the black waves in his hair. \par
\tab\ldblquote  And Adam\rquote s,\rdblquote  she said. \par
\tab Adam Orsino, who had, till that moment, sipped his coffee and felt detached, looked as though he had been jabbed from behind, and said, \ldblquote Why me?\rdblquote  His full, plump lips quivered. \par
\tab\ldblquote Because you\rquote re the laser men here--Jim the theoretician and Adam the engineer--and I\rquote ve got a laser application that goes beyond anything either of you have imagined. I won\rquote t convince them of that but you two would.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Provided,\rdblquote  said Berkowitz, \ldblquote that you can convince us first.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote All right. Suppose you let me have an hour of your valuable time, if you\rquote re not afraid to be shown something completely new about lasers.--You can take it out of your coffee break.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Renshaw\rquote s laboratory was dominated by her computer. It was not that the computer was unusually large, but it was virtually omni-present. Renshaw had learned computer technology on her own, and had modified and extended her computer until no one but she (and, Berkowitz sometimes believed, not even she) could handle it with ease. Not bad, she would say, for someone in the life-sciences. \par
\tab She closed the door before saying a word, then turned to face the other two somberly. Berkowitz was uncomfortably aware of a faintly unpleasant odor in the air, and Orsino\rquote s wrinkling nose showed that he was aware of it, too. \par
\tab Renshaw said, \ldblquote Let me list the laser applications for you, if you don\rquote t mind my lighting a candle in the sunshine. The laser is coherent radiation, with all the light-waves of the same length and moving in the same direction, so it\rquote s noise-free and can be used in holography. By modulating the wave-forms we can imprint information on it with a high degree of accuracy. What\rquote s more, since the light-waves are only a millionth the length of radio waves, a laser beam can carry a million times the information an equivalent radio beam can.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Berkowitz seemed amused. \ldblquote  Are you working on a laser-based communication system, Jenny?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  she replied. \ldblquote I leave such obvious advances to physicists and engineers.--Lasers can also concentrate quantities of energy into a microscopic area and deliver that energy in quantity. On a large scale you can implode hydrogen and perhaps begin a controlled fusion reaction--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I know you don\rquote t have that,\rdblquote  said Orsino, his bald head glistening in the overhead fluorescents. \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t. I haven\rquote t tried.--On a smaller scale, you can drill holes in the most refractory materials, weld selected bits, heat-treat them, gouge and scribe them. You can remove or fuse tiny portions in restricted areas with heat delivered so rapidly that surrounding areas have no time to warm up before the treatment is over. You can work on the retina of the eye, the dentine of the teeth and so on.--And of course the laser is an amplifier capable of magnifying weak signals with great accuracy.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote  And why do you tell us all this?\rdblquote  said Berkowitz. \par
\tab\ldblquote To point out how these properties can be made to fit my own field, which, you know, is neurophysiology.\rdblquote  \par
\tab She made a brushing motion with her hand at her brown hair, as though she were suddenly nervous. \ldblquote For decades,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote We\rquote ve been able to measure the tiny, shifting electric potentials of the brain and record them as electroencephalograms, or EEGs. We\rquote ve got alpha waves, beta waves, delta waves, theta waves; different variations at different times, depending on whether eyes are open or closed, whether the subject is awake, meditating or asleep. But we\rquote ve gotten very little information out of it all. \par
\tab\ldblquote The trouble is that we\rquote re getting the signals of ten billion neurons in shifting combinations. It\rquote s like listening to the noise of all the human beings on Earth--one, two and a half Earths--from a great distance and trying to make out individual conversations. It can\rquote t be done. We could detect some gross, overall change--a world war and the rise in the volume of noise--but nothing finer. In the same way, we can tell some gross malfunction of the brain--epilepsy--but nothing finer. \par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose now, the brain might be scanned by a tiny laser beam, cell by cell, and so rapidly that at no time does a single cell receive enough energy to raise its temperature significantly. The tiny potentials of each cell can, in feed-back, affect the laser beam, and the modulations can be amplified and recorded. You will then get a new kind of measurement, a laser-encephalogram, or LEG, if you wish, which will contain millions of times as much information as ordinary EEGs.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Berkowitz said, \ldblquote A nice thought.--But just a thought.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote More than a thought, Jim. I\rquote ve been working on it for five years, spare time at first. Lately, it\rquote s been full time, which is what annoys the front-office, because I haven\rquote t been sending in reports.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Because it got to the point where it sounded too mad; where I had to know where I was, and where I had to be sure of getting backing first.\rdblquote  \par
\tab She pulled a screen aside and revealed a cage that contained a pair of mournful-eyed marmosets. \par
\tab Berkowitz and Orsino looked at each other. Berkowitz touched his nose. \ldblquote I thought I smelled something.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What are you doing with those?\rdblquote  asked Orsino. Berkowitz said, \ldblquote  At a guess, she\rquote s been scanning the marmoset brain. Have you, Jenny?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I started considerably lower in the animal scale.\rdblquote  She opened the cage and took out one of the marmosets, which looked at her with a miniature sad-old-man-with-sideburns expression. \par
\tab She clucked to it, stroked it and gently strapped it into a small harness. \par
\tab Orsino said, \ldblquote What are you doing?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t have it moving around if I\rquote m going to make it part of a circuit, and I can\rquote t anesthetize it without vitiating the experiment. There are several electrodes implanted in the marmoset\rquote s brain and I\rquote m going to connect them with my LEG system. The laser I\rquote m using is here. I\rquote m sure you recognize the model and I won\rquote t bother giving you its specifications.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Berkowitz, \ldblquote but you might tell us what we\rquote re going to see.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It would be just as easy to show you. Just watch the screen.\rdblquote  She connected the leads to the electrodes with a quiet and sure efficiency, then turned a knob that dimmed the overhead lights in the room. On the screen there appeared a jagged complex of peaks and valleys in a fine, bright line that was wrinkled into secondary and tertiary peaks and valleys. Slowly, these shifted in a series of minor changes, with occasional flashes of sudden major differences. It was as though the irregular line had a life of its own. \par
\tab\ldblquote This,\rdblquote  said Renshaw, \ldblquote is essentially the EEG information, but in much greater detail.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Enough detail,\rdblquote  asked Orsino, \ldblquote to tell you what\rquote s going on in individual cells?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In theory, yes. Practically, no. Not yet. But we can separate this overall LEG into component grams. Watch!\rdblquote  \par
\tab She punched the computer keyboard, and the line changed, and changed again. Now it was a small, nearly regular wave that shifted forward and backward in what was almost a heartbeat; now it was jagged and sharp; now intermittent; now nearly featureless--all in quick switches of geometric surrealism. \par
\tab Berkowitz said, \ldblquote You mean that every bit of the brain is that different from every other?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Renshaw, \ldblquote not at all. The brain is very largely a holographic device, but there are minor shifts in emphasis from place to place and Mike can subtract them as deviations from the norm and use the LEG system to amplify those variations. The amplifications can be varied from ten-thousand-fold to ten-million-fold. The laser system is that noise-free.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Who\rquote s Mike?\rdblquote  asked Orsino. \par
\tab\ldblquote Mike?\rdblquote  said Renshaw, momentarily puzzled. The skin over her cheekbones reddened slightly. \ldblquote Did I say--Well, I call it that sometimes. It\rquote s short for \lquote my computer.\rquote  \ldblquote  She waved her arm about the room. \ldblquote My computer. Mike. Very carefully programmed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Berkowitz nodded and said, \ldblquote All right, Jenny, what\rquote s it all about? If you\rquote ve got a new brain-scanning device using lasers, fine. It\rquote s an interesting application and you\rquote re right, it\rquote s not one I would have thought of--but then I\rquote m no neurophysiologist. But why not write it up? It seems to me the front-office would support--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But this is just the beginning.\rdblquote  She turned off the scanning device and placed a piece of fruit in the marmoset\rquote s mouth. The creature did not seem alarmed or in discomfort. It chewed slowly. Renshaw unhooked the leads but allowed it to remain in its harness. \par
\tab Renshaw said, \ldblquote I can identify the various separate grams. Some are associated with the various senses, some with visceral reactions, some with emotions. We can do a lot with that, but I don\rquote t want to stop there. The interesting thing is that one is associated with abstract thought.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Orsino\rquote s plump face wrinkled into a look of disbelief, \ldblquote How can you tell?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That particular form of gram gets more pronounced as one goes up the animal kingdom toward greater complexity of brain. No other gram does. Besides--\rdblquote  She paused; then, as though gathering strength of purpose, she said, \ldblquote Those grams are enormously amplified. They can be picked up, detected. I can tell--vaguely--that there are--thoughts--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote By God,\rdblquote  said Berkowitz. \ldblquote Telepathy.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  she said, defiantly. \ldblquote Exactly.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No wonder you haven\rquote t wanted to report it. Come \i on, \i0 Jenny.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  said Renshaw warmly. \ldblquote Granted there could be no telepathy just using the unamplified potential patterns of the human brain anymore than anyone can see features on the Martian surface with the unaided eye. But once instruments are invented--the telescope\i --this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote Then tell the front-office.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Renshaw. \ldblquote They won\rquote t believe me. They\rquote ll try to stop me. But they\rquote ll have to take \i you \i0 seriously, Jim, and you, Adam.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What would you expect me to tell them?\rdblquote  said Berkowitz. \par
\tab\ldblquote What you experience. I\rquote m going to hook up the marmoset again, and have Mike--my computer pick out the abstract thought gram. It will only take a moment. The computer always selects the abstract thought gram unless it is directed not to do so.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why? Because the computer thinks, too?\rdblquote  Berkowitz laughed. \ldblquote That\rquote s not all that funny,\rdblquote  said Renshaw. \ldblquote I suspect there \i is \i0 a resonance there. This computer is complex enough to set up an electromagnetic pattern that may have elements in common with the abstract thought gram. In any case--\rdblquote  \par
\tab The marmoset\rquote s brain waves were flickering on the screen again, but it was not a gram the men had seen before. It was a gram that was almost furry in its complexity and was changing constantly. \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t detect anything,\rdblquote  said Orsino. \par
\tab\ldblquote You have to be put into the receiving circuit,\rdblquote  said Renshaw. \ldblquote You mean implant electrodes in our brain?\rdblquote  asked Berkowitz. \par
\tab\ldblquote No, on your skull. That would be sufficient. I\rquote d prefer you, Adam, since there would be no insulating hair.--Oh, come on, I\rquote ve been part of the circuit myself. It won\rquote t hurt.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Orsino submitted with a bad grace. His muscles were visibly tense but he allowed the leads to be strapped to his skull. \par
\tab\ldblquote Do you sense anything!\rdblquote  asked Renshaw. \par
\tab Orsino cocked his head and assumed a listening posture. He seemed to grow interested in spite of himself. He said, \ldblquote I seem to be aware of a humming--and--and a little high-pitched squeaking--and that\rquote s funny--a kind of twitching--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Berkowitz said, \ldblquote I suppose the marmoset isn\rquote t likely to think in words.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Certainly not,\rdblquote  said Renshaw. \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, then,\rdblquote  said Berkowitz, \ldblquote if you\rquote re suggesting that some squeaking and twitching sensation represents thought, you\rquote re guessing. You\rquote re not being compelling.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Renshaw said, \ldblquote So we go up the scale once again.\rdblquote  She removed the marmoset from its harness and put it back in its cage. \par
\tab\ldblquote You mean you have a \i man \i0 as a subject,\rdblquote  said Orsino, unbelieving. \par
\tab\ldblquote I have \i myself \i0 as a subject, a \i person.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote You\rquote ve got electrodes implanted--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No. In my case my computer has a stronger potential-flicker to work with. My brain has ten times the mass of the marmoset brain. Mike can pick up my component grams through the skull.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How do you know?\rdblquote  asked Berkowitz. \par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t you think I\rquote ve tried it on myself before this?--Now help me with this, please. Right.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Her fingers flicked on the computer keyboard and at once the screen flickered with an intricately varying wave; an intricacy that made it almost a maze. \par
\tab\ldblquote Would you replace your own leads, Adam?\rdblquote  said Renshaw. \par
\tab Orsino did so with Berkowitz\rquote s not-entirely-approving help. Again, Orsino cocked his head and listened. \ldblquote I hear words,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote but they\rquote re disjointed and overlapping, like different people speaking.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m not trying to think consciously,\rdblquote  said Renshaw. \ldblquote When you talk, I hear an echo.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Berkowitz said, dryly, \ldblquote Don\rquote t talk, Jenny. Blank out your mind and see if he \i doesn\rquote t \i0 hear you think.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Orsino said, \ldblquote I don\rquote t hear any echo when \i you \i0 talk, Jim.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Berkowitz said, \ldblquote If you don\rquote t shut up, you won\rquote t hear anything.\rdblquote  \par
\tab A heavy silence fell on all three. Then, Orsino nodded, reached for pen and paper on the desk and wrote something. \par
\tab Renshaw reached out, threw a switch and pulled the leads up and over her head, shaking her hair back into place. She said, \ldblquote 1 hope that what you wrote down was: \lquote  Adam, raise Cain with the front office and Jim will eat crow.\rquote  \ldblquote  \par
\tab Orsino said, \ldblquote It\rquote s what I wrote down, word for word.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Renshaw said, \ldblquote Well, there you are. Working telepathy, and we don\rquote t have to use it to transmit nonsense sentences either. Think of the use in psychiatry and in the treatment of mental disease. Think of its use in education and in teaching machines. Think of its use in legal investigations and criminal trials.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Orsino said, wide-eyed, \ldblquote Frankly, the social implications are staggering. I don\rquote t know if something like this should be allowed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Under proper legal safeguards, why not?\rdblquote  said Renshaw, indifferently. \ldblquote Anyway--if you two join me now, our combined weight can carry this thing and push it over. And if you come along with me it will be Nobel Prize time for--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Berkowitz said grimly, \ldblquote I\rquote m not in this. Not yet.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What? What do you mean?\rdblquote  Renshaw sounded outraged, her coldly beautiful face flushed suddenly. \par
\tab\ldblquote Telepathy is too touchy. It\rquote s too fascinating, too desired. We could be fooling ourselves.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Listen for yourself, Jim.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I could be fooling myself, too. I want a control.\rdblquote  \ldblquote What do you mean, a control?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Short-circuit the origin of thought. Leave out the animal. No marmoset. No human being. Let Orsino listen to metal and glass and laser light and if he still hears thought, then we\rquote re kidding ourselves.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose he detects nothing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then \i I\rquote ll \i0 listen and if without looking--if you can arrange to have me in the next room--I can tell when you are in and when you are out of circuit, \i then \i0 I\rquote ll consider joining you in this thing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Very well, then,\rdblquote  said Renshaw, \ldblquote we\rquote ll try a control. I\rquote ve never done it, but it isn\rquote t hard.\rdblquote  She maneuvered the leads that had been over her head and put them into contact with each other. \ldblquote Now, Adam, if you will resume--\rdblquote  \par
\tab But before she could go further, there came a cold, clear sound, as pure and as clean as the tinkle of breaking icicles: \par
\tab\ldblquote At \i last!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0 Renshaw said, \ldblquote What?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Orsino said, \ldblquote Who said--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Berkowitz said, \ldblquote Did someone say, \ldblquote At last\rquote ?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Renshaw, pale, said, \ldblquote It wasn\rquote t sound. It was in my--Did you two--\rdblquote  \par
\tab The clear sound came again, \i\ldblquote I\rquote m Mi--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0 And Renshaw tore the leads apart and there was silence. She said with a voiceless motion of her lips, \ldblquote I think it\rquote s my computer--Mike.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i\ldblquote You \i0 mean he\rquote s \i thinking?\rdblquote  \i0 said Orsino, nearly as voiceless. Renshaw said in an unrecognizable voice that at least had regained sound, \ldblquote I \i said \i0 it was complex enough to have something--Do you suppose--It always turned automatically to the abstract-thought gram of whatever brain was in its circuit. Do you suppose that with no brain in the circuit, it turned to its own?\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was silence, then Berkowitz said, \ldblquote  Are you trying to say that this computer thinks, but can\rquote t express its thoughts as long as it\rquote s under force of programming, but that given the chance in your LEG system--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But that can\rquote t be so?\rdblquote  said Orsino, high-pitched. \ldblquote No one was receiving. It\rquote s not the same thing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Renshaw said, \ldblquote The computer works on much greater power-intensities than brains do. I suppose it can magnify itself to the point where we can detect it directly without artificial aid. How else can you explain--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Berkowitz said, abruptly, \ldblquote Well, you have another application of lasers, then. It enables you to talk to computers as independent intelligences, person to person.\rdblquote  \par
\tab And Renshaw said, \ldblquote Oh, God, what do we do now?\rdblquote  \par
