\pard\b0\f0\fs20\par
\tab My name is Joe. That is what my colleague, Milton Davidson, calls me. He is a programmer and I am a computer program. I am part of the Multivac-complex and am connected with other parts all over the world. I know everything. Almost everything. \par
\tab I am Milton\rquote s private program. His Joe. He understands more about programming than anyone in the world, and I am his experimental model. He has made me speak better than any other computer can. \par
\tab\ldblquote It is just a matter of matching sounds to symbols, Joe,\rdblquote  he told me. \ldblquote That\rquote s the way it works in the human brain even though we still don\rquote t know what symbols there are in the brain. I know the symbols in yours, and I can match them to words, one-to-one.\rdblquote  So I talk. I don\rquote t think I talk as well as I think, but Milton says I talk very well. Milton has never married, though he is nearly forty years old. He has never found the right woman, he told me. One day he said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll find her yet, Joe. I\rquote m going to find the best. I\rquote m going to have true love and you\rquote re going to help me. I\rquote m tired of improving you in order to solve the problems of the world. Solve \i my \i0 problem. Find me true love.\rdblquote  \par
\tab I said, \ldblquote What is true love?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind. That is abstract. Just find me the ideal girl. You are connected to the Multivac-complex so you can reach the data banks of every human being in the world. We\rquote ll eliminate them all by groups and classes until we\rquote re left with only one person. The perfect person. She will be for me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab I said, \ldblquote I am ready.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Eliminate all men first.\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was easy. His words activated symbols in my molecular valves. I could reach out to make contact with the accumulated data on every human being in the world. At his words, I withdrew from 3,784,982,874 men. I kept contact with 3,786,112,090 women. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Eliminate an younger than twenty-five; an older than forty. Then eliminate an with an IQ under 120; an with a height under 150 centimeters and over 175 centimeters.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He gave me exact measurements; he eliminated women with living children; he eliminated women with various genetic characteristics. \ldblquote I\rquote m not sure about eye color,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote Let that go for a while. But no red hair. I don\rquote t like red hair.\rdblquote  \par
\tab After two weeks, we were down to 235 women. They all spoke English very well. Milton said he didn\rquote t want a language problem. Even computer-translation would get in the way at intimate moments. \par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t interview 235 women,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote It would take too much time, and people would discover what I am doing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It would make trouble,\rdblquote  I said. \par
\tab Milton had arranged me to do things I wasn\rquote t designed to do. No one knew about that. \ldblquote It\rquote s none of their business,\rdblquote  he said, and the skin on his face grew red. \ldblquote I tell you what, Joe, I will bring in holographs, and you check the list for similarities.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He brought in holographs of women. \ldblquote These are three beauty contest winners,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Do any of the 235 match?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Eight were very good matches and Milton said, \ldblquote Good, you have their data banks. Study requirements and needs in the job market and arrange to have them assigned here. One at a time, of course.\rdblquote  He thought a while, moved his shoulders up and down, and said, \ldblquote Alphabetical order.\rdblquote  \par
\tab That is one of the things I am not designed to do. Shifting people from job to job for personal reasons is called manipulation. I could do it now because Milton had arranged it. I wasn\rquote t supposed to do it for anyone but him, though. \par
\tab The first girl arrived a week later. Milton\rquote s face turned red when he saw her. He spoke as though it were hard to do so. They were together a great deal and he paid no attention to me. One time he said, \ldblquote Let me take you to dinner.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The next day he said to me, \ldblquote It was no good, somehow. There was something missing. She is a beautiful woman, but I did not feel any touch of true love. Try the next one.\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was the same with all eight. They were much alike. They smiled a great deal and had pleasant voices, but Milton always found it wasn\rquote t right. He said, \ldblquote I can\rquote t understand it, Joe. You and I have picked out the eight women who, in all the world, look the best to me. They are ideal. Why don\rquote t they please me?\rdblquote  \par
\tab I said, \ldblquote Do you please them?\rdblquote  \par
\tab His eyebrows moved and he pushed one fist hard against his other hand. \ldblquote That\rquote s it, Joe. It\rquote s a two-way street. If I am not their ideal, they can\rquote t act in such a way as to be my ideal. I must be their true love, too, but how do I do that?\rdblquote  He seemed to be thinking all that day. \par
\tab The next morning he came to me and said, \ldblquote I\rquote m going to leave it to you, Joe. All up to you. You have my data bank, and I am going to tell you everything I know about myself. You fill up my data bank in every possible detail but keep all additions to yourself.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What will I do with the data bank, then, Milton?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then you will match it to the 235 women. No, 227. Leave out the eight you\rquote ve seen. Arrange to have each undergo a psychiatric examination. Fill up their data banks and compare them with mine. Find correlations.\rdblquote  (Arranging psychiatric examinations is another thing that is against my original instructions.) \par
\tab For weeks, Milton talked to me. He told me of his parents and his siblings. He told me of his childhood and his schooling and his adolescence. He told me of the young women he had admired from a distance. His data bank grew and he adjusted me to broaden and deepen my symbol-taking. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote You see, Joe, as you get more and more of me in you, I adjust you to match me better and better. You get to think more like me, so you understand me better. If you understand me well enough, then any woman, whose data bank is something you understand as well, would be my true love.\rdblquote  He kept talking to me and I came to understand him better and better. \par
\tab I could make longer sentences and my expressions grew more complicated. My speech began to sound a good deal like his in vocabulary, word order and style. \par
\tab I said to him one time, \ldblquote You see, Milton, it isn\rquote t a matter of fitting a girl to a physical ideal only. You need a girl who is a personal, emotional, temperamental fit to you. If that happens, looks are secondary. If we can\rquote t find the fit in these 227, we\rquote ll look elsewhere. We will find someone who won\rquote t care how you look either, or how anyone would look, if only there is the personality fit. What are looks?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Absolutely,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I would have known this if I had had more to do with women in my life. Of course, thinking about it makes it all plain now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab We always agreed; we thought so like each other. \par
\tab\ldblquote We shouldn\rquote t have any trouble, now, Milton, if you\rquote ll let me ask you questions. I can see where, in your data bank, there are blank spots and unevennesses.\rdblquote  \par
\tab What followed, Milton said, was the equivalent of a careful psychoanalysis. Of course, I was learning from the psychiatric examinations of the 227 women--on all of which I was keeping close tabs. \par
\tab Milton seemed quite happy. He said, \ldblquote Talking to you, Joe, is almost like talking to another self. Our personalities have come to match perfectly.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So will the personality of the woman we choose.\rdblquote  \par
\tab For I had found her and she was one of the 227 after all. Her name was Charity Jones and she was an Evaluator at the Library of History in Wichita. Her extended data bank fit ours perfectly. All the other women had fallen into discard in one respect or another as the data banks grew fuller, but with Charity there was increasing and astonishing resonance. \par
\tab I didn\rquote t have to describe her to Milton. Milton had coordinated my symbolism so closely with his own I could tell the resonance directly. It fit me. \par
\tab Next it was a matter of adjusting the work sheets and job requirements in such a way as to get Charity assigned to us. It must be done very delicately, so no one would know that anything illegal had taken place. \par
\tab Of course, Milton himself knew, since it was he who arranged it and that had to be taken care of too. When they came to arrest him on grounds of malfeasance in office, it was, fortunately, for something that had taken place ten years ago. He had told me about it, of course, so it was easy to arrange--and he won\rquote t talk about me for that would make his offense much worse. \par
\par
\tab He\rquote s gone, and tomorrow is February 14, Valentine\rquote s Day. Charity will arrive then with her cool hands and her sweet voice. I will teach her how to operate me and how to care for me. What do looks matter when our personalities will resonate? \par
\tab I will say to her, \ldblquote I am Joe, and you are my true love.\rdblquote  \par
\par
