\tab The spaceship leaked, as the saying goes, like a sieve. It was supposed to. In fact, that was the whole idea. The result, of course, was that during the journey from Ganymede to Jupiter, the ship was crammed just as full as it could be with the very hardest space vacuum. And since the ship also lacked heating devices, this space vacuum was at normal temperature, which is a fraction of a degree above absolute zero. \par
\tab This, also, was according to plan. Little things like the absence of heat and air didn\rquote t annoy anyone at all on the particular spaceship. \par
\tab The first near vacuum wisps of Jovian atmosphere began percolating into the ship several thousand miles above the Jovian surface. It was practically all hydrogen, though perhaps a careful gas analysis might have located a trace of helium as well. The pressure gauges began creeping skyward. \par
\tab That creep continued at an accelerating pace as the ship dropped downward in a Jupiter-circling spiral. The pointers of successive gauges, each designed for progressively higher pressures, began to move until they reached the neighborhood of a million or so atmospheres, where figures lost most of their meaning. The temperature, as recorded by thermocouples, rose slowly and erratically, and finally steadied at about seventy below zero, Centigrade. \par
\tab The ship moved slowly toward the end, plowing its way heavily through a maze of gas molecules that crowded together so closely that hydrogen itself was squeezed to the density of a liquid. Ammonia vapor, drawn from the incredibly vast oceans of that liquid, saturated the horrible atmosphere. The wind, which had begun a thousand miles higher, had risen to a pitch inadequately described as a hurricane. \par
\tab It was quite plain long before the ship landed on a fairly large Jovian island, perhaps seven times the size of Asia, that Jupiter was not a very pleasant world. \par
\tab And yet the three members of the crew thought it was. They were quite convinced it was. But then, the three members of the crew were not exactly human. And neither were they exactly Jovian. \par
\tab They were simply robots, designed on Earth for Jupiter. ZZ Three said, \ldblquote It appears to be a rather desolate place.\rdblquote  ZZ Two joined him and regarded the wind-blasted landscape somberly. \ldblquote There are structures of some sort in the distance,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote which are obviously artificial. I suggest we wait for the inhabitants to come to us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Across the room ZZ One listened, but made no reply. He was the first constructed of the three, and half experimental. Consequently he spoke a little less frequently than his two companions. \par
\tab The wait was not long. An air vessel of queer design swooped overhead. More followed. And then a line of ground vehicles approached, took position, and disgorged organisms. Along with these organisms came various inanimate accessories that might have been weapons. Some of these were borne by a single Jovian, some by several, and some advanced under their own power, with Jovians perhaps inside. \par
\tab The robots couldn\rquote t tell. ZZ Three said, \ldblquote They\rquote re all around us now. The logical peaceful gesture would be to come out in the open. Agreed?\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was, and ZZ One shoved open the heavy door, which was not double or, for that matter, particularly airtight. \par
\tab Their appearance through the door was the signal for an excited stir among the surrounding Jovians. Things were done to several of the very largest of the inanimate accessories, and ZZ Three became aware of a temperature rise on the outer rind of his beryllium-iridium-bronze body. \par
\tab He glanced at ZZ Two. \ldblquote Do you feel it? They\rquote re aiming heat energy at us, I believe.\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ Two indicated his surprise. \ldblquote I wonder why?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Definitely a heat ray of some sort. Look at that!\rdblquote  One of the rays had been jarred out of alignment for some undiscernible cause, and its line of radiation intersected a brook of sparkling pure ammonia-- which promptly boiled furiously. \par
\tab Three turned to ZZ One, \ldblquote Make a note of this, One, will you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure.\rdblquote  It was to ZZ One that the routine secretarial work fell, and his method of taking a note was to make a mental addition to the accurate memory scroll within him. He had already gathered the hour-by-hour record of every important instrument on board ship during the trip to Jupiter. He added agreeably, \ldblquote What reason shall I put for the reaction? The human masters would probably enjoy knowing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No reason. Or better,\rdblquote  Three corrected himself, \ldblquote no apparent reason. You might say the maximum temperature of the ray was about plus thirty, Centigrade.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Two interrupted, \ldblquote Shall we try communicating?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It would be a waste of time,\rdblquote  said Three. \ldblquote There can\rquote t be more than a very few Jovians who know the radio-click code that\rquote s been developed between Jupiter and Ganymede. They\rquote ll have to send for one, and when he comes, he\rquote ll establish contact soon enough. Meanwhile let\rquote s watch them. I don\rquote t understand their actions, I tell you frankly.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Nor did understanding come immediately. Heat radiation ceased, and other instruments were brought to the forefront and put into play. Several capsules fell at the feet of the watching robots, dropping rapidly and forcefully under Jupiter\rquote s gravity. They popped open and a blue liquid exuded, forming pools which proceeded to shrink rapidly by evaporation. \par
\tab The nightmare wind whipped the vapors away and where those vapors went, Jovians scrambled out of the way. One was too slow, threshed about wildly, and became very limp and still. \par
\tab ZZ Two bent, dabbed a finger in one of the pools and stared at the dripping liquid. \ldblquote I think this is oxygen,\rdblquote  he said. \par
\tab\ldblquote Oxygen, all right,\rdblquote  agreed Three. \ldblquote This becomes stranger and stranger. It must certainly be a dangerous practice, for I would say that oxygen is poisonous to the creatures. One of them died!\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was a pause, and then ZZ One, whose greater simplicity led at times to an increased directness of thought, said heavily, \ldblquote It might be that these strange creatures in a rather childish way are attempting to destroy us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab And Two, struck by the suggestion, answered, \ldblquote You know, One, I think you\rquote re right!\rdblquote  \par
\tab There had been a slight lull in Jovian activity and now a new structure was brought up. It possessed a slender rod that pointed skyward through the impenetrable Jovian murk. It stood in that starkly incredible wind with a rigidity that plainly indicated remarkable structural strength. From its tip came a cracking and then a Bash that lit up the depths of the atmosphere into a gray fog. \par
\tab For a moment the robots were bathed in clinging radiance and then Three said thoughtfully, \ldblquote High-tension electricity! Quite respectable power, too. One, I think you\rquote re right. After all, the human masters have told us that these creatures seek to destroy all humanity, and organisms possessing such insane viciousness as to harbor a thought of harm against a human being\rdblquote --his voice trembled at the thought--\rdblquote would scarcely scruple at attempting to destroy us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s a shame to have such distorted minds,\rdblquote  said ZZ One. \ldblquote Poor fellows!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I find it a very saddening thought,\rdblquote  admitted Two. \ldblquote Let\rquote s go back to the ship. We\rquote ve seen enough for now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab They did so, and settled down to wait. As ZZ Three said, Jupiter was a roomy planet, and it might take time for Jovian transportation to bring a radio code expert to the ship. However, patience is a cheap commodity to robots. \par
\tab As a matter of fact, Jupiter turned on its axis three times, according to chronometer, before the expert arrived. The rising and setting of the sun made no difference, of course, to the dead darkness at the bottom of three thousand miles of liquid-dense gas, so that one could not speak of day and night. But then, neither Jovian nor robot saw by visible light radiation and that didn\rquote t matter. \par
\tab Through this thirty-hour interval the surrounding Jovians continued their attack with a patience and persevering relentlessness concerning which robot ZZ One made a good many mental notes. The ship was assaulted by as many varieties of forces as there were hours, and the robots observed every attack attentively, analyzing such weapons as they recognized. They by no means recognized all. \par
\tab But the human masters had built well. It had taken fifteen years to construct the ship and the robots, and their essentials could be expressed in a single phrase-- raw strength. The attack spent itself uselessly and neither ship nor robot seemed the worse for it. \par
\tab Three said, \ldblquote This atmosphere handicaps them, I think. They can\rquote t use atomic disruptors, since they would only tear a hole in that soupy air and blow themselves up.\rdblquote  \par
\tab  \ldblquote They haven\rquote t used high explosives either,\rdblquote  said Two, \ldblquote which is well.  They couldn\rquote t have hurt us, naturally, but it would have thrown us about a bit.\rdblquote\par
\tab  \ldblquote High explosives are out of the question.  You can\rquote t have an explosive without gas expansion and gas just can\rquote t expand in this atmosphere.\rdblquote\par
\tab  \ldblquote It\rquote s a very good atmosphere,\rdblquote  muttered One.  \ldblquote I like it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Which was natural, because he was built for it.  The ZZ robots were the first robots ever turned out by the United States Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation that were not even faintly human in appearance.  They were low and squat, with a center of gravity less than a foot above ground level.  They had six legs apiece, stumpy and thick, designed to lift tons against two and a half times normal Earth gravity.  Their reflexes were that many times Earth-normal speed, to make up for the gravity.  And they were composed of a berylliam-iridium-bronze alloy that was proof against any known corrosive agent, also any known destructive agent short of a thousand-megaton atomic disruptor, under any conditions whatsoever.\par
\tab To dispense with further description, they were indestructible, and so impressively powerful that they were the only robots ever built on whom the roboticists of the corporation had never quite had the nerve to pin a serial-number nickname. One bright young fellow had suggested Sissy One, Two, and Three--but not in a very loud voice, and the suggestion was never repeated.\par
\tab The last hours of the wait were spent in a puzzled discussion to find a possible description of a Jovian\rquote s appearance.  ZZ One had made a note of their possession of tentacles and of their radial symmetry--and there he had struck.  Two and Three did their best, but couldn\rquote t help.\par
\tab  \ldblquote You can\rquote t very well describe anything,\rdblquote  Three declared finally, \ldblquote without a standard of reference.  These creatures are like nothing I know of--completely outside the postitronic paths of my brain.  It\rquote s like trying to describe gamma light to a robot unequipped for gamma-ray reception.\rdblquote\par
\tab It was just at that time that the weapon barrage ceased once more.  The robots turned their attention to outside the ship.\par
\tab A group of Jovians were advancing in curiously uneven fashion, but no amount of careful watching could determine the exact method of their locomotion.  How they used their tentacles was uncertain.  At times the organisms took on a remarkable slithering motion, and then they moved at great speed, perhaps with the wind\rquote s help, for they were moving downwind. \par
\tab The robots stepped out to meet the Jovians, who halted ten feet away. Both sides remained silent and motionless. \par
\tab ZZ Two said, \ldblquote They must be watching us, but I don\rquote t know how. Do either of you see any photosensitive organs?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t say,\rdblquote  grunted Three in response. \ldblquote I don\rquote t see anything about them that makes sense at all.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was a sudden metallic clicking from among the Jovian group and ZZ One said delightedly, \ldblquote It\rquote s the radio code. They\rquote ve got the communications expert here.\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was, and they had. The complicated dot-dash system that over a period of twenty-five years had been laboriously developed by the beings of Jupiter and the Earthmen of Ganymede into a remarkably flexible means of communication was finally being put into practice at close range. \par
\tab One Jovian remained in the forefront now, the others having fallen back. It was he that was speaking. The clicking said, \ldblquote Where are you from?\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ Three, as the most mentally advanced, naturally assumed spokesmanship for the robot group. \ldblquote We are from Jupiter\rquote s satellite, Ganymede.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian continued, \ldblquote What do you want?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Information. We have come to study your world and to bring back our findings. If we could have your cooperation--\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian clicking interrupted. \ldblquote You must be destroyed!\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ Three paused and said in a thoughtful aside to his two companions, \ldblquote Exactly the attitude the human masters said they would take. They are very unusual.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Returning to his clicking, he asked simply, \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian evidently considered certain questions too obnoxious to be answered. He said, \ldblquote If you leave within a single period of revolution, we will spare you-- until such time as we emerge from our world to destroy the un-Jovian vermin of Ganymede.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I would like to point out,\rdblquote  said Three, \ldblquote that we of Ganymede and the inner planets--\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian interrupted, \ldblquote Our astronomy knows of the Sun and of our four satellites. There are no inner planets.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three conceded the point wearily, \ldblquote We of Ganymede, then. We have no designs on Jupiter. We\rquote re prepared to offer friendship. For twenty-five years your people communicated freely with the human beings of Ganymede. Is there any reason to make sudden war upon the humans?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote For twenty-five years,\rdblquote  was the cold response, \ldblquote we assumed the inhabitants of Ganymede to be Jovians. When we found out they were not, and that we had been treating lower animals on the scale of Jovian intelligences, we were bound to take steps to wipe out the dishonor.\rdblquote\par
\tab Slowly and forcefully he finished, \ldblquote We of Jupiter will suffer the existence of no vermin!\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian was backing away in some fashion, tacking against the wind, and the interview was evidently over. \par
\tab The robots retreated inside the ship. \par
\tab ZZ Two said, \ldblquote It looks bad, doesn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  He continued thoughtfully, \ldblquote It is as the human masters said. They possess an ultimately developed superiority complex, combined with an extreme intolerance for anyone or anything that disturbs that complex.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The intolerance,\rdblquote  observed Three, \ldblquote is the natural consequence of the complex. The trouble is that their intolerance has teeth in it. They have weapons-- and their science is great.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I am not surprised now,\rdblquote  burst out ZZ One, \ldblquote that we were specifically instructed to disregard Jovian orders. They are horrible, intolerant, pseudo-superior beings!\rdblquote  He added emphatically, with robotical loyalty and faith, \ldblquote No human master could ever be like that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That, though true, is beside the point,\rdblquote  said Three. \ldblquote The fact remains that the human masters are in terrible danger. This is a gigantic world and these Jovians are greater in numbers and resources by a hundred times or more than the humans of the entire Terrestrial Empire. If they can ever develop the force field to the point where they can use it as a spaceship hull-- as the human masters have already done-- they will overrun the system at will. The question remains as to how far they have advanced in that direction, what other weapons they have, what preparations they are making, and so on. To return with that information is our function, of course, and we had better decide on our next step.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It may be difficult,\rdblquote  said Two. \ldblquote The Jovians won\rquote t help us.\rdblquote  Which, at the moment, was rather an understatement. \par
\tab Three thought awhile. \ldblquote It seems to me that we need only wait,\rdblquote  he observed. \ldblquote They have tried to destroy us for thirty hours now and haven\rquote t succeeded. Certainly they have done their best. Now a superiority complex always involves the eternal necessity of saving face, and the ultimatum given us proves it in this case. They would never allow us to leave if they could destroy us. But if we don\rquote t leave, then rather than admit they cannot force us away, they will surely pretend that they are willing, for their own purposes, to have us stay.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Once again they waited. The day passed. The weapon barrage did not resume. The robots did not leave. The bluff was called. And now the robots faced the Jovian radio-code expert once again. \par
\tab If the ZZ models had been equipped with a sense of humor, they would have enjoyed themselves immensely. As it was, they felt merely a solemn sense of satisfaction. \par
\tab The Jovian said, \ldblquote It has been our decision that you will be allowed to remain for a very short time, so that you see our power for yourself. You shall then return to Ganymede to inform your companion vermin of the disastrous end to which they will unfailingly come within a solar revolution.\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ One made a mental note that a Jovian revolution took twelve earthly years. \par
\tab Three replied casually, \ldblquote Thank you. May we accompany you to the nearest town? There are many things we would like to learn.\rdblquote  He added as an afterthought, \ldblquote Our ship is not to be touched, of course.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He said this as a request, not as a threat, for no ZZ model was ever pugnacious. All capacity for even the slightest annoyance had been carefully barred in their construction. With robots as vastly powerful as the ZZ\rquote s, unfailing good temper was essential for safety during the years of testing on Earth. \par
\tab The Jovian said, \ldblquote We are not interested in your verminous ship. No Jovian will pollute himself by approaching it. You may accompany us, but you must on no account approach closer than ten feet to any Jovian, or you will be instantly destroyed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Stuck up, aren\rquote t they?\rdblquote  observed Two in a genial whisper, as they plowed into the wind. \par
\tab The town was a port on the shores of an incredible ammonia lake. The external wind whipped furious, frothy waves that shot across the liquid surface at the hectic rate enforced by the gravity. The port itself was neither large nor impressive and it seemed fairly evident that most of the construction was underground. \par
\tab\ldblquote What is the population of this place?\rdblquote  asked Three. \par
\tab The Jovian replied, \ldblquote It is a small town of ten million.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I see. Make a note of that, One.\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ One did so mechanically, and then turned once more to the lake, at which he had been staring in fascination. He pulled at Three\rquote s elbow. \ldblquote Say, do you suppose they have fish here?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What difference does it make?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I think we ought to know. The human masters ordered us to find out everything we could.\rdblquote  Of the robots, One was the simplest and, consequently, the one who took orders in the most literal fashion. \par
\tab Two said, \ldblquote Let One go and look if he likes. It won\rquote t do any harm if we let the kid have his fun.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote All right. There\rquote s no real objection if he doesn\rquote t waste his time. Fish aren\rquote t what we came for--but go ahead, One.\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ One made off in great excitement and slogged rapidly down the beach, plunging into the ammonia with a splash. The Jovians watched attentively. They had understood none of the previous conversation, of course. \par
\tab The radio code expert clicked out, \ldblquote It is apparent that your companion has decided to abandon life in despair at our greatness.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three said in surprise, \ldblquote Nothing of the sort. He wants to investigate the living organisms, if any, that live in the ammonia.\rdblquote  He added apologetically, \ldblquote Our friend is very curious at times, and he isn\rquote t quite as bright as we are, though that is only his misfortune. We understand that and try to humor him whenever we can.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was a long pause, and the Jovian observed, \ldblquote He will drown.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three replied casually, \ldblquote No danger of that. We don\rquote t drown. May we enter the town as soon as he returns?\rdblquote  \par
\tab At that moment there was a spurt of liquid several hundred feet out in the lake. It sprayed upward wildly and then hurtled down in a wind-driven mist. Another spurt and another, then a wild white foaming that formed a trail toward shore, gradually quieting as it approached. \par
\tab The two robots watched this in amazement, and the utter lack of motion on the part of the Jovians indicated that they were watching as well. \par
\tab Then the head of ZZ One broke the surface and he made his slow way out on to dry land. But something followed him! Some organism of gigantic size that seemed nothing but fangs, claws, and spines. Then they saw that it wasn\rquote t following him under its own power, but was being dragged across the beach by ZZ One. There was a significant flabbiness about it. \par
\tab ZZ One approached rather timidly and took communication into his own hands. He tapped out a message to the Jovian in agitated fashion. \ldblquote I am very sorry this happened, but the thing attacked me. I was merely taking notes on it. It is not a valuable creature, I hope.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He was not answered immediately, for at the first appearance of the monster there had been a wild break in the Jovian ranks. These reformed slowly, and cautious observation having proven the creator to be indeed dead, order was restored. Some of the bolder were curiously prodding the body. \par
\tab ZZ Three said humbly, \ldblquote I hope you will pardon our friend. He is sometimes clumsy. We have absolutely no intention of harming any Jovian creature.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He attacked me,\rdblquote  explained One. \ldblquote He bit at me without provocation. See!\rdblquote  And he displayed a two-foot fang that ended in a jagged break. \ldblquote He broke it on my shoulder and almost left a scratch. I just slapped it a bit to send it away-- and it died. I\rquote m sorry!\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian finally spoke, and his code clicking was a rather stuttery affair. \ldblquote It is a wild creature, rarely found so close to shore, but the lake is deep just here.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three said, still anxiously, \ldblquote If you can use it for food, we are only too glad--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No. We can get food for ourselves without the help of verm--without the help of others. Eat it yourselves.\rdblquote  \par
\tab At that ZZ One heaved the creature up and back into the sea, with an easy motion of one arm. Three said casually, \ldblquote Thank you for your kind offer, but we have no use for food. We don\rquote t eat, of course.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Escorted by two hundred or so armed Jovians, the robots passed down a series of ramps into the underground city. If, above the surface, the city had looked small and unimpressive, then from beneath it took on the appearance of a vast megalopolis. \par
\tab They were ushered into ground cars that were operated by remote control--for no honest, self-respecting Jovian would risk his superiority by placing himself in the same car with vermin--and driven at frightful speed to the center of the town. They saw enough to decide that it extended fifty miles from end to end and reached downward into Jupiter\rquote s crust at least eight miles. \par
\tab ZZ Two did not sound happy as he said, \ldblquote If this is a sample of Jovian development then we shall not have a hopeful report to bring back to the human masters. After all, we landed on the vast surface of Jupiter at random, with the chances a thousand to one against coming near any really concentrated center of population. This must be, as the code expert says, a mere town.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Ten million Jovians,\rdblquote  said Three abstractedly. \ldblquote Total population must be in the trillions, which is high, very high, even for Jupiter. They probably have a completely urban civilization, which means that their scientific development must be tremendous. If they have force fields--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three had no neck, for in the interest of strength the heads of the ZZ models were riveted firmly onto the torso, with the delicate positronic brains protected by three separate layers in inch-thick iridium alloy. But if he had had one, he would have shaken his head dolefully. \par
\tab They had stopped now in a cleared space. Everywhere about them they could see avenues and structures crowded with Jovians, as curious as any terrestrial crowd would have been in similar circumstances. \par
\tab The code expert approached. \ldblquote It is time now for me to retire until the next period of activity. We have gone so far as to arrange quarters for you at great inconvenience to ourselves for, of course, the structure will have to be pulled down and rebuilt afterward. Nevertheless, you will be allowed to sleep for a space.\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ Three waved an arm in deprecation and tapped out, \ldblquote We thank you but you must not trouble yourself. We don\rquote t mind remaining right here. If you want to sleep and rest, by all means do. We\rquote ll wait for you. As for us,\rdblquote  casually, \ldblquote we don\rquote t sleep.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian said nothing, though if it had had a face, the expression upon it might have been interesting. It left, and the robots remained in the car, with squads of well-armed Jovians, frequently replaced, surrounding them as guards. \par
\tab It was hours before the ranks of those guards parted to allow the code expert to return. Along with him were other Jovians, whom he introduced. \par
\tab\ldblquote There are with me two officials of the central government who have graciously consented to speak with you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab One of the officials evidently knew the code, for his clicking interrupted the code expert sharply. He addressed the robots, \ldblquote Vermin! Emerge from the ground car that we may look at you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The robots were only too willing to comply, so while Three and Two vaulted over the right side of the car, ZZ One dashed through the left side. The word through is used advisedly, for since he neglected to work the mechanism that lowered a section of side so that one might exit, he carried that side, plus two wheels and an axle, along with him. The car collapsed, and ZZ One stood staring at the ruins in embarrassed silence. \par
\tab At last he clicked out gently, \ldblquote I\rquote m very sorry. I hope it wasn\rquote t an expensive car.\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ Two added apologetically, \ldblquote Our companion is often clumsy. You must excuse him,\rdblquote  and ZZ Three made a halfhearted attempt to put the car back together again. \par
\tab ZZ One made another effort to excuse himself. \ldblquote The material of the car was rather flimsy. You see?\rdblquote  He lifted a square-yard sheet of three-inch-thick, metal-hard plastic in both hands and exerted a bit of pressure. The sheet promptly snapped in two. \ldblquote I should have made allowances,\rdblquote  he admitted. \par
\tab The Jovian government official said in slightly less sharp fashion, \ldblquote The car would have had to be destroyed anyway, after being polluted by your presence.\rdblquote  He paused, then, \ldblquote Creatures! We Jovians lack vulgar curiosity concerning lower animals, but our scientists seek facts.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re right with you,\rdblquote  replied Three cheerfully. \ldblquote So do we.\rdblquote  The Jovian ignored him. \ldblquote You lack the mass-sensitive organ, apparently. How is it that you are aware of distant objects?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three grew interested. \ldblquote Do you mean your people are directly sensitive to mass?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I am not here to answer your questions-- your impudent questions-- about us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I take it then that objects of low specific mass would be transparent to you, even in the absence of radiation.\rdblquote  He turned to Two, \ldblquote That\rquote s how they see. Their atmosphere is as transparent as space to them.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian clicking began once more, \ldblquote You will answer my first question immediately, or my patience will end and I will order you destroyed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three said at once, \ldblquote We are energy-sensitive, Jovian. We can adjust ourselves to the entire electromagnetic scale at will. At present, our long-distance sight is due to radio-wave radiation that we emit ourselves, and at close range we see by--\rdblquote  He paused, and said to Two, \ldblquote There isn\rquote t any code word for gamma ray, is there?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not that I know of,\rdblquote  Two answered. \par
\tab Three continued to the Jovian, \ldblquote At close range we see by other radiation for which there is no code word.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Of what is your body composed?\rdblquote  demanded the Jovian. \par
\tab Two whispered, \ldblquote He probably asks that because his mass sensitivity can\rquote t penetrate past our skin. High density, you know. Ought we to tell him?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three replied uncertainly, \ldblquote Our human masters didn\rquote t particularly say we were to keep anything secret.\rdblquote  In radio code, to the Jovian he said, \ldblquote We are mostly iridium. For the rest, copper, tin, a little beryllium, and a scattering of other substances.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovians fell back and by the obscure writhing of various portions of their thoroughly indescribable bodies gave the impression that they were in animated conversation, although they made no sound. \par
\tab And then the official returned. \ldblquote Beings of Ganymede! It has been decided to show you through some of our factories that we may exhibit a tiny part of our great achievements. We will then allow you to return so that you may spread despair among the other verm--the other beings of the outer world.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three said to Two, \ldblquote Note the effect of their psychology. They must hammer home their superiority. It\rquote s still a matter of saving face.\rdblquote  And in radio code, \ldblquote We thank you for the opportunity.\rdblquote  \par
\tab But the face saving was efficient, as the robots realized soon enough. The demonstration became a tour, and the tour a Grand Exhibition. The Jovians displayed everything, explained everything, answered all questions eagerly, and ZZ One made hundreds of despairing notes. \par
\tab The war potential of that single so-called unimportant town was greater by several times than that of all Ganymede. Ten more such towns would outproduce all the Terrestrial Empire. Yet ten more such towns would not be the fingernail fragment of the strength all Jupiter must be able to exert. \par
\tab Three turned as One nudged him. \ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ One said seriously, \ldblquote 1f they have force fields, the human masters are lost, aren\rquote t they?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid so. Why do you ask?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Because the Jovians aren\rquote t showing us through the right wing of this factory. It might be that force fields are being developed there. They would be wanting to keep it secret if they were. We\rquote d better find out. It\rquote s the main point, you know.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three regarded One somberly. \ldblquote Perhaps you\rquote re right. It\rquote s no use ignoring anything.\rdblquote  \par
\tab They were in a huge steel mill now, watching hundred-foot beams of ammonia-resistant silicon-steel alloy being turned out twenty to the second. Three asked quietly, \ldblquote What does that wing contain?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The government official inquired of those in charge of the factory and explained, \ldblquote That is the section of great heat. Various processes require huge temperatures which life cannot bear, and they must all be handled indirectly.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He led the way to a partition from which heat could be felt to radiate and indicated a small round area of transparent material. It was one of a row of such, through which the foggy red light of lines of glowing forges could be made out through the soupy atmosphere. \par
\tab ZZ One fastened a look of suspicion on the Jovian and clicked out, \ldblquote Would it be all right if I went in and looked around? I am very interested in this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three said, \ldblquote You\rquote re being childish, One. They\rquote re telling the truth. Oh well, nose around if you must. But don\rquote t take too long; we\rquote ve got to move on.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian said, \ldblquote You have no understanding of the heat involved. You will die.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh no,\rdblquote  explained One casually. \ldblquote Heat doesn\rquote t bother us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was a Jovian conference, and then a scene of scurrying confusion as the life of the factory was geared to this unusual emergency. Screens of heat-absorbent material were set up, and then a door dropped open, a door that had never before budged while the forges were working. ZZ One entered and the door closed behind him. Jovian officials crowded to the transparent areas to watch. \par
\tab ZZ One walked to the nearest forge and tapped the outside. Since he was too short to see into it comfortably, he tipped the forge until the molten metal licked at the lip of the container. He peered at it curiously, then dipped his hand in and stirred it awhile to test the consistency. Having done this, he withdrew his hand, shook off some of the fiery metallic droplets and wiped the rest on one of his six thighs. Slowly he went down the line of forges, then signified his desire to leave. \par
\tab The Jovians retired to a great distance when he came out of the door and played a stream of ammonia on him, which hissed, bubbled and steamed until he was brought to bearable temperature once more. \par
\tab ZZ One ignored the ammonia shower and said, \ldblquote They were telling the truth. No force fields.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three began, \ldblquote You see--\rdblquote  but One interrupted impatiently, \ldblquote But there\rquote s no use delaying. The human masters instructed us to find out everything and that\rquote s that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He turned to the Jovian and clicked out, without the slightest hesitation, \ldblquote Listen, has Jovian science developed force fields?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bluntness was, of course, one of the natural consequences of One\rquote s less well developed mental powers. Two and Three knew that, so they refrained from expressing disapproval of the remark. \par
\tab The Jovian official relaxed slowly from his strangely stiffened attitude, which had somehow given the impression that he had been staring stupidly at One\rquote s hand--the one he had dipped into the molten metal. The Jovian said slowly, \ldblquote Force fields? That, then, is your main object of curiosity?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said One with emphasis. \par
\tab There was a sudden and patent gain in confidence on the Jovian\rquote s part, for the clicking grew sharper. \ldblquote Then come, vermin!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Whereupon Three said to Two, \ldblquote We\rquote re vermin again, I see, which sounds as if there\rquote s bad news ahead.\rdblquote  And Two gloomily agreed. \par
\tab It was to the very edge of the city that they were now led-- to the portion which on Earth would have been termed the suburbs-- and into one of a series of closely integrated structures, which might have corresponded vaguely to a terrestrial university. \par
\tab There were no explanations, however, and none was asked for. The Jovian official led the way rapidly, and the robots followed with the grim conviction that the worst was just about to happen. \par
\tab It was ZZ One who stopped before an opened wall section after the rest had passed on. \ldblquote What\rquote s this?\rdblquote  he wanted to know. \par
\tab The room was equipped with narrow, low benches, along which Jovians manipulated rows of strange devices, of which strong, inch-long electromagnets formed the principal feature. \par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s this?\rdblquote  asked One again. \par
\tab The Jovian turned back and exhibited impatience. \ldblquote This is a students\rquote  biological laboratory. There\rquote s nothing there to interest you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But what are they doing?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote They are studying microscopic life. Haven\rquote t you ever seen a microscope before?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three interrupted in explanation, \ldblquote He has, but not that type. Our microscopes are meant for energy-sensitive organs and work by refraction of radiant energy. Your microscopes evidently work on a mass-expansion basis. Rather ingenious.\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ One said, \ldblquote Would it be all right if I inspected some of your specimens?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Of what use will that be? You cannot use our microscopes because of your sensory limitations and it will simply force us to discard such specimens as you approach for no decent reason.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But I don\rquote t need a microscope,\rdblquote  explained One, with surprise. \ldblquote I can easily adjust myself for microscopic vision.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He strode to the nearest bench, while the students in the room crowded to the corner in an attempt to avoid contamination. ZZ One shoved a microscope aside and inspected the slide carefully. He backed away, puzzled, then tried another...a third...a fourth. \par
\tab He came back and addressed the Jovian. \ldblquote Those are supposed to be alive, aren\rquote t they? I mean those little worm things.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Jovian said, \ldblquote Certainly.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s strange-- when I look at them, they die!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three exclaimed sharply and said to his two companions, \ldblquote We\rquote ve forgotten our gamma-ray radiation. Let\rquote s get out of here, One, or we\rquote ll kill every bit of microscopic life in the room.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He turned to the Jovian, \ldblquote I\rquote m afraid that our presence is fatal to weaker forms of life. We had better leave. We hope the specimens are not too difficult to replace. And, while we\rquote re about it, you had better not stay too near us, or our radiation may affect you adversely. You feel all right so far, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote  he asked. \par
\tab The Jovian led the way onward in proud silence, but it was to be noticed that thereafter he doubled the distance he had hitherto kept between himself and them. \par
\tab Nothing more was said until the robots found themselves in a vast room. In the very center of it huge ingots of metal rested unsupported in mid-air--or, rather, supported by nothing visible--against mighty Jovian gravity. \par
\tab The Jovian clicked, \ldblquote There is your force field in ultimate form, as recently perfected. Within that bubble is a vacuum, so that it is supporting the full weight of our atmosphere plus an amount of metal equivalent to two large spaceships. What do you say to that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That space travel now becomes a possibility for you,\rdblquote  said Three. \ldblquote Definitely. No metal or plastic has the strength to hold our atmosphere against a vacuum, but a force field can-- and a force-field bubble will be our spaceship. Within the year we will be turning them out by the hundreds of thousands. Then we will swarm down upon Ganymede to destroy the verminous so-called intelligences that attempt to dispute our dominion of the universe.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The human beings of Ganymede have never attempted--\rdblquote  began Three, in mild expostulation. \par
\tab\ldblquote Silence!\rdblquote  snapped the Jovian. \ldblquote Return now and tell them what you\rquote ve seen. Their own feeble force fields-- such as the one your ship is equipped with-- will not stand against us, for our smallest ship will be a hundred times the size and power of yours.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Three said, \ldblquote Then there\rquote s nothing more to do and we will return, as you say, with the information. If you could lead us back to our ship, we\rquote ll say good-by. But by the way, just as a matter for the record, there\rquote s something you don\rquote t understand. The humans of Ganymede have force fields, of course, but our particular ship isn\rquote t equipped with one. We don\rquote t need any.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The robot turned away and motioned his companions to follow. For a moment they did not speak, then ZZ One muttered dejectedly, \ldblquote Can\rquote t we try to destroy this place?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It won\rquote t help,\rdblquote  said Three. \ldblquote They\rquote d get us by weight of numbers. It\rquote s no use. In an earthly decade the human masters will be finished. It is impossible to stand against Jupiter. There\rquote s just too much of it. As long as Jovians were tied to the surface, the humans were safe. But now that they have force fields. All we can do is to bring the news. By the preparation of hiding places, some few may survive for a short while.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The city was behind them. They were out on the open plain by the lake, with their ship a dark spot on the horizon, when the Jovian spoke suddenly: \par
\tab\ldblquote Creatures, you say you have no force field?\rdblquote  Three replied without interest, \ldblquote We don\rquote t need one.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How then does your ship stand the vacuum of space without exploding because of the atmospheric pressure within?\rdblquote  And he moved a tentacle as if in mute gesture at the Jovian atmosphere that was weighing down upon them with a force of twenty million pounds to the square inch. \par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  explained Three, \ldblquote that\rquote s simple. Our ship isn\rquote t airtight. Pressures equalize within and without.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Even in space? A vacuum in your ship? You lie!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re welcome to inspect our ship. It has no force field and it isn\rquote t airtight. What\rquote s marvelous about that? We don\rquote t breathe. Our energy is obtained through direct atomic power. The presence or absence of air pressure makes little difference to us and we\rquote re quite at home in a vacuum.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But absolute zero!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter. We regulate our own heat. We\rquote re not interested in outside temperatures.\rdblquote  He paused. \ldblquote Well, we can make our own way back to the ship. Good-by. We\rquote ll give the humans of Ganymede your message-- war to the end!\rdblquote  \par
\tab But the Jovian said, \ldblquote Wait! I\rquote ll be back.\rdblquote  He turned and went toward the city. \par
\tab The robots stared, and then waited in silence. It was three hours before he returned and when he did, it was in breathless haste. He stopped within the usual ten feet of the robots, but then began inching his way forward in a curious groveling fashion. He did not speak until his rubbery gray skin was almost touching them, and then the radio code sounded, subdued and respectful. \par
\tab\ldblquote Honored sirs, I have been in communication with the head of our central government, who is now aware of all the facts, and I can assure you that Jupiter desires only peace,\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I beg your pardon?\rdblquote  asked Three blankly. The Jovian drove on hastily. \ldblquote We are ready to resume communication with Ganymede and will gladly promise to make no attempt to venture into space. Our force field will be used only on the Jovian surface.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But--\rdblquote  Three began. \ldblquote Our government will be glad to receive any other representatives our honorable human brothers of Ganymede would care to send. If your honors will now condescend to swear peace--\rdblquote  a scaly tentacle swung out toward them and Three, quite dazed, grasped it. Two and One did likewise as two more were extended to them. \par
\tab The Jovian said solemnly: \ldblquote There is then eternal peace between Jupiter and Ganymede.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The spaceship which leaked like a sieve was out in space again. The pressure and temperature were once more at zero, and the robots watched the huge but steadily shrinking globe that was Jupiter. \par
\tab\ldblquote They\rquote re definitely sincere,\rdblquote  said ZZ Two, \ldblquote and it\rquote s very gratifying, this complete about-face, but I don\rquote t get it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It is my idea,\rdblquote  observed ZZ One, \ldblquote that the Jovians came to their senses just in time and realized the incredible evil involved in the thought of harm to a human master. That would be only natural.\rdblquote  \par
\tab ZZ Three sighed and said, \ldblquote Look, it\rquote s all a matter of psychology. Those Jovians had a superiority complex a mile thick and when they couldn\rquote t destroy us, they were bound to save face. All their exhibitions, all their explanations, were simply a form of braggadocio, designed to impress us into the proper state of humiliation before their power and superiority.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I see all that,\rdblquote  interrupted Two, \ldblquote but--\rdblquote  Three went on, \ldblquote But it worked the wrong way. All they did was to prove to themselves that we were stronger, that we didn\rquote t drown, that we didn\rquote t eat or sleep, that molten metal didn\rquote t hurt us. Even our very presence was fatal to Jovian life. Their last trump was the force field. And when they found out that \i we \i0 didn\rquote t need them at all, and could live in a vacuum at absolute zero, they broke.\rdblquote  He paused and added philosophically, \ldblquote When a superiority complex like that breaks, it breaks all the way.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The other two considered that, and then Two said, \ldblquote But it still doesn\rquote t make sense. Why should they care what we can or can\rquote t do? We\rquote re only robots. We\rquote re not the ones they have to fight.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And that\rquote s the whole point, Two,\rdblquote  said Three softly. \ldblquote It\rquote s only after we left Jupiter that I thought of it. Do you know that through an oversight, quite unintentionally, we neglected to tell them we were only robots.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote They never asked us,\rdblquote  said One. \ldblquote Exactly. So they thought we were human beings and that all the other human beings were like us!\rdblquote  \par
\tab He looked once more at Jupiter, thoughtfully. \ldblquote No wonder they decided to quit!\rdblquote  \par
