\cf2\tab The surgeon looked up without expression. \ldblquote Is he ready?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Ready is a relative term,\rdblquote  said the med-eng. \i\ldblquote We\rquote re \i0 ready. He\rquote s restless.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote They always are. . . . Well, it\rquote s a serious operation.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Serious or not, he should be thankful. He\rquote s been chosen for it over an enormous number of possibles and frankly, I don\rquote t think . . .\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Don\rquote t say it,\rdblquote  said the surgeon. \ldblquote The decision is not ours to make.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote We accept it. But do we have to agree?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said the surgeon, crisply. \ldblquote We agree. Completely and wholeheart\-edly. The operation is entirely too intricate to approach with mental reserva\-tions. This man has proven his worth in a number of ways and his profile is suitable for the Board of Mortality.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  said the med-eng, unmollified.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The surgeon said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll see him right in here, I think. It is small enough and personal enough to be comforting.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote It won\rquote t help. He\rquote s nervous, and he\rquote s made up his mind.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Has he indeed?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Yes. He wants metal; they always do.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The surgeon\rquote s face did not change expression. He stared at his hands. \ldblquote Sometimes one can talk them out of it.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Why bother?\rdblquote  said the med-eng, indifferently. \ldblquote If he wants metal, let it be metal.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote You don\rquote t care?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Why should I?\rdblquote  The med-eng said it almost brutally. \ldblquote Either way it\rquote s a\cf0  \cf2 medical engineering problem and I\rquote m a medical engineer. Either way, I can handle it. Why should I go beyond that?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The surgeon said stolidly, \ldblquote To me, it is a matter of the fitness of things.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Fitness! You can\rquote t use that as an argument. What does the patient care about the fitness of things?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote I care.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote You care in a minority. The trend is against you. You have no chance.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote I have to try.\rdblquote  The surgeon waved the med-eng into silence with a quick wave of his hand--no impatience to it, merely quickness. He had already informed the nurse and he had already been signaled concerning her ap\-proach. He pressed a small button and the double-door pulled swiftly apart. The patient moved inward in his motorchair, the nurse stepping briskly along beside him.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote You may go, nurse,\rdblquote  said the surgeon, \ldblquote but wait outside. I will be calling you.\rdblquote  He nodded to the med-eng, who left with the nurse, and the door closed behind them.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The man in the chair looked over his shoulder and watched them go. His neck was scrawny and there were fine wrinkles about his eyes. He was freshly shaven and the fingers of his hands, as they gripped the arms of the chair tightly, showed manicured nails. He was a high-priority patient and he was being taken care of. ... But there was a look of settled peevishness on his face.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 He said, \ldblquote Will we be starting today?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The surgeon nodded. \ldblquote This afternoon, Senator.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote I understand it will take weeks.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Not for the operation itself, Senator. But there are a number of subsid\-iary points to be taken care of. There are some circulatory renovations that must be carried through, and hormonal adjustments. These are tricky things.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Are they dangerous?\rdblquote  Then, as though feeling the need for establishing a friendly relationship, but patently against his will, he added, \ldblquote . . . doc\-tor?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The surgeon paid no attention to the nuances of expression. He said, flatly, \ldblquote Everything is dangerous. We take our time in order that it be less dangerous. It is the time required, the skill of many individuals united, the equipment, that makes such operations available to so few...\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote I know that,\rdblquote  said the patient, restlessly. \ldblquote I refuse to feel guilty about that. Or are you implying improper pressure?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Not at all, Senator. The decisions of the Board have never been ques\-tioned. I mention the difficulty and intricacy of the operation merely to explain my desire to have it conducted in the best fashion possible.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Well, do so, then. That is my desire, also.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Then I must ask you to make a decision. It is possible to supply you with either of two types of cyber-hearts, metal or . . .\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Plastic!\rdblquote  said the patient, irritably. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t that the alternative you were going to offer, doctor? Cheap plastic. I don\rquote t want that. I\rquote ve made my choice. I want the metal.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote But . . .\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote See here. I\rquote ve been told the choice rests with me. Isn\rquote t that so?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The surgeon nodded. \ldblquote Where two alternate procedures are of equal value from a medical standpoint, the choice rests with the patient. In actual practice, the choice rests with the patient even when the alternate proce\-dures are \i not \i0 of equal value, as in this case.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The patient\rquote s eyes narrowed. \ldblquote Are you trying to tell me the plastic heart is superior?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote It depends on the patient. In my opinion, in your individual case, it is. And we prefer not to use the term, plastic. It is a fibrous cyber-heart.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote It\rquote s plastic as far as I am concerned.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Senator,\rdblquote  said the surgeon, infinitely patient, \ldblquote the material is not plastic in the ordinary sense of the word. It is a polymeric material true, but one that is far more complex than ordinary plastic. It is a complex protein-like fibre designed to imitate, as closely as possible, the natural structure of the human heart you now have within your chest.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Exactly, and the human heart I now have within my chest is worn out although I am not yet sixty years old. I don\rquote t want another one like it, thank you. I want something better.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote We all want something better for you, Senator. The fibrous cyber-heart will be better. It has a potential life of centuries. It is absolutely non-allergenic ...\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Isn\rquote t that so for the metallic heart, too?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Yes, it is,\rdblquote  said the surgeon. \ldblquote The metallic cyber is of titanium alloy that . . .\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote And it doesn\rquote t wear out? And it is stronger than plastic? Or fibre or whatever you want to call it?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote The metal is physically stronger, yes, but mechanical strength is not a point at issue. Its mechanical strength does you no particular good since the heart is well protected. Anything capable of reaching the heart will kill you for other reasons even if the heart stands up under manhandling.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The patient shrugged. \ldblquote If I ever break a rib, I\rquote ll have that replaced by titanium, also. Replacing bones is easy. Anyone can have that done anytime. I\rquote ll be as metallic as I want to be, doctor.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote That is your right, if you so choose. However, it is only fair to tell you that although no metallic cyber-heart has ever broken down mechanically, a number have broken down electronically.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote What does that mean?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote It means that every cyber-heart contains a pacemaker as part of its structure. In the case of the metallic variety, this is an electronic device that keeps the cyber in rhythm. It means an entire battery of miniaturized equipment must be included to alter the heart\rquote s rhythm to suit an individual\rquote s emotional and physical state. Occasionally something goes wrong there and people have died before that wrong could be corrected.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote I never heard of such a thing.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote I assure you it happens.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Are you telling me it happens often?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Not at all. It happens very rarely.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Well, then, I\rquote ll take my chance. What about the plastic heart? Doesn\rquote t that contain a pacemaker?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Of course it does, Senator. But the chemical structure of a fibrous cyber-heart is quite close to that of human tissue. It can respond to the ionic and hormonal controls of the body itself. The total complex that need be in\-serted is far simpler than in the case of the metal cyber.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote But doesn\rquote t the plastic heart ever pop out of hormonal control?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote None has ever yet done so.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Because you haven\rquote t been working with them long enough. Isn\rquote t that so?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The surgeon hesitated. \ldblquote It is true that the fibrous cybers have not been used nearly as long as the metallic.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote There you are. What is it anyway, doctor? Are you afraid I\rquote m making myself into a robot . . . into a Metallo, as they call them since citizenship went through?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote There is nothing wrong with a Metallo as a Metallo. As you say, they are citizens. But you\rquote re \i not \i0 a Metallo. You\rquote re a human being. Why not stay a human being?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Because I want the best and that\rquote s a metallic heart. You see to that.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The surgeon nodded. \ldblquote Very well. You will be asked to sign the necessary permissions and you will then be fitted with a metal heart.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote And you\rquote ll be the surgeon in charge? They tell me you\rquote re the best.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote I will do what I can to make the changeover an easy one.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The door opened and the chair moved the patient out to the waiting nurse.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The med-eng came in, looking over his shoulder at the receding patient until the doors had closed again.\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 He turned to the surgeon. \ldblquote Well, I can\rquote t tell what happened just by looking at you. What was his decision?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 The surgeon bent over his desk, punching out the final items for his records. \ldblquote What you predicted. He insists on the metallic cyber-heart.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote After all, they are better.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not significantly. They\rquote ve been around longer; no more than that. It\rquote s this mania that\rquote s been plaguing humanity ever since Metallos have become citizens. Men have this odd desire to make Metallos out of themselves. They yearn for the physical strength and endurance one associates with them.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote It isn\rquote t one-sided, doc. You don\rquote t work with Metallos but I do; so I know. The last two who came in for repairs have asked for fibrous elements.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Did they get them?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote In one case, it was just a matter of supplying tendons; it didn\rquote t make much difference there, metal or fibre. The other wanted a blood system or its equivalent. I told him I couldn\rquote t; not without a complete rebuilding of the structure of his body in fibrous material. ... I suppose it will come to that some day. Metallos that aren\rquote t really Metallos at all, but a kind of flesh and blood.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote You don\rquote t mind that thought?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Why not? And metallized human beings, too. We have two varieties of intelligence on Earth now and why bother with two. Let them approach each other and eventually we won\rquote t be able to tell the difference. Why should we want to? We\rquote d have the best of both worlds; the advantages of man combined with those of robot.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote You\rquote d get a hybrid,\rdblquote  said the surgeon, with something that approached fierceness. \ldblquote You\rquote d get something that is not both, but neither. Isn\rquote t it logical to suppose an individual would be too proud of his structure and identity to want to dilute it with something alien? Would he \i want \i0 mongrelization?\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote That\rquote s segregationist talk.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2\ldblquote Then let it be that.\rdblquote  The surgeon said with calm emphasis, \ldblquote I believe in being what one is. I wouldn\rquote t change a bit of my own structure for any reason. If some of it absolutely required replacement, I would have that replacement as close to the original in nature as could possibly be managed. I am \i myself; \i0 well pleased to be myself; and would not be anything else.\rdblquote\cf0\par
\tab\cf2 He had finished now and had to prepare for the operation. He placed his strong hands into the heating oven and let them reach the dull red-hot glow that would sterilize them completely. For all his impassioned words, his voice had never risen, and on his burnished metal face there was (as always) no sign of expression.\cf0\par
