\ldblquote\scaps Ninety-eight - ninety-nine - one hundred\scaps0 .\rdblquote  Gloria withdrew her chubby little forearm from before her eyes and stood for a moment, wrinkling her nose and blinking in the sunlight. Then, trying to watch in all directions at once, she withdrew a few cautious steps from the tree against which she had been leaning.\par
\tab She craned her neck to investigate the possibilities of a clump of bushes to the right and then withdrew farther to obtain a better angle for viewing its dark recesses. The quiet was profound except for the incessant buzzing of insects and the occasional chirrup of some hardy bird, braving the midday sun.\par
\tab Gloria pouted, \ldblquote I bet he went inside the house, and I\rquote ve told him a million times that that\rquote s not fair.\rdblquote\par
\tab With tiny lips pressed together tightly and a severe frown crinkling her forehead, she moved determinedly toward the two-story building up past the driveway.\par
\tab Too late she heard the rustling sound behind her, followed by the distinctive and rhythmic clump-clump of Robbie\rquote s metal feet. She whirled about to see her triumphing companion emerge from hiding and make for the home-tree at full speed.\par
\tab Gloria shrieked in dismay. \ldblquote Wait, Robbie! That wasn\rquote t fair, Robbie! You promised you wouldn\rquote t run until I found you.\rdblquote  Her little feet could make no headway at all against Robbie\rquote s giant strides. Then, within ten feet of the goal, Robbie\rquote s pace slowed suddenly to the merest of crawls, and Gloria, with one final burst of wild speed, dashed pantingly past him to touch the welcome bark of home-tree first.\par
\tab Gleefully, she turned on the faithful Robbie, and with the basest of ingratitude, rewarded him for his sacrifice by taunting him cruelly for a lack of running ability.\par
\tab\ldblquote Robbie can\rquote t run,\rdblquote  she shouted at the top of her eight-year-old voice. \ldblquote I can beat him any day. I can beat him any day.\rdblquote  She chanted the words in a shrill rhythm.\par
\tab Robbie didn\rquote t answer, of course -- not in words. He pantomimed running instead, inching away until Gloria found herself running after him as he dodged her narrowly, forcing her to veer in helpless circles, little arms outstretched and fanning at the air.\par
\tab\ldblquote Robbie,\rdblquote  she squealed, \ldblquote stand still!\rdblquote  -- And the laughter was forced out of her in breathless jerks.\par
\tab Until he turned suddenly and caught her up, whirling her round, so that for her the world fell away for a moment with a blue emptiness beneath, and green trees stretching hungrily downward toward the void. Then she was down in the grass again, leaning against Robbie\rquote s leg and still holding a hard, metal finger.\par
\tab After a while, her breath returned. She pushed uselessly at her disheveled hair in vague imitation of one of her mother\rquote s gestures and twisted to see if her dress were torn.\par
\tab She slapped her hand against Robbie\rquote s torso, \ldblquote Bad boy! I\rquote ll spank you!\rdblquote\par
\tab And Robbie cowered, holding his hands over his face so that she had to add, \ldblquote No, I won\rquote t, Robbie. I won\rquote t spank you. But anyway, it\rquote s my turn to hide now because you\rquote ve got longer legs and you promised not to run till I found you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Robbie nodded his head -- a small parallelepiped with rounded edges and corners attached to a similar but much larger parallelepiped that served as torso by means of a short, flexible stalk -- and obediently faced the tree. A thin, metal film descended over his glowing eyes and from within his body came a steady, resonant ticking.\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t peek now -- and don\rquote t skip any numbers,\rdblquote  warned Gloria, and scurried for cover.\par
\tab With unvarying regularity, seconds were ticked off, and at the hundredth, up went the eyelids, and the glowing red of Robbie\rquote s eyes swept the prospect. They rested for a moment on a bit of colorful gingham that protruded from behind a boulder. He advanced a few steps and convinced himself that it was Gloria who squatted behind it.\par
\tab Slowly, remaining always between Gloria and home-tree, he advanced on the hiding place, and when Gloria was plainly in sight and could no longer even theorize to herself that she was not seen, he extended one arm toward her, slapping the other against his leg so that it rang again. Gloria emerged sulkily.\par
\tab\ldblquote You peeked!\rdblquote  she exclaimed, with gross unfairness. \ldblquote Besides I\rquote m tired of playing hide-and-seek. I want a ride.\rdblquote\par
\tab But Robbie was hurt at the unjust accusation, so he seated himself carefully and shook his head ponderously from side to side.\par
\tab Gloria changed her tone to one of gentle coaxing immediately, \ldblquote Come on, Robbie. I didn\rquote t mean it about the peeking. Give me a ride.\rdblquote\par
\tab Robbie was not to be won over so easily, though. He gazed stubbornly at the sky, and shook his head even more emphatically.\par
\tab\ldblquote Please, Robbie, please give me a ride.\rdblquote  She encircled his neck with rosy arms and hugged tightly. Then, changing moods in a moment, she moved away. \ldblquote If you don\rquote t, I\rquote m going to cry,\rdblquote  and her face twisted appallingly in preparation.\par
\tab Hard-hearted Robbie paid scant attention to this dreadful possibility, and shook his head a third time. Gloria found it necessary to play her trump card.\par
\tab\ldblquote If you don\rquote t,\rdblquote  she exclaimed warmly, \ldblquote I won\rquote t tell you any more stories, that\rquote s all. Not one-\rdblquote\par
\tab Robbie gave in immediately and unconditionally before this ultimatum, nodding his head vigorously until the metal of his neck hummed. Carefully, he raised the little girl and placed her on his broad, flat shoulders.\par
\tab Gloria\rquote s threatened tears vanished immediately and she crowed with delight. Robbie\rquote s metal skin, kept at a constant temperature of seventy by the high resistance coils within, felt nice and comfortable, while the beautifully loud sound her heels made as they bumped rhythmically against his chest was enchanting.\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re an air-coaster, Robbie, you\rquote re a big, silver aircoaster. Hold out your arms straight. -- You got to, Robbie, if you\rquote re going to be an aircoaster.\rdblquote\par
\tab The logic was irrefutable. Robbie\rquote s arms were wings catching the air currents and he was a silver \lquote coaster.\par
\tab Gloria twisted the robot\rquote s head and leaned to the right. He banked sharply. Gloria equipped the \lquote coaster with a motor that went \ldblquote Br-r-r\rdblquote  and then with weapons that went \ldblquote Powie\rdblquote  and \ldblquote Sh-sh-shshsh.\rdblquote  Pirates were giving chase and the ship\rquote s blasters were coming into play. The pirates dropped in a steady rain.\par
\tab\ldblquote Got another one. Two more,\rdblquote  she cried.\par
\tab Then \ldblquote Faster, men,\rdblquote  Gloria said pompously, \ldblquote we\rquote re running out of ammunition.\rdblquote  She aimed over her shoulder with undaunted courage and Robbie was a blunt-nosed spaceship zooming through the void at maximum acceleration.\par
\tab Clear across the field he sped, to the patch of tall grass on the other side, where he stopped with a suddenness that evoked a shriek from his flushed rider, and then tumbled her onto the soft, green carpet.\par
\tab Gloria gasped and panted, and gave voice to intermittent whispered exclamations of \ldblquote That was nice!\rdblquote\par
\tab Robbie waited until she had caught her breath and then pulled gently at a lock of hair.\par
\tab\ldblquote You want something?\rdblquote  said Gloria, eyes wide in an apparently artless complexity that fooled her huge \ldblquote nursemaid\rdblquote  not at all. He pulled the curl harder.\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, I know. You want a story.\rdblquote\par
\tab Robbie nodded rapidly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Which one?\rdblquote\par
\tab Robbie made a semi-circle in the air with one finger.\par
\tab The little girl protested, \ldblquote Again? I\rquote ve told you Cinderella a million times. Aren\rquote t you tired of it? -It\rquote s for babies.\rdblquote\par
\tab Another semi-circle.\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, well,\rdblquote  Gloria composed herself, ran over the details of the tale in her mind (together with her own elaborations, of which she had several) and began:\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you ready? Well -- once upon a time there was a beautiful little girl whose name was Ella. And she had a terribly cruel step-mother and two very ugly and very cruel step-sisters and-\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Gloria was reaching the very climax of the tale -- midnight was striking and everything was changing back to the shabby originals lickety-split, while Robbie listened tensely with burning eyes -- when the interruption came.\par
\tab\ldblquote Gloria!\rdblquote\par
\tab It was the high-pitched sound of a woman who has been calling not once, but several times; and had the nervous tone of one in whom anxiety was beginning to overcome impatience.\par
\tab\ldblquote Mamma\rquote s calling me,\rdblquote  said Gloria, not quite happily. \ldblquote You\rquote d better carry me back to the house, Robbie.\rdblquote\par
\tab Robbie obeyed with alacrity for somehow there was that in him which judged it best to obey Mrs. Weston, without as much as a scrap of hesitation. Gloria\rquote s father was rarely home in the daytime except on Sunday -- today, for instance -- and when he was, he proved a genial and understanding person. Gloria\rquote s mother, however, was a source of uneasiness to Robbie and there was always the impulse to sneak away from her sight.\par
\tab Mrs. Weston caught sight of them the minute they rose above the masking tufts of long grass and retired inside the house to wait.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve shouted myself hoarse, Gloria,\rdblquote  she said, severely. \ldblquote Where were you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I was with Robbie,\rdblquote  quavered Gloria. \ldblquote I was telling him Cinderella, and I forgot it was dinner-time.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s a pity Robbie forgot, too.\rdblquote  Then, as if that reminded her of the robot\rquote s presence, she whirled upon him. \ldblquote You may go, Robbie. She doesn\rquote t need you now.\rdblquote  Then, brutally, \ldblquote And don\rquote t come back till I call you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Robbie turned to go, but hesitated as Gloria cried out in his defense, \ldblquote Wait, Mamma, you got to let him stay. I didn\rquote t finish Cinderella for him. I said I would tell him Cinderella and I\rquote m not finished.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Gloria!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Honest and truly, Mamma, he\rquote ll stay so quiet, you won\rquote t even know he\rquote s here. He can sit on the chair in the corner, and he won\rquote t say a word, I mean he won\rquote t do anything. Will you, Robbie?\rdblquote\par
\tab Robbie, appealed to, nodded his massive head up and down once.\par
\tab\ldblquote Gloria, if you don\rquote t stop this at once, you shan\rquote t see Robbie for a whole week.\rdblquote\par
\tab The girl\rquote s eyes fell, \ldblquote All right! But Cinderella is his favorite story and I didn\rquote t finish it. --And he likes it so much.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot left with a disconsolate step and Gloria choked back a sob.\par
\par
\tab George Weston was comfortable. It was a habit of his to be comfortable on Sunday afternoons. A good, hearty dinner below the hatches; a nice, soft, dilapidated couch on which to sprawl; a copy of the Times; slippered feet and shirtless chest; how could anyone help but be comfortable?\par
\tab He wasn\rquote t pleased, therefore, when his wife walked in. After ten years of married life, be still was so unutterably foolish as to love her, and there was no question that he was always glad to see her -- still Sunday afternoons just after dinner were sacred to him and his idea of solid comfort was to be left in utter solitude for two or three hours. Consequently, he fixed his eye firmly upon the latest reports of the Lefebre-Yoshida expedition to Mars (this one was to take off from Lunar Base and might actually succeed) and pretended she wasn\rquote t there.\par
\tab Mrs. Weston waited patiently for two minutes, then impatiently for two more, and finally broke the silence.\par
\tab\ldblquote George!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hmpph?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote George, I say! Will you put down that paper and look at me?\rdblquote\par
\tab The paper rustled to the floor and Weston turned a weary face toward his wife, \ldblquote What is it, dear?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You know what it is, George. It\rquote s Gloria and that terrible machine.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What terrible machine?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Now don\rquote t pretend you don\rquote t know what I\rquote m talking about. It\rquote s that robot Gloria calls Robbie. He doesn\rquote t leave her for a moment.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, why should he? He\rquote s not supposed to. And he certainly isn\rquote t a terrible machine. He\rquote s the best darn robot money can buy and I\rquote m damned sure he set me back half a year\rquote s income. He\rquote s worth it, though -- darn sight cleverer than half my office staff.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab He made a move to pick up the paper again, but his wife was quicker and snatched it away.\par
\tab\ldblquote You listen to me, George. I won\rquote t have my daughter entrusted to a machine -- and I don\rquote t care how clever it is. It has no soul, and no one knows what it may be thinking. A child just isn\rquote t made to be guarded by a thing of metal.\rdblquote\par
\tab Weston frowned, \ldblquote When did you decide this? He\rquote s been with Gloria two years now and I haven\rquote t seen you worry till now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It was different at first. It was a novelty; it took a load off me, and -- and it was a fashionable thing to do. But now I don\rquote t know. The neighbors-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, what have the neighbors to do with it? Now, look. A robot is infinitely more to be trusted than a human nursemaid. Robbie was constructed for only one purpose really -- to be the companion of a little child. His entire \lquote mentality\rquote  has been created for the purpose. He just can\rquote t help being faithful and loving and kind. He\rquote s a machine-made so. That\rquote s more than you can say for humans.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But something might go wrong. Some- some-\rdblquote  Mrs. Weston was a bit hazy about the insides of a robot, \ldblquote some little jigger will come loose and the awful thing will go berserk and- and-\rdblquote  She couldn\rquote t bring herself to complete the quite obvious thought.\par
\tab\ldblquote Nonsense,\rdblquote  Weston denied, with an involuntary nervous shiver. \ldblquote That\rquote s completely ridiculous. We had a long discussion at the time we bought Robbie about the First Law of Robotics. You know that it is impossible for a robot to harm a human being; that long before enough can go wrong to alter that First Law, a robot would be completely inoperable. It\rquote s a mathematical impossibility. Besides I have an engineer from U. S. Robots here twice a year to give the poor gadget a complete overhaul. Why, there\rquote s no more chance of any thing at all going wrong with Robbie than there is of you or I suddenly going loony -- considerably less, in fact. Besides, how are you going to take him away from Gloria?\rdblquote\par
\tab He made another futile stab at the paper and his wife tossed it angrily into the next room.\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s just it, George! She won\rquote t play with anyone else. There are dozens of little boys and girls that she should make friends with, but she won\rquote t. She won\rquote t go near them unless I make her. That\rquote s no way for a little girl to grow up. You want her to be normal, don\rquote t you? You want her to be able to take her part in society.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re jumping at shadows, Grace. Pretend Robbie\rquote s a dog. I\rquote ve seen hundreds of children who would rather have their dog than their father.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A dog is different, George. We must get rid of that horrible thing. You can sell it back to the company. I\rquote ve asked, and you can.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ve asked? Now look here, Grace, let\rquote s not go off the deep end. We\rquote re keeping the robot until Gloria is older and I don\rquote t want the subject brought up again.\rdblquote  And with that he walked out of the room in a huff.\par
\par
\tab Mrs. Weston met her husband at the door two evenings later. \ldblquote You\rquote ll have to listen to this, George. There\rquote s bad feeling in the village.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote About what?\rdblquote  asked Weston? He stepped into the washroom and drowned out any possible answer by the splash of water.\par
\tab Mrs. Weston waited. She said, \ldblquote About Robbie.\rdblquote\par
\tab Weston stepped out, towel in hand, face red and angry, \ldblquote What are you talking about?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, it\rquote s been building up and building up. I\rquote ve tried to close my eyes to it, but I\rquote m not going to any more. Most of the villagers consider Robbie dangerous. Children aren\rquote t allowed to go near our place in the evenings.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We trust \i our\i0  child with the thing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, people aren\rquote t reasonable about these things.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then to hell with them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Saying that doesn\rquote t solve the problem. I\rquote ve got to do my shopping down there. I\rquote ve got to meet them every day. And it\rquote s even worse in the city these days when it comes to robots. New York has just passed an ordinance keeping all robots off the streets between sunset and sunrise.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right, but they can\rquote t stop us from keeping a robot in our home. Grace, this is one of your campaigns. I recognize it. But it\rquote s no use. The answer is still, no! We\rquote re keeping Robbie!\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab And yet he loved his wife -- and what was worse, his wife knew it. George Weston, after all, was only a man -- poor thing -- and his wife made full use of every device which a clumsier and more scrupulous sex has learned, with reason and futility, to fear.\par
\tab Ten times in the ensuing week, he cried, \ldblquote Robbie stays, and that\rquote s final!\rdblquote  and each time it was weaker and accompanied by a louder and more agonized groan.\par
\tab Came the day at last, when Weston approached his daughter guiltily and suggested a \ldblquote beautiful\rdblquote  visivox show in the village.\par
\tab Gloria clapped her hands happily, \ldblquote Can Robbie go?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, dear,\rdblquote  he said, and winced at the sound of his voice, \ldblquote they won\rquote t allow robots at the visivox -- but you can tell him all about it when you get home.\rdblquote  He stumbled all over the last few words and looked away.\par
\tab Gloria came back from town bubbling over with enthusiasm, for the visivox had been a gorgeous spectacle indeed.\par
\tab She waited for her father to maneuver the jet-car into the sunken garage, \ldblquote Wait till I tell Robbie, Daddy. He would have liked it like anything. Especially when Francis Fran was backing away so-o-o quietly, and backed right into one of the Leopard-Men and had to run.\rdblquote  She laughed again, \ldblquote Daddy, are there really Leopard-Men on the Moon?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Probably not,\rdblquote  said Weston absently. \ldblquote It\rquote s just funny make-believe.\rdblquote  He couldn\rquote t take much longer with the car. He\rquote d have to face it.\par
\tab Gloria ran across the lawn. \ldblquote Robbie. --Robbie!\rdblquote\par
\tab Then she stopped suddenly at the sight of a beautiful collie which regarded her out of serious brown eyes as it wagged its tail on the porch.\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, what a nice dog!\rdblquote  Gloria climbed the steps, approached cautiously and patted it. \ldblquote Is it for me, Daddy?\rdblquote\par
\tab Her mother had joined them. \ldblquote Yes, it is, Gloria. Isn\rquote t it nice -- soft and furry? It\rquote s very gentle. It likes little girls.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can he play games?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Surely. He can do any number of tricks. Would you like to see some?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Right away. I want Robbie to see him, too. Robbie!\rdblquote  She stopped, uncertainly, and frowned, \ldblquote I\rquote ll bet he\rquote s just staying in his room because he\rquote s mad at me for not taking him to the visivox. You\rquote ll have to explain to him, Daddy. He might not believe me, but he knows if you say it, it\rquote s so.\rdblquote\par
\tab Weston\rquote s lip grew tighter. He looked toward his wife but could not catch her eye.\par
\tab Gloria turned precipitously and ran down the basement steps, shouting as she went, \ldblquote Robbie-- Come and see what Daddy and Mamma brought me. They brought me a dog, Robbie.\rdblquote\par
\tab In a minute she had returned, a frightened little girl. \ldblquote Mamma, Robbie isn\rquote t in his room. Where is he?\rdblquote  There was no answer and George Weston coughed and was suddenly extremely interested in an aimlessly drifting cloud. Gloria\rquote s voice quavered on the verge of tears, \ldblquote Where\rquote s Robbie, Mamma?\rdblquote\par
\tab Mrs. Weston sat down and drew her daughter gently to her, \ldblquote Don\rquote t feel bad, Gloria. Robbie has gone away, I think.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Gone away? Where? Where\rquote s he gone away, Mamma?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No one knows, darling. He just walked away. We\rquote ve looked and we\rquote ve looked and we\rquote ve looked for him, but we can\rquote t find him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean he\rquote ll never come back again?\rdblquote  Her eyes were round with horror.\par
\tab\ldblquote We may find him soon. We\rquote ll keep looking for him. And meanwhile you can play with your nice new doggie. Look at him! His name is Lightning and he can-\rdblquote\par
\tab But Gloria\rquote s eyelids had overflown, \ldblquote I don\rquote t want the nasty dog -- I want Robbie. I want you to find me Robbie.\rdblquote  Her feelings became too deep for words, and she spluttered into a shrill wail.\par
\tab Mrs. Weston glanced at her husband for help, but he merely shuffled his feet morosely and did not withdraw his ardent stare from the heavens, so she bent to the task of consolation, \ldblquote Why do you cry, Gloria? Robbie was only a machine, just a nasty old machine. He wasn\rquote t alive at all.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He was not no machine!\rdblquote  screamed Gloria, fiercely and ungrammatically. \ldblquote He was a person just like you and me and he was my friend. I want him back. Oh, Mamma, I want him back.\rdblquote\par
\tab Her mother groaned in defeat and left Gloria to her sorrow.\par
\tab\ldblquote Let her have her cry out,\rdblquote  she told her husband. \ldblquote Childish griefs are never lasting. In a few days, she\rquote ll forget that awful robot ever existed.\rdblquote\par
\tab But time proved Mrs. Weston a bit too optimistic. To be sure, Gloria ceased crying, but she ceased smiling, too, and the passing days found her ever more silent and shadowy. Gradually, her attitude of passive unhappiness wore Mrs. Weston down and all that kept her from yielding was the impossibility of admitting defeat to her husband.\par
\tab Then, one evening, she flounced into the living room, sat down, folded her arms and looked boiling mad.\par
\tab Her husband stretched his neck in order to see her over his newspaper, \ldblquote What now, Grace?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s that child, George. I\rquote ve had to send back the dog today. Gloria positively couldn\rquote t stand the sight of him, she said. She\rquote s driving me into a nervous breakdown.\rdblquote\par
\tab Weston laid down the paper and a hopeful gleam entered his eye, \ldblquote Maybe-- Maybe we ought to get Robbie back. It might be done, you know. I can get in touch with-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  she replied, grimly. \ldblquote I won\rquote t hear of it. We\rquote re not giving up that easily. My child shall not be brought up by a robot if it takes years to break her of it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Weston picked up his paper again with a disappointed air. \ldblquote A year of this will have me prematurely gray.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re a big help, George,\rdblquote  was the frigid answer. \ldblquote What Gloria needs is a change of environment? Of course she can\rquote t forget Robbie here. How can she when every tree and rock reminds her of him? It is really the silliest situation I have ever heard of. Imagine a child pining away for the loss of a robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, stick to the point. What\rquote s the change in environment you\rquote re planning?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re going to take her to New York.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The city! In August! Say, do you know what New York is like in August? It\rquote s unbearable.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Millions do bear it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They don\rquote t have a place like this to go to. If they didn\rquote t have to stay in New York, they wouldn\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, we have to. I say we\rquote re leaving now -- or as soon as we can make the arrangements. In the city, Gloria will find sufficient interests and sufficient friends to perk her up and make her forget that machine.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, Lord,\rdblquote  groaned the lesser half, \ldblquote those frying pavements!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We have to,\rdblquote  was the unshaken response. \ldblquote Gloria has lost five pounds in the last month and my little girl\rquote s health is more important to me than your comfort.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s a pity you didn\rquote t think of your little girl\rquote s health before you deprived her of her pet robot,\rdblquote  he muttered -- but to himself.\par
\par
\tab Gloria displayed immediate signs of improvement when told of the impending trip to the city. She spoke little of it, but when she did, it was always with lively anticipation. Again, she began to smile and to eat with something of her former appetite.\par
\tab Mrs. Weston hugged herself for joy and lost no opportunity to triumph over her still skeptical husband.\par
\tab\ldblquote You see, George, she helps with the packing like a little angel, and chatters away as if she hadn\rquote t a care in the world. It\rquote s just as I told you -- all we need do is substitute other interests.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hmpph,\rdblquote  was the skeptical response, \ldblquote I hope so.\rdblquote\par
\tab Preliminaries were gone through quickly. Arrangements were made for the preparation of their city home and a couple were engaged as housekeepers for the country home. When the day of the trip finally did come, Gloria was all but her old self again, and no mention of Robbie passed her lips at all.\par
\tab In high good-humor the family took a taxi-gyro to the airport (Weston would have preferred using his own private \lquote gyro, but it was only a two-seater with no room for baggage) and entered the waiting liner.\par
\tab\ldblquote Come, Gloria,\rdblquote  called Mrs. Weston. \ldblquote I\rquote ve saved you a seat near the window so you can watch the scenery.\rdblquote\par
\tab Gloria trotted down the aisle cheerily, flattened her nose into a white oval against the thick clear glass, and watched with an intentness that increased as the sudden coughing of the motor drifted backward into the interior. She was too young to be frightened when the ground dropped away as if let through a trap door and she herself suddenly became twice her usual weight, but not too young to be mightily interested. It wasn\rquote t until the ground had changed into a tiny patchwork quilt that she withdrew her nose, and faced her mother again.\par
\tab\ldblquote Will we soon be in the city, Mamma?\rdblquote  she asked, rubbing her chilled nose, and watching with interest as the patch of moisture which her breath had formed on the pane shrank slowly and vanished.\par
\tab\ldblquote In about half an hour, dear.\rdblquote  Then, with just the faintest trace of anxiety, \ldblquote Aren\rquote t you glad we\rquote re going? Don\rquote t you think you\rquote ll be very happy in the city with all the buildings and people and things to see? We\rquote ll go to the visivox every day and see shows and go to the circus and the beach and-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Mamma,\rdblquote  was Gloria\rquote s unenthusiastic rejoinder. The liner passed over a bank of clouds at the moment, and Gloria was instantly absorbed in the usual spectacle of clouds underneath one. Then they were over clear sky again, and she turned to her mother with a sudden mysterious air of secret knowledge.\par
\tab\ldblquote I know why we\rquote re going to the city, Mamma.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you?\rdblquote  Mrs. Weston was puzzled. \ldblquote Why, dear?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You didn\rquote t tell me because you wanted it to be a surprise, but I know.\rdblquote  For a moment, she was lost in admiration at her own acute penetration, and then she laughed gaily. \ldblquote We\rquote re going to New York so we can find Robbie, aren\rquote t we? --With detectives.\rdblquote\par
\tab The statement caught George Weston in the middle of a drink of water, with disastrous results. There was a sort of strangled gasp, a geyser of water, and then a bout of choking coughs. When all was over, he stood there, a red-faced, water-drenched and very, very annoyed person.\par
\tab Mrs. Weston maintained her composure, but when Gloria repeated her question in a more anxious tone of voice, she found her temper rather bent.\par
\tab\ldblquote Maybe,\rdblquote  she retorted, tartly. \ldblquote Now sit and be still, for Heaven\rquote s sake.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab New York City, 1998 A.D., was a paradise for the sightseer more than ever in its history. Gloria\rquote s parents realized this and made the most of it.\par
\tab On direct orders from his wife, George Weston arranged to have his business take care of itself for a month or so, in order to be free to spend the time in what he termed, \ldblquote dissipating Gloria to the verge of ruin.\rdblquote  Like everything else Weston did, this was gone about in an efficient, thorough, and business-like way. Before the month had passed, nothing that could be done had not been done.\par
\tab She was taken to the top of the half-mile tall Roosevelt Building, to gaze down in awe upon the jagged panorama of rooftops that blended far off in the fields of Long Island and the flatlands of New Jersey. They visited the zoos where Gloria stared in delicious fright at the \ldblquote real live lion\rdblquote  (rather disappointed that the keepers fed him raw steaks, instead of human beings, as she had expected), and asked insistently and peremptorily to see \ldblquote the whale.\rdblquote\par
\tab The various museums came in for their share of attention, together with the parks and the beaches and the aquarium.\par
\tab She was taken halfway up the Hudson in an excursion steamer fitted out in the archaism of the mad Twenties. She traveled into the stratosphere on an exhibition trip, where the sky turned deep purple and the stars came out and the misty earth below looked like a huge concave bowl. Down under the waters of the Long Island Sound she was taken in a glass-walled sub-sea vessel, where in a green and wavering world, quaint and curious sea-things ogled her and wiggled suddenly away.\par
\tab On a more prosaic level, Mrs. Weston took her to the department stores where she could revel in another type of fairyland.\par
\tab In fact, when the month had nearly sped, the Westons were convinced that everything conceivable had been done to take Gloria\rquote s mind once and for all off the departed Robbie -- but they were not quite sure they had succeeded.\par
\tab The fact remained that wherever Gloria went, she displayed the most absorbed and concentrated interest in such robots as happened to be present. No matter how exciting the spectacle before her, nor how novel to her girlish eyes, she turned away instantly if the corner of her eye caught a glimpse of metallic movement.\par
\tab Mrs. Weston went out of her way to keep Gloria away from all robots.\par
\tab And the matter was finally climaxed in the episode at the Museum of Science and Industry. The Museum had announced a special \ldblquote children\rquote s program\rdblquote  in which exhibits of scientific witchery scaled down to the child mind were to be shown. The Westons, of course, placed it upon their list of \ldblquote absolutely.\rdblquote\par
\tab It was while the Westons were standing totally absorbed in the exploits of a powerful electro-magnet that Mrs. Weston suddenly became aware of the fact that Gloria was no longer with her. Initial panic gave way to calm decision and, enlisting the aid of three attendants, a careful search was begun.\par
\tab Gloria, of course, was not one to wander aimlessly, however. For her age, she was an unusually determined and purposeful girl, quite full of the maternal genes in that respect. She had seen a huge sign on the third floor, which had said, \ldblquote This Way to the Talking Robot\rdblquote  Having spelled it out to herself and having noticed that her parents did not seem to wish to move in the proper direction, she did the obvious thing. Waiting for an opportune moment of parental distraction, she calmly disengaged herself and followed the sign.\par
\par
\tab The Talking Robot was a tour de force, a thoroughly impractical device, possessing publicity value only. Once an hour, an escorted group stood before it and asked questions of the robot engineer in charge in careful whispers. Those the engineer decided were suitable for the robot\rquote s circuits were transmitted to the Talking Robot.\par
\tab It was rather dull. It may be nice to know that the square of fourteen is one hundred ninety-six, that the temperature at the moment is 72 degrees Fahrenheit, and the air-pressure 30.02 inches of mercury, that the atomic weight of sodium is 23, but one doesn\rquote t really need a robot for that. One especially does not need an unwieldy, totally immobile mass of wires and coils spreading over twenty-five square yards.\par
\tab Few people bothered to return for a second helping, but one girl in her middle teens sat quietly on a bench waiting for a third. She was the only one in the room when Gloria entered.\par
\tab Gloria did not look at her. To her at the moment, another human being was but an inconsiderable item. She saved her attention for this large thing with the wheels. For a moment, she hesitated in dismay. It didn\rquote t look like any robot she had ever seen.\par
\tab Cautiously and doubtfully she raised her treble voice; \ldblquote Please, Mr. Robot, sir, are you the Talking Robot, sir?\rdblquote  She wasn\rquote t sure, but it seemed to her that a robot that actually talked was worth a great deal of politeness.\par
\tab (The girl in her mid-teens allowed a look of intense concentration to cross her thin, plain face. She whipped out a small notebook and began writing in rapid pothooks.)\par
\tab There was an oily whir of gears and a mechanically timbered voice boomed out in words that lacked accent and intonation, \ldblquote I- am- the- robot- that- talks.\rdblquote\par
\tab Gloria stared at it ruefully. It did talk, but the sound came from inside somewheres. There was no face to talk to. She said, \ldblquote Can you help me, Mr. Robot, sir?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Talking Robot was designed to answer questions, and only such questions as it could answer had ever been put to it. It was quite confident of its ability, therefore, \ldblquote I- can- help- you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you, Mr. Robot, sir. Have you seen Robbie?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Who -is Robbie?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s a robot, Mr. Robot, sir.\rdblquote  She stretched to tiptoes. \ldblquote He\rquote s about so high, Mr. Robot, sir, only higher, and he\rquote s very nice. He\rquote s got a head, you know. I mean you haven\rquote t, but he has, Mr. Robot, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Talking Robot had been left behind, \ldblquote A- robot?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Mr. Robot, sir. A robot just like you, except he can\rquote t talk, of course, and -- looks like a real person.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A- robot- like- me?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Mr. Robot, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab To which the Talking Robot\rquote s only response was an erratic splutter and an occasional incoherent sound. The radical generalization offered it, i.e., its existence, not as a particular object, but as a member of a general group, was too much for it. Loyally, it tried to encompass the concept and half a dozen coils burnt out. Little warning signals were buzzing.\par
\tab (The girl in her mid-teens left at that point. She had enough for her Physics-1 paper on \ldblquote Practical Aspects of Robotics.\rdblquote  This paper was Susan Calvin\rquote s first of many on the subject.)\par
\tab Gloria stood waiting, with carefully concealed impatience, for the machine\rquote s answer when she heard the cry behind her of \ldblquote There she is,\rdblquote  and recognized that cry as her mother\rquote s.\par
\tab\ldblquote What are you doing here, you bad girl?\rdblquote  cried Mrs. Weston, anxiety dissolving at once into anger. \ldblquote Do you know you frightened your mamma and daddy almost to death? Why did you run away?\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot engineer had also dashed in, tearing his hair, and demanding who of the gathering crowd had tampered with the machine. \ldblquote Can\rquote t anybody read signs?\rdblquote  he yelled. \ldblquote You\rquote re not allowed in here without an attendant.\rdblquote\par
\tab Gloria raised her grieved voice over the din, \ldblquote I only came to see the Talking Robot, Mamma. I thought he might know where Robbie was because they\rquote re both robots.\rdblquote  And then, as the thought of Robbie was suddenly brought forcefully home to her, she burst into a sudden storm of tears, \ldblquote And I got to find Robbie, Mamma. I got to.\rdblquote\par
\tab Mrs. Weston strangled a cry, and said, \ldblquote Oh, good Heavens. Come home, George. This is more than I can stand.\rdblquote\par
\tab That evening, George Weston left for several hours, and the next morning, he approached his wife with something that looked suspiciously like smug complacence.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve got an idea, Grace.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote About what?\rdblquote  was the gloomy, uninterested query?\par
\tab\ldblquote About Gloria.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re not going to suggest buying back that robot?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, of course not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then go ahead. I might as well listen to you. Nothing I\rquote ve done seems to have done any good.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. Here\rquote s what I\rquote ve been thinking. The whole trouble with Gloria is that she thinks of Robbie as a person and not as a machine. Naturally, she can\rquote t forget him. Now if we managed to convince her that Robbie was nothing more than a mess of steel and copper in the form of sheets and wires with electricity its juice of life, how long would her longings last? It\rquote s the psychological attack, if you see my point.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How do you plan to do it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Simple. Where do you suppose I went last night? I persuaded Robertson of U. S. Robots and Mechanical Men, Inc. to arrange for a complete tour of his premises tomorrow. The three of us will go, and by the time we\rquote re through, Gloria will have it drilled into her that a robot is not alive.\rdblquote\par
\tab Mrs. Weston\rquote s eyes widened gradually and something glinted in her eyes that was quite like sudden admiration, \ldblquote Why, George, that\rquote s a good idea.\rdblquote\par
\tab And George Weston\rquote s vest buttons strained. \ldblquote Only kind I have,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\par
\tab Mr. Struthers was a conscientious General Manager and naturally inclined to be a bit talkative. The combination, therefore, resulted in a tour that was fully explained, perhaps even over-abundantly explained, at every step. However, Mrs. Weston was not bored. Indeed, she stopped him several times and begged him to repeat his statements in simpler language so that Gloria might understand. Under the influence of this appreciation of his narrative powers, Mr. Struthers expanded genially and became ever more communicative, if possible.\par
\tab George Weston, himself, showed a gathering impatience.\par
\tab\ldblquote Pardon me, Struthers,\rdblquote  he said, breaking into the middle of a lecture on the photoelectric cell, \ldblquote haven\rquote t you a section of the factory where only robot labor is employed?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Eh? Oh, yes! Yes, indeed!\rdblquote  He smiled at Mrs. Weston. \ldblquote A vicious circle in a way, robots creating more robots. Of course, we are not making a general practice out of it. For one thing, the unions would never let us. But we can turn out a very few robots using robot labor exclusively, merely as a sort of scientific experiment. You see,\rdblquote  he tapped his pince-nez into one palm argumentatively, \ldblquote what the labor unions don\rquote t realize -- and I say this as a man who has always been very sympathetic with the labor movement in general -- is that the advent of the robot, while involving some dislocation to begin with, will inevitably-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Struthers,\rdblquote  said Weston, \ldblquote but about that section of the factory you speak of  -- may we see it? It would be very interesting, I\rquote m sure.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes! Yes, of course!\rdblquote  Mr. Struthers replaced his pince-nez in one convulsive movement and gave vent to a soft cough of discomfiture. \ldblquote Follow me, please.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was comparatively quiet while leading the three through a long corridor and down a flight of stairs. Then, when they had entered a large well-lit room that buzzed with metallic activity, the sluices opened and the flood of explanation poured forth again.\par
\tab\ldblquote There you are!\rdblquote  he said with pride in his voice. \ldblquote Robots only! Five men act as overseers and they don\rquote t even stay in this room. In five years, that is, since we began this project, not a single accident has occurred. Of course, the robots here assembled are comparatively simple, but...\rdblquote\par
\tab The General Manager\rquote s voice had long died to a rather soothing murmur in Gloria\rquote s ears. The whole trip seemed rather dull and pointless to her, though there were many robots in sight. None were even remotely like Robbie, though, and she surveyed them with open contempt.\par
\tab In this room, there weren\rquote t any people at all, she noticed. Then her eyes fell upon six or seven robots busily engaged at a round table halfway across the room. They widened in incredulous surprise. It was a big room. She couldn\rquote t see for sure, but one of the robots looked like -- looked like -- it was!\par
\tab\ldblquote Robbie!\rdblquote  Her shriek pierced the air, and one of the robots about the table faltered and dropped the tool he was holding. Gloria went almost mad with joy. Squeezing through the railing before either parent could stop her, she dropped lightly to the floor a few feet below, and ran toward her Robbie, arms waving and hair flying.\par
\tab And the three horrified adults, as they stood frozen in their tracks, saw what the excited little girl did not see, -- a huge, lumbering tractor bearing blindly down upon its appointed track.\par
\tab It took split-seconds for Weston to come to his senses, and those split-seconds meant everything, for Gloria could not be overtaken. Although Weston vaulted the railing in a wild attempt, it was obviously hopeless. Mr. Struthers signaled wildly to the overseers to stop the tractor, but the overseers were only human and it took time to act.\par
\tab It was only Robbie that acted immediately and with precision.\par
\tab With metal legs eating up the space between himself and his little mistress he charged down from the opposite direction. Everything then happened at once. With one sweep of an arm, Robbie snatched up Gloria, slackening his speed not one iota, and, consequently, knocking every breath of air out of her. Weston, not quite comprehending all that was happening, felt, rather than saw, Robbie brush past him, and came to a sudden bewildered halt. The tractor intersected Gloria\rquote s path half a second after Robbie had, rolled on ten feet further and came to a grinding, long drawn-out stop.\par
\tab Gloria regained her breath, submitted to a series of passionate hugs on the part of both her parents and turned eagerly toward Robbie. As far as she was concerned, nothing had happened except that she had found her friend.\par
\tab But Mrs. Weston\rquote s expression had changed from one of relief to one of dark suspicion. She turned to her husband, and, despite her disheveled and undignified appearance, managed to look quite formidable, \ldblquote You engineered this, didn\rquote t you?\par
\tab George Weston swabbed at a hot forehead with his handkerchief. His hand was unsteady, and his lips could curve only into a tremulous and exceedingly weak smile.\par
\tab Mrs. Weston pursued the thought, \ldblquote Robbie wasn\rquote t designed for engineering or construction work. He couldn\rquote t be of any use to them. You had him placed there deliberately so that Gloria would find him. You know you did.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, I did,\rdblquote  said Weston. \ldblquote But, Grace, how was I to know the reunion would be so violent? And Robbie has saved her life; you\rquote ll have to admit that. You can\rquote t send him away again.\rdblquote\par
\tab Grace Weston considered. She turned toward Gloria and Robbie and watched them abstractedly for a moment. Gloria had a grip about the robot\rquote s neck that would have asphyxiated any creature but one of metal, and was prattling nonsense in half-hysterical frenzy. Robbie\rquote s chrome-steel arms (capable of bending a bar of steel two inches in diameter into a pretzel) wound about the little girl gently and lovingly, and his eyes glowed a deep, deep red.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weston, at last, \ldblquote I guess he can stay with us until he rusts.\rdblquote\par
