\tab\i0 In science fiction it is not uncommon to have a robot built with a surface, at least, of synthetic flesh; and an appearance that is, at best, indistinguishable from the human being. Sometimes such humanoid robots are called \ldblquote androids\rdblquote  (from a Greek term meaning \ldblquote manlike\rdblquote ) and some writers are meticulous in making the distinction. I am not. To me a robot is a robot. \par
\tab But then, Karel Capek\rquote s play R.U.R., which introduced the term \ldblquote robot\rdblquote  to the world in 1920, did not involve robots in the strictest sense of the word. The robots manufactured by Rossum\rquote s Universal Robots (the \ldblquote R.U.R.\rdblquote  of the title) were androids. \par
