\tab A kind of peace had endured for a century and people had forgotten what anything else was like. They would scarcely have known how to react had they discovered that a kind of war had finally come. \par
\tab Certainly, Elias Lynn, Chief of the Bureau of Robotics, wasn\rquote t sure how he ought to react when \i he \i0 finally found out. The Bureau of Robotics was headquartered in Cheyenne, in line with the century-old trend toward decentralization, and Lynn stared dubiously at the young Security officer from Washington who had brought the news. \par
\tab Elias Lynn was a large man, almost charmingly homely, with pale blue eyes that bulged a bit. Men weren\rquote t usually comfortable under the stare of those eyes, but the Security officer remained calm. \par
\tab Lynn decided that his first reaction ought to be incredulity. Hell, it \i was \i0 incredulity! He just didn\rquote t believe it! \par
\tab He eased himself back in his chair and said, \ldblquote How certain is the information?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Security officer, who had introduced himself as Ralph G. Breckenridge and had presented credentials to match, had the softness of youth about him; full lips, plump cheeks that flushed easily, and guileless eyes. His clothing was out of line with Cheyenne but it suited a universally air-conditioned Washington, where Security, despite everything, was still centered. \par
\tab Breckenridge flushed and said, \ldblquote There\rquote s no doubt about it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You people know all about Them, I suppose,\rdblquote  said Lynn and was unable to keep a trace of sarcasm out of his tone. He was not particularly aware of his use of a slightly stressed pronoun in his reference to the enemy, the equivalent of capitalization in print. It was a cultural habit of this generation and the one preceding. No one said the \ldblquote East\rdblquote  or the \ldblquote Reds\rdblquote  or the \ldblquote Soviets\rdblquote  or the \ldblquote Russians\rdblquote  any more. That would have been too confusing, since some of Them weren\rquote t of the East, weren\rquote t Reds, Soviets, and especially not Russians. It was much simpler to say We and They, and much more precise. \par
\tab Travelers had frequently reported that They did the same in reverse. Over there, They were \ldblquote We\rdblquote  (in the appropriate language) and We were \ldblquote They.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Scarcely anyone gave thought to such things any more. It was all quite comfortable and casual. There was no hatred, even. At the beginning, it had been called a Cold War. Now it was only a game, almost a good-natured game, with unspoken rules and a kind of decency about it. \par
\tab Lynn said abruptly, \ldblquote Why should They want to disturb the situation?\rdblquote  \par
\tab He rose and stood staring at a wall map of the world, split into two regions with faint edgings of color. An irregular portion on the left of the map was edged in a mild green. A smaller, but just as irregular, portion on the right of the map was bordered in a washed-out pink. We and They. \par
\tab The map hadn\rquote t changed much in a century. The loss of Formosa and the gain of East Germany some eighty years before had been the last territorial switch of importance. \par
\tab There had been another change, though, that was significant enough and that was in the colors. Two generations before, Their territory had been a brooding, bloody red, Ours a pure and undefiled white. Now there was a neutrality about the colors. Lynn had seen Their maps and it was the same on Their side. \par
\tab\ldblquote They wouldn\rquote t do it,\rdblquote  he said. \par
\tab\ldblquote They are doing it, \ldblquote  said Breckenridge, \ldblquote and you had better accustom yourself to the fact. Of course, sir, I realize that it isn\rquote t pleasant to think that They may be that far ahead of us in robotics.\rdblquote  \par
\tab His eyes remained as guileless as ever, but the hidden knife-edges of the words plunged deep, and Lynn quivered at the impact. \par
\tab Of course, that would account for why the Chief of Robotics learned of this so late and through a Security officer at that. He had lost caste in the eyes of the Government; if Robotics had really failed in the struggle, Lynn could expect no political mercy. \par
\tab Lynn said wearily, \ldblquote Even if what you say is true, They\rquote re not far ahead of us. We could build humanoid robots.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Have we, sir?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. As a matter of fact, we have built a few models for experimental purposes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote They were doing so ten years ago. They\rquote ve made ten years\rquote  progress since.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn was disturbed. He wondered if his incredulity concerning the whole business was really the result of wounded pride and fear for his job and reputation. He was embarrassed by the possibility that this might be so, and yet he was forced into defense. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Look, young man, the stalemate between Them and Us was never perfect in every detail, you know. They have always been ahead in one facet or another and We in some other facet or another. If They\rquote re ahead of us right now in robotics, it\rquote s because They\rquote ve placed a greater proportion of Their effort into robotics than We have. And that means that some other branch of endeavor has received a greater share of Our efforts than it has to Theirs. It would mean We\rquote re ahead in force-field research or in hyperatomics, perhaps.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn felt distressed at his own statement that the stalemate wasn\rquote t perfect. It was true enough, but that was the one great danger threatening the world. The world depended on the stalemate being as perfect as possible. If the small unevennesses that always existed overbalanced too far in one direction or the other\par
\tab Almost at the beginning of what had been the Cold War, both sides had developed thermonuclear weapons, and war became unthinkable. Competition switched from the military to the economic and psychological and had stayed there ever since. \par
\tab But always there was the driving effort on each side to break the stalemate, to develop a parry for every possible thrust, to develop a thrust that could not be parried in time--something that would make war possible again. And that was not because either side wanted war so desperately, but because both were afraid that the other side would make the crucial discovery first. \par
\tab For a hundred years each side had kept the struggle even. And in the process, peace had been maintained for a hundred years while, as byproducts of the continuously intensive research, force fields had been produced and solar energy and insect control and robots. Each side was making a beginning in the understanding of mentalics, which was the name given to the biochemistry and biophysics of thought. Each side had its outposts on the Moon and on Mars. Mankind was advancing in giant strides under forced draft. \par
\tab It was even necessary for both sides to be as decent and humane as possible among themselves, lest through cruelty and tyranny, friends be made for the other side. \par
\tab It couldn\rquote t be that the stalemate would now be broken and that there would be war. \par
\tab Lynn said, \ldblquote I want to consult one of my men. I want his opinion. \par
\tab\ldblquote Is he trustworthy?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn looked disgusted. \ldblquote Good Lord, what man in Robotics has not been investigated and cleared to death by your people? Yes, I vouch for him. If you can\rquote t trust a man like Humphrey Carl Laszlo, then we\rquote re in no position to face the kind of attack you say They are launching, no matter what else we do.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve heard of Laszlo,\rdblquote  said Breckenridge. \ldblquote Good. Does he pass?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then, I\rquote ll have him in and we\rquote ll find out what he thinks about the possibility that robots could invade the U .S.A.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not exactly,\rdblquote  said Breckenridge, softly. \ldblquote You still don\rquote t accept the full truth. Find out what he thinks about the fact that robots have \i already \i0 invaded the U.S.A.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Laszlo was the grandson of a Hungarian who had broken through what had then been called the Iron Curtain, and he had a comfortable above-suspicion feeling about himself because of it. He was thick-set and balding with a pugnacious look graven forever on his snub face, but his accent was clear Harvard and he was almost excessively soft-spoken. \par
\tab To Lynn, who was conscious that after years of administration he was no longer expert in the various phases of modem robotics, Laszlo was a comforting receptacle for complete knowledge. Lynn felt better because of the man\rquote s mere presence. \par
\tab Lynn said, \ldblquote What do you think?\rdblquote  A scowl twisted Laszlo\rquote s face ferociously. \ldblquote That They\rquote re that far ahead of us. Completely incredible. It would mean They\rquote ve produced humanoids that could not be told from humans at close quarters. It would mean a considerable advance in robo-mentalics.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re personally involved,\rdblquote  said Breckenridge, coldly. \ldblquote Leaving professional pride out of account, exactly why is it impossible that They be ahead of Us?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Laszlo shrugged. \ldblquote I assure you that I\rquote m well acquainted with Their literature on robotics. I know approximately where They are.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You know approximately where They want you to \i think \i0 They are, is what you really mean,\rdblquote  corrected Breckenridge. \ldblquote Have you ever visited the other side?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I haven\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Laszlo, shortly. \ldblquote Nor you, Dr. Lynn?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn said, \ldblquote No, I haven\rquote t, either.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Breckenridge said, \ldblquote Has any robotics man visited the other side in twenty-five years?\rdblquote  He asked the question with a kind of confidence that indicated he knew the answer. \par
\tab For a matter of seconds, the atmosphere was heavy with thought. Discomfort crossed Lazlo\rquote s broad face. He said, \ldblquote As a matter of fact, They haven\rquote t held any conferences on robotics in a long time.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In twenty-five years,\rdblquote  said Breckenridge. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t that significant?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Maybe,\rdblquote  said Laszlo, reluctantly. \ldblquote Something else bothers me, though. None of Them have ever come to Our conferences on robotics. None that I can remember.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Were They invited?\rdblquote  asked Breckenridge. \par
\tab Lynn, staring and worried, interposed quickly, \ldblquote Of course.\rdblquote  Breckenridge said, \ldblquote Do They refuse attendance to any other types of scientific conferences We hold?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Laszlo. He was pacing the floor now. \ldblquote I haven\rquote t heard of any cases. Have you, Chief?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Lynn. \par
\tab Breckenridge said, \ldblquote Wouldn\rquote t you say it was as though They didn\rquote t want to be put in the position of having to return any such invitation? Or as though They were afraid one of Their men might talk too much?\rdblquote  \par
\tab That was exactly how it seemed, and Lynn felt a helpless conviction that Security\rquote s story was true after all steal over him. \par
\tab Why else had there been no contact between sides on robotics? There had been a cross-fertilizing trickle of researchers moving in both directions on a strictly one-for-one basis for years, dating back to the days of Eisenhower and Krushchev. There were a great many good motives for that: an honest appreciation of the supranational character of science; impulses of friendliness that are hard to wipe out completely in the individual human being; the desire to be exposed to a fresh and interesting outlook and to have your own slightly stale notions greeted by others as fresh and interesting. \par
\tab The governments themselves were anxious that this continue. There was always the obvious thought that by learning all you could and telling as little as you could, your own side would gain by the exchange. \par
\tab But not in the case of robotics. Not there. \par
\tab Such a little thing to carry conviction. And a thing, moreover, they had known all along. Lynn thought darkly: \i We\rquote ve taken the complacent way out. \par
\tab\i0 Because the other side had done nothing publicly on robotics, it had been tempting to sit back smugly and be comfortable in the assurance of superiority. Why hadn\rquote t it seemed possible, even likely, that They were hiding superior cards, a trump hand, for the proper time? \par
\tab Laszlo said shakenly, \ldblquote What do we do?\rdblquote  It was obvious that the same line of thought had carried the same conviction to him. \par
\tab\ldblquote Do?\rdblquote  parroted Lynn. It was hard to think right now of anything but the complete horror that came with conviction. There were ten humanoid robots somewhere in the United States, each one carrying a fragment of a TC bomb. \par
\tab TC! The race for sheer horror in bombery had ended there. TCI Total Conversion! The sun was no longer a synonym one could use. Total conversion made the sun a penny candle. \par
\tab Ten humanoids, each completely harmless in separation, could, by the simple act of coming together, exceed critical mass and Lynn rose to his feet heavily, the dark pouches under his eyes, which ordinarily lent his ugly face a look of savage foreboding, more prominent than ever. \ldblquote It\rquote s going to be up to us to figure out ways and means of telling a humanoid from a human and then finding the humanoids.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How quickly?\rdblquote  muttered Laszlo. \par
\tab\ldblquote Not later than five minutes before they get together,\rdblquote  barked Lynn, \ldblquote and I don\rquote t know when that will be.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Breckenridge nodded. \ldblquote I\rquote m glad you\rquote re with us now, sir, I\rquote m to bring you back to Washington for conference, you know.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn raised his eyebrows. \ldblquote All right.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He wondered if, had he delayed longer in being convinced, he might not have been replaced forthwith--if some other Chief of the Bureau of Robotics might not be conferring in Washington. He suddenly wished earnestly that exactly that had come to pass. \par
\tab The First Presidential Assistant was there, the Secretary of Science, the Secretary of Security, Lynn himself, and Breckenridge. Five of them sitting about a table in the dungeons of an underground fortress near Washington. \par
\tab Presidential Assistant Jeffreys was an impressive man, handsome in a white-haired and just-a-trifle-jowly fashion, solid, thoughtful and as unobtrusive, politically, as a Presidential Assistant ought to be. \par
\tab He spoke incisively. \ldblquote There are three questions that face us as I see it. First, when are the humanoids going to get together? Second, where are they going to get together? Third, how do we stop them before they get together?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Secretary of Science Amberley nodded convulsively at that. He had been Dean of Northwestern Engineering before his appointment. He was thin, sharp-featured and noticeably edgy. His forefinger traced slow circles on the table\par
\tab\ldblquote As far as \i when \i0 they\rquote ll get together,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I suppose it\rquote s definite that it won\rquote t be for some time.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why do you say that?\rdblquote  asked Lynn sharply. \par
\tab\ldblquote They\rquote ve been in the U.S. at least a month already. So Security says.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn turned automatically to look at Breckenridge, and Secretary of Security Macalaster intercepted the glance. Macalaster said, \ldblquote The information is reliable. Don\rquote t let Breckenridge\rquote s apparent youth fool you, Dr. Lynn. That\rquote s part of his value to us. Actually, he\rquote s thirty-four and has been with the department for ten years. He has been in Moscow for nearly a year and without him, none of this terrible danger would be known to us. As it is, we have most of the details.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not the crucial ones,\rdblquote  said Lynn. \par
\tab Macalaster of Security smiled frostily. His heavy chin and close-set eyes were well-known to the public but almost nothing else about him was. He said, \ldblquote We are all finitely human, Dr. Lynn. Agent Breckenridge has done a great deal.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Presidential Assistant Jeffreys cut in. \ldblquote Let us say we have a certain amount of time. If action at the instant were necessary, it would have happened before this. It seems likely that they are waiting for a specific time. If we knew the place, perhaps the time would become self-evident. \par
\tab\ldblquote If they are going to TC a target, they will want to cripple us as much as possible, so it would seem that a major city would have to be it. In any case, a major metropolis is the only target worth a TC bomb. I think there are four possibilities: Washington, as the administrative center; New York, as the financial center; and Detroit and Pittsburgh as the two chief industrial centers.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Macalaster of Security said, \ldblquote I vote for New York. Administration and industry have both been decentralized to the point where the destruction of anyone particular city won\rquote t prevent instant retaliation.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then why New York?\rdblquote  asked Amberly of Science, perhaps more sharply than he intended. \ldblquote Finance has been decentralized as well.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A question of morale. It may be they intend to destroy our will to resist, to induce surrender by the sheer horror of the first blow. The greatest destruction of human life would be in the New York Metropolitan area--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Pretty cold-blooded,\rdblquote  muttered Lynn. \ldblquote I know,\rdblquote  said Macalaster of Security, \ldblquote but they\rquote re capable of it, if they thought it would mean final victory at a stroke. Wouldn\rquote t we--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Presidential Assistant Jeffreys brushed back his white hair. \ldblquote Let\rquote s assume the worst. Let\rquote s assume that New York will be destroyed some time during the winter, preferably immediately after a serious blizzard when communications are at their worst and the disruption of utilities and food supplies in fringe areas will be most serious in their effect. Now, how do we stop them?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Amberley of Science could only say, \ldblquote Finding ten men in two hundred and twenty million is an awfully small needle in an awfully large haystack.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Jeffreys shook his head. \ldblquote You have it wrong. Ten humanoids among two hundred twenty million humans.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No difference,\rdblquote  said Amberley of Science. \ldblquote We don\rquote t know that a humanoid can be differentiated from a human at sight. Probably not.\rdblquote  He looked at Lynn. They all did. \par
\tab Lynn said heavily, \ldblquote We in Cheyenne couldn\rquote t make one that would pass as human in the daylight.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But They can,\rdblquote  said Macalaster of Security, \ldblquote and not only physically. We\rquote re sure of that. They\rquote ve advanced mentalic procedures to the point where They can reel off the micro-electronic pattern of the brain and focus it on the positronic pathways of the robot.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn stared. \ldblquote Are you implying that They can create the replica of a human being complete with personality and memory?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I am.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of specific human beings?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Is this also based on Agent Breckenridge\rquote s findings?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. The evidence can\rquote t be disputed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn bent his head in thought for a moment. Then he said, \ldblquote Then ten men in the United States are not men but humanoids. But the originals would have had to be available to them. They couldn\rquote t be Orientals, who would be too easy to spot, so they would have to be East Europeans. How would they be introduced into this country, then? With the radar network over the entire world border as tight as a drum, how could They introduce any individual, human or humanoid, without our knowing it?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Macalaster of Security said, \ldblquote It can be done. There are certain legitimate seepages across the border. Businessmen, pilots, even tourists. They\rquote re watched, of course, on both sides. Still ten of them might have been kidnaped and used as models for humanoids. The humanoids would then be sent back in their place. Since we wouldn\rquote t expect such a substitution, it would pass us by. If they were Americans to begin with, there would be no difficulty in their getting into this country. It\rquote s as simple as that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And even their friends and family could not tell the difference?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We must assume so. Believe me, we\rquote ve been waiting for any report that might imply sudden attacks of amnesia or troublesome changes in personality. We\rquote ve checked on thousands.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Amberley of Science stared at his finger tips. \ldblquote I think ordinary measures won\rquote t work. The attack must come from the Bureau of Robotics and I depend on the chief of that bureau.\rdblquote  Again eyes turned sharply, expectantly, on Lynn. Lynn felt bitterness rise. It seemed to him that this was what the conference came to and was intended for. Nothing that had been said had not been said before. He was sure of that. There was no solution to the problem, no pregnant suggestion. It was a device for the record, a device on the part of men who gravely feared defeat and who wished the responsibility for it placed clearly and unequivocally on someone else. \par
\tab And yet there was justice in it. It was in robotics that We had fallen short. And Lynn was not Lynn merely. He was Lynn of Robotics and the responsibility had to be his. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I will do what I can.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He spent a wakeful night and there was a haggardness about both body and soul when he sought and attained another interview with Presidential Assistant Jeffreys the next morning. Breckenridge was there, and though Lynn would have preferred a private conference, he could see the justice in the situation. It was obvious that Breckenridge had attained enormous influence with the government as a result of his successful Intelligence work. Well, why not? \par
\tab Lynn said, \ldblquote Sir, I am considering the possibility that we are hopping uselessly to enemy piping.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In what way?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sure that however impatient the public may grow at times, and however legislators sometimes find it expedient to talk, the government at least recognizes the world stalemate to be beneficial. They must recognize it also. Ten humanoids with one TC bomb is a trivial way of breaking the stalemate.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The destruction of fifteen million human beings is scarcely trivial.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It is from the world power standpoint. It would not so demoralize us to make us surrender or so cripple us as to convince us we could not win. There would just be the same old planetary death war that both sides have avoided so long and so successfully. And all They would have accomplished is to force us to fight minus one city. It\rquote s not enough.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What do you suggest?\rdblquote  said Jeffreys coldly. \ldblquote That They do not have ten humanoids in our country? That there is not a TC bomb waiting to get together?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll agree that those things are here, but perhaps for some reason greater than just midwinter bomb madness.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Such as?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It may be that the physical destruction resulting from the humanoids getting together is not the worst thing that can happen to us. What about the moral and intellectual destruction that comes of their being here at all? With all due respect to Agent Breckenridge, what if They \i intended \i0 for us to find out about the humanoids; what if the humanoids are never supposed to get together, but merely to remain separate in order to give us something to worry about.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Tell me this. What measures have already been taken against the humanoids? I suppose that Security is going through the files of all citizens who have ever been across the border or close enough to it to make kidnapping possible. I know, since Macalaster mentioned it yesterday, that they are following up suspicious psychiatric cases. What else?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Jeffreys said, \ldblquote Small X-ray devices are being installed in key places in the large cities. In the mass arenas, for instance--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Where ten humanoids might slip in among a hundred thousand spectators of a football game or an air-polo match?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And concert halls and churches?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We must start somewhere. We can\rquote t do it all at once.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Particularly when panic must be avoided,\rdblquote  said Lynn. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t that so? It wouldn\rquote t do to have the public realize that at any unpredictable moment, some unpredictable city and its human contents would suddenly cease to exist.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I suppose that\rquote s obvious. What are you driving at?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn said strenuously, \ldblquote That a growing fraction of our national effort will be diverted entirely into the nasty problem of what Amberley called finding a very small needle in a very large haystack. We\rquote ll be chasing our tails madly, while They increase their research lead to the point where we find we can no longer catch up; when we must surrender without the chance even of snapping our fingers in retaliation. \par
\tab\ldblquote Consider further that this news will leak out as more and more people become involved in our countermeasures and more and more people begin to guess what we\rquote re doing. Then what? The panic might do us more harm than anyone TC bomb.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Presidential Assistant said irritably, \ldblquote In Heaven\rquote s name, man, what do you suggest we do, then?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  said Lynn. \ldblquote Call their bluff. Live as we have lived and gamble that They won\rquote t dare break the stalemate for the sake of a one-bomb head start.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Impossible!\rdblquote  said Jeffreys. \ldblquote Completely impossible. The welfare of all of Us is very largely in my hands, and doing nothing is the one thing I cannot do. I agree with you, perhaps, that X-ray machines at sports arenas are a kind of skin-deep measure that won\rquote t be effective, but it has to be done so that people, in the aftermath, do not come to the bitter conclusion that we tossed our country away for the sake of a subtle line of reasoning that encouraged donothingism. In fact, our counter-gambit will be active indeed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In what way?\rdblquote  Presidential Assistant Jeffreys looked at Breckenridge. The young Security officer, hitherto calmly silent, said, \ldblquote It\rquote s no use talking about a possible future break in the stalemate when the stalemate is broken now. It doesn\rquote t matter whether these humanoids explode or do not. Maybe they \i are \i0 only a bait to divert us, as you say. But the fact remains that we are a quarter of a century behind in robotics, and that may be fatal. What other advances in robotics will there be to surprise us if war does start? The only answer is to divert our entire force immediately, now, into a crash program of robotics research, and the first problem is to find the humanoids. Call it an exercise in robotics, if you will, or call it the prevention of the death of fifteen million men, women and children.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn shook his head helplessly. \ldblquote You \i can\rquote t. \i0 You\rquote d be playing into their hands. They want us lured into the one blind alley while they\rquote re free to advance in all other directions.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Jeffreys said impatiently, \ldblquote That\rquote s your guess. Breckenridge has made his suggestion through channels and the government has approved, and we will begin with an all-Science conference.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote All-Science?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Breckenridge said, \ldblquote We have listed every important scientist of every branch of natural science. They\rquote ll all be at Cheyenne. There will be only one point on the agenda: How to advance robotics. The major specific subheading under that will be: How to develop a receiving device for the electromagnetic fields of the cerebral cortex that will be sufficiently delicate to distinguish between a protoplasmic human brain and a positronic humanoid brain.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Jeffreys said, \ldblquote We had hoped you would be willing to be in charge of the conference.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I was not consulted in this.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Obviously time was short, sir. Do you agree to be in charge?\rdblquote  Lynn smiled briefly. It was a matter of responsibility again. The responsibility must be clearly that of Lynn of Robotics. He had the feeling it would be Breckenridge who would really be in charge. But what could he do? \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I agree.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Breckenridge and Lynn returned together to Cheyenne, where that evening Laszlo listened with a sullen mistrust to Lynn\rquote s description of coming events. \par
\tab Laszlo said, \ldblquote While you were gone, Chief, I\rquote ve started putting five experimental models of humanoid structure through the testing procedures. Our men are on a twelve-hour day, with three shifts overlapping. If we\rquote ve got to arrange a conference, we\rquote re going to be crowded and red-taped out of everything. Work will come to a halt.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Breckenridge said, \ldblquote That will be only temporary. You will gain more than you lose.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Laszlo scowled. \ldblquote A bunch of astrophysicists and geochemists around won\rquote t help a damn toward robotics.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Views from specialists of other fields may be helpful.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Are you sure? How do we know that there \i is \i0 any way of detecting brain waves or that, even if we can, there is a way of differentiating human and humanoid by wave pattern? Who set up the project, anyway?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I did,\rdblquote  said Breckenridge. \par
\tab\ldblquote You did? Are you a robotics man?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The young Security agent said calmly, \ldblquote I have studied robotics.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s not the same thing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve had access to text material dealing with Russian robotics--in Russian. Top-secret material well in advance of anything you have here.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn said ruefully, \ldblquote He has us there, Laszlo.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It was on the basis of that material,\rdblquote  Breckenridge went on, \ldblquote that I suggested this particular line of investigation. It is reasonably certain that in copying off the electromagnetic pattern of a specific human mind into a specific positronic brain, a perfectly exact duplicate cannot be made. For one thing, the most complicated positronic brain small enough to fit into a human-sized skull is hundreds of times less complex than the human brain. It can\rquote t pick up all the overtones, therefore, and there must be some way to take advantage of that fact.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Laszlo looked impressed despite himself and Lynn smiled grimly. It was easy to resent Breckenridge and the coming intrusion of several hundred scientists of nonrobotics specialties, but the problem itself was an intriguing one. There was that consolation, at least. \par
\tab It came to him quietly. Lynn found he had nothing to do but sit in his office alone, with an executive position that had grown merely titular. Perhaps that helped. It gave him time to think, to picture the creative scientists of half the world converging on Cheyenne. \par
\tab It was Breckenridge who, with cool efficiency, was handling the details of preparation. There had been a kind of confidence in the way he said, \ldblquote Let\rquote s get together and we\rquote ll lick Them.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Let\rquote s get together. It came to Lynn so quietly that anyone watching Lynn at that moment might have seen his eyes blink slowly twice--but surely nothing more. \par
\tab He did what he had to do with a whirling detachment that kept him calm when he felt that, by all rights, he ought to be going mad. \par
\tab He sought out Breckenridge in the other\rquote s improvised quarters. Breckenridge was alone and frowning. \ldblquote Is anything wrong, sir?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lynn said wearily, \ldblquote Everything\rquote s right, I think. I\rquote ve invoked martial-law.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote As chief of a division I can do so if I am of the opinion the situation warrants it. Over my division I can then be dictator. Chalk up one for the beauties of decentralization.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You will rescind that order immediately.\rdblquote  Breckenridge took a step forward. \ldblquote When Washington hears this, you will be ruined.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m ruined anyway. Do you think I don\rquote t realize that I\rquote ve been set up for the role of the greatest villain in American history: the man who let Them break the stalemate? I have nothing to lose--and perhaps a great deal to gain.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He laughed a little wildly. \ldblquote What a target the Division of Robotics will be, eh, Breckenridge? Only a few thousand men to be killed by a TC bomb capable of wiping out three hundred square miles in one micro-second. But five hundred of those men would be our greatest scientists. We would be in the peculiar position of having to fight a war with our brains shot out, or surrendering. I think we\rquote d surrender.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But this is impossible. Lynn, do you hear me? Do you understand? How could the humanoids pass our security provisions? How could they get together?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But they \i are \i0 getting together! We\rquote re helping them to do so. We\rquote re ordering them to do so. Our scientists visit the other side, Breckenridge. They visit Them regularly. You made a point of how strange it was that no one in robotics did. Well, ten of those scientists are still there and in their place, ten humanoids are converging on Cheyenne.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s a ridiculous guess.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I think it\rquote s a good one, Breckenridge. But it wouldn\rquote t work unless we knew humanoids were in America so that we would call the conference in the first place. Quite a coincidence that you brought the news of the humanoids \i and \i0 suggested the conference \i and \i0 suggested the agenda \i and \i0 are running the show \i and \i0 know exactly which scientists were invited. Did you make sure the right ten were included?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Dr. Lynn!\rdblquote  cried Breckenridge in outrage. He poised to rush forward. \par
\tab Lynn said, \ldblquote Don\rquote t move. I\rquote ve got a blaster here. Well just wait for the scientists to get here one by one. One by one we\rquote ll X-ray them. One by one, we\rquote ll monitor them for radioactivity. No two will get together without being checked, and if all five hundred are clear, I\rquote ll give you my blaster and surrender to you. Only I think we\rquote ll find the ten humanoids. Sit down, Breckenridge.\rdblquote  \par
\tab They both sat. Lynn said, \ldblquote We wait. When I\rquote m tired, Laszlo will spell me. We wait.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Professor Manuelo Jiminez of the Institute of Higher Studies of Buenos Aires exploded while the stratospheric jet on which he traveled was three miles above the Amazon Valley. It was a simple chemical explosion but it was enough to destroy the plane. \par
\tab Dr. Herman Liebowitz of M.I.T. exploded in a monorail, killing twenty people and injuring a hundred others. \par
\tab In similar manner, Dr. Auguste Marin of L \lquote Institut Nucleonique of Montreal and seven others died at various stages of their journey to Cheyenne. \par
\tab Laszlo hurtled in, pale-faced and stammering, with the first news of it. It had only been two hours that Lynn had sat there, facing Breckenridge, blaster in hand. \par
\tab Laszlo said, \ldblquote I thought you were nuts, Chief, but you were right. They \i were \i0 humanoids. They \i had \i0 to be.\rdblquote  He turned to stare with hate-filled eyes at Breckenridge. \ldblquote Only they were warned. He warned them, and now there won\rquote t be one left intact. Not one to study.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote God!\rdblquote  cried Lynn and in a frenzy of haste thrust his blaster out toward Breckenridge and fired. The Security man\rquote s neck vanished; the torso fell; the head dropped, thudded against the floor and rolled crookedly. \par
\tab Lynn moaned, \ldblquote I didn\rquote t understand, I thought he was a traitor. Nothing more.\rdblquote  \par
\tab And Laszlo stood immobile, mouth open, for the moment incapable of speech. \par
\tab Lynn said wildly, \ldblquote Sure, he warned them. But how could he do so while sitting in that chair unless he were equipped with built-in radio transmission? Don\rquote t you see it? Breckenridge had been in Moscow. The real Breckenridge is still there. Oh my God, there were \i eleven \i0 of them.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Laszlo managed a hoarse squeak. \ldblquote Why didn\rquote t \i he \i0 explode?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He was hanging on, I suppose, to make sure the others had received his message and were safely destroyed. Lord, Lord, when you brought the news and I realized the truth, I couldn\rquote t shoot fast enough. God knows by how few seconds I may have beaten him to it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Laszlo said shakily, \ldblquote At least, we\rquote ll have one to study.\rdblquote  He bent and put his fingers on the sticky fluid trickling out of the mangled remains at the neck end of the headless body. \par
\tab Not blood, but high-grade machine oil. \par
