\scaps It was one of Gregory Powell\rquote s favorite\scaps0  platitudes that nothing was to be gained from excitement, so when Mike Donovan came leaping down the stairs toward him, red hair matted with perspiration, Powell frowned.\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s wrong?\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Break a fingernail?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yaaaah,\rdblquote  snarled Donovan, feverishly. \ldblquote What have you been doing in the sublevels all day?\rdblquote  He took a deep breath and blurted out, \ldblquote Speedy never returned.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell\rquote s eyes widened momentarily and he stopped on the stairs; then he recovered and resumed his upward steps. He didn\rquote t speak until he reached the head of the flight, and then:\par
\tab\ldblquote You sent him after the selenium?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And how long has he been out?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Five hours now.\rdblquote\par
\tab Silence! This was a devil of a situation. Here they were, on Mercury exactly twelve hours -- and already up to the eyebrows in the worst sort of trouble. Mercury had long been the jinx world of the System, but this was drawing it rather strong -- even for a jinx.\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote Start at the beginning, and let\rquote s get this straight.\rdblquote\par
\tab They were in the radio room now -- with its already subtly antiquated equipment, untouched for the ten years previous to their arrival. Even ten years, technologically speaking, meant so much. Compare Speedy with the type of robot they must have had back in 2005. But then, advances in robotics these days were tremendous. Powell touched a still gleaming metal surface gingerly. The air of disuse that touched everything about the room -- and the entire Station -- was infinitely depressing.\par
\tab Donovan must have felt it. He began: \ldblquote I tried to locate him by radio, but it was no go. Radio isn\rquote t any good on the Mercury Sunside -- not past two miles, anyway. That\rquote s one of the reasons the First Expedition failed. And we can\rquote t put up the ultrawave equipment for weeks yet -\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Skip all that. What did you get?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I located the unorganized body signal in the short wave. It was no good for anything except his position. I kept track of him that way for two hours and plotted the results on the map.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a yellowed square of parchment in his hip pocket -- a relic of the unsuccessful First Expedition -- and he slapped it down on the desk with vicious force, spreading it flat with the palm of his hand. Powell, hands clasped across his chest, watched it at long range.\par
\tab Donovan\rquote s pencil pointed nervously. \ldblquote The red cross is the selenium pool. You marked it yourself.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Which one is it?\rdblquote  interrupted Powell. \ldblquote There were three that MacDougal located for us before he left.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I sent Speedy to the nearest, naturally; seventeen miles away. But what difference does that make?\rdblquote  There was tension in his voice. \ldblquote There are the penciled dots that mark Speedy\rquote s position.\rdblquote\par
\tab And for the first time Powell\rquote s artificial aplomb was shaken and his hands shot forward for the map.\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you serious? This is impossible.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There it is,\rdblquote  growled Donovan.\par
\tab The little dots that marked the position formed a rough circle about the red cross of the selenium pool. And Powell\rquote s fingers went to his brown mustache, the unfailing signal of anxiety.\par
\tab Donovan added: \ldblquote In the two hours I checked on him, he circled that damned pool four times. It seems likely to me that he\rquote ll keep that up forever. Do you realize the position we\rquote re in?\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell looked up shortly, and said nothing. Oh, yes, he realized the position they were in. It worked itself out as simply as a syllogism. The photocell banks that alone stood between the full power of Mercury\rquote s monstrous sun and themselves were shot to hell. \par
\tab The only thing that could save them was selenium. The only thing that could get the selenium was Speedy. If Speedy didn\rquote t come back, no selenium. No selenium, no photocell banks. No photo-banks -- well, death by slow broiling is one of the more unpleasant ways of being done in.\par
\tab Donovan rubbed his red mop of hair savagely and expressed himself with bitterness. \ldblquote We\rquote ll be the laughingstock of the System, Greg. How can everything have gone so wrong so soon? The great team of Powell and Donovan is sent out to Mercury to report on the advisability of reopening the Sunside Mining Station with modern techniques and robots and we ruin everything the first day. A purely routine job, too. We\rquote ll never live it down.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We won\rquote t have to, perhaps,\rdblquote  replied Powell, quietly. \ldblquote If we don\rquote t do something quickly, living anything down -- or even just plain living -- will be out of the question.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t be stupid! If you feel funny about it, Greg, I don\rquote t. It was criminal, sending us out here with only one robot. And it was your bright idea that we could handle the photocell banks ourselves.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Now you\rquote re being unfair. It was a mutual decision and you know it. All we needed was a kilogram of selenium, a Stillhead Dielectrode Plate and about three hours\rquote  time and there are pools of pure selenium all over Sunside. MacDougal\rquote s spectroreflector spotted three for us in five minutes, didn\rquote t it? What the devil! We couldn\rquote t have waited for next conjunction.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, what are we going to do? Powell, you\rquote ve got an idea. I know you have, or you wouldn\rquote t be so calm. You\rquote re no more a hero than I am. Go on, spill it!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We can\rquote t go after Speedy ourselves, Mike -- not on the Sunside. Even the new insosuits aren\rquote t good for more than twenty minutes in direct sunlight. But you know the old saying, \lquote Set a robot to catch a robot\rquote  Look, Mike, maybe things aren\rquote t so bad. We\rquote ve got six robots down in the sublevels, that we may be able to use, if they work. If they work.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a glint of sudden hope in Donovan\rquote s eyes. \ldblquote You mean six robots from the First Expedition. Are you sure? They may be subrobotic machines. Ten years is a long time as far as robot-types are concerned, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, they\rquote re robots. I\rquote ve spent all day with them and I know. They\rquote ve got positronic brains: primitive, of course.\rdblquote  He placed the map in his pocket. \ldblquote Let\rquote s go down.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab The robots were on the lowest sublevel -- all six of them surrounded by musty packing cases of uncertain content. They were large, extremely so, and even though they were in a sitting position on the floor, legs straddled out before them, their heads were a good seven feet in the air.\par
\tab Donovan whistled. \ldblquote Look at the size of them, will you? The chests must be ten feet around.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s because they\rquote re supplied with the old McGuffy gears. I\rquote ve been over the insides -- crummiest set you\rquote ve ever seen.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Have you powered them yet?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. There wasn\rquote t any reason to. I don\rquote t think there\rquote s anything wrong with them. Even the diaphragm is in reasonable order. They might talk.\rdblquote\par
\tab He had unscrewed the chest plate of the nearest as he spoke, inserted the two-inch sphere that contained the tiny spark of atomic energy that was a robot\rquote s life. There was difficulty in fitting it, but he managed, and then screwed the plate back on again in laborious fashion. The radio controls of more modern models had not been heard of ten years earlier. And then to the other five.\par
\tab Donovan said uneasily, \ldblquote They haven\rquote t moved.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No orders to do so,\rdblquote  replied Powell, succinctly. He went back to the first in the line and struck him on the chest. \ldblquote You! Do you hear me?\rdblquote\par
\tab The monster\rquote s head bent slowly and the eyes fixed themselves on Powell. Then, in a harsh, squawking voice -- like that of a medieval phonograph, he grated, \ldblquote Yes, Master!\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell grinned humorlessly at Donovan. \ldblquote Did you get that? Those were the days of the first talking robots when it looked as if the use of robots on Earth would be banned. The makers were fighting that and they built good, healthy slave complexes into the damned machines.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It didn\rquote t help them,\rdblquote  muttered Donovan.\par
\tab\ldblquote No, it didn\rquote t, but they sure tried.\rdblquote  He turned once more to the robot. \ldblquote Get up!\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot towered upward slowly and Donovan\rquote s head craned and his puckered lips whistled.\par
\tab Powell said: \ldblquote Can you go out upon the surface? In the light?\rdblquote\par
\tab There was consideration while the robot\rquote s slow brain worked. Then, \ldblquote Yes, Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good. Do you know what a mile is?\rdblquote\par
\tab Another consideration, and another slow answer. \ldblquote Yes, Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We will take you up to the surface then, and indicate a direction. You will go about seventeen miles, and somewhere in that general region you will meet another robot, smaller than yourself. You understand so far?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You will find this robot and order him to return. If he does not wish to, you are to bring him back by force.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan clutched at Powell\rquote s sleeve. \ldblquote Why not send him for the selenium direct?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because I want Speedy back, nitwit. I want to find out what\rquote s wrong with him.\rdblquote  And to the robot, \ldblquote All right, you, follow me.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot remained motionless and his voice rumbled: \ldblquote Pardon, Master, but I cannot. You must mount first.\rdblquote  His clumsy arms had come together with a thwack, blunt fingers interlacing.\par
\tab Powell stared and then pinched at his mustache. \ldblquote Uh... oh!\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan\rquote s eyes bulged. \ldblquote We\rquote ve got to ride him? Like a horse?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I guess that\rquote s the idea. I don\rquote t know why, though. I can\rquote t see -- Yes, I do. I told you they were playing up robot-safety in those days. Evidently, they were going to sell the notion of safety by not allowing them to move about, without a mahout on their shoulders all the time. What do we do now?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s what I\rquote ve been thinking,\rdblquote  muttered Donovan. \ldblquote We can\rquote t go out on the surface, with a robot or without. Oh, for the love of Pete\rdblquote  -- and he snapped his fingers twice. He grew excited. \ldblquote Give me that map you\rquote ve got. I haven\rquote t studied it for two hours for nothing. This is a Mining Station. What\rquote s wrong with using the tunnels?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Mining Station was a black circle on the map, and the light dotted lines that were tunnels stretched out about it in spider web fashion.\par
\tab Donovan studied the list of symbols at the bottom of the map. \ldblquote Look,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote the small black dots are openings to the surface, and here\rquote s one maybe three miles away from the selenium pool. There\rquote s a number here -- you\rquote d think they\rquote d write larger -- 13a. If the robots know their way around here-\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell shot the question and received the dull \ldblquote Yes, Master,\rdblquote  in reply. \ldblquote Get your insosuit,\rdblquote  he said with satisfaction.\par
\tab It was the first time either had worn the insosuits -- which marked one time more than either had expected to upon their arrival the day before -- and they tested their limb movements uncomfortably.\par
\tab The insosuit was far bulkier and far uglier than the regulation spacesuit; but withal considerably lighter, due to the fact that they were entirely nonmetallic in composition. Composed of heat-resistant plastic and chemically treated cork layers, and equipped with a desiccating unit to keep the air bone-dry, the insosuits could withstand the full glare of Mercury\rquote s sun for twenty minutes. Five to ten minutes more, as well, without actually killing the occupant.\par
\tab And still the robot\rquote s hands formed the stirrup, nor did he betray the slightest atom of surprise at the grotesque figure into which Powell had been converted.\par
\tab Powell\rquote s radio-harshened voice boomed out: \ldblquote Are you ready to take us to Exit 13a?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab Good, thought Powell; they might lack radio control but at least they were fitted for radio reception. \ldblquote Mount one or the other, Mike,\rdblquote  he said to Donovan.\par
\tab He placed a foot in the improvised stirrup and swung upward. He found the seat comfortable; there was the humped back of the robot, evidently shaped for the purpose, a shallow groove along each shoulder for the thighs and two elongated \ldblquote ears\rdblquote  whose purpose now seemed obvious.\par
\tab Powell seized the ears and twisted the head. His mount turned ponderously. \ldblquote Lead on, Macduff.\rdblquote  But he did not feel at all lighthearted.\par
\tab The gigantic robots moved slowly, with mechanical precision, through the doorway that cleared their heads by a scant foot, so that the two men had to duck hurriedly, along a narrow corridor in which their unhurried footsteps boomed monotonously and into the, air lock.\par
\tab The long, airless tunnel that stretched to a pinpoint before them brought home forcefully to Powell the exact magnitude of the task accomplished by the First Expedition, with their crude robots and their start-from-scratch necessities. They might have been a failure, but their failure was a good deal better than the usual run of the System\rquote s successes.\par
\tab The robots plodded onward with a pace that never varied and with footsteps that never lengthened.\par
\tab Powell said: \ldblquote Notice that these tunnels are blazing with lights and that the temperature is Earth-normal. It\rquote s probably been like this all the ten years that this place has remained empty.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How\rquote s that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Cheap energy; cheapest in the System. Sunpower, you know, and on Mercury\rquote s Sunside, sunpower is something. That\rquote s why the Station was built in the sunlight rather than in the shadow of a mountain. It\rquote s really a huge energy converter. The heat is turned into electricity, light, mechanical work and what have you; so that energy is supplied and the Station is cooled in a simultaneous process.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Look,\rdblquote  said Donovan. \ldblquote This is all very educational, but would you mind changing the subject? It so happens that this conversion of energy that you talk about is carried on by the photocell banks mainly -- and that is a tender subject with me at the moment.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell grunted vaguely, and when Donovan broke the resulting silence, it was to change the subject completely. \ldblquote Listen, Greg. What the devil\rquote s wrong with Speedy, anyway? I can\rquote t understand it.\rdblquote\par
\tab It\rquote s not easy to shrug shoulders in an insosuit, but Powell tried it. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know, Mike. You know he\rquote s perfectly adapted to a Mercurian environment. Heat doesn\rquote t mean anything to him and he\rquote s built for the light gravity and the broken ground. He\rquote s foolproof -- or, at least, he should be.\rdblquote\par
\tab Silence fell. This time, silence that lasted.\par
\tab\ldblquote Master,\rdblquote  said the robot, \ldblquote we are here.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Eh?\rdblquote  Powell snapped out of a semidrowse. \ldblquote Well, get us out of here -- out to the surface.\rdblquote\par
\tab They found themselves in a tiny substation, empty, airless, ruined. Donovan had inspected a jagged hole in the upper reaches of one of the walls by the light of his pocket flash.\par
\tab\ldblquote Meteorite, do you suppose?\rdblquote  he had asked.\par
\tab Powell shrugged. \ldblquote To hell with that. It doesn\rquote t matter. Let\rquote s get out.\rdblquote\par
\tab A towering cliff of a black, basaltic rock cut off the sunlight, and the deep night shadow of an airless world surrounded them. Before them, the shadow reached out and ended in knife-edge abruptness into an all-but-unbearable blaze of white light, that glittered from myriad crystals along a rocky ground.\par
\tab\ldblquote Space!\rdblquote  gasped Donovan. \ldblquote It looks like snow.\rdblquote  And it did.\par
\tab Powell\rquote s eyes swept the jagged glitter of Mercury to the horizon and winced at the gorgeous brilliance.\par
\tab\ldblquote This must be an unusual area,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote The general albedo of Mercury is low and most of the soil is gray pumice. Something like the Moon, you know. Beautiful, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\par
\tab He was thankful for the light filters in their visiplates. Beautiful or not, a look at the sunlight through straight glass would have blinded them inside of half a minute.\par
\tab Donovan was looking at the spring thermometer on his wrist. \ldblquote Holy smokes, the temperature is eighty centigrade!\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell checked his own and said: \ldblquote Um-m-m. A little high. Atmosphere, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote On Mercury? Are you nuts?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Mercury isn\rquote t really airless,\rdblquote  explained Powell, in absentminded fashion. He was adjusting the binocular attachments to his visiplate, and the bloated fingers of the insosuit were clumsy at it. \ldblquote There is a thin exhalation that clings to its surface -- vapors of the more volatile elements and compounds that are heavy enough for Mercurian gravity to retain. You know: selenium, iodine, mercury, gallium, potassium, bismuth, volatile oxides. The vapors sweep into the shadows and condense, giving up heat. It\rquote s a sort of gigantic still. In fact, if you use your flash, you\rquote ll probably find that the side of the cliff is covered with, say, hoar-sulphur, or maybe quicksilver dew.\par
\tab\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter, though. Our suits can stand a measly eighty indefinitely.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell had adjusted the binocular attachments, so that he seemed as eye-stalked as a snail.\par
\tab Donovan watched tensely. \ldblquote See anything?\rdblquote\par
\tab The other did not answer immediately, and when he did, his voice was anxious and thoughtful. \ldblquote There\rquote s a dark spot on the horizon that might be the selenium pool. It\rquote s in the right place. But I don\rquote t see Speedy.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell clambered upward in an instinctive striving for better view, till he was standing in unsteady fashion upon his robot\rquote s shoulders. Legs straddled wide, eyes straining, he said: \ldblquote I think... I think -- Yes, it\rquote s definitely he. He\rquote s coming this way.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan followed the pointing finger. He had no binoculars, but there was a tiny moving dot, black against the blazing brilliance of the crystalline ground.\par
\tab\ldblquote I see him,\rdblquote  he yelled. \ldblquote Let\rquote s get going!\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell had hopped down into a sitting position on the robot again, and his suited hand slapped against the Gargantuan\rquote s barrel chest. \ldblquote Get going!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Giddy-ap,\rdblquote  yelled Donovan, and thumped his heels, spur fashion.\par
\tab The robots started off, the regular thudding of their footsteps silent in the airlessness, for the nonmetallic fabric of the insosuits did not transmit sound. There was only a rhythmic vibration just below the border of actual hearing.\par
\tab\ldblquote Faster,\rdblquote  yelled Donovan. The rhythm did not change.\par
\tab\ldblquote No use,\rdblquote  cried Powell, in reply. \ldblquote These junk heaps are only geared to one speed. Do you think they\rquote re equipped with selective flexors?\rdblquote\par
\tab They had burst through the shadow, and the sunlight came down in a white-hot wash and poured liquidly about them.\par
\tab Donovan ducked involuntarily. \ldblquote Wow! Is it imagination or do I feel heat?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ll feel more presently,\rdblquote  was the grim reply. \ldblquote Keep your eye on Speedy.\rdblquote\par
\tab Robot SPD 13 was near enough to be seen in detail now. His graceful, streamlined body threw out blazing highlights as he loped with easy speed across the broken ground. His name was derived from his serial initials, of course, but it was apt, nevertheless, for the SPD models were among the fastest robots turned out by the United States Robot & Mechanical Men Corp.\par
\tab\ldblquote Hey, Speedy,\rdblquote  howled Donovan, and waved a frantic hand.\par
\tab\ldblquote Speedy!\rdblquote  shouted Powell. \ldblquote Come here!\rdblquote\par
\tab The distance between the men and the errant robot was being cut down momentarily -- more by the efforts of Speedy than the slow plodding of the fifty-year-old antique mounts of Donovan and Powell.\par
\tab They were close enough now to notice that Speedy\rquote s gait included a peculiar rolling stagger, a noticeable side-to-side lurch -- and then, as Powell waved his hand again and sent maximum juice into his compact headset radio sender, in preparation for another shout, Speedy looked up and saw them.\par
\tab Speedy hopped to a halt and remained standing for a moment with just a tiny, unsteady weave, as though he were swaying in a light wind.\par
\tab Powell yelled: \ldblquote All right, Speedy. Come here, boy.\rdblquote\par
\tab Whereupon Speedy\rquote s robot voice sounded in Powell\rquote s earphones for the first time.\par
\tab It said: \ldblquote Hot dog, let\rquote s play games. You catch me and I catch you; no love can cut our knife in two. For I\rquote m Little Buttercup, sweet Little Buttercup. Whoops!\rdblquote  Turning on his heel, he sped off in the direction from which he had come, with a speed and fury that kicked up gouts of baked dust.\par
\tab And his last words as he receded into the distance were, \ldblquote There grew a little flower \lquote neath a great oak tree,\rdblquote  followed by a curious metallic clicking that might have been a robotic equivalent of a hiccup.\par
\tab Donovan said weakly: \ldblquote Where did he pick up the Gilbert and Sullivan? Say, Greg, he... he\rquote s drunk or something.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If you hadn\rquote t told me,\rdblquote  was the bitter response, \ldblquote I\rquote d never realize it. Let\rquote s get back to the cliff. I\rquote m roasting.\rdblquote\par
\tab It was Powell who broke the desperate silence. \ldblquote In the first place,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote Speedy isn\rquote t drunk -- not in the human sense -- because he\rquote s a robot, and robots don\rquote t get drunk. However, there\rquote s something wrong with him which is the robotic equivalent of drunkenness\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To me, he\rquote s drunk,\rdblquote  stated Donovan, emphatically, \ldblquote and all I know is that he thinks we\rquote re playing games. And we\rquote re not. It\rquote s a matter of life and very gruesome death.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. Don\rquote t hurry me. A robot\rquote s only a robot. Once we find out what\rquote s wrong with him, we can fix it and go on.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Once,\rdblquote  said Donovan, sourly.\par
\tab Powell ignored him. \ldblquote Speedy is perfectly adapted to normal Mercurian environment. But this region\rdblquote  -- and his arm swept wide -- \ldblquote is definitely abnormal. There\rquote s our clue. Now where do these crystals come from? They might have formed from a slowly cooling liquid; but where would you get liquid so hot that it would cool in Mercury\rquote s sun?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Volcanic action,\rdblquote  suggested Donovan, instantly, and Powell\rquote s body tensed.\par
\tab\ldblquote Out of the mouths of sucklings,\rdblquote  he said in a small, strange voice and remained very still for five minutes.\par
\tab Then, he said, \ldblquote Listen, Mike, what did you say to Speedy when you sent him after the selenium?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan was taken aback. \ldblquote Well damn it -- I don\rquote t know. I just told him to get it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I know, but how? Try to remember the exact words.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I said... uh... I said: \lquote Speedy, we need some selenium. You can get it such-and-such a place. Go get it -- that\rquote s all. What more did you want me to say?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You didn\rquote t put any urgency into the order, did you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What for? It was pure routine.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell sighed. \ldblquote Well, it can\rquote t be helped now -- but we\rquote re in a fine fix.\rdblquote  He had dismounted from his robot, and was sitting, back against the cliff. Donovan joined him and they linked arms: In the distance the burning sunlight seemed to wait cat-and-mouse for them, and just next them, the two giant robots were invisible but for the dull red of their photoelectric eyes that stared down at them, unblinking, unwavering and unconcerned.\par
\tab Unconcerned! As was all this poisonous Mercury, as large in jinx as it was small in size.\par
\tab Powell\rquote s radio voice was tense in Donovan\rquote s ear: \ldblquote Now, look, let\rquote s start with the three fundamental Rules of Robotics -- the three rules that are built most deeply into a robot\rquote s positronic brain.\rdblquote  In the darkness, his gloved fingers ticked off each point.\par
\tab\ldblquote We have: One, a robot may not injure a human being, or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Right!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Two,\rdblquote  continued Powell, \ldblquote a robot must obey the orders given it by human beings except where such orders would conflict with the First Law.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Right\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And three, a robot must protect its own existence as long as such protection does not conflict with the First or Second Laws.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Right! Now where are we?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly at the explanation. The conflict between the various rules is ironed out by the different positronic potentials in the brain. We\rquote ll say that a robot is walking into danger and knows it. The automatic potential that Rule 3 sets up turns him back. But suppose you order him to walk into that danger. In that case, Rule 2 sets up a counterpotential higher than the previous one and the robot follows orders at the risk of existence.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, I know that. What about it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Let\rquote s take Speedy\rquote s case. Speedy is one of the latest models, extremely specialized, and as expensive as a battleship. It\rquote s not a thing to be lightly destroyed\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So Rule 3 has been strengthened -- that was specifically mentioned, by the way, in the advance notices on the SPD models -- so that his allergy to danger is unusually high. At the same time, when you sent him out after the selenium, you gave him his order casually and without special emphasis, so that the Rule 2 potential set-up was rather weak. Now, hold on; I\rquote m just stating facts.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right, go ahead. I think I get it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You see how it works, don\rquote t you? There\rquote s some sort of danger centering at the selenium pool. It increases as he approaches, and at a certain distance from it the Rule 3 potential, unusually high to start with, exactly balances the Rule 2 potential, unusually low to start with.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan rose to his feet in excitement. \ldblquote  And it strikes an equilibrium. I see. Rule 3 drives him back and Rule 2 drives him forward-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So he follows a circle around the selenium pool, staying on the locus of all points of potential equilibrium. And unless we do something about it, he\rquote ll stay on that circle forever, giving us the good old runaround.\rdblquote  Then, more thoughtfully: \ldblquote And that, by the way, is what makes him drunk. At potential equilibrium, half the positronic paths of his brain are out of kilter. I\rquote m not a robot specialist, but that seems obvious. Probably he\rquote s lost control of just those parts of his voluntary mechanism that a human drunk has. Ve-e-ery pretty.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But what\rquote s the danger? If we knew what he was running from-\rdblquote ?\par
\tab\ldblquote You suggested it. Volcanic action. Somewhere right above the selenium pool is a seepage of gas from the bowels of Mercury. Sulphur dioxide, carbon dioxide -- and carbon monoxide. Lots of it and at this temperature.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan gulped audibly. \ldblquote Carbon monoxide plus iron gives the volatile iron carbonyl.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And a robot,\rdblquote  added Powell, \ldblquote is essentially iron.\rdblquote  Then, grimly: \ldblquote There\rquote s nothing like deduction. We\rquote ve determined everything about our problem but the solution. We can\rquote t get the selenium ourselves. It\rquote s still too far. We can\rquote t send these robot horses, because they can\rquote t go themselves, and they can\rquote t carry us fast enough to keep us from crisping. And we can\rquote t catch Speedy, because the dope thinks we\rquote re playing games, and he can run sixty miles to our four.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If one of us goes,\rdblquote  began Donovan, tentatively, \ldblquote and comes back cooked, there\rquote ll still be the other.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  came the sarcastic reply, \ldblquote it would be a most tender sacrifice -- except that a person would be in no condition to give orders before he ever reached the pool, and I don\rquote t think the robots would ever turn back to the cliff without orders. Figure it out! We\rquote re two or three miles from the pool -- call it two -- the robot travels at four miles an hour; and we can last twenty minutes in our suits. It isn\rquote t only the heat, remember. Solar radiation out here in the ultraviolet and below is poison.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Um-m-m,\rdblquote  said Donovan, \ldblquote ten minutes short.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote As good as an eternity. And another thing, in order for Rule 3 potential to have stopped Speedy where it did, there must be an appreciable amount of carbon monoxide in the metal-vapor atmosphere -- and there must be an appreciable corrosive action therefore. He\rquote s been out hours now -- and how do we know when a knee joint, for instance, won\rquote t be thrown out of kilter and keel him over. It\rquote s not only a question of thinking -- we\rquote ve got to think fast!\rdblquote\par
\tab Deep, dark, dank, dismal silence!\par
\tab Donovan broke it, voice trembling in an effort to keep itself emotionless. He said: \ldblquote As long as we can\rquote t increase Rule 2 potential by giving further orders, how about working the other way? If we increase the danger, we increase Rule 3 potential and drive him backward.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell\rquote s visiplate had turned toward him in a silent question.\par
\tab\ldblquote You see,\rdblquote  came the cautious explanation, \ldblquote all we need to do to drive him out of his rut is to increase the concentration of carbon monoxide in his vicinity. Well, back at the Station there\rquote s a complete analytical laboratory.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Naturally,\rdblquote  assented Powell. \ldblquote It\rquote s a Mining Station.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. There must be pounds of oxalic acid for calcium precipitations.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Holy space! Mike, you\rquote re a genius.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So-so,\rdblquote  admitted Donovan, modestly. \ldblquote It\rquote s just a case of remembering that oxalic acid on heating decomposes into carbon dioxide, water, and good old carbon monoxide. College chem, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell was on his feet and had attracted the attention of one of the monster robots by the simple expedient of pounding the machine\rquote s thigh.\par
\tab\ldblquote Hey,\rdblquote  he shouted, \ldblquote can you throw?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Master?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind.\rdblquote  Powell damned the robot\rquote s molasses-slow brain. He scrabbled up a jagged brick-size rock. \ldblquote Take this,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote and hit the patch of bluish crystals just across the crooked fissure. You see it?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan pulled at his shoulder. \ldblquote Too far, Greg. It\rquote s almost half a mile off.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Quiet,\rdblquote  replied Powell. \ldblquote It\rquote s a case of Mercurian gravity and a steel throwing arm. Watch, will you?\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot\rquote s eyes were measuring the distance with machinely accurate stereoscopy. His arm adjusted itself to the weight of the missile and drew back. In the darkness, the robot\rquote s motions went unseen, but there was a sudden thumping sound as he shifted his weight, and seconds later the rock flew blackly into the sunlight. There was no air resistance to slow it down, nor wind to turn it aside -- and when it hit the ground it threw up crystals precisely in the center of the \ldblquote blue patch.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell yelled happily and shouted, \ldblquote Let\rquote s go back after the oxalic acid, Mike.\rdblquote\par
\tab And as they plunged into the ruined substation on the way back to the tunnels, Donovan said grimly: \ldblquote Speedy\rquote s been hanging about on this side of the selenium pool, ever since we chased after him. Did you see him?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I guess he wants to play games. Well, we\rquote ll play him games!\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab They were back hours later, with three-liter jars of the white chemical and a pair of long faces. The photocell banks were deteriorating more rapidly than had seemed likely. The two steered their robots into the sunlight and toward the waiting Speedy in silence and with grim purpose.\par
\tab Speedy galloped slowly toward them. \ldblquote Here we are again. Whee! I\rquote ve made a little list, the piano organist; all people who eat peppermint and puff it in your face.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ll puff something in your face,\rdblquote  muttered Donovan. \ldblquote He\rquote s limping, Greg.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I noticed that,\rdblquote  came the low, worried response. \ldblquote The monoxide\rquote ll get him yet, if we don\rquote t hurry.\rdblquote\par
\tab They were approaching cautiously now, almost sidling, to refrain from setting off the thoroughly irrational robot. Powell was too far off to tell, of course, but even already he could have sworn the crack-brained Speedy was setting himself for a spring.\par
\tab\ldblquote Let her go,\rdblquote  he gasped. \ldblquote Count three! One- two-\rdblquote\par
\tab Two steel arms drew back and snapped forward simultaneously and two glass jars whirled forward in towering parallel arcs, gleaming like diamonds in the impossible sun. And in a pair of soundless puffs, they hit the ground behind Speedy in crashes that sent the oxalic acid flying like dust.\par
\tab In the full heat of Mercury\rquote s sun, Powell knew it was fizzing like soda water.\par
\tab Speedy turned to stare, then backed away from it slowly -- and as slowly gathered speed. In fifteen seconds, he was leaping directly toward the two humans in an unsteady canter.\par
\tab Powell did not get Speedy\rquote s words just then, though he heard something that resembled, \ldblquote Lover\rquote s professions when uttered in Hessians.\rdblquote\par
\tab He turned away. \ldblquote Back to the cliff, Mike. He\rquote s out of the rut and he\rquote ll be taking orders now. I\rquote m getting hot.\rdblquote\par
\tab They jogged toward the shadow at the slow monotonous pace of their mounts, and it was not until they had entered it and felt the sudden coolness settle softly about them that Donovan looked back. \ldblquote Greg!\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell looked and almost shrieked. Speedy was moving slowly now -- so slowly -- and in the wrong direction. He was drifting; drifting back into his rut; and he was picking up speed. He looked dreadfully close, and dreadfully unreachable, in the binoculars.\par
\tab Donovan shouted wildly, \ldblquote After him!\rdblquote  and thumped his robot into its pace, but Powell called him back.\par
\tab\ldblquote You won\rquote t catch him, Mike -- it\rquote s no use.\rdblquote  He fidgeted on his robot\rquote s shoulders and clenched his fist in tight impotence. \ldblquote Why the devil do I see these things five seconds after it\rquote s all over? Mike, we\rquote ve wasted hours.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We need more oxalic acid,\rdblquote  declared Donovan, stolidly. \ldblquote The concentration wasn\rquote t high enough.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Seven tons of it wouldn\rquote t have been enough -- and we haven\rquote t the hours to spare to get it, even if it were, with the monoxide chewing him away. Don\rquote t you see what it is, Mike?\rdblquote\par
\tab And Donovan said flatly, \ldblquote No.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We were only establishing new equilibriums. When we create new monoxide and increase Rule 3 potential, he moves backward till he\rquote s in balance again -- and when the monoxide drifted away, he moved forward, and again there was balance.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell\rquote s voice sounded thoroughly wretched. \ldblquote It\rquote s the same old runaround. We can push at Rule 2 and pull at Rule 3 and we can\rquote t get anywhere -- we can only change the position of balance. We\rquote ve got to get outside both rules.\rdblquote  And then he pushed his robot closer to Donovan\rquote s so that they were sitting face-to-face, dim shadows in the darkness, and he whispered, \ldblquote Mike!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is it the finish?\rdblquote  -- dully. \ldblquote I suppose we go back to the Station, wait for the banks to fold, shake hands, take cyanide, and go out like gentlemen.\rdblquote  He laughed shortly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Mike,\rdblquote  repeated Powell earnestly, \ldblquote we\rquote ve got to get Speedy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Mike,\rdblquote  once more, and Powell hesitated before continuing. \ldblquote There\rquote s always Rule 1. I thought of it -- earlier -- but it\rquote s desperate.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan looked up and his voice livened. \ldblquote We\rquote re desperate.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. According to Rule 1, a robot can\rquote t see a human come to harm because of his own inaction. Two and 3 can\rquote t stand against it. They can\rquote t, Mike.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Even when the robot is half cra- Well, he\rquote s drunk. You know he is.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s the chances you take.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Cut it. What are you going to do?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m going out there now and see what Rule 1 will do. If it won\rquote t break the balance, then what the devil -- it\rquote s either now or three-four days from now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hold on, Greg. There are human rules of behavior, too. You don\rquote t go out there just like that. Figure out a lottery, and give me my chance.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. First to get the cube of fourteen goes.\rdblquote  And almost immediately, \ldblquote Twenty-seven forty-four!\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan felt his robot stagger at a sudden push by Powell\rquote s mount and then Powell was off into the sunlight. Donovan opened his mouth to shout, and then clicked it shut. Of course, the damn fool had worked out the cube of fourteen in advance, and on purpose. Just like him.\par
\par
\tab The sun was hotter than ever and Powell felt a maddening itch in the small of his back. Imagination, probably, or perhaps hard radiation beginning to tell even through the insosuit.\par
\tab Speedy was watching him, without a word of Gilbert and Sullivan gibberish as greeting. Thank God for that! But he daren\rquote t get too close.\par
\tab He was three hundred yards away when Speedy began backing, a step at a time, cautiously -- and Powell stopped. He jumped from his robot\rquote s shoulders and landed on the crystalline ground with a light thump and a flying of jagged fragments.\par
\tab He proceeded on foot, the ground gritty and slippery to his steps, the low gravity causing him difficulty. The soles of his feet tickled with warmth. He cast one glance over his shoulder at the blackness of the cliff\rquote s shadow and realized that he had come too far to return -- either by himself or by the help of his antique robot. It was Speedy or nothing now, and the knowledge of that constricted his chest.\par
\tab Far enough! He stopped.\par
\tab\ldblquote Speedy,\rdblquote  he called. \ldblquote Speedy!\rdblquote\par
\tab The sleek, modern robot ahead of him hesitated and halted his backward steps, then resumed them.\par
\tab Powell tried to put a note of pleading into his voice, and found it didn\rquote t take much acting. \ldblquote Speedy, I\rquote ve got to get back to the shadow or the sun\rquote ll get me. It\rquote s life or death, Speedy. I need you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Speedy took one step forward and stopped. He spoke, but at the sound Powell groaned, for it was, \ldblquote When you\rquote re lying awake with a dismal headache and repose is tabooed-\rdblquote  It trailed off there, and Powell took time out for some reason to murmur, \ldblquote Iolanthe.\rdblquote\par
\tab It was roasting hot! He caught a movement out of the corner of his eye, and whirled dizzily; then stared in utter astonishment, for the monstrous robot on which he had ridden was moving -- moving toward him, and without a rider.\par
\tab He was talking: \ldblquote Pardon, Master. I must not move without a Master upon me, but you are in danger.\rdblquote\par
\tab Of course, Rule 1 potential above everything. But he didn\rquote t want that clumsy antique; he wanted Speedy. He walked away and motioned frantically: \ldblquote I order you to stay away. I order you to stop!\rdblquote\par
\tab It was quite useless. You could not beat Rule 1 potential. The robot said stupidly, \ldblquote You are in danger, Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell looked about him desperately. He couldn\rquote t see clearly. His brain was in a heated whirl; his breath scorched when he breathed, and the ground all about him was a shimmering haze.\par
\tab He called a last time, desperately: \ldblquote Speedy! I\rquote m dying, damn you! Where are you? Speedy, I need you.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was still stumbling backward in a blind effort to get away from the giant robot he didn\rquote t want, when he felt steel fingers on his arms, and a worried, apologetic voice of metallic timbre in his ears.\par
\tab\ldblquote Holy smokes, boss; what are you doing here? And what am I doing -- I\rquote m so confused --\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind,\rdblquote  murmured Powell, weakly. \ldblquote Get me to the shadow of the cliff -- and hurry!\rdblquote  There was one last feeling of being lifted into the air and a sensation of rapid motion and burning heat, and he passed out.\par
\par
\tab He woke with Donovan bending over him and smiling anxiously. \ldblquote How are you, Greg?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Fine!\rdblquote  came the response, \ldblquote Where\rquote s Speedy?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Right here. I sent him out to one of the other selenium pools -- with orders to get that selenium at all cost this time. He got it back in forty-two minutes and three seconds. I timed him. He still hasn\rquote t finished apologizing for the runaround he gave us. He\rquote s scared to come near you for fear of what you\rquote ll say.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Drag him over,\rdblquote  ordered Powell. \ldblquote It wasn\rquote t his fault.\rdblquote  He held out a hand and gripped Speedy\rquote s metal paw. \ldblquote It\rquote s O.K., Speedy.\rdblquote  Then, to Donovan, \ldblquote You know, Mike, I was just thinking-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  -- he rubbed his face -- the air was so delightfully cool, \ldblquote you know that when we get things set up here and Speedy put through his Field Tests, they\rquote re going to send us to the Space Stations next-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes! At least that\rquote s what old lady Calvin told me just before we left, and I didn\rquote t say anything about it, because I was going to fight the whole idea.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Fight it?\rdblquote  cried Donovan. \ldblquote But -\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know. It\rquote s all right with me now. Two hundred seventy-three degrees Centigrade below zero. Won\rquote t it be a pleasure?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Space Station,\rdblquote  said Donovan, \ldblquote here I come.\rdblquote\par
