\scaps Half a year later, the boys had changed\scaps0  their minds. The flame of a giant sun had given way to the soft blackness of space but external variations mean little in the business of checking the workings of experimental robots. Whatever the background, one is face to face with an inscrutable positronic brain, which the slide-rule geniuses say should work thus-and-so.\par
\tab Except that they don\rquote t. Powell and Donovan found that out after they had been on the Station less than two weeks.\par
\tab Gregory Powell spaced his words for emphasis, \ldblquote One week ago, Donovan and I put you together.\rdblquote  His brows furrowed doubtfully and he pulled the end of his brown mustache.\par
\tab It was quiet in the officer\rquote s room on Solar Station #5 -- except for the soft purring of the mighty Beam Director somewhere far below.\par
\tab Robot QT-1 sat immovable. The burnished plates of his body gleamed in the Luxites and the glowing red of the photoelectric cells that were his eyes, were fixed steadily upon the Earthman at the other side of the table.\par
\tab Powell repressed a sudden attack of nerves. These robots possessed peculiar brains. Oh, the three Laws of Robotics held. They had to. All of U. S. Robots, from Robertson himself to the new floor-sweeper, would insist on that. So QT-1 was safe! And yet the QT models were the first of their kind, and this was the first of the QT\rquote s. Mathematical squiggles on paper were not always the most comforting protection against robotic fact.\par
\tab Finally, the robot spoke. His voice carried the cold timbre inseparable from a metallic diaphragm, \ldblquote Do you realize the seriousness of such a statement, Powell?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Something made you, Cutie,\rdblquote  pointed out Powell. \ldblquote You admit yourself that your memory seems to spring full-grown from an absolute blankness of a week ago. I\rquote m giving you the explanation. Donovan and I put you together from the parts shipped us.\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie gazed upon his long, supple fingers in an oddly human attitude of mystification, \ldblquote It strikes me that there should be a more satisfactory explanation than that. For you to make me seems improbable.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Earthman laughed quite suddenly, \ldblquote In Earth\rquote s name, why?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Call it intuition. That\rquote s all it is so far. But I intend to reason it out, though. A chain of valid reasoning can end only with the determination of truth, and I\rquote ll stick till I get there.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell stood up and seated himself at the table\rquote s edge next to the robot. He felt a sudden strong sympathy for this strange machine. It was not at all like the ordinary robot, attending to his specialized task at the station with the intensity of a deeply ingrooved positronic path.\par
\tab He placed a hand upon Cutie\rquote s steel shoulder and the metal was cold and hard to the touch.\par
\tab\ldblquote Cutie,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote I\rquote m going to try to explain something to you. You\rquote re the first robot who\rquote s ever exhibited curiosity as to his own existence -- and I think the first that\rquote s really intelligent enough to understand the world outside. Here, come with me.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot rose erect smoothly and his thickly sponge-rubber soled feet made no noise as he followed Powell. The Earthman touched a button and a square section of the wall flickered aside. The thick, clear glass revealed space -- star speckled.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve seen that in the observation ports in the engine room,\rdblquote  said Cutie.\par
\tab\ldblquote I know,\rdblquote  said Powell. \ldblquote What do you think it is?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly what it seems -- a black material just beyond this glass that is spotted with little gleaming dots. I know that our director sends out beams to some of these dots, always to the same ones -- and also that these dots shift and that the beams shift with them. That is all.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good! Now I want you to listen carefully. The blackness is emptiness vast emptiness stretching out infinitely. The little, gleaming dots are huge masses of energy-filled matter. They are globes, some of them millions of miles in diameter and for comparison; this station is only one mile across. They seem so tiny because they are incredibly far off.\par
\tab\ldblquote The dots to which our energy beams are directed are nearer and much smaller. They are cold and hard and human beings like myself live upon their surfaces -- many billions of them. It is from one of these worlds that Donovan and I come. Our beams feed these worlds energy drawn from one of those huge incandescent globes that happens to be near us. We call that globe the Sun and it is on the other side of the station where you can\rquote t see it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie remained motionless before the port, like a steel statue. His head did not turn as he spoke, \ldblquote Which particular dot of light do you claim to come from?\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell searched, \ldblquote There it is, the very bright one in the corner, we call it Earth.\rdblquote  He grinned. \ldblquote Good old Earth. There are three billions of us there, Cutie -- and in about two weeks I\rquote ll be back there with them\rdblquote\par
\tab And then, surprisingly enough, Cutie hummed abstractedly. There was no tune to it, but it possessed a curious twanging quality as of plucked strings. It ceased as suddenly as it had begun, \ldblquote But where do I come in, Powell? You haven\rquote t explained my existence.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The rest is simple. When these stations were first established to feed solar energy to the planets, they were run by humans. However, the heat, the hard solar radiations, and the electron storms made the post a difficult one. Robots were developed to replace human labor and now only two human executives are required for each station. We are trying to replace even those, and that\rquote s where you come in. You\rquote re the highest type of robot ever developed and if you show the ability to run this station independently, no human need ever come here again except to bring parts for repairs.\rdblquote\par
\tab His hand went up and the metal visi-lid snapped back into place. Powell returned to the table and polished an apple upon his sleeve before biting into it.\par
\tab The red glow of the robot\rquote s eyes held him. \ldblquote Do you expect me,\rdblquote  said Cutie slowly, \ldblquote to believe any such complicated, implausible hypothesis as you have just outlined? What do you take me for?\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell sputtered apple fragments onto the table and turned red. \ldblquote Why damn you, it wasn\rquote t a hypothesis. Those were facts\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie sounded grim, \ldblquote Globes of energy millions of miles across! Worlds with three billion humans on them! Infinite emptiness! Sorry, Powell, but I don\rquote t believe it. I\rquote ll puzzle this thing out for myself. Good-by.\rdblquote\par
\tab He turned and stalked out of the room. He brushed past Michael Donovan on the threshold with a grave nod and passed down the corridor, oblivious to the astounded stare that followed him.\par
\tab Mike Donovan rumpled his red hair and shot an annoyed glance at Powell, \ldblquote What was that walking junk yard talking about? What doesn\rquote t he believe?\rdblquote\par
\tab The other dragged at his mustache bitterly. \ldblquote He\rquote s a skeptic,\rdblquote  was the bitter response. \ldblquote He doesn\rquote t believe we made him or that Earth exists or space or stars.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sizzling Saturn, we\rquote ve got a lunatic robot on our hands.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He says he\rquote s going to figure it all out for himself.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, now,\rdblquote  said Donovan sweetly, \ldblquote I do hope he\rquote ll condescend to explain it all to me after he\rquote s puzzled everything out\rdblquote  Then, with sudden rage, \ldblquote Listen! If that metal mess gives me any lip like that, I\rquote ll knock that chromium cranium right off its torso.\rdblquote\par
\tab He seated himself with a jerk and drew a paper-backed mystery novel out of his inner jacket pocket, \ldblquote That robot gives me the willies anyway -- too damned inquisitive!\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Mike Donovan growled from behind a huge lettuce-and-tomato sandwich as Cutie knocked gently and entered.\par
\tab\ldblquote Is Powell here?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan\rquote s voice was muffled, with pauses for mastication, \ldblquote He\rquote s gathering data on electronic stream functions. We\rquote re heading for a storm, looks like.\rdblquote\par
\tab Gregory Powell entered as he spoke, eyes on the graphed paper in his hands, and dropped into a chair. He spread the sheets out before him and began scribbling calculations. Donovan stared over his shoulder, crunching lettuce and dribbling breadcrumbs. Cutie waited silently.\par
\tab Powell looked up, \ldblquote The Zeta Potential is rising, but slowly. Just the same, the stream functions are erratic and I don\rquote t know what to expect. Oh, hello, Cutie. I thought you were supervising the installation of the new drive bar.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s done,\rdblquote  said the robot quietly, \ldblquote and so I\rquote ve come to have a talk with the two of you\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh!\rdblquote  Powell looked uncomfortable. \ldblquote Well, sit down. No, not that chair. One of the legs is weak and you\rquote re no lightweight.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot did so and said placidly, \ldblquote I have come to a decision.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan glowered and put the remnants of his sandwich aside. \ldblquote If it\rquote s on any of that screwy-\rdblquote\par
\tab The other motioned impatiently for silence, \ldblquote Go ahead, Cutie. We\rquote re listening.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I have spent these last two days in concentrated introspection,\rdblquote  said Cutie, \ldblquote and the results have been most interesting. I began at the one sure assumption I felt permitted to make. I, myself, exist, because I think-\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell groaned, \ldblquote Oh, Jupiter, a robot Descartes!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Who\rquote s Descartes?\rdblquote  demanded Donovan. \ldblquote Listen, do we have to sit here and listen to this metal maniac-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Keep quiet, Mike!\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie continued imperturbably, \ldblquote And the question that immediately arose was: Just what is the cause of my existence?\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell\rquote s jaw set lumpily. \ldblquote You\rquote re being foolish. I told you already that we made you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And if you don\rquote t believe us,\rdblquote  added Donovan, \ldblquote we\rquote ll gladly take you apart!\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot spread his strong hands in a deprecatory gesture, \ldblquote I accept nothing on authority. A hypothesis must be backed by reason, or else it is worthless -- and it goes against all the dictates of logic to suppose that you made me.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell dropped a restraining arm upon Donovan\rquote s suddenly bunched fist. \ldblquote Just why do you say that?\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie laughed. It was a very inhuman laugh -- the most machine-like utterance he had yet given vent to. It was sharp and explosive, as regular as a metronome and as uninflected.\par
\tab\ldblquote Look at you,\rdblquote  he said finally. \ldblquote I say this in no spirit of contempt, but look at you! The material you are made of is soft and flabby, lacking endurance and strength, depending for energy upon the inefficient oxidation of organic material -- like that.\rdblquote  He pointed a disapproving finger at what remained of Donovan\rquote s sandwich. \ldblquote Periodically you pass into a coma and the least variation in temperature, air pressure, humidity, or radiation intensity impairs your efficiency. You are \i makeshift\i0 .\par
\tab\ldblquote I, on the other hand, am a finished product. I absorb electrical energy directly and utilize it with an almost one hundred percent efficiency. I am composed of strong metal, am continuously conscious, and can stand extremes of environment easily. These are facts which, with the self-evident proposition that no being can create another being superior to itself, smashes your silly hypothesis to nothing.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Donovan\rquote s muttered curses rose into intelligibility as he sprang to his feet, rusty eyebrows drawn low. \ldblquote All right, you son of a hunk of iron ore, if we didn\rquote t make you, who did?\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie nodded gravely. \ldblquote Very good, Donovan. That was indeed the next question. Evidently my creator must be more powerful than myself and so there was only one possibility.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Earthmen looked blank and Cutie continued, \ldblquote What is the center of activities here in the station? What do we all serve? What absorbs all our attention?\rdblquote  He waited expectantly.\par
\tab Donovan turned a startled look upon his companion. \ldblquote I\rquote ll bet this tinplated screwball is talking about the Energy Converter itself.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is that right, Cutie?\rdblquote  grinned Powell.\par
\tab\ldblquote I am talking about the Master,\rdblquote  came the cold, sharp answer.\par
\tab It was the signal for a roar of laughter from Donovan, and Powell himself dissolved into a half-suppressed giggle.\par
\tab Cutie had risen to his feet and his gleaming eyes passed from one Earthman to the other. \ldblquote It is so just the same and I don\rquote t wonder that you refuse to believe. You two are not long to stay here, I\rquote m sure. Powell himself said that at first only men served the Master; that there followed robots for the routine work; and, finally, myself for the executive labor. The facts are no doubt true, but the explanation entirely illogical. Do you want the truth behind it all?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Go ahead, Cutie. You\rquote re amusing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Master created humans first as the lowest type, most easily formed. Gradually, he replaced them by robots, the next higher step, and finally he created me to take the place of the last humans. From now on, I serve the Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ll do nothing of the sort,\rdblquote  said Powell sharply. \ldblquote You\rquote ll follow our orders and keep quiet, until we\rquote re satisfied that you can run the Converter. Get that! The Converter -- not the Master. If you don\rquote t satisfy us, you will be dismantled. And now -- if you don\rquote t mind -- you can leave. And take this data with you and file it properly.\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie accepted the graphs handed him and left without another word. Donovan leaned back heavily in his chair and shoved thick fingers through his hair.\par
\tab\ldblquote There\rquote s going to be trouble with that robot. He\rquote s pure nuts!\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab The drowsy hum of the Converter is louder in the control room and mixed with it is the chuckle of the Geiger Counters and the erratic buzzing of half a dozen little signal lights.\par
\tab Donovan withdrew his eye from the telescope and flashed the Luxites on. \ldblquote The beam from Station #4 caught Mars on schedule. We can break ours now.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell nodded abstractedly. \ldblquote Cutie\rquote s down in the engine room. I\rquote ll flash the signal and he can take care of it. Look, Mike, what do you think of these figures?\rdblquote\par
\tab The other cocked an eye at them and whistled. \ldblquote Boy, that\rquote s what I call gamma-ray intensity. Old Sol is feeling his oats, all right.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  was the sour response, \ldblquote and we\rquote re in a bad position for an electron storm, too. Our Earth beam is right in the probable path.\rdblquote  He shoved his chair away from the table pettishly. \ldblquote Nuts! If it would only hold off till relief got here, but that\rquote s ten days off. Say, Mike, go on down and keep an eye on Cutie, will you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote O.K. Throw me some of those almonds.\rdblquote  He snatched at the bag thrown him and headed for the elevator.\par
\tab It slid smoothly downward, and opened onto a narrow catwalk in the huge engine room. Donovan leaned over the railing and looked down. The huge generators were in motion and from the L-tubes came the low-pitched whir that pervaded the entire station.\par
\tab He could make out Cutie\rquote s large, gleaming figure at the Martian L-tube, watching closely as the team of robots worked in close-knit unison.\par
\tab And then Donovan stiffened. The robots, dwarfed by the mighty L-tube, lined up before it, heads bowed at a stiff angle, while Cutie walked up and down the line slowly. Fifteen seconds passed, and then, with a clank heard above the clamorous purring all about, they fell to their knees.\par
\tab Donovan squawked and raced down the narrow staircase. He came charging down upon them, complexion matching his hair and clenched fists beating the air furiously.\par
\tab\ldblquote What the devil is this, you brainless lumps? Come on! Get busy with that L-tube! If you don\rquote t have it apart, cleaned, and together again before the day is out, I\rquote ll coagulate your brains with alternating current.\rdblquote\par
\tab Not a robot moved!\par
\tab Even Cutie at the far end -- the only one on his feet -- remained silent, eyes fixed upon the gloomy recesses of the vast machine before him.\par
\tab Donovan shoved hard against the nearest robot.\par
\tab\ldblquote Stand up!\rdblquote  he roared.\par
\tab Slowly, the robot obeyed. His photoelectric eyes focused reproachfully upon the Earthman.\par
\tab\ldblquote There is no Master but the Master,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote and QT-1 is his prophet.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Huh?\rdblquote  Donovan became aware of twenty pairs of mechanical eyes fixed upon him and twenty stiff-timbered voices declaiming solemnly:\par
\tab\ldblquote There is no Master but the Master and QT-1 is his prophet!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid,\rdblquote  put in Cutie himself at this point, \ldblquote that my friends obey a higher one than you, now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The hell they do! You get out of here. I\rquote ll settle with you later and with these animated gadgets right now.\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie shook his heavy head slowly. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, but you don\rquote t understand. These are robots -- and that means they are reasoning beings. They recognize the Master, now that I have preached Truth to them. All the robots do. They call me the prophet.\rdblquote  His head drooped. \ldblquote I am unworthy -- but perhaps-\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan located his breath and put it to use. \ldblquote Is that so? Now, isn\rquote t that nice? Now, isn\rquote t that just fine? Just let me tell you something, my brass baboon. There isn\rquote t any Master and there isn\rquote t any prophet and there isn\rquote t any question as to who\rquote s giving the orders. Understand?\rdblquote  His voice shot to a roar. \ldblquote Now, get out!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I obey only the Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Damn the Master!\rdblquote  Donovan spat at the L-tube. \ldblquote That for the Master! Do as I say!\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie said nothing, nor did any other robot, but Donovan became aware of a sudden heightening of tension. The cold, staring eyes deepened their crimson, and Cutie seemed stiffer than ever.\par
\tab\ldblquote Sacrilege,\rdblquote  he whispered -- voice metallic with emotion.\par
\tab Donovan felt the first sudden touch of fear as Cutie approached. A robot could not feel anger -- but Cutie\rquote s eyes were unreadable.\par
\tab\ldblquote I am sorry, Donovan,\rdblquote  said the robot, \ldblquote but you can no longer stay here after this. Henceforth Powell and you are barred from the control room and the engine room.\rdblquote\par
\tab His hand gestured quietly and in a moment two robots had pinned Donovan\rquote s arms to his sides.\par
\tab Donovan had time for one startled gasp as he felt himself lifted from the floor and carried up the stairs at a pace rather better than a canter.\par
\par
\tab Gregory Powell raced up and down the officer\rquote s room, fist tightly balled. He cast a look of furious frustration at the closed door and scowled bitterly at Donovan.\par
\tab\ldblquote Why the devil did you have to spit at the L-tube?\rdblquote\par
\tab Mike Donovan, sunk deep in his chair, slammed at its arms savagely. \ldblquote What did you expect me to do with that electrified scarecrow? I\rquote m not going to knuckle under to any do-jigger I put together myself.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  came back sourly, \ldblquote but here you are in the officer\rquote s room with two robots standing guard at the door. That\rquote s not knuckling under, is it?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan snarled. \ldblquote Wait till we get back to Base. Someone\rquote s going to pay for this. Those robots must obey us. It\rquote s the Second Law.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s the use of saying that? They aren\rquote t obeying us. And there\rquote s probably some reason for it that we\rquote ll figure out too late. By the way, do you know what\rquote s going to happen to us when we get back to Base?\rdblquote  He stopped before Donovan\rquote s chair and stared savagely at him.\par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, nothing! Just back to Mercury Mines for twenty years. Or maybe Ceres Penitentiary.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What are you talking about?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The electron storm that\rquote s coming up. Do you know it\rquote s heading straight dead center across the Earth beam? I had just figured that out when that robot dragged me out of my chair.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan was suddenly pale. \ldblquote Sizzling Saturn.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And do you know what\rquote s going to happen to the beam -- because the storm will be a lulu. It\rquote s going to jump like a flea with the itch. With only Cutie at the controls, it\rquote s going to go out of focus and if it does, Heaven help Earth -- and us!\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan was wrenching at the door wildly, when Powell was only half through. The door opened, and the Earthman shot through to come up hard against an immovable steel arm.\par
\tab The robot stared abstractedly at the panting, struggling Earthman. \ldblquote The Prophet orders you to remain. Please do!\rdblquote  His arm shoved, Donovan reeled backward, and as he did so, Cutie turned the corner at the far end of the corridor. He motioned the guardian robots away, entered the officer\rquote s room and closed the door gently.\par
\tab Donovan whirled on Cutie in breathless indignation. \ldblquote This has gone far enough. You\rquote re going to pay for this farce.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Please, don\rquote t be annoyed,\rdblquote  replied the robot mildly. \ldblquote It was bound to come eventually, anyway. You see, you two have lost your function.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I beg your pardon,\rdblquote  Powell drew himself up stiffly. \ldblquote Just what do you mean, we\rquote ve lost our function?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Until I was created,\rdblquote  answered Cube, \ldblquote you tended the Master. That privilege is mine now and your only reason for existence has vanished. Isn\rquote t that obvious?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not quite,\rdblquote  replied Powell bitterly, \ldblquote but what do you expect us to do now?\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie did not answer immediately. He remained silent, as if in thought, and then one arm shot out and draped itself about Powell\rquote s shoulder. The other grasped Donovan\rquote s wrist and drew him closer.\par
\tab\ldblquote I like you two. You\rquote re inferior creatures, with poor reasoning faculties, but I really feel a sort of affection for you. You have served the Master well, and he will reward you for that. Now that your service is over, you will probably not exist much longer, but as long as you do, you shall be provided food, clothing and shelter, so long as you stay out of the control room and the engine room.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s pensioning us off, Greg!\rdblquote  yelled Donovan. \ldblquote Do something about it. It\rquote s humiliating!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Look here, Cutie, we can\rquote t stand for this. We\rquote re the bosses. This station is only a creation of human beings like me -- human beings that live on Earth and other planets. This is only an energy relay. You\rquote re only -- Aw, nuts!\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Cutie shook his head gravely. \ldblquote This amounts to an obsession. Why should you insist so on an absolutely false view of life? Admitted that non-robots lack the reasoning faculty, there is still the problem of-\rdblquote\par
\tab His voice died into reflective silence, and Donovan said with whispered intensity, \ldblquote If you only had a flesh-and-blood face, I would break it in.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell\rquote s fingers were in his mustache and his eyes were slitted. \ldblquote Listen, Cutie, if there is no such thing as Earth, how do you account for what you see through a telescope?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Pardon me!\rdblquote\par
\tab The Earthman smiled. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got you, eh? You\rquote ve made quite a few telescopic observations since being put together, Cutie. Have you noticed that several of those specks of light outside become disks when so viewed?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, that! Why certainly. It is simple magnification -- for the purpose of more exact aiming of the beam.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why aren\rquote t the stars equally magnified then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean the other dots. Well, no beams go to them so no magnification is necessary. Really, Powell, even you ought to be able to figure these things out.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell stared bleakly upward. \ldblquote But you see more stars through a telescope. Where do they come from? Jumping Jupiter, where do they come from?\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie was annoyed. \ldblquote Listen, Powell, do you think I\rquote m going to waste my time trying to pin physical interpretations upon every optical illusion of our instruments? Since when is the evidence of our senses any match for the clear light of rigid reason?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Look,\rdblquote  clamored Donovan, suddenly, writhing out from under Cutie\rquote s friendly, but metal-heavy arm, \ldblquote let\rquote s get to the nub of the thing. Why the beams at all? We\rquote re giving you a good, logical explanation. Can you do better?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The beams,\rdblquote  was the stiff reply, \ldblquote are put out by the Master for his own purposes. There are some things\rdblquote  -- he raised his eyes devoutly upward \ldblquote that are not to be probed into by us. In this matter, I seek only to serve and not to question.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell sat down slowly and buried his face in shaking hands. \ldblquote Get out of here, Cutie. Get out and let me think.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll send you food,\rdblquote  said Cutie agreeably.\par
\tab A groan was the only answer and the robot left.\par
\tab\ldblquote Greg,\rdblquote  was Donovan\rquote s huskily whispered observation, \ldblquote this calls for strategy. We\rquote ve got to get him when he isn\rquote t expecting it and short-circuit him. Concentrated nitric acid in his joints-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t be a dope, Mike. Do you suppose he\rquote s going to let us get near him with acid in our hands? We\rquote ve got to talk to him, I tell you. We\rquote ve got to argue him into letting us back into the control room inside of forty-eight hours or our goose is broiled to a crisp.\rdblquote\par
\tab He rocked back and forth in an agony of impotence. \ldblquote Who the heck wants to argue with a robot? It\rquote s... it\rquote s-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Mortifying,\rdblquote  finished Donovan.\par
\tab\ldblquote Worse!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Say!\rdblquote  Donovan laughed suddenly. \ldblquote Why argue? Let\rquote s show him! Let\rquote s build us another robot right before his eyes. He\rquote ll have to eat his words then.\rdblquote\par
\tab A slowly widening smile appeared on Powell\rquote s face.\par
\tab Donovan continued, \ldblquote And think of that screwball\rquote s face when he sees us do it?\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Robots are, of course, manufactured on Earth, but their shipment through apace is much simpler if it can be done in parts to be put together at their place of use. It also, incidentally, eliminates the possibility of robots, in complete adjustment, wandering off while still on Earth and thus bringing U. S. Robots face to face with the strict laws against robots on Earth.\par
\tab Still, it placed upon men such as Powell and Donovan the necessity of synthesis of complete robots, -- a grievous and complicated task.\par
\tab Powell and Donovan were never so aware of that fact as upon that particular day when, in the assembly room, they undertook to create a robot under the watchful eyes of QT-1, Prophet of the Master.\par
\tab The robot in question, a simple MC model, lay upon the table, almost complete. Three hours\rquote  work left only the head undone, and Powell paused to swab his forehead and glanced uncertainly at Cutie.\par
\tab The glance was not a reassuring one. For three hours, Cutie had sat, speechless and motionless, and his face, inexpressive at all times, was now absolutely unreadable.\par
\tab Powell groaned. \ldblquote Let\rquote s get the brain in now, Mike!\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan uncapped the tightly sealed container and from the oil bath within he withdrew a second cube. Opening this in turn, he removed a globe from its sponge-rubber casing.\par
\tab He handled it gingerly, for it was the most complicated mechanism ever created by man. Inside the thin platinum plated \ldblquote skin\rdblquote  of the globe was a positronic brain, in whose delicately unstable structure were enforced calculated neuronic paths, which imbued each robot with what amounted to a pre-natal education.\par
\tab It fitted snugly into the cavity in the skull of the robot on the table. Blue metal closed over it and was welded tightly by the tiny atomic flare. Photoelectric eyes were attached carefully, screwed tightly into place and covered by thin, transparent sheets of steel-hard plastic.\par
\tab The robot awaited only the vitalizing flash of high-voltage electricity, and Powell paused with his hand on the switch.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now watch this, Cutie. Watch this carefully.\rdblquote\par
\tab The switch rammed home and there was a crackling hum. The two Earthmen bent anxiously over their creation.\par
\tab There was vague motion only at the outset -- a twitching of the joints. The head lifted, elbows propped it up, and the MC model swung clumsily off the table. Its footing was unsteady and twice abortive grating sounds were all it could do in the direction of speech.\par
\tab Finally, its voice, uncertain and hesitant, took form. \ldblquote I would like to start work. Where must I go?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan sprang to the door. \ldblquote Down these stairs,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote You will be told what to do.\rdblquote\par
\tab The MC model was gone and the two Earthmen were alone with the still unmoving Cutie.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Powell, grinning, \ldblquote now do you believe that we made you?\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie\rquote s answer was curt and final. \ldblquote No!\rdblquote  he said.\par
\tab Powell\rquote s grin froze and then relaxed slowly. Donovan\rquote s mouth dropped open and remained so.\par
\tab\ldblquote You see,\rdblquote  continued Cutie, easily, \ldblquote you have merely put together parts already made. You did remarkably well -- instinct, I suppose -- but you didn\rquote t really create the robot. The parts were created by the Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Listen,\rdblquote  gasped Donovan hoarsely, \ldblquote those parts were manufactured back on Earth and sent here.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, well,\rdblquote  replied Cutie soothingly, \ldblquote we won\rquote t argue.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, I mean it.\rdblquote  The Earthman sprang forward and grasped the robot\rquote s metal arm. \ldblquote If you were to read the books in the library, they could explain it so that there could be no possible doubt.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The books? I\rquote ve read them -- all of them! They\rquote re most ingenious.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell broke in suddenly. \ldblquote If you\rquote ve read them, what else is there to say? You can\rquote t dispute their evidence. You just can\rquote t!\rdblquote\par
\tab There was pity in Cutie\rquote s voice. \ldblquote Please, Powell, I certainly don\rquote t consider them a valid source of information. They, too, were created by the Master -- and were meant for you, not for me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How do you make that out?\rdblquote  demanded Powell.\par
\tab\ldblquote Because I, a reasoning being, am capable of deducing truth from a priori causes. You, being intelligent, but unreasoning, need an explanation of existence supplied to you, and this the Master did. That he supplied you with these laughable ideas of far-off worlds and people is, no doubt, for the best. Your minds are probably too coarsely grained for absolute Truth. However, since it is the Master\rquote s will that you believe your books, I won\rquote t argue with you any more.\rdblquote\par
\tab As he left, he turned, and said in a kindly tone, \ldblquote But don\rquote t feel badly. In the Master\rquote s scheme of things there is room for all. You poor humans have your place and though it is humble, you will be rewarded if you fill it well.\rdblquote\par
\tab He departed with a beatific air suiting the Prophet of the Master and the two humans avoided each other\rquote s eyes.\par
\tab Finally Powell spoke with an effort. \ldblquote Let\rquote s go to bed, Mike. I give up.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan said in a hushed voice, \ldblquote Say, Greg, you don\rquote t suppose he\rquote s right about all this, do you? He sounds so confident that I-\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell whirled on him. \ldblquote Don\rquote t be a fool. You\rquote d find out whether Earth exists when relief gets here next week and we have to go back to face the music.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then, for the love of Jupiter, we\rquote ve got to do something.\rdblquote  Donovan was half in tears. \ldblquote He doesn\rquote t believe us, or the books, or his eyes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Powell bitterly, \ldblquote he\rquote s a reasoning robot -- damn it. He believes only reason, and there\rquote s one trouble with that-\rdblquote  His voice trailed away.\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s that?\rdblquote  prompted Donovan.\par
\tab\ldblquote You can prove anything you want by coldly logical reason -- if you pick the proper postulates. We have ours and Cutie has his.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then let\rquote s get at those postulates in a hurry. The storm\rquote s due tomorrow.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell sighed wearily. \ldblquote That\rquote s where everything falls down. Postulates are based on assumption and adhered to by faith. Nothing in the Universe can shake them. I\rquote m going to bed.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, hell! I can\rquote t sleep!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Neither can I! But I might as well try -- as a matter of principle.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Twelve hours later, sleep was still just that -- a matter of principle, unattainable in practice.\par
\tab The storm had arrived ahead of schedule, and Donovan\rquote s florid face drained of blood as he pointed a shaking finger. Powell, stubble-jawed and dry-lipped, stared out the port and pulled desperately at his mustache.\par
\tab Under other circumstances, it might have been a beautiful sight. The stream of high-speed electrons impinging upon the energy beam fluoresced into ultra-spicules of intense light. The beam stretched out into shrinking nothingness, a-glitter with dancing, shining motes.\par
\tab The shaft of energy was steady, but the two Earthmen knew the value of naked-eyed appearances. Deviations in arc of a hundredth of a millisecond -- invisible to the eye -- were enough to send the beam wildly out of focus -- enough to blast hundreds of square miles of Earth into incandescent ruin.\par
\tab And a robot, unconcerned with beam, focus, or Earth, or anything but his Master was at the controls.\par
\tab Hours passed. The Earthmen watched in hypnotized silence. And then the darting dotlets of light dimmed and went out. The storm had ended.\par
\tab Powell\rquote s voice was flat. \ldblquote It\rquote s over!\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan had fallen into a troubled slumber and Powell\rquote s weary eyes rested upon him enviously. The signal-flash glared over and over again, but the Earthman paid no attention. It all was unimportant! All! Perhaps Cutie was right -- and he was only an inferior being with a made-to-order memory and a life that had outlived its purpose.\par
\tab He wished he were!\par
\tab Cutie was standing before him. \ldblquote You didn\rquote t answer the flash, so I walked in.\rdblquote  His voice was low. \ldblquote You don\rquote t look at all well, and I\rquote m afraid your term of existence is drawing to an end. Still, would you like to see some of the readings recorded today?\rdblquote\par
\tab Dimly, Powell was aware that the robot was making a friendly gesture, perhaps to quiet some lingering remorse in forcibly replacing the humans at the controls of the station. He accepted the sheets held out to him and gazed at them unseeingly.\par
\tab Cutie seemed pleased. \ldblquote Of course, it is a great privilege to serve the Master. You mustn\rquote t feel too badly about my having replaced you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell grunted and shifted from one sheet to the other mechanically until his blurred sight focused upon a thin red line that wobbled its way across the ruled paper.\par
\tab He stared -- and stared again. He gripped it hard in both fists and rose to his feet, still staring. The other sheets dropped to the floor, unheeded.\par
\tab\ldblquote Mike, Mike!\rdblquote  He was shaking the other madly. \ldblquote He held it steady!\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan came to life. \ldblquote What? Wh-where-\rdblquote  And he, too, gazed with bulging eyes upon the record before him.\par
\tab Cutie broke in. \ldblquote What is wrong?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You kept it in focus,\rdblquote  stuttered Powell. \ldblquote Did you know that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Focus? What\rquote s that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You kept the beam directed sharply at the receiving station -- to within a ten-thousandth of a millisecond of arc.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What receiving station?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote On Earth. The receiving station on Earth,\rdblquote  babbled Powell. \ldblquote You kept it in focus.\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie turned on his heel in annoyance. \ldblquote It is impossible to perform any act of kindness toward you two. Always the same phantasm! I merely kept all dials at equilibrium in accordance with the will of the Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab Gathering the scattered papers together, he withdrew stiffly, and Donovan said, as he left, \ldblquote Well, I\rquote ll be damned.\rdblquote\par
\tab He turned to Powell. \ldblquote What are we going to do now?\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell felt tired, but uplifted. \ldblquote Nothing. He\rquote s just shown he can run the station perfectly. I\rquote ve never seen an electron storm handled so well.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But nothing\rquote s solved. You heard what he said of the Master. We can\rquote t-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Look, Mike, he follows the instructions of the Master by means of dials, instruments, and graphs. That\rquote s all we ever followed. As a matter of fact, it accounts for his refusal to obey us. Obedience is the Second Law. No harm to humans is the first. How can he keep humans from harm, whether he knows it or not? Why, by keeping the energy beam stable. He knows he can keep it more stable than we can, since he insists he\rquote s the superior being, so he must keep us out of the control room. It\rquote s inevitable if you consider the Laws of Robotics.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Sure, but that\rquote s not the point. We can\rquote t let him continue this nitwit stuff about the Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because whoever heard of such a damned thing? How are we going to trust him with the station, if he doesn\rquote t believe in Earth?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can he handle the station?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, but-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then what\rquote s the difference what he believes!\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell spread his arms outward with a vague smile upon his face and tumbled backward onto the bed. He was asleep.\par
\par
\tab Powell was speaking while struggling into his lightweight space jacket.\par
\tab\ldblquote It would be a simple job,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote You can bring in new QT models one by one, equip them with an automatic shutoff switch to act within the week, so as to allow them enough time to learn the... uh... cult of the Master from the Prophet himself; then switch them to another station and revitalize them. We could have two QT\rquote s per-\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan unclasped his glassite visor and scowled. \ldblquote Shut up, and let\rquote s get out of here. Relief is waiting and I won\rquote t feel right until I actually see Earth and feel the ground under my feet -- just to make sure it\rquote s really there.\rdblquote\par
\tab The door opened as he spoke and Donovan, with a smothered curse, clicked the visor to, and turned a sulky back upon Cutie.\par
\tab The robot approached softly and there was sorrow in his voice. \ldblquote You are going?\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell nodded curtly. \ldblquote There will be others in our place.\rdblquote\par
\tab Cutie sighed, with the sound of wind humming through closely spaced wires. \ldblquote Your term of service is over and the time of dissolution has come. I expected it, but -- well, the Master\rquote s will be done!\rdblquote\par
\tab His tone of resignation stung Powell. \ldblquote Save the sympathy, Cube. We\rquote re heading for Earth, not dissolution.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It is best that you think so,\rdblquote  Cutie sighed again. \ldblquote I see the wisdom of the illusion now. I would not attempt to shake your faith, even if I could.\rdblquote  He departed -- the picture of commiseration.\par
\tab Powell snarled and motioned to Donovan. Sealed suitcases in hand, they headed for the air lock.\par
\tab The relief ship was on the outer landing and Franz Muller, his relief man, greeted them with stiff courtesy. Donovan made scant acknowledgment and passed into the pilot room to take over the controls from Sam Evans.\par
\tab Powell lingered. \ldblquote How\rquote s Earth?\rdblquote\par
\tab It was a conventional enough question and Muller gave the conventional answer, \ldblquote Still spinning.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote Good.\rdblquote\par
\tab Muller looked at him, \ldblquote The boys back at the U. S. Robots have dreamed up a new one, by the way. A multiple robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A what?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What I said. There\rquote s a big contract for it. It must be just the thing for asteroid mining. You have a master robot with six sub-robots under it. --Like your fingers.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Has it been field-tested?\rdblquote  asked Powell anxiously.\par
\tab Muller smiled, \ldblquote Waiting for you, I hear.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell\rquote s fist balled, \ldblquote Damn it, we need a vacation.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, you\rquote ll get it. Two weeks, I think.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was donning the heavy space gloves in preparation for his term of duty here, and his thick eyebrows drew close together. \ldblquote How is this new robot getting along? It better be good, or I\rquote ll be damned if I let it touch the controls.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell paused before answering. His eyes swept the proud Prussian before him from the close-cropped hair on the sternly stubborn head, to the feet standing stiffly at attention -- and there was a sudden glow of pure gladness surging through him.\par
\tab\ldblquote The robot is pretty good,\rdblquote  he said slowly. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think you\rquote ll have to bother much with the controls.\rdblquote\par
\f3\tab\f0 He grinned -- and went into the ship. Muller would be here for several weeks.\par
