\scaps The vacation was longer than two weeks\scaps0 , that, Mike Donovan had to admit. It had been six months, with pay. He admitted that, too. But that, as he explained furiously, was fortuitous. U. S. Robots had to get the bugs out of the multiple robots, and there were plenty of bugs, and there are always at least half a dozen bugs left for the field-testing. So they waited and relaxed until the drawing-board men and the slide-rule boys had said \ldblquote OK!\rdblquote  And now he and Powell were out on the asteroid and it was not OK. He repeated that a dozen times, with a face that had gone beety, \ldblquote For the love of Pete, Greg, get realistic. What\rquote s the use of adhering to the letter of the specifications and watching the test go to pot? It\rquote s about time you got the red tape out of your pants and went to work.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m only saying,\rdblquote  said Gregory Powell, patiently, as one explaining electronics to an idiot child, \ldblquote that according to spec, those robots are equipped for asteroid mining without supervision. We\rquote re not supposed to watch them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. Look -- logic!\rdblquote  He lifted his hairy fingers and pointed. \ldblquote One: That new robot passed every test in the home laboratories. Two: United States Robots guaranteed their passing the test of actual performance on an asteroid. Three: The robots are not passing said tests. Four: If they don\rquote t pass, United States Robots loses ten million credits in cash and about one hundred million in reputation. Five: If they don\rquote t pass and we can\rquote t explain why they don\rquote t pass, it is just possible two good jobs may have to be bidden a fond farewell.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell groaned heavy behind a noticeably insincere smile. The unwritten motto of United States Robot and Mechanical Men Corp. was well known: \ldblquote No employee makes the same mistake twice. He is fired the first time.\rdblquote\par
\tab Aloud he said, \ldblquote You\rquote re as lucid as Euclid with everything except the facts. You\rquote ve watched that robot group for three shifts, you redhead, and they did their work perfectly. You said so yourself. What else can we do?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Find out what\rquote s wrong, that\rquote s what we can do. So they did work perfectly when I watched them. But on three different occasions when I didn\rquote t watch them, they didn\rquote t bring in any ore. They didn\rquote t even come back on schedule. I had to go after them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And was anything wrong?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not a thing. Not a thing. Everything was perfect. Smooth and perfect as the luminiferous ether. Only one little insignificant detail disturbed me -- there was no ore.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell scowled at the ceiling and pulled at his brown mustache. \ldblquote I\rquote ll tell you what, Mike. We\rquote ve been stuck with pretty lousy jobs in our time, but this takes the iridium asteroid. The whole business is complicated past endurance. Look, that robot, DV-5, has six robots under it. And not just under it -- they\rquote re part of it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know that-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Shut up!\rdblquote  said Powell, savagely, \ldblquote I know you know it, but I\rquote m just describing the hell of it. Those six subsidiaries are part of DV-5 like your fingers are part of you and it gives them their orders neither by voice nor radio, but directly through positronic fields. Now -- there isn\rquote t a roboticist back at United States Robots that knows what a positronic field is or how it works. And neither do I. Neither do you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The last,\rdblquote  agreed Donovan, philosophically, \ldblquote I know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then look at our position. If everything works -- fine! If anything goes wrong -- we\rquote re out of our depth and there probably isn\rquote t a thing we can do, or anybody else. But the job belongs to us and not to anyone else so we\rquote re on the spot, Mike.\rdblquote  He blazed away for a moment in silence. Then, \ldblquote All right, have you got him outside?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is everything normal now?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well he hasn\rquote t got religious mania, and he isn\rquote t running around in a circle spouting Gilbert and Sullivan, so I suppose he\rquote s normal.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan passed out the door, shaking his head viciously.\par
\par
\tab Powell reached for the \ldblquote Handbook of Robotics\rdblquote  that weighed down one side of his desk to a near-founder and opened it reverently. He had once jumped out of the window of a burning house dressed only in shorts and the \ldblquote Handbook.\rdblquote  In a pinch, he would have skipped the shorts.\par
\tab The \ldblquote Handbook\rdblquote  was propped up before him, when Robot DV-5 entered, with Donovan kicking the door shut behind him.\par
\tab Powell said somberly, \ldblquote Hi, Dave. How do you feel?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Fine,\rdblquote  said the robot. \ldblquote Mind if I sit down?\rdblquote  He dragged up the specially reinforced chair that was his, and folded gently into it.\par
\tab Powell regarded Dave -- laymen might think of robots by their serial numbers; roboticists never -- with approval. It was not over-massive by any means, in spite of its construction as thinking-unit of an integrated seven-unit robot team. It was seven feet tall, and a half-ton of metal and electricity. A lot? Not when that half-ton has to be a mass of condensers, circuits, relays, and vacuum cells that can handle practically any psychological reaction known to humans. And a positronic brain, which with ten pounds of matter and a few quintillions of positrons runs the whole show.\par
\tab Powell groped in his shirt pocket for a loose cigarette. \ldblquote Dave,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote you\rquote re a good fellow. There\rquote s nothing flighty or prima donnaish about you. You\rquote re a stable, rockbottom mining robot, except that you\rquote re equipped to handle six subsidiaries in direct coordination. As far as I know, that has not introduced any unstable paths in your brain-path map.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot nodded, \ldblquote That makes me feel swell, but what are you getting at, boss?\rdblquote  He was equipped with an excellent diaphragm, and the presence of overtones in the sound unit robbed him of much of that metallic flatness that marks the usual robot voice.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m going to tell you. With all that in your favor, what\rquote s going wrong with your job? For instance, today\rquote s B-shift?\rdblquote\par
\tab Dave hesitated, \ldblquote As far as I know, nothing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You didn\rquote t produce any ore.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, then-\rdblquote\par
\tab Dave was having trouble, \ldblquote I can\rquote t explain that, boss. It\rquote s been giving me a case of nerves, or it would if I let it -- my subsidiaries worked smoothly. I know I did.\rdblquote  He considered, his photoelectric eyes glowing intensely. Then, \ldblquote I don\rquote t remember. The day ended and there was Mike and there were the ore cars, mostly empty.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan broke in, \ldblquote You didn\rquote t report at shift-end those days, Dave. You know that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know. But as to why-\rdblquote  He shook his head slowly and ponderously.\par
\tab Powell had the queasy feeling that if the robot\rquote s face were capable of expression, it would be one of pain and mortification. A robot, by its very nature, cannot bear to fail its function.\par
\tab Donovan dragged his chair up to Powell\rquote s desk and leaned over, \ldblquote Amnesia, do you think?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can\rquote t say. But there\rquote s no use in trying to pin disease names on this. Human disorders apply to robots only as romantic analogies. They\rquote re no help to robotic engineering.\rdblquote  He scratched his neck; \ldblquote I hate to put him through the elementary brain-reaction tests. It won\rquote t help his self-respect any.\rdblquote\par
\tab He looked at Dave thoughtfully and then at the Field-Test outline given in the \ldblquote Handbook.\rdblquote  He said, \ldblquote See here, Dave, what about sitting through a test? It would be the wise thing to do.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot rose, \ldblquote If you say so, boss.\rdblquote  There was pain in his voice.\par
\par
\tab It started simply enough. Robot DV-5 multiplied five-place figures to the heartless ticking of a stopwatch. He recited the prime numbers between a thousand and ten thousand. He extracted cube roots and integrated functions of varying complexity. He went through mechanical reactions in order of increasing difficulty. And, finally, worked his precise mechanical mind over the highest function of the robot world -- the solutions of problems in judgment and ethics.\par
\tab At the end of two hours, Powell was copiously besweated. Donovan had enjoyed a none-too-nutritious diet of fingernail and the robot said, \ldblquote How does it look, boss?\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve got to think it over, Dave. Snap judgments won\rquote t help much. Suppose you go back to the C-shift. Take it easy. Don\rquote t press too hard for quota just for a while -- and we\rquote ll fix things up.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot left. Donovan looked at Powell.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well-\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell seemed determined to push up his mustache by the roots. He said, \ldblquote There is nothing wrong with the currents of his positronic brain.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote d hate to be that certain.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, Jupiter, Mike! The brain is the surest part of a robot. It\rquote s quintuple-checked back on Earth. If they pass the field test perfectly, the way Dave did, there just isn\rquote t a chance of brain misfunction. That test covered every key path in the brain.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So where are we?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t rush me. Let me work this out. There\rquote s still the possibility of a mechanical breakdown in the body. That leaves about fifteen hundred condensers, twenty thousand individual electric circuits, five hundred vacuum cells, a thousand relays, and upty-ump thousand other individual pieces of complexity that can be wrong. And these mysterious positron is fields no one knows anything about.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Listen, Greg,\rdblquote  Donovan grew desperately urgent. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got an idea. That robot may be lying. He never-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Robots can\rquote t knowingly lie, you fool. Now if we had the McCormack-Wesley tester, we could check each individual item in his body within twenty-four to forty-eight hours, but the only two M-W testers existing are on Earth, and they weigh ten tons, are on concrete foundations and can\rquote t be moved. Isn\rquote t that peachy?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan pounded the desk, \ldblquote But, Greg, he only goes wrong when we\rquote re not around. There\rquote s something -- sinister -- about -- that.\rdblquote  He punctuated the sentence with slams of fist against desk.\par
\tab\ldblquote You,\rdblquote  said Powell, slowly, \ldblquote make me sick. You\rquote ve been reading adventure novels.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What I want to know,\rdblquote  shouted Donovan, \ldblquote is what we\rquote re going to do about it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll tell you. I\rquote m going to install a visiplate right over my desk. Right on the wall over there, see!\rdblquote  He jabbed a vicious finger at the spot. \ldblquote Then I\rquote m going to focus it at whatever part of the mine is being worked, and I\rquote m going to watch. That\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s all? Greg-\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell rose from his chair and leaned his balled fists on the desk, \ldblquote Mike, I\rquote m having a hard time.\rdblquote  His voice was weary. \ldblquote For a week, you\rquote ve been plaguing me about Dave. You say he\rquote s gone wrong. Do you know how he\rquote s gone wrong? No! Do you know what shape this wrongness takes? No! Do you know what brings it on? No! Do you know what snaps him out? No! Do you know anything about it? No! Do I know anything about it? No! So what do you want me to do?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan\rquote s arm swept outward in a vague, grandiose gesture, \ldblquote You got me!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So I tell you again. Before we do anything toward a cure, we\rquote ve got to find out what the disease is in the first place. The first step in cooking rabbit stew is catching the rabbit. Well, we\rquote ve got to catch that rabbit! Now get out of here.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Donovan stared at the preliminary outline of his field report with weary eyes. For one thing, he was tired and for another, what was there to report while things were unsettled? He felt resentful.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Greg, we\rquote re almost a thousand tons behind schedule.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You,\rdblquote  replied Powell, never looking up, \ldblquote are telling me something I don\rquote t know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What I want to know,\rdblquote  said Donovan, in sudden savagery, \ldblquote is why we\rquote re always tangled up with new-type robots. I\rquote ve finally decided that the robots that were good enough for my great-uncle on my mother\rquote s side are good enough for me. I\rquote m for what\rquote s tried and true. The test of time is what counts -- good, solid, old-fashioned robots that never go wrong.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell threw a book with perfect aim, and Donovan went tumbling off his seat.\par
\tab\ldblquote Your job,\rdblquote  said Powell, evenly, \ldblquote for the last five years has been to test new robots under actual working conditions for United States Robots. Because you and I have been so injudicious as to display proficiency at the task, we\rquote ve been rewarded with the dirtiest jobs. That,\rdblquote  he jabbed holes in the air with his finger in Donovan\rquote s direction, \ldblquote is your work. You\rquote ve been griping about it, from personal memory, since about five minutes after United States Robots signed you up. Why don\rquote t you resign?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, I\rquote ll tell you.\rdblquote  Donovan rolled onto his stomach, and took a firm grip on his wild, red hair to hold his head up. \ldblquote There\rquote s a certain principle involved. After all, as a troubleshooter, I\rquote ve played a part in the development of new robots. There\rquote s the principle of aiding scientific advance. But don\rquote t get me wrong. It\rquote s not the principle that keeps me going; it\rquote s the money they pay us. Greg!\rquote\par
\tab Powell jumped at Donovan\rquote s wild shout, and his eyes followed the redhead\rquote s to the visiplate, when they goggled in fixed horror. He whispered, \ldblquote Holy -- howling -- Jupiter!\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan scrambled breathlessly to his feet, \ldblquote Look at them, Greg. They\rquote ve gone nuts.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote Get a pair of suits. We\rquote re going out there.\rdblquote\par
\tab He watched the posturings of the robots on the visiplate. They were bronzy gleams of smooth motion against the shadowy crags of the airless asteroid. There was a marching formation now, and in their own dim body light, the roughhewn walls of the mine tunnel swam past noiselessly, checkered with misty erratic blobs of shadow. They marched in unison, seven of them, with Dave at the head. They wheeled and turned in macabre simultaneity; and melted through changes of formation with the weird ease of chorus dancers in Lunar Bowl.\par
\tab Donovan was back with the suits, \ldblquote They\rquote ve gone jingo on us, Greg. That\rquote s a military march.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For all you know,\rdblquote  was the cold response, \ldblquote it may be a series of callisthenic exercises. Or Dave may be under the hallucination of being a dancing master. Just you think first, and don\rquote t bother to speak afterward, either.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan scowled and slipped a detonator into the empty side holster with an ostentatious shove. He said, \ldblquote Anyway, there you are. So we work with new-model robots. It\rquote s our job, granted. But answer me one question. Why... why does something invariably go wrong with them?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because,\rdblquote  said Powell, somberly, \ldblquote we are accursed. Let\rquote s go!\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Far ahead through the thick velvety blackness of the corridors that reached past the illuminated circles of their flashlights, robot light twinkled.\par
\tab\ldblquote There they are,\rdblquote  breathed Donovan.\par
\tab Powell whispered tensely, \ldblquote I\rquote ve been trying to get him by radio but he doesn\rquote t answer. The radio circuit is probably out.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then I\rquote m glad the designers haven\rquote t worked out robots who can work in total darkness yet. I\rquote d hate to have to find seven mad robots in a black pit without radio communication, if they weren\rquote t lit up like blasted radioactive Christmas trees.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Crawl up on the ledge above, Mike. They\rquote re coming this way, and I want to watch them at close range. Can you make it?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan made the jump with a grunt. Gravity was considerably below Earth-normal, but with a heavy suit, the advantage was not too great, and the ledge meant a near ten-foot jump. Powell followed.\par
\tab The column of robots was trailing Dave single-file. In mechanical rhythm, they converted to double and returned to single in different order. It was repeated over and over again and Dave never turned his head.\par
\tab Dave was within twenty feet when the play-acting ceased. The subsidiary robots broke formation, waited a moment, then clattered off into the distance -- very rapidly. Dave looked after them, then slowly sat down. He rested his head in one hand in a very human gesture.\par
\tab His voice sounded in Powell\rquote s earphones, \ldblquote Are you here, boss?\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell beckoned to Donovan and hopped off the ledge.\par
\tab\ldblquote O.K., Dave, what\rquote s been going on?\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot shook his head, \ldblquote I don\rquote t know. One moment I was handling a tough outcropping in Tunnel 17, and the next I was aware of humans close by, and I found myself half a mile down main-stem.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Where are the subsidiaries now?\rdblquote  asked Donovan.\par
\tab\ldblquote Back at work, of course. How much time has been lost?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not much. Forget it.\rdblquote  Then to Donovan, Powell added, \ldblquote Stay with him the rest of the shift. Then, come back. I\rquote ve got a couple of ideas.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab It was three hours before Donovan returned. He looked tired. Powell said, \ldblquote How did it go?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan shrugged wearily, \ldblquote Nothing ever goes wrong when you watch them. Throw me a butt, will you?\rdblquote\par
\tab The redhead lit it with exaggerated care and blew a careful smoke ring. He said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve been working it out, Greg. You know, Dave has a queer background for a robot. There are six others under him in an extreme regimentation. He\rquote s got life and death power over those subsidiary robots and it must react on his mentality. Suppose he finds it necessary to emphasize this power as a concession to his ego.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Get to the point.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s right here. Suppose we have militarism. Suppose he\rquote s fashioning himself an army. Suppose --  he\rquote s training them in military maneuvers. Suppose-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose you go soak your head. Your nightmares must be in technicolor. You\rquote re postulating a major aberration of the positronic brain. If your analysis were correct, Dave would have to break down the First Law of Robotics: that a robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to be injured. The type of militaristic attitude and domineering ego you propose must have as the end-point of its logical implications, domination of humans.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. How do you know that isn\rquote t the fact of the matter?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because any robot with a brain like that would, one, never have left the factory, and two, be spotted immediately if it ever was. I tested Dave, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell shoved his chair back and put his feet on the desk. \ldblquote No. We\rquote re still in the position where we can\rquote t make our stew because we haven\rquote t the slightest notion as to what\rquote s wrong. For instance, if we could find out what that dance macabre we witnessed was all about, we would be on the way out.\rdblquote\par
\tab He paused, \ldblquote Now listen, Mike, how does this sound to you? Dave goes wrong only when neither of us is present. And when he is wrong, the arrival of either of us snaps him out of it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I once told you that was sinister.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t interrupt. How is a robot different when humans are not present? The answer is obvious. There is a larger requirement of personal initiative. In that case, look for the body parts that are affected by the new requirements.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Golly.\rdblquote  Donovan sat up straight, then subsided. \ldblquote No, no. Not enough. It\rquote s too broad. It doesn\rquote t cut the possibilities much.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can\rquote t help that. In any case, there\rquote s no danger of not making quota. We\rquote ll take shifts watching those robots through the visor. Any time anything goes wrong, we get to the scene of action immediately. That will put them right.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But the robots will fail spec anyway, Greg. United States Robots can\rquote t market DV models with a report like that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Obviously. We\rquote ve got to locate the error in make-up and correct it -- and we\rquote ve got ten days to do it in.\rdblquote  Powell scratched his head. \ldblquote The trouble is... well, you had better look at the blueprints yourself.\rdblquote\par
\tab The blueprints covered the floor like a carpet and Donovan crawled over the face of them following Powell\rquote s erratic pencil.\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote Here\rquote s where you come in, Mike. You\rquote re the body specialist, and I want you to check me. I\rquote ve been trying to cut out all circuits not involved in the personal initiative hookup. Right here, for instance, is the trunk artery involving mechanical operations. I cut out all routine side routes as emergency divisions-\rdblquote  He looked up, \ldblquote What do you think?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan had a very bad taste in his mouth, \ldblquote The job\rquote s not that simple, Greg. Personal initiative isn\rquote t an electric circuit you can separate from the rest and study. When a robot is on his own, the intensity of the body activity increases immediately on almost all fronts. There isn\rquote t a circuit entirely unaffected. What must be done is to locate the particular condition -- a very specific condition -- that throws him off, and then start eliminating circuits.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell got up and dusted himself, \ldblquote Hmph. All right. Take away the blueprints and burn them.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan said, \ldblquote You see when activity intensifies, anything can happen, given one single faulty part. Insulation breaks down, a condenser spills over, a connection sparks, a coil overheats. And if you work blind, with the whole robot to choose from, you\rquote ll never find the bad spot. If you take Dave apart and test every point of his body mechanism one by one, putting him together each time, and trying him out\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. All right. I can see through a porthole, too.\rdblquote\par
\tab They faced each other hopelessly, and then Powell said cautiously, \ldblquote Suppose we interview one of the subsidiaries.\rdblquote\par
\tab Neither Powell nor Donovan had ever had previous occasion to talk to a \ldblquote finger.\rdblquote  It could talk; it wasn\rquote t quite the perfect analogy to a human finger. In fact, it had a fairly developed brain, but that brain was tuned primarily to the reception of orders via positronic field, and its reaction to independent stimuli was rather fumbling.\par
\tab Nor was Powell certain as to its name. Its serial number was DV-5-2, but that was not very useful.\par
\tab He compromised. \ldblquote Look, pal,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote I\rquote m going to ask you to do some hard thinking and then you can go back to your boss.\rdblquote\par
\tab The \ldblquote finger\rdblquote  nodded its head stiffly, but did not exert its limited brainpower on speech.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now on four occasions recently,\rdblquote  Powell said, \ldblquote your boss deviated from brain-scheme. Do you remember those occasions?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan growled angrily, \ldblquote He remembers. I tell you there is something very sinister-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, go bash your skull. Of course, the \lquote finger\rquote  remembers. There is nothing wrong with him.\rdblquote  Powell turned back to the robot, \ldblquote What were you doing each time... I mean the whole group\rdblquote\par
\tab The \ldblquote finger\rdblquote  had a curious air of reciting by rote, as if he answered questions by the mechanical pressure of his brainpan, but without any enthusiasm whatever.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote The first time we were at work on a difficult outcropping in Tunnel 17, Level B. The second time we were buttressing the roof against a possible cave-in. The third time we were preparing accurate blasts in order to tunnel farther without breaking into a subterranean fissure. The fourth time was just after a minor cave-in\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What happened at these times?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It is difficult to describe. An order would be issued, but before we could receive and interpret it, a new order came to march in queer formation.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell snapped out, \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan broke in tensely, \ldblquote What was the first order... the one that was superseded by the marching directions?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. I sensed that an order was sent, but there was never time to receive it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Could you tell us anything about it? Was it the same order each time?\rdblquote\par
\tab The \ldblquote finger\rdblquote  shook his head unhappily, \ldblquote I don\rquote t know.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell leaned back, \ldblquote All right, get back to your boss.\rdblquote\par
\tab The \ldblquote finger\rdblquote  left, with visible relief.\par
\tab Donovan said, \ldblquote Well, we accomplished a lot that time. That was real sharp dialogue all the way through. Listen, Dave and that imbecile \lquote finger\rquote  are both holding out on us. There is too much they don\rquote t know and don\rquote t remember. We\rquote ve got to stop trusting them, Greg.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell brushed his mustache the wrong way, \ldblquote So help me, Mike, another fool remark out of you, and I\rquote ll take away your rattle and teething ring.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. You\rquote re the genius of the team. I\rquote m just a poor sucker. Where do we stand?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Right behind the eight ball. I tried to work it backward through the \lquote finger,\rquote  and couldn\rquote t. So we\rquote ve got to work it forward.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A great man,\rdblquote  marveled Donovan. \ldblquote How simple that makes it. Now translate that into English, Master.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Translating it into baby talk would suit you better. I mean that we\rquote ve got to find out what order it is that Dave gives just before everything goes black. It would be the key to the business.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And how do you expect to do that? We can\rquote t get close to him because nothing will go wrong as long as we are there. We can\rquote t catch the orders by radio because they are transmitted via this positronic field. That eliminates the close-range and the long-range method, leaving us a neat, cozy zero.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote By direct observation, yes. There\rquote s still deduction.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Huh?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re going on shifts, Mike.\rdblquote  Powell smiled grimly. \ldblquote And we are not taking our eyes off the visiplate. We\rquote re going to watch every action of those steel headaches. When they go off into their act, we\rquote re going to see what happened immediately before and we\rquote re going to deduce the order.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan opened his mouth and left it that way for a full minute. Then he said in strangled tones, \ldblquote I resign. I quit.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You have ten days to think up something better,\rdblquote  said Powell wearily.\par
\tab Which, for eight days, Donovan tried mightily to do. For eight days, on alternate four-hour shifts, he watched with aching and bleary eyes those glinty metallic forms move against the vague background. And for eight days in the four-hour in-betweens, he cursed United States Robots, the DV models, and the day he was born.\par
\tab And then on the eighth day, when Powell entered with an aching head and sleepy eyes for his shift, Donovan stood up and with very careful and deliberate aim launched a heavy bookend for the exact center of the visiplate. There was a very appropriate splintering noise.\par
\tab Powell gasped, \ldblquote What did you do that for?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because,\rdblquote  said Donovan, almost calmly, \ldblquote I\rquote m not watching it any more. We\rquote ve got two days left and we haven\rquote t found out a thing. DV-5 is a lousy loss. He\rquote s stopped five times since I\rquote ve been watching and three times on your shift, and I can\rquote t make out what orders he gave, and you couldn\rquote t make it out. And I don\rquote t believe you could ever make it out because I know I couldn\rquote t ever.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Jumping Space, how can you watch six robots at the same time? One makes with the hands, and one with the feet and one like a windmill and another is jumping up and down like a maniac. And the other two... devil knows what they are doing. And then they all stop. So! So!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Greg, we\rquote re not doing it right. We got to get up close. We\rquote ve got to watch what they\rquote re doing from where we can see the details.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell broke a bitter silence. \ldblquote Yeah, and wait for something to go wrong with only two days to go.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is it any better watching from here?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s more comfortable.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Ah -- But there\rquote s something you can do there that you can\rquote t do here.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You can make them stop -- at whatever time you choose and while you\rquote re prepared and watching to see what goes wrong.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell startled into alertness, \ldblquote Howzzat?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, figure it out, yourself. You\rquote re the brains you say. Ask yourself some questions. When does DV-5 go out of whack? When did that \lquote finger\rquote  say he did? When a cave-in threatened, or actually occurred, when delicately measured explosives were being laid down, when a difficult seam was hit.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In other words, during emergencies,\rdblquote  Powell was excited.\par
\tab\ldblquote Right! When did you expect it to happen! It\rquote s the personal initiative factor that\rquote s giving us the trouble. And it\rquote s just during emergencies in the absence of a human being that personal initiative is most strained. Now what is the logical deduction? How can we create our own stoppage when and where we want it?\rdblquote  He paused triumphantly -- he was beginning to enjoy his role -- and answered his own question to forestall the obvious answer on Powell\rquote s tongue. \ldblquote By creating our own emergency.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote Mike -- you\rquote re right.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thanks, pal. I knew I\rquote d do it some day.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right, and skip the sarcasm. We\rquote ll save it for Earth, and preserve it in jars for future long, cold winters. Meanwhile, what emergency can we create?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We could flood the mines, if this weren\rquote t an airless asteroid.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A witticism, no doubt,\rdblquote  said Powell. \ldblquote Really, Mike, you\rquote ll incapacitate me with laughter. What about a mild cave-in?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan pursed his lips and said, \ldblquote O.K. by me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good. Let\rquote s get started.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell felt uncommonly like a conspirator as he wound his way over the craggy landscape. His sub-gravity walk teetered across the broken ground, kicking rocks to right and left under his weight in noiseless puffs of gray dust. Mentally, though, it was the cautious crawl of the plotter.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Do you know where they are?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I think so, Greg.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  Powell said gloomily, \ldblquote but if any \lquote finger\rquote  gets within twenty feet of us, we\rquote ll be sensed whether we are in the line of sight or not. I hope you know that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote When I need an elementary course in robotics, I\rquote ll file an application with you formally, and in triplicate. Down through here.\rdblquote\par
\tab They were in the tunnels now; even the starlight was gone. The two hugged the walls, flashes flickering out the way in intermittent bursts. Powell felt for the security of his detonator.\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you know this tunnel, Mike?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not so good. It\rquote s a new one. I think I can make it out from what I saw in the visiplate, though-\rdblquote\par
\tab Interminable minutes passed, and then Mike said, \ldblquote Feel that!\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a slight vibration thrumming the wall against the fingers of Powell\rquote s metal-incased hand. There was no sound, naturally.\par
\tab\ldblquote Blasting! We\rquote re pretty close.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Keep your eyes open,\rdblquote  said Powell.\par
\tab Donovan nodded impatiently.\par
\tab It was upon them and gone before they could seize themselves -- just a bronze glint across the field of vision. They clung together in silence.\par
\tab Powell whispered, \ldblquote Think it sensed us?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hope not. But we\rquote d better flank them. Take the first side tunnel to the right.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose we miss them altogether?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well what do you want to do? Go back?\rdblquote  Donovan grunted fiercely. \ldblquote They\rquote re within a quarter of a mile. I was watching them through the visiplate, wasn\rquote t I? And we\rquote ve got two days-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, shut up. You\rquote re wasting your oxygen. Is this a side passage here?\rdblquote  The flash flicked. \ldblquote It is. Let\rquote s go.\rdblquote\par
\tab The vibration was considerably more marked and the ground below shuddered uneasily.\par
\tab\ldblquote This is good,\rdblquote  said Donovan, \ldblquote if it doesn\rquote t give out on us, though.\rdblquote  He flung his light ahead anxiously.\par
\tab They could touch the roof of the tunnel with a half-upstretched hand, and the bracings had been newly placed.\par
\tab Donovan hesitated, \ldblquote Dead end, let\rquote s go back.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. Hold on.\rdblquote  Powell squeezed clumsily past. \ldblquote Is that light ahead?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Light? I don\rquote t see any. Where would there be light down here?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Robot light.\rdblquote  He was scrambling up a gentle incline on hands and knees. His voice was hoarse and anxious in Donovan\rquote s ears. \ldblquote Hey, Mike, come up here.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was light. Donovan crawled up and over Powell\rquote s outstretched legs. \ldblquote An opening?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. They must be working into this tunnel from the other side now I think.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan felt the ragged edges of the opening that looked out into what the cautious flashlight showed to be a larger and obviously main stem tunnel. The hole was too small for a man to go through, almost too small for two men to look through simultaneously.\par
\tab There\rquote s nothing there,\rdblquote  said Donovan.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, not now. But there must have been a second ago or we wouldn\rquote t have seen light. Watch out!\rdblquote\par
\tab The walls rolled about them and they felt the impact. A fine dust showered down. Powell lifted a cautious head and looked again. \ldblquote All right, Mike. They\rquote re there.\rdblquote\par
\tab The glittering robots clustered fifty feet down the main stem. Metal arms labored mightily at the rubbish heap brought down by the last blast.\par
\tab Donovan urged eagerly, \ldblquote Don\rquote t waste time. It won\rquote t be long before they get through, and the next blast may get us.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For Pete\rquote s sake, don\rquote t rush me.\rdblquote  Powell unlimbered the detonator, and his eyes searched anxiously across the dusky background where the only light was robot light and it was impossible to tell a projecting boulder from a shadow.\par
\tab\ldblquote There\rquote s a spot in the roof, see it, almost over them. The last blast didn\rquote t quite get it. If you can get it at the base, half the roof will cave in.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell followed the dim finger, \ldblquote Check! Now fasten your eye on the robots and pray they don\rquote t move too far from that part of the tunnel. They\rquote re my light sources. Are all seven there?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan counted, \ldblquote All seven.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, then, watch them. Watch every motion!\rdblquote\par
\tab His detonator was lifted and remained poised while Donovan watched and cursed and blinked the sweat out of his eye.\par
\tab It flashed!\par
\tab There was a jar, a series of hard vibrations, and then a jarring thump that threw Powell heavily against Donovan.\par
\tab Donovan yowled, \ldblquote Greg, you threw me off. I didn\rquote t see a thing.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell stared about wildly, \ldblquote Where are they?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan fell into a stupid silence. There was no sign of the robots. It was dark as the depths of the River Styx.\par
\tab\ldblquote Think we buried them?\rdblquote  quavered Donovan.\par
\tab\ldblquote Let\rquote s get down there. Don\rquote t ask me what I think.\rdblquote  Powell crawled backward at tumbling speed.\par
\tab\ldblquote Mike!\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan paused in the act of following. \ldblquote What\rquote s wrong now?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hold on!\rdblquote  Powell\rquote s breathing was rough and irregular in Donovan\rquote s ears. \ldblquote Mike! Do you hear me, Mike?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m right here. What is it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re blocked in. It wasn\rquote t the ceiling coming down fifty feet away that knocked us over. It was our own ceiling. The shock\rquote s tumbled it!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What!\rdblquote  Donovan scrambled up against a hard barrier. \ldblquote Turn on the flash.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell did so. At no point was there room for a rabbit to squeeze through.\par
\tab Donovan said softly, \ldblquote Well, what do you know?\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab They wasted a few moments and some muscular power in an effort to move the blocking barrier. Powell varied this by wrenching at the edges of the original hole. For a moment, Powell lifted his blaster. But in those close quarters, a flash would be suicide and he knew it. He sat down.\par
\tab\ldblquote You know, Mike,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote we\rquote ve really messed this up. We are no nearer finding out what\rquote s wrong with Dave. It was a good idea but it blew up in our face.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan\rquote s glance was bitter with an intensity totally wasted on the darkness, \ldblquote I hate to disturb you, old man, but quite apart from what we know or don\rquote t know of Dave, we\rquote re slightly trapped. If we don\rquote t get loose, fella, we\rquote re going to die. D-I-E, die. How much oxygen have we anyway? Not more than six hours.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve thought of that.\rdblquote  Powell\rquote s fingers went up to his long-suffering mustache and clanged uselessly against the transparent visor. \ldblquote Of course, we could get Dave to dig us out easily in that time, except that our precious emergency must have thrown him off, and his radio circuit is out.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And isn\rquote t that nice?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan edged up to the opening and managed to get his metal incased head out. It was an extremely tight fit.\par
\tab\ldblquote Hey, Greg!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose we get Dave within twenty feet. He\rquote ll snap to normal. That will save us.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure, but where is he?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Down the corridor -- way down. For Pete\rquote s sake, stop pulling before you drag my head out of its socket. I\rquote ll give you your chance to look.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell maneuvered his head outside, \ldblquote We did it all right. Look at those saps. That must be a ballet they\rquote re doing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind the side remarks. Are they getting any closer?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can\rquote t tell yet. They\rquote re too far away. Give me a chance. Pass me my flash, will you? I\rquote ll try to attract their attention that way.\rdblquote\par
\tab He gave up after two minutes, \ldblquote Not a chance! They must be blind. Uh-oh, they\rquote re starting toward us. What do you know?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan said, \ldblquote Hey, let me see!\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a silent scuffle. Powell said, \ldblquote All right!\rdblquote  and Donovan got his head out.\par
\tab They were approaching. Dave was high-stepping the way in front and the six \ldblquote fingers\rdblquote  were a weaving chorus line behind him.\par
\tab Donovan marveled, \ldblquote What are they doing? That\rquote s what I want to know. It looks like the Virginia reel -- and Dave\rquote s a major-domo, or I never saw one.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, leave me alone with your descriptions,\rdblquote  grumbled Powell. \ldblquote How near are they?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Within fifty feet and coming this way. We\rquote ll be out in fifteen min--Uh-huh-HUH-HEY-Y!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s going on?\rdblquote  It took Powell several seconds to recover from his stunned astonishment at Donovan\rquote s vocal gyrations. \ldblquote Come on, give me a chance at that hole. Don\rquote t be a hog about it.\rdblquote\par
\tab He fought his way upward, but Donovan kicked wildly, \ldblquote They did an about-face, Greg. They\rquote re leaving. Dave! Hey, Da-a ave!\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell shrieked, \ldblquote What\rquote s the use of that, you fool? Sound won\rquote t carry.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, then,\rdblquote  panted Donovan, \ldblquote kick the walls, slam them, get some vibration started. We\rquote ve got to attract their attention somehow, Greg, or we\rquote re through. \ldblquote  He pounded like a madman.\par
\tab Powell shook him, \ldblquote Wait, Mike, wait. Listen, I\rquote ve got an idea. Jumping Jupiter, this is a fine time to get around to the simple solutions. Mike!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What do you want?\rdblquote  Donovan pulled his head in.\par
\tab\ldblquote Let me in there fast before they get out of range.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Out of range! What are you going to do? Hey, what are you going to do with that detonator?\rdblquote  He grabbed Powell\rquote s arm.\par
\tab Powell shook off the grip violently. \ldblquote I\rquote m going to do a little shooting.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s for later. Let\rquote s see if it works first. If it doesn\rquote t, then -- Get out of the way and let me shoot!\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab The robots were flickers, small and getting smaller, in the distance. Powell lined up the sights tensely, and pulled the trigger three times. He lowered the guns and peered anxiously. One of the subsidiaries was down! There were only six gleaming figures now.\par
\tab Powell called into his transmitter uncertainly. \ldblquote Dave!\rdblquote\par
\tab A pause, then the answer sounded to both men, \ldblquote Boss? Where are you? My third subsidiary has had his chest blown in. He\rquote s out of commission.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind your subsidiary,\rdblquote  said Powell. \ldblquote We\rquote re trapped in a cave-in where you were blasting. Can you see our flashlight?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure. We\rquote ll be right there.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell sat back and relaxed, \ldblquote That, my fran\rquote , is that\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan said very softly with tears in his voice, \ldblquote All right, Greg. You win. I beat my forehead against the ground before your feet. Now don\rquote t feed me any bull. Just tell me quietly what it\rquote s all about.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Easy. It\rquote s just that all through we missed the obvious -- as usual. We knew it was the personal initiative circuit, and that it always happened during emergencies, but we kept looking for a specific order as the cause. Why should it be an order?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, look, why not a type of order. What type of order requires the most initiative? What type of order would occur almost always only in an emergency?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t ask me, dreg. Tell me!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m doing it! It\rquote s the six-way order. Under all ordinary conditions, one or more of the \lquote fingers\rquote  would be doing routine tasks requiring no close supervision -- in the sort of offhand way our bodies handle the routine walking motions. But in an emergency, all six subsidiaries must be mobilized immediately and simultaneously. Dave must handle six robots at a time and something gives. The rest was easy. Any decrease in initiative required, such as the arrival of humans, snaps him back. So I destroyed one of the robots. When I did, he was transmitting only five-way orders. Initiative decreases -- he\rquote s normal\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How did you get all that?\rdblquote  demanded Donovan.\par
\tab\ldblquote Just logical guessing. I tried it and it worked.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot\rquote s voice was in their ears again, \ldblquote Here I am. Can you hold out half an hour?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Easy!\rdblquote  said Powell. Then, to Donovan, he continued, \ldblquote And now the job should be simple. We\rquote ll go through the circuits, and check off each part that gets an extra workout in a six-way order as against a five-way. How big a field does that leave us?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan considered, \ldblquote Not much, I think. If Dave is like the preliminary model we saw back at the factory, there\rquote s a special coordinating circuit that would be the only section involved.\rdblquote  He cheered up suddenly and amazingly, \ldblquote Say, that wouldn\rquote t be bad at all. There\rquote s nothing to that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. You think it over and we\rquote ll check the blueprints when we get back. And now, till Daves reaches us, I\rquote m relaxing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hey, wait! Just tell me one thing. What were those queer shifting marches, those funny dance steps, that the robots went through every time they went screwy?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That? I don\rquote t know. But I\rquote ve got a notion. Remember, those subsidiaries were Dave\rquote s \lquote fingers.\rquote  We were always saying that, you know. Well, it\rquote s my idea that in all these interludes, whenever Dave became a psychiatric case, he went off into a moronic maze, spending his time \i twiddling his fingers\i0 .\rdblquote\par
