\scaps Alfred Lanning lit his cigar carefully, but\scaps0  the tips of his fingers were trembling slightly. His gray eyebrows hunched low as he spoke between puffs.\par
\tab\ldblquote It reads minds all right-damn little doubt about that! But why?\rdblquote  He looked at Mathematician Peter Bogert, \ldblquote Well?\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert flattened his black hair down with both hands, \ldblquote That was the thirty-fourth RB model we\rquote ve turned out, Lanning. All the others were strictly orthodox.\rdblquote\par
\tab The third man at the table frowned. Milton Ashe was the youngest officer of U. S. Robot & Mechanical Men, Inc., and proud of his post.\par
\tab\ldblquote Listen, Bogert. There wasn\rquote t a hitch in the assembly from start to finish. I guarantee that.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert\rquote s thick lips spread in a patronizing smile, \ldblquote Do you? If you can answer for the entire assembly line, I recommend your promotion. By exact count, there are seventy-five thousand, two hundred and thirty-four operations necessary for the manufacture of a single positronic brain, each separate operation depending for successful completion upon any number of factors, from five to a hundred and five. If any one of them goes seriously wrong, the \lquote brain\rquote  is ruined. I quote our own information folder, Ashe.\rdblquote\par
\tab Milton Ashe flushed, but a fourth voice cut off his reply.\par
\tab\ldblquote If we\rquote re going to start by trying to fix the blame on one another, I\rquote m leaving.\rdblquote  Susan Calvin\rquote s hands were folded tightly in her lap, and the little lines about her thin, pale lips deepened, \ldblquote We\rquote ve got a mind-reading robot on our hands and it strikes me as rather important that we find out just why it reads minds. We\rquote re not going to do that by saying, \lquote Your fault! My fault!\rquote  \ldblquote\par
\tab Her cold gray eyes fastened upon Ashe, and he grinned.\par
\tab Lanning grinned too, and, as always at such times, his long white hair and shrewd little eyes made him the picture of a biblical patriarch, \ldblquote True for you, Dr. Calvin.\rdblquote\par
\tab His voice became suddenly crisp, \ldblquote Here\rquote s everything in pill-concentrate form. We\rquote ve produced a positronic brain of supposedly ordinary vintage that\rquote s got the remarkable property of being able to tune in on thought waves. It would mark the most important advance in robotics in decades, if we knew how it happened. We don\rquote t, and we have to find out. Is that clear?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote May I make a suggestion?\rdblquote  asked Bogert.\par
\tab\ldblquote Go ahead!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote d say that until we do figure out the mess -- and as a mathematician I expect it to be a very devil of a mess -- we keep the existence of RD-34 a secret. I mean even from the other members of the staff. As heads of the departments, we ought not to find it an insoluble problem, and the fewer know about it-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Bogert is right,\rdblquote  said Dr. Calvin. \ldblquote Ever since the Interplanetary Code was modified to allow robot models to be tested in the plants before being shipped out to space, antirobot propaganda has increased. If any word leaks out about a robot being able to read minds before we can announce complete control of the phenomenon, pretty effective capital could be made out of it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning sucked at his cigar and nodded gravely. He turned to Ashe; \ldblquote I think you said you were alone when you first stumbled on this thought-reading business.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll say I was alone -- I got the scare of my life. RB-34 had just been taken off the assembly table and they sent him down to me. Obermann was off somewheres, so I took him down to the testing rooms myself -- at least I started to take him down.\rdblquote  Ashe paused, and a tiny smile tugged at his lips, \ldblquote Say, did any of you ever carry on a thought conversation without knowing it?\rdblquote\par
\tab No one bothered to answer, and he continued, \ldblquote You don\rquote t realize it at first, you know. He just spoke to me -- as logically and sensibly as you can imagine -- and it was only when I was most of the way down to the testing rooms that I realized that I hadn\rquote t said anything. Sure, I thought lots, but that isn\rquote t the same thing, is it? I locked that thing up and ran for Lanning. Having it walking beside me, calmly peering into my thoughts and picking and choosing among them gave me the willies.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I imagine it would,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin thoughtfully. Her eyes fixed themselves upon Ashe in an oddly intent manner. \ldblquote We are so accustomed to considering our own thoughts private.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning broke in impatiently, \ldblquote Then only the four of us know. All right! We\rquote ve got to go about this systematically. Ashe, I want you to check over the assembly line from beginning to end --everything. You\rquote re to eliminate all operations in which there was no possible chance of an error, and list all those where there were, together with its nature and possible magnitude.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Tall order,\rdblquote  grunted Ashe.\par
\tab\ldblquote Naturally! Of course, you\rquote re to put the men under you to work on this  -- every single one if you have to, and I don\rquote t care if we go behind schedule, either. But they\rquote re not to know why, you understand.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hm-m-m, yes!\rdblquote  The young technician grinned wryly. \ldblquote It\rquote s still a lulu of a job.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning swiveled about in his chair and faced Calvin, \ldblquote You\rquote ll have to tackle the job from the other direction. You\rquote re the robo-psychologist of the plant, so you\rquote re to study the robot itself and work backward. Try to find out how he ticks. See what else is tied up with his telepathic powers, how far they extend, how they warp his outlook, and just exactly what harm it has done to his ordinary RB properties. You\rquote ve got that?\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning didn\rquote t wait for Dr. Calvin to answer.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll co-ordinate the work and interpret the findings mathematically.\rdblquote  He puffed violently at his cigar and mumbled the rest through the smoke; \ldblquote Bogert will help me there, of course.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert polished the nails of one pudgy hand with the other and said blandly, \ldblquote I dare say. I know a little in the line.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well! I\rquote ll get started.\rdblquote  Ashe shoved his chair back and rose. His pleasantly youthful face crinkled in a grin, \ldblquote I\rquote ve got the darnedest job of any of us, so I\rquote m getting out of here and to work.\rdblquote\par
\tab He left with a slurred, \ldblquote B\rquote  seein\rquote  ye!\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin answered with a barely perceptible nod, but her eyes followed him out of sight and she did not answer when Lanning grunted and said, \ldblquote Do you want to go up and see RB-34 now, Dr. Calvin?\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab RB-34\rquote s photoelectric eyes lifted from the book at the muffled sound of binges turning and he was upon his feet when Susan Calvin entered.\par
\tab She paused to readjust the huge \ldblquote No Entrance\rdblquote  sign upon the door and then approached the robot.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve brought you the texts upon hyperatomic motors, Herbie -- a few anyway. Would you care to look at them?\rdblquote\par
\tab RB-34 -- otherwise known as Herbie -- lifted the three heavy books from her arms and opened to the title page of one:\par
