\tab And again there was nothing but dull silence, until from the end of the room Susan Calvin\rquote s laugh rang out suddenly, high-pitched and semi-hysterical.\par
\tab The two mathematicians jumped, and Bogerts eyes narrowed, \ldblquote You here? What\rquote s so funny?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nothing\rquote s funny.\rdblquote  Her voice was not quite natural. \ldblquote It\rquote s just that I\rquote m not the only one that\rquote s been caught. There\rquote s irony in three of the greatest experts in robotics in the world falling into the same elementary trap, isn\rquote t there?\rdblquote  Her voice faded, and she put a pale hand to her forehead, \ldblquote But it isn\rquote t funny!\rdblquote\par
\tab This time the look that passed between the two men was one of raised eyebrows. \ldblquote What trap are you talking about?\rdblquote  asked Lansing stiffly. \ldblquote Is something wrong with Herbie?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  she approached them slowly, \ldblquote nothing is wrong with him -- only with us.\rdblquote  She whirled suddenly and shrieked at the robot, \ldblquote Get away from me! Go to the other end of the room and don\rquote t let me look at you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Herbie cringed before the fury of her eyes and stumbled away in a clattering trot.\par
\tab Lanning\rquote s voice was hostile, \ldblquote What is all this, Dr. Calvin?\rdblquote\par
\tab She faced them and spoke sarcastically, \ldblquote Surely you know the fundamental First Law of Robotics.\rdblquote\par
\tab The other two nodded together. \ldblquote Certainly,\rdblquote  said Bogert, Irritably, \ldblquote a robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow him to come to harm\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How nicely put,\rdblquote  sneered Calvin. \ldblquote But what kind of harm?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why -- any kind.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly! Any kind! But what about hurt feelings? What about deflation of one\rquote s ego? What about the blasting of one\rquote s hopes? Is that injury?\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning frowned, \ldblquote What would a robot know about-\rdblquote  And then he caught himself with a gasp.\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ve caught on, have you? \i This\i0  robot reads minds. Do you suppose it doesn\rquote t know everything about mental injury? Do you suppose that if asked a question, it wouldn\rquote t give exactly that answer that one wants to hear? Wouldn\rquote t any other answer hurt us, and wouldn\rquote t Herbie know that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good Heavens!\rdblquote  muttered Bogert.\par
\tab The psychologist cast a sardonic glance at him, \ldblquote I take it you asked him whether Lanning had resigned. You wanted to hear that he had resigned and so that\rquote s what Herbie told you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And I suppose that is why,\rdblquote  said Lanning, tonelessly, \ldblquote it would not answer a little while ago. It couldn\rquote t answer either way without hurting one of us.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a short pause in which the men looked thoughtfully across the room at the robot, crouching in the chair by the bookcase, head resting in one hand.\par
\tab Susan Calvin stared steadfastly at the floor, \ldblquote He knew of all this. That... that devil knows everything -- including what went wrong in his assembly.\rdblquote  Her eyes were dark and brooding.\par
\tab Lanning looked up, \ldblquote You\rquote re wrong there, Dr. Calvin. He doesn\rquote t know what went wrong. I asked him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What does that mean?\rdblquote  cried Calvin. \ldblquote Only that you didn\rquote t want him to give you the solution. It would puncture your ego to have a machine do what you couldn\rquote t. Did you ask him?\rdblquote  she shot at Bogert.\par
\tab\ldblquote In a way.\rdblquote  Bogert coughed and reddened. \ldblquote He told me he knew very little about mathematics.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning laughed, not very loudly and the psychologist smiled caustically. She said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll ask him! A solution by him won\rquote t hurt my ego\rdblquote  She raised her voice into a cold, imperative, \ldblquote Come here!\rdblquote\par
\tab Herbie rose and approached with hesitant steps.\par
\tab\ldblquote You know, I suppose,\rdblquote  she continued, \ldblquote just exactly at what point in the assembly an extraneous factor was introduced or an essential one left out.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Herbie, in tones barely heard.\par
\tab\ldblquote Hold on,\rdblquote  broke in Bogert angrily. \ldblquote That\rquote s not necessary true. You want to hear that, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t be a fool,\rdblquote  replied Calvin. \ldblquote He certainly knows as much math as you and Lanning together, since he can read minds. Give him his chance.\rdblquote\par
\tab The mathematician subsided, and Calvin continued, \ldblquote All right, then, Herbie, give! We\rquote re waiting.\rdblquote  And in an aside, \ldblquote Get pencils and paper, gentlemen.\rdblquote\par
\tab But Herbie remained silent, and there was triumph in the psychologist\rquote s voice, \ldblquote Why don\rquote t you answer, Herbie?\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot blurted out suddenly, \ldblquote I cannot. You know I cannot! Dr. Bogert and Dr. Lanning don\rquote t want me to.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They want the solution.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But not from me.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning broke in, speaking slowly and distinctly, \ldblquote Don\rquote t be foolish, Herbie. We do want you to tell us.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert nodded curtly.\par
\tab Herbie\rquote s voice rose to wild heights, \ldblquote What\rquote s the use of saying that? Don\rquote t you suppose that I can see past the superficial skin of your mind? Down below, you don\rquote t want me to. I\rquote m a machine, given the imitation of life only by virtue of the positronic interplay in my brain -- which is man\rquote s device. You can\rquote t lose face to me without being hurt. That is deep in your mind and won\rquote t be erased. I can\rquote t give the solution.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ll leave,\rdblquote  said Dr. Lanning. \ldblquote Tell Calvin.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That would make no difference,\rdblquote  cried Herbie, \ldblquote since you would know anyway that it was I that was supplying the answer.\rdblquote\par
\tab Calvin resumed, \ldblquote But you understand, Herbie, that despite that, Drs. Lanning and Bogert want that solution.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote By their own efforts!\rdblquote  insisted Herbie.\par
\tab\ldblquote But they want it, and the fact that you have it and won\rquote t give it hurts them. You see that, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes! Yes!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And if you tell them that will hurt them, too\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes! Yes!\rdblquote  Herbie was retreating slowly, and step-by-step Susan Calvin advanced. The two men watched in frozen bewilderment.\par
\tab\ldblquote You can\rquote t tell them,\rdblquote  droned the psychologist slowly, \ldblquote because that would hurt and you mustn\rquote t hurt. But if you don\rquote t tell them, you hurt, so you must tell them. And if you do, you will hurt and you mustn\rquote t, so you can\rquote t tell them; but if you don\rquote t, you hurt, so you must; but if you do, you hurt, so you mustn\rquote t; but if you don\rquote t, you hurt, so you must; but if you do, you-\rdblquote\par
\tab Herbie was up against the wall, and here he dropped to his knees. \ldblquote Stop!\rdblquote  he shrieked. \ldblquote Close your mind! It is full of pain and frustration and hate! I didn\rquote t mean it, I tell you! I tried to help! I told you what you wanted to hear. I had to!\rdblquote\par
\tab The psychologist paid no attention. \ldblquote You must tell them, but if you do, you hurt, so you mustn\rquote t; but if you don\rquote t, you hurt, so you must; but-\rdblquote\par
\tab And Herbie screamed!\par
\tab It was like the whistling of a piccolo many times magnified -- shrill and shriller till it keened with the terror of a lost soul and filled the room with the piercingness of itself.\par
\tab And when it died into nothingness, Herbie collapsed into a huddled heap of motionless metal.\par
\tab Bogert\rquote s face was bloodless, \ldblquote He\rquote s dead!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  Susan Calvin burst into body-racking gusts of wild laughter, \ldblquote not dead -- merely insane. I confronted him with the insoluble dilemma, and he broke down. You can scrap him now -- because he\rquote ll never speak again.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning was on his knees beside the thing that had been Herbie. His fingers touched the cold, unresponsive metal face and he shuddered. \ldblquote You did that on purpose.\rdblquote  He rose and faced her, face contorted.\par
\tab\ldblquote What if I did? You can\rquote t help it now.\rdblquote  And in a sudden access of bitterness, \ldblquote He deserved it.\rdblquote\par
\tab The director seized the paralyzed, motionless Bogert by the wrist, \ldblquote What\rquote s the difference. Come, Peter.\rdblquote  He sighed, \ldblquote A thinking robot of this type is worthless anyway.\rdblquote  His eyes were old and tired, and he repeated, \ldblquote Come, Peter!\rdblquote\par
\tab It was minutes after the two scientists left that Dr. Susan Calvin regained part of her mental equilibrium. Slowly, her eyes turned to the living-dead Herbie and the tightness returned to her face. Long she stared while the triumph faded and the helpless frustration returned -- and of all her turbulent thoughts only one infinitely bitter word passed her lips.\par
\tab\ldblquote\i Liar!\i0\rdblquote\par
