\tab Tony was tall and darkly handsome, with an incredibly patrician air drawn into every line of his unchangeable expression, and Claire Belmont regarded him through the crack in the door with a mixture of horror and dismay.\par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t, Larry. I just can\rquote t have him in the house.\rdblquote  Feverishly, she was searching her paralyzed mind for a stronger way of putting it; some way that would make sense and settle things, but she could only end with a simple repetition.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, I can\rquote t!\rdblquote\par
\tab Larry Belmont regarded his wife stiffly, and there was that spark of impa\-tience in his eyes that Claire hated to see, since she felt her own incompe\-tence mirrored in it. \ldblquote We\rquote re committed, Claire,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote and I can\rquote t have you backing out now. The company is sending me to Washington on this basis, and it probably means a promotion. It\rquote s perfectly safe and you know it. What\rquote s your objection?\rdblquote\par
\tab She frowned helplessly. \ldblquote It just gives me the chills. I couldn\rquote t bear him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s as human as you or I, almost. So, no nonsense. Come, get out there.\rdblquote\par
\tab His hand was in the small of her back, shoving; and she found herself in her own living room, shivering. \i It\i0  was there, looking at her with a precise politeness, as though appraising his hostess-to-be of the next three weeks. Dr. Susan Calvin was there, too, sitting stiffly in thin-lipped abstraction. She had the cold, faraway look of someone who has worked with machines so long that a little of the steel had entered the blood.\par
\tab\ldblquote Hello,\rdblquote  crackled Claire in general, and ineffectual, greeting.\par
\tab But Larry was busily saving the situation with a spurious gaiety. \ldblquote Here, Claire, I want you to meet Tony, a swell guy. This is my wife, Claire, Tony, old boy.\rdblquote  Larry\rquote s hand draped itself amiably over Tony\rquote s shoulder, but Tony remained unresponsive and expressionless under the pressure.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote How do you do, Mrs. Belmont.\rdblquote\par
\tab And Claire jumped at Tony\rquote s voice. It was deep and mellow, smooth as the hair on his head or the skin on his face.\par
\tab Before she could stop herself, she said, \ldblquote Oh, my--you talk.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not? Did you expect that I didn\rquote t?\rdblquote\par
\tab But Claire could only smile weakly. She didn\rquote t really know what she had expected. She looked away, then let him slide gently into the comer of her eye. His hair was smooth and black, like polished plastic--or was it really composed of separate hairs? And was the even, olive skin of his hands and face continued on past the obscurement of his formally cut clothing?\par
\tab She was lost in the shuddering wonder of it, and had to force her thoughts back into place to meet Dr. Calvin\rquote s flat, unemotional voice.\par
\tab\ldblquote Mrs. Belmont, I hope you appreciate the importance of this experiment. Your husband tells me he has given you some of the background. I would like to give you more, as the senior psychologist of the U.S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation.\par
\tab\ldblquote Tony is a robot. His actual designation on the company files is TN-3, but he will answer to Tony. He \i is\i0  not a mechanical monster, nor simply a calculating machine of the type that were developed during World War II, fifty years ago. He has an artificial brain nearly as complicated as our own. It is an immense telephone switchboard on an atomic scale, so that billions of possible \lquote telephone connections\rquote  can be compressed into an instrument that will fit inside a skull.\par
\tab\ldblquote Such brains are manufactured for each model of robot specifically. Each contains a precalculated set of connections so that each robot knows the English language to start with and enough of anything else that may be necessary to perform his job.\par
\tab\ldblquote Until now, U.S. Robots has confined its manufacturing activity to indus\-trial models for use in places where human labor is impractical--in deep mines, for instance, or in underwater work. But we want to invade the city and the home. To do so, we must get the ordinary man and woman to accept these robots without fear. You understand that there is nothing to fear.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There isn\rquote t, Claire,\rdblquote  interposed Larry earnestly. \ldblquote Take my word for it. It\rquote s impossible for him to do any harm. You know I wouldn\rquote t leave him with you otherwise.\rdblquote\par
\tab Claire cast a quick, secret glance at Tony and lowered her voice. \ldblquote What if I make him angry?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You needn\rquote t whisper,\rdblquote  said Dr. Calvin calmly. \ldblquote He \i can\rquote t\i0  get angry with you, my dear. I told you that the switchboard connections of his brain were predetermined. Well, the most important connection of all is what we call The First Law of Robotics,\rquote  and it is merely this: \lquote No robot can harm a human being, or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm.\rquote  All robots are built so. No robot can be forced in any way to do harm to any human. So, you see, we need you and Tony as a preliminary experiment for our own guidance, while your husband is in Washington to arrange for government-supervised legal tests.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean all this isn\rquote t legal?\rdblquote\par
\tab Larry cleared his throat. \ldblquote Not just yet, but it\rquote s all right. He won\rquote t leave the house, and you mustn\rquote t let anyone see him. That\rquote s all.... And, Claire, I\rquote d stay with you, but I know too much about the robots. We must have a completely inexperienced tester so that we can have severe condi\-tions. It\rquote s necessary.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, well,\rdblquote  muttered Claire. Then, as a thought struck her, \ldblquote But what does he do?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Housework,\rdblquote  said Dr. Calvin shortly.\par
\tab She got up to leave, and it was Larry who saw her to the front door. Claire stayed behind drearily. She caught a glimpse of herself in the mirror above the mantelpiece, and looked away hastily. She was very tired of her small, mousy face and her dim, unimaginative hair. Then she caught Tony\rquote s eyes upon her and almost smiled before she remembered....\par
\tab He was only a machine.\par
\par
\tab Larry Belmont was on his way to the airport when he caught a glimpse of Gladys Claffern. She was the type of woman who seemed made to be seen in glimpses.... Perfectly and precisely manufactured; dressed with thoughtful hand and eye; too gleaming to be stared at.\par
\tab The little smile that preceded her and the faint scent that trailed her were a pair of beckoning fingers. Larry felt his stride break; he touched his hat, then hurried on.\par
\tab As always he felt that vague anger. If Claire could only push her way into the Claffern clique, it would help so much. But what was the use.\par
\tab Claire! The few times she had come face to face with Gladys, the little fool had been tongue-tied. He had no illusions. The testing of Tony was his big chance, and it was in Claire\rquote s hands. How much safer it would be in the hands of someone like Gladys Claffern.\par
\par
\tab Claire woke the second morning to the sound of a subdued knock on the bedroom door. Her mind clamored, then went icy. She had avoided Tony the first day, smiling thinly when she met him and brushing past with a wordless sound of apology.\par
\tab\ldblquote Is that you--Tony?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Mrs. Belmont. May I enter?\rdblquote\par
\tab She must have said yes, because he was in the room, quite suddenly and noiselessly. Her eyes and nose were simultaneously aware of the tray he was carrying.\par
\tab\ldblquote Breakfast?\rdblquote  she said.\par
\tab\ldblquote If you please.\rdblquote\par
\tab She wouldn\rquote t have dared to refuse, so she pushed herself slowly into a sitting position and received it: poached eggs, buttered toast, coffee.\par
\tab\ldblquote I have brought the sugar and cream separately,\rdblquote  said Tony. \ldblquote I expect to learn your preference with time, in this and in other things.\rdblquote\par
\tab She waited.\par
\tab Tony, standing there straight and pliant as a metal rule, asked, after a moment, \ldblquote Would you prefer to eat in privacy?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.... I mean, if you don\rquote t mind.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Will you need help later in dressing?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, my, no!\rdblquote  She clutched frantically at the sheet, so that the coffee hovered at the edge of catastrophe. She remained so, in rigor, then sank helplessly back against the pillow when the door closed him out of her sight again.\par
\tab She got through breakfast somehow.... He was only a machine, and if it were only more visible that he were it wouldn\rquote t be so frightening. Or if his expression would change. It just stayed there, nailed on. You couldn\rquote t tell what went on behind those dark eyes and that smooth, olive skin-stuff. The coffee cup beat a faint castanet for a moment as she set it back, empty, on the tray.\par
\tab Then she realized that she had forgotten to add the sugar and cream after all, and she did so hate black coffee.\par
\par
\tab She burned a straight path from bedroom to kitchen after dressing. It was her house, after all, and there wasn\rquote t anything frippy about her, but she liked her kitchen clean. He should have waited for supervision....\par
\tab But when she entered, she found a kitchen that might have been minted fire-new from the factory the moment before.\par
\tab She stopped, stared, turned on her heel and nearly ran into Tony. She yelped.\par
\tab\ldblquote May I help?\rdblquote  he asked.\par
\tab\ldblquote Tony,\rdblquote  and she scraped the anger off the edges of her mind\rquote s panic, \ldblquote you must make some noise when you walk. I can\rquote t have you stalking me, you know.... Didn\rquote t you use this kitchen?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I did, Mrs. Belmont.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t look it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I cleaned up afterward. Isn\rquote t that customary?\rdblquote\par
\tab Claire opened her eyes wide. After all, what could one say to that. She opened the oven compartment that held the pots, took a quick, unseeing look at the metallic glitter inside, then said with a tremor, \ldblquote Very good. Quite satisfactory.\rdblquote\par
\tab If at the moment, he had beamed; if he had smiled; if he had quirked the corner of his mouth the slightest bit, she felt that she could have warmed to him. But he remained an English lord in repose, as he said, \ldblquote Thank you, Mrs. Belmont. Would you come into the living room?\rdblquote\par
\tab She did, and it struck her at once. \ldblquote Have you been polishing the furni\-ture?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is it satisfactory, Mrs. Belmont?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But when? You didn\rquote t do it yesterday.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Last night, of course.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You burned the lights all night?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, no. That wouldn\rquote t have been necessary. I\rquote ve a built-in ultra-violet source. I can see in ultraviolet. And, of course, I don\rquote t require sleep.\rdblquote\par
\tab He did require admiration, though. She realized that, then. He had to know that he was pleasing her. But she couldn\rquote t bring herself to supply that pleasure for him.\par
\tab She could only say sourly, \ldblquote Your kind will put ordinary houseworkers out of business.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There is work of much greater importance they can be put to in the world, once they are freed of drudgery. After all, Mrs. Belmont, things like myself can be manufactured. But nothing yet can imitate the creativity and versatility of a human brain, like yours.\rdblquote\par
\tab And though his face gave no hint, his voice was warmly surcharged with awe and admiration, so that Claire flushed and muttered, \ldblquote My brain! You can have it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Tony approached a little and said, \ldblquote You must be unhappy to say such a thing. Is there anything I can do?\rdblquote\par
\tab For a moment, Claire felt like laughing. It \i was\i0  a ridiculous situation. Here was an animated carpet-sweeper, dishwasher, furniture-polisher, general fac\-totum, rising from the factory table--and offering his services as consoler and confidant.\par
\tab Yet she said suddenly, in a burst of woe and voice, \ldblquote Mr. Belmont doesn\rquote t think I have a brain, if you must know.... And I suppose I haven\rquote t.\rdblquote  She couldn\rquote t cry in front of him. She felt, for some reason, that she had the honor of the human race to support against this mere creation.\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s lately,\rdblquote  she added. \ldblquote It was all right when he was a student; when he was just starting. But I can\rquote t be a big man\rquote s wife; and he\rquote s getting to be a big man. He wants me to be a hostess and an entry into social life for him--like G--guh--guh--Gladys Claffern.\rdblquote\par
\tab Her nose was red, and she looked away.\par
\tab But Tony wasn\rquote t watching her. His eyes wandered about the room. \ldblquote I can help you run the house.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But it\rquote s no good,\rdblquote  she said fiercely. \ldblquote It needs a touch I can\rquote t give it. I can \tab only make it comfortable; I can\rquote t ever make it the kind they take pictures of for the Home Beautiful magazines.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you want that kind?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Does it do any good--wanting?\rdblquote\par
\tab Tony\rquote s eyes were on her, full. \ldblquote I could help.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you know anything about interior decoration?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is it something a good housekeeper should know?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then I have the potentialities of learning it. Can you get me books on the subject?\rdblquote\par
\tab Something started then.\par
\par
\tab Claire, clutching her hat against the brawling liberties of the wind, had manipulated two fat volumes on the home arts back from the public library. She watched Tony as he opened one of them and flipped the pages. It was the first time she had watched his fingers flicker at anything like fine work.\par
\tab I don\rquote t see how they do it, she thought, and on a sudden impulse reached for his hand and pulled it toward herself. Tony did not resist, but let it lie limp for inspection.\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote It\rquote s remarkable. Even your fingernails look natural.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s deliberate, of course,\rdblquote  said Tony. Then, chattily, \ldblquote The skin is a flexible plastic, and the skeletal framework is a light metal alloy. Does that amuse you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, no.\rdblquote  She lifted her reddened face. \ldblquote I just feel a little embarrassed at sort of poking into your insides. It\rquote s none of my business. You don\rquote t ask me about mine.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote My brain paths don\rquote t include that type of curiosity. I can only act within my limitations, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab And Claire felt something tighten inside her in the silence that followed. Why did she keep forgetting he was a machine. Now the thing itself had to remind her. Was she so starved for sympathy that she would even accept a robot as equal--because he sympathized?\par
\tab She noticed Tony was still flipping the pages--almost helplessly--and there was a quick, shooting sense of relieved superiority within her. \ldblquote You can\rquote t read, can you?\rdblquote\par
\tab Tony looked up at her; his voice calm, unreproachful. \ldblquote I \i am\i0  reading, Mrs. Belmont.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But--\rdblquote  She pointed at the book in a meaningless gesture.\par
\tab\ldblquote I am scanning the pages, if that\rquote s what you mean. My sense of reading is photographic.\rdblquote\par
\tab It was evening then, and when Claire eventually went to bed Tony was well into the second volume, sitting there in the dark, or what seemed dark to Claire\rquote s limited eyes.\par
\tab Her last thought, the one that clamored at her just as her mind let go and tumbled, was a queer one. She remembered his hand again; the touch of it. It had been warm and soft, like a human being\rquote s. \par
\tab How clever of the factory, she thought, and softly ebbed to sleep.\par
\par
\tab It was the library continuously, thereafter, for several days. Tony sug\-gested the fields of study, which branched out quickly. There were books on color matching and on cosmetics; on carpentry and on fashions; on art and on the history of costumes.\par
\tab He turned the pages of each book before his solemn eyes, and, as quickly as he turned, he read; nor did he seem capable of forgetting.\par
\tab Before the end of the week, he had insisted on cutting her hair, introduc\-ing her to a new method of arranging it, adjusting her eyebrow line a bit and changing the shade of her powder and lipstick.\par
\tab She had palpitated in nervous dread for half an hour under the delicate touch of his inhuman fingers and then looked in the mirror.\par
\tab\ldblquote There is more that can be done,\rdblquote  said Tony, \ldblquote especially in clothes. How do you find it for a beginning?\rdblquote\par
\tab And she hadn\rquote t answered; not for quite a while. Not until she had ab\-sorbed the identity of the stranger in the glass and cooled the wonder at the beauty of it all. Then she had said chokingly, never once taking her eyes from the warming image, \ldblquote Yes, Tony, quite good--for a beginning.\rdblquote\par
\tab She said nothing of this in her letters to Larry. Let him see it all at once. And something in her realized that it wasn\rquote t only the surprise she would enjoy. It was going to be a kind of revenge.\par
\par
\tab Tony said one morning, \ldblquote It\rquote s time to start buying, and I\rquote m not allowed to leave the house. If I write out exactly what we must have, can I trust you to get it? We need drapery, and furniture fabric, wallpaper, carpeting, paint, clothing--and any number of small things.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You can\rquote t get these things to your own specifications at a stroke\rquote s no\-tice,\rdblquote  said Claire doubtfully.\par
\tab\ldblquote You can get fairly close, if you go through the city and if money is no object.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But, Tony, money is certainly an object.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all. Stop off at U.S. Robots in the first place. I\rquote ll write a note for you. You see Dr. Calvin, and tell her that I said it was part of the experi\-ment.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Dr. Calvin, somehow, didn\rquote t frighten her as on that first evening. With her new face and a new hat, she couldn\rquote t be quite the old Claire. The psychologist listened carefully, asked a few questions, nodded--and then Claire found herself walking out, armed with an unlimited charge account against the assets of U.S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation.\par
\tab It is wonderful what money will do. With a store\rquote s contents at her feet, a saleslady\rquote s dictum was not necessarily a voice from above; the uplifted eye\-brow of a decorator was not anything like Jove\rquote s thunder.\par
\tab And once, when an Exalted Plumpness at one of the most lordly of the garment salons had insistently poohed her description of the wardrobe she must have with counterpronouncements in accents of the purest Fifty-sev\-enth Street French, she called up Tony, then held the phone out to Mon\-sieur.\par
\tab\ldblquote If you don\rquote t mind\rdblquote --voice firm, but fingers twisting a bit--\rdblquote I\rquote d like you to talk to my--uh--secretary.\rdblquote\par
\tab Pudgy proceeded to the phone with a solemn arm crooked behind his back. He lifted the phone in two fingers and said delicately, \ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  A short pause, another \ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  then a much longer pause, a squeaky beginning of an objection that perished quickly, another pause, a very meek \ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  and the phone was restored to its cradle.\par
\tab\ldblquote If Madam will come with me,\rdblquote  he said, hurt and distant, \ldblquote I will try to supply her needs.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Just a second.\rdblquote  Claire rushed back to the phone, and dialed again. \ldblquote Hello, Tony. I don\rquote t know what you said, but it worked. Thanks. You\rquote re a--\rdblquote  She struggled for the appropriate word, gave up and ended in a final little squeak, \ldblquote --a--a dear!\rdblquote\par
\tab It was Gladys Claffern looking at her when she turned from the phone again. A slightly amused and slightly amazed Gladys Claffern, looking at her out of a face tilted a bit to one side.\par
\tab\ldblquote Mrs. Belmont?\rdblquote\par
\tab It all drained out of Claire--just like that. She could only nod--stupidly, like a marionette.\par
\tab Gladys smiled with an insolence you couldn\rquote t put your finger on. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t know you shopped here?\rdblquote  As if the place had, in her eyes, definitely lost caste through the fact.\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t, usually,\rdblquote  said Claire humbly.\par
\tab\ldblquote And haven\rquote t you done something to your hair? It\rquote s quite--quaint.... Oh, I hope you\rquote ll excuse me, but isn\rquote t your husband\rquote s name Lawrence? It seems to me that it\rquote s Lawrence.\rdblquote\par
\tab Claire\rquote s teeth clenched, but she had to explain. She \i had\i0  to. \ldblquote Tony is a friend of my husband\rquote s. He\rquote s helping me select some things.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I understand. And quite a \i dear\i0  about it, I imagine.\rdblquote  She passed on smiling, carrying the light and the warmth of the world with her.\par
\par
\tab Claire did not question the fact that it was to Tony that she turned for consolation. Ten days had cured her of reluctance. And she could weep before him; weep and rage.\par
\tab\ldblquote I was a complete f-fool,\rdblquote  she stormed, wrenching at her water-togged handkerchief. \ldblquote She does that to me. I don\rquote t know why. She just does. I should have--kicked her. I should have knocked her down and stamped on her.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can you hate a human being so much?\rdblquote  asked Tony, in puzzled softness. \ldblquote That part of a human mind is closed to me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, it isn\rquote t she,\rdblquote  she moaned. \ldblquote It\rquote s myself, I suppose. She\rquote s everything I want to be--on the outside, anyway.... And I can\rquote t be.\rdblquote\par
\tab Tony\rquote s voice was forceful and low in her ear. \ldblquote You can be, Mrs. Belmont. You can be. We have ten days yet, and in ten days the house will no longer be itself. Haven\rquote t we been planning that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And how will that help me--with her?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Invite her here. Invite her friends. Have it the evening before I--before I leave. It will be a housewarming, in a way.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote She won\rquote t come.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, she will. She\rquote ll come to laugh.... And she won\rquote t be able to.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you really think so? Oh, Tony, do you think we can do it?\rdblquote  She had both his hands in hers.... And then, with her face flung aside, \ldblquote But what good would it be? It won\rquote t be I; it will be you that\rquote s doing it. I can\rquote t ride your back.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nobody lives in splendid singleness,\rdblquote  whispered Tony. \ldblquote They\rquote ve put that knowledge in me. What you, or anyone, see in Gladys Claffern is not just Gladys Claffern. She rides the back of all that money and social position can bring. She doesn\rquote t question that. Why should you? ... And look at it this way, Mrs. Belmont. I am manufactured to obey, but the extent of my obedience is for myself to determine. I can follow orders niggardly or liber\-ally. For you, it is liberal, because you are what I have been manufactured to see human beings as. You are kind, friendly, unassuming. Mrs. Claffern, as you describe her, is not, and I wouldn\rquote t obey her as I would you. So it \i is\i0  you, and not \i I\i0 , Mrs. Belmont, that is doing all this.\rdblquote\par
\tab He withdrew his hands from hers then, and Claire looked at that expres\-sionless face no one could read--wondering. She was suddenly frightened \lquote  again in a completely new way.\par
\tab She swallowed nervously and stared at her hands, which were still tingling \lquote  with the pressure of his fingers. She hadn\rquote t imagined it; his fingers had pressed hers, gently, tenderly, just before they moved away. \par
\tab\i No!\par
\i0\tab\i Its\i0  fingers ... \i Its\i0  fingers....\par
\tab She ran to the bathroom and scrubbed her hands--blindly, uselessly.\par
\par
\tab She was a bit shy of him the next day; watching him narrowly; waiting to see what might follow--and for a while nothing did.\par
\tab Tony was working. If there was any difficulty in technique in putting up wallpaper, or utilizing the quick-drying paint, Tony\rquote s activity did not show it. His hands moved precisely; his fingers were deft and sure.\par
\tab He worked all night. She never heard him, but each morning was a new adventure. She couldn\rquote t count the number of things that had been done, and by evening she was still finding new touches--and another night had come.\par
\tab She tried to help only once and her human clumsiness marred that. \i He\i0  was in the next room, and she was hanging a picture in the spot marked by Tony\rquote s mathematical eyes. The little mark was there; the picture was there; and a revulsion against idleness was there.\par
\tab But she was nervous, or the ladder was rickety. It didn\rquote t matter. She felt it going, and she cried out. It tumbled without her, for Tony, with far more than flesh-and-blood quickness, had been under her.\par
\tab His calm, dark eyes said nothing at all, and his warm voice said only words. \ldblquote Are you hurt, Mrs. Belmont?\rdblquote\par
\tab She noticed for an instant that her falling hand must have mussed that sleek hair of his, because for the first time she could see for herself that it was composed of distinct strands--fine black hairs.\par
\tab And then, all at once, she was conscious of his arms about her shoulders and under her knees--holding her tightly and warmly.\par
\tab She pushed, and her scream was loud in her own ears. She spent the rest of the day in her room, and thereafter she slept with a chair upended against the doorknob of her bedroom door.\par
\par
\tab She had sent out the invitations, and, as Tony had said, they were ac\-cepted. She had only to wait for the last evening.\par
\tab It came, too, after the rest of them, in its proper place. The house was scarcely her own. She went through it one last time--and every room had been changed. She, herself, was in clothes she would never have dared wear before.... And when you put them on, you put on pride and confidence with them.\par
\tab She tried a polite look of contemptuous amusement before the minor, and the mirror sneered back at her masterfully.\par
\tab What would Larry say? ... It didn\rquote t matter, somehow. The exciting days weren\rquote t coming with him. They were leaving with Tony. Now wasn\rquote t that strange? She tried to recapture her mood of three weeks before and failed completely.\par
\par
\tab The clock shrieked eight at her in eight breathless installments, and she turned to Tony. \ldblquote They\rquote ll be here soon, Tony. You\rquote d better get into the basement. We can\rquote t let them--\rdblquote\par
\tab She stared a moment, then said weakly, \ldblquote Tony?\rdblquote  and more strongly, \ldblquote Tony?\rdblquote  and nearly a scream, \ldblquote\i Tony!\i0\rdblquote\par
\tab But his arms were around her now; his face was close to hers; the pressure of his embrace was relentless. She heard his voice through a haze of emo\-tional jumble.\par
\tab\ldblquote Claire,\rdblquote  the voice said, \ldblquote there are many things I am not made to under\-stand, and this must be one of them. I am leaving tomorrow, and I don\rquote t want to. I find that there is more in me than just a desire to please you. Isn\rquote t it strange?\rdblquote\par
\tab His face was closer; his lips were warm, but with no breath behind them --for machines do not breathe. They were almost on hers.\par
\tab ... And the bell sounded.\par
\tab For a moment, she struggled breathlessly, and then he was gone and nowhere in sight, and the bell was sounding again. Its intermittent shrillness was insistent.\par
\tab The curtains on the front windows had been pulled open. They had been closed fifteen minutes earlier. She knew that.\par
\tab They must have seen, then. They must \i all\i0  have seen--everything!\par
\par
\tab They came in so politely, all in a bunch--the pack come to howl--with their sharp, darting eyes piercing everywhere. They \i had\i0  seen. Why else would Gladys ask in her jabbingest manner after Larry? And Claire was spurred to a desperate and reckless defiance.\par
\tab Yes, he \i is\i0  away. He\rquote ll be back tomorrow, I suppose. No, I haven\rquote t been lonely here myself. Not a bit. I\rquote ve had an exciting time. And she laughed at them. Why not? What could they do? Larry would know the truth, if it ever came to him, the story of what they thought they saw.\par
\tab But \i they\i0  didn\rquote t laugh.\par
\tab She could read that in the fury in Gladys Claffern\rquote s eyes; in the false sparkle of her words; in her desire to leave early. And as she parted with them, she caught one last, anonymous whisper--disjointed.\par
\tab\ldblquote ... never saw anything like ... so \i handsome\i0 --\rdblquote\par
\tab And she knew what it was that had enabled her to finger-snap them so. Let each cat mew; and let each cat know--that she might be prettier than Claire Belmont, and grander, and richer--but not one, \i not one\i0 , could have so handsome a lover!\par
\tab And then she remembered again--again--again, that Tony was a ma\-chine, and her skin crawled.\par
\tab\ldblquote Go away! Leave me be!\rdblquote  she cried to the empty room and ran to her bed. She wept wakefully all that night and the next morning, almost before dawn, when the streets were empty, a car drew up to the house and took Tony away.\par
\par
\tab Lawrence Belmont passed Dr. Calvin\rquote s office, and, on impulse, knocked. He found her with Mathematician Peter Bogert, but did not hesitate on that account.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Claire tells me that U.S. Robots paid for all that was done at my house--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dr. Calvin. \ldblquote We\rquote ve written it off, as a valuable and necessary part of the experiment. With your new position as Associate Engineer, you\rquote ll be able to keep it up, I think.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s not what I\rquote m worried about. With Washington agreeing to the tests, we\rquote ll be able to get a TN model of our own by next year, I think.\rdblquote  He turned hesitantly, as though to go, and as hesitantly turned back again.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, Mr. Belmont?\rdblquote  asked Dr. Calvin, after a pause.\par
\tab\ldblquote I wonder--\rdblquote  began Larry. \ldblquote I wonder what really happened there. She-- Claire, I mean--seems so different. It\rquote s not just her looks--though, frankly, I\rquote m amazed.\rdblquote  He laughed nervously. \ldblquote It\rquote s \i her!\i0  She\rquote s not my wife, really--I can\rquote t explain it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why try? Are you disappointed with any part of the change?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote On the contrary. But it\rquote s a little frightening, too, you see--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t worry, Mr. Belmont. Your wife has handled herself very well. Frankly, I never expected to have the experiment yield such a thorough and complete test. We know exactly what corrections must be made in the TN model, and the credit belongs entirely to Mrs. Belmont. If you want me to be very honest, I think your wife deserves your promotion more than you do.\rdblquote\par
\tab Larry flinched visibly at that. \ldblquote As long as it\rquote s in the family,\rdblquote  he murmured unconvincingly and left.\par
\par
\tab Susan Calvin looked after him, \ldblquote I think that hurt--I hope.... Have you read Tony\rquote s report, Peter?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thoroughly,\rdblquote  said Bogert. \ldblquote And won\rquote t the TN-3 model need changes?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, you think so, too?\rdblquote  questioned Calvin sharply. \ldblquote What\rquote s your reason\-ing?\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert frowned. \ldblquote I don\rquote t need any. It\rquote s obvious on the face of it that we can\rquote t have a robot loose which makes love to his mistress, if you don\rquote t mind the pun.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Love! Peter, you sicken me. You really don\rquote t understand? That machine had to obey the First Law. He couldn\rquote t allow harm to come to a human being, and harm was coming to Claire Belmont through her own sense of inadequacy. So he made love to her, since what woman would fail to appre\-ciate the compliment of being able to stir passion in a machine--in a cold, soulless machine. And he opened the curtains that night deliberately, that the others might see and envy--without any risk possible to Claire\rquote s mar\-riage. I think it was clever of Tony--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you? What\rquote s the difference whether it was pretense or not, Susan? It still has its horrifying effect. Read the report again. She avoided him. She screamed when he held her. She didn\rquote t sleep that last night--in hysterics. We can\rquote t have that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Peter, you\rquote re blind. You\rquote re as blind as I was. The TN model will be rebuilt entirely, but not for your reason. Quite otherwise; quite otherwise. Strange that I overlooked it in the first place,\rdblquote  her eyes were opaquely thoughtful, \ldblquote but perhaps it reflects a shortcoming in myself. You see, Peter, machines can\rquote t fall in love, but--even when it\rquote s hopeless and horrifying-- women can!\rdblquote\par
