\tab United States Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation had a problem. The problem was people. \par
\tab Peter Bogert, Senior Mathematician, was on his way to Assembly when he encountered Alfred Lanning, Research Director. Lanning was bending his ferocious white eyebrows together and staring down across the railing into the computer room. \par
\tab On the floor below the balcony, a trickle of humanity of both sexes and various ages was looking about curiously, while a guide intoned a set speech about robotic computing. \par
\tab\ldblquote This computer you see before you,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote is the largest of its type in the world. It contains five million three hundred thousand cryotrons and is capable of dealing simultaneously with over one hundred thousand variables. With its help, U. S. Robots is able to design with precision the positronic brains of new models. \ldblquote The requirements are fed in on tape which is perforated by the action of this keyboard--something like a very complicated typewriter or linotype machine, except that it does not deal with letters but with concepts. Statements are broken down into the symbolic logic equivalents and those in turn converted to perforation patterns. \par
\tab\ldblquote The computer can, in less than one hour, present our scientists with a design for a brain which will give all the necessary positronic paths to make a robot...\rdblquote  \par
\tab Alfred Lanning looked up at last and noticed the other. \ldblquote Ah, Peter,\rdblquote  he said. \par
\tab Bogert raised both hands to smooth down his already perfectly smooth and glossy head of black hair. He said, \ldblquote You don\rquote t look as though you think much of this, Alfred.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lanning grunted. The idea of public guided tours of U. S. Robots was of fairly recent origin, and was supposed to serve a dual function. On the one hand, the theory went, it allowed people to see robots at close quarters and counter their almost instinctive fear of the mechanical objects through increased familiarity. And on the other hand, it was supposed to interest at least an occasional person in taking up robotics research as a life work. \par
\tab\ldblquote You know I don\rquote t,\rdblquote  Lanning said finally. \ldblquote Once a week, work is disrupted. Considering the man-hours lost, the return is insufficient.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Still no rise in job applications, then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, some, but only in the categories where the need isn\rquote t vital. It\rquote s research men that are needed. You know that. The trouble is that with robots forbidden on Earth itself, there\rquote s something unpopular about being a roboticist.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The damned Frankenstein complex,\rdblquote  said Bogert, consciously imitating one of the other\rquote s pet phrases. \par
\tab Lanning missed the gentle jab. He said, \ldblquote I ought to be used to it, but I never will. You\rquote d think that by now every human being on Earth would know that the Three Laws represented a perfect safeguard; that robots are simply not dangerous. Take this bunch.\rdblquote  He glowered down. \ldblquote Look at them. Most of them go through the robot assembly room for the thrill of fear, like riding a roller coaster. Then when they enter the room with the MEC model--damn it, Peter, a MEC model that will do nothing on God\rquote s green Earth but take two steps forward, say \lquote Pleased to meet you, sir,\rquote  shake hands, then take two steps back--they back away and mothers snatch up their kids. How do we expect to get brainwork out of such idiots?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bogert had no answer. Together, they stared down once again at the line of sightseers, now passing out of the computer room and into the positronic brain assembly section. Then they left. They did not, as it turned out, observe Mortimer W. Jacobson, age 16--who, to do him complete justice, meant no harm whatever. \par
\par
\tab In fact, it could not even be said to be Mortimer\rquote s fault. The day of the week on which the tour took place was known to all workers. \par
\tab All devices in its path ought to have been carefully neutralized or locked, since it was unreasonable to expect human beings to withstand the temptation to handle knobs, keys, handles and pushbuttons. In addition, the guide ought to have been very carefully on the watch for those who succumbed. \par
\tab But, at the time, the guide had passed into the next room and Mortimer was tailing the line. He passed the keyboard on which instructions were fed into the computer. He had no way of suspecting that the plans for a new robot design were being fed into it at that moment, or, being a good kid, he would have avoided the keyboard. He had no way of knowing that, by what amounted to almost criminal negligence, a technician had not inactivated the keyboard. \par
\tab So Mortimer touched the keys at random as though he were playing a musical instrument. \par
\tab He did not notice that a section of perforated tape stretched itself out of the instrument in another part of the room--soundlessly, unobtrusively. \par
\tab Nor did the technician, when he returned, discover any signs of tampering. He felt a little uneasy at noticing that the keyboard was live, but did not think to check. After a few minutes, even his first trifling uneasiness was gone, and he continued feeding data into the computer. \par
\tab As for Mortimer, neither then, nor ever afterward, did he know what he had done. \par
\par
\tab The new LNE model was designed for the mining of boron in the asteroid belt. The boron hydrides were increasing in value yearly as primers for the proton micropiles that carried the ultimate load of power production on spaceships, and Earth\rquote s own meager supply was running thin. \par
\tab Physically, that meant that the LNE robots would have to be equipped with eyes sensitive to those lines prominent in the spectroscopic analysis of boron ores and the type of limbs most useful for the working up of ore to finished product. As always, though, the mental equipment was the major problem. \par
\tab The first LNE positronic brain had been completed now. It was the prototype and would join all other prototypes in U. S. Robots\rquote  collection. When finally tested, others would then be manufactured for leasing (never selling) to mining corporations. \par
\tab LNE-Prototype was complete now. Tall, straight, polished, it looked from outside like any of a number of not-too-specialized robot models. \par
\tab The technician in charge, guided by the directions for testing in the \i Handbook of Robotics, \i0 said, \ldblquote How are you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The indicated answer was to have been, \ldblquote I am well and ready to begin my functions. I trust you are well, too,\rdblquote  or some trivial modification thereof. \par
\tab This first exchange served no purpose but to show that the robot could hear, understand a routine question, and make a routine reply congruent with what one would expect of a robotic attitude. Beginning from there, one could pass on to more complicated matters that would test the different Laws and their interaction with the specialized knowledge of each particular model. \par
\tab So the technician said, \ldblquote How are you?\rdblquote  He was instantly jolted by the nature of LNE-Prototype\rquote s voice. It had a quality like no robotic voice he had ever heard (and he had heard many). It formed syllables like the chimes of a low-pitched celeste. \par
\tab So surprising was this that it was only after several moments that the technician heard, in retrospect, the syllables that had been formed by those heavenly tones. They were, \ldblquote Da, da, da, goo.\rdblquote  The robot still stood tall and straight but its right hand crept upward and a finger went into its mouth. \par
\tab The technician stared in absolute horror and bolted. He locked the door behind him and, from another room, put in an emergency call to Dr. Susan Calvin. \par
\par
\tab Dr. Susan Calvin was U. S. Robots\rquote  (and, virtually, mankind\rquote s) only robopsychologist. She did not have to go very far in her testing of LNE-Prototype before she called very peremptorily for a transcript of the computer-drawn plans of the positronic brain-paths and the taped instructions that had directed them. After some study, she, in turn, sent for Bogert. \par
\tab Her iron-gray hair was drawn severely back; her cold face, with its strong vertical lines marked off by the horizontal gash of the pale, thin-lipped mouth, turned intensely upon him. \par
\tab\ldblquote What \i is \i0 this, Peter?\rdblquote  Bogert studied the passages she pointed out with increasing stupefaction and said, \ldblquote Good Lord, Susan, it makes no sense.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It most certainly doesn\rquote t. How did it get into the instructions?\rdblquote  The technician in charge, called upon, swore in all sincerity that it was none of his doing, and that he could not account for it. The computer checked out negative for all attempts at flaw-finding. \par
\tab\ldblquote The positronic brain,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin, thoughtfully, \ldblquote is past redemption. So many of the higher functions have been cancelled out by these meaningless directions that the result is very like a human baby.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bogert looked surprised, and Susan Calvin took on a frozen attitude at once, as she always did at the least expressed or implied doubt of her word. She said, \ldblquote We make every effort to make a robot as mentally like a man as possible. Eliminate what we call the adult functions and what is naturally left is a human infant, mentally speaking. Why do you look so surprised, Peter?\rdblquote  \par
\tab LNE-Prototype, who showed no signs of understanding any of the things that were going on around it, suddenly slipped into a sitting position and began a minute examination of its feet. \par
\tab Bogert stared at it. \ldblquote It\rquote s a shame to have to dismantle the creature. It\rquote s a handsome job.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Dismantle it?\rdblquote  said the robopsychologist forcefully. \ldblquote Of course, Susan. What\rquote s the use of this thing? Good Lord, if there\rquote s one object completely and abysmally useless it\rquote s a robot without a job it can perform. You don\rquote t pretend there\rquote s a job this thing can do, do you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No, of course not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, then?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin said, stubbornly, \ldblquote I want to conduct more tests.\rdblquote  Bogert looked at her with a moment\rquote s impatience, then shrugged. If there was one person at U. S. Robots with whom it was useless to dispute, surely that was Susan Calvin. Robots were all she loved, and long association with them, it seemed to Bogert, had deprived her of any appearance of humanity. She was no more to be argued out of a decision than was a triggered micropile to be argued out of operating. \par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s the use?\rdblquote  he breathed; then aloud, hastily: \ldblquote Will you let us know when your tests are complete?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I will,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Come, Lenny.\rdblquote  \par
\tab (LNE, thought Bogert. That becomes Lenny. Inevitable.) \par
\tab Susan Calvin held out her hand but the robot only stared at it. Gently, the robopsychologist reached for the robot\rquote s hand and took it. Lenny rose smoothly to its feet (its mechanical coordination, at least, worked well). Together they walked out, robot topping woman by two feet. Many eyes followed them curiously down the long corridors. \par
\par
\tab One wall of Susan Calvin\rquote s laboratory, the one opening directly off her private office, was covered with a highly magnified reproduction of a positronic-path chart. Susan Calvin had studied it with absorption for the better part of a month. \par
\tab She was considering it now, carefully, tracing the blunted paths through their contortions. Behind her, Lenny sat on the floor, moving its legs apart and together, crooning meaningless syllables to itself in a voice so beautiful that one could listen to the nonsense and be ravished. \par
\tab Susan Calvin turned to the robot, \ldblquote Lenny--Lenny--\rdblquote  \par
\tab She repeated this patiently until finally Lenny looked up and made an inquiring sound. The robopsychologist allowed a glimmer of pleasure to cross her face fleetingly. The robot\rquote s attention was being gained in progressively shorter intervals. \par
\tab She said, \ldblquote Raise your hand, Lenny. Hand-up. Hand-up.\rdblquote  She raised her own hand as she said it, over and over. \par
\tab Lenny followed the movement with its eyes. Up, down, up, down. Then it made an abortive gesture with its own hand and chimed, \ldblquote Eh-uh.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Very good, Lenny,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin, gravely. \ldblquote Try it again. Hand-up.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Very gently, she reached out her own hand, took the robot\rquote s, and raised it, lowered it. \ldblquote Hand-up. Hand-up.\rdblquote  \par
\tab A voice from her office called and interrupted. \ldblquote Susan?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Calvin halted with a tightening of her lips. \ldblquote What is it, Alfred?\rdblquote  The research director walked in, and looked at the chart on the wall and at the robot. \ldblquote Still at it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m at my work, yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, you know, Susan...\rdblquote  He took out a cigar, staring at it hard, and made as though to bite off the end. In doing so, his eyes met the woman\rquote s stern look of disapproval; and he put the cigar away and began over. \ldblquote Well, you know, Susan, the LNE model is in production now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So I\rquote ve heard. Is there something in connection with it you wish of me?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No-o. Still, the mere fact that it is in production and is doing well means that working with this messed-up specimen is useless. Shouldn\rquote t it be scrapped?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In short, Alfred, you are annoyed that I am wasting my so-valuable time. Feel relieved. My time is not being wasted. I am \i working \i0 with this robot.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But the work has no meaning.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll be the judge of that, Alfred.\rdblquote  Her voice was ominously quiet, and Lanning thought it wiser to shift his ground. \par
\tab\ldblquote Will you tell me what meaning it has? What are you doing with it right now, for instance?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m trying to get it to raise its hand on the word of command. I\rquote m trying to get it to imitate the sound of the word.\rdblquote  \par
\tab As though on cue, Lenny said, \ldblquote Eh-uh\rdblquote And raised its hand waveringly. \par
\tab Lanning shook his head. \ldblquote That voice is amazing. How does it happen?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin said, \ldblquote I don\rquote t quite know. Its transmitter is a normal one. It could speak normally, I\rquote m sure. It doesn\rquote t, however; it speaks like this as a consequence of something in the positronic paths that I have not yet pinpointed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, pinpoint it, for Heaven\rquote s sake. Speech like that might be useful.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, then there is some possible use in my studies on Lenny?\rdblquote  Lanning shrugged in embarrassment. \ldblquote Oh, well, it\rquote s a minor point.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry you don\rquote t see the major points, then,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin with asperity, \ldblquote which are much more important, but that\rquote s not my fault. Would you leave now, Alfred, and let me go on with my work?\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Lanning got to his cigar, eventually, in Bogert\rquote s office. He said, sourly, \ldblquote That woman is growing more peculiar daily.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bogert understood perfectly. In the U. S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation, there was only one \ldblquote that woman.\rdblquote  He said, \ldblquote Is she still scuffing about with that pseudo-robot--that Lenny of hers?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Trying to get it to talk, so help me.\rdblquote  Bogert shrugged. \ldblquote Points up the company problem. I mean, about getting qualified personnel for research. If we had other robopsychologists, we could retire Susan. Incidentally, I presume the directors\rquote  meeting scheduled for tomorrow is for the purpose of dealing with the procurement problem?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lanning nodded and looked at his cigar as though it didn\rquote t taste good. \ldblquote Yes. Quality, though, not quantity. We\rquote ve raised wages until there\rquote s a steady stream of applicants--those who are interested primarily in money. The trick is to get those who are interested primarily in robotics--a few more like Susan Calvin.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Hell, no. Not like her.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, not like her personally. But you\rquote ll have to admit, Peter, that she\rquote s single-minded about robots. She has no other interest in life.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I know. And that\rquote s exactly what makes her so unbearable.\rdblquote  Lanning nodded. He had lost count of the many times it would have done his soul good to have fired Susan Calvin. He had also lost count of the number of millions of dollars she had at one time or another saved the company. She was a truly indispensable woman and would remain one until she died--or until they could lick the problem of finding men and women of her own high caliber who were interested in robotics research. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I think we\rquote ll cut down on the tour business.\rdblquote  Peter shrugged. \ldblquote If you say so. But meanwhile, seriously, what do we do about Susan? She can easily tie herself up with Lenny indefinitely. You know how she is when she gets what she considers an interesting problem.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What \i can \i0 we do?\rdblquote  said Lanning. \ldblquote If we become too anxious to pull her off, she\rquote ll stay on out of feminine contrariness. In the last analysis, we can\rquote t force her to do anything.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The dark-haired mathematician smiled. \ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t ever apply the adjective \lquote feminine\rquote  to any part of her.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, well,\rdblquote  said Lanning, grumpily. \ldblquote At least, it won\rquote t do anyone any actual harm.\rdblquote  \par
\tab In that, if in nothing else, he was wrong. The emergency signal is always a tension-making thing in any large industrial establishment. Such signals had sounded in the history of U. S. Robots a dozen times--for fire, flood, riot and insurrection. \par
\tab But one thing had never occurred in all that time. Never had the particular signal indicating \ldblquote Robot out of control\rdblquote  sounded. No one ever expected it to sound. It was only installed at government insistence. (\ldblquote Damn the Frankenstein complex,\rdblquote  Lanning would mutter on those rare occasions when he thought of it.) \par
\tab Now, finally, the shrill siren rose and fell at ten-second intervals, and practically no worker from the President of the Board of Directors down to the newest janitor\rquote s assistant recognized the significance of the strange sound for a few moments. After those moments passed, there was a massive convergence of armed guards and medical men to the indicated area of danger and U. S. Robots was struck with paralysis. \par
\tab Charles Randow, computing technician, was taken off to hospital level with a broken arm. There was no other damage. No other physical damage. \par
\tab\ldblquote But the moral damage,\rdblquote  roared Lanning, \ldblquote is beyond estimation.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin faced him, murderously calm. \ldblquote You will do nothing to Lenny. Nothing. Do you understand?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Do \i you \i0 understand, Susan?\rdblquote  That thing has hurt a human being. It has broken First Law. Don\rquote t you know what First Law is?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You will do nothing to Lenny.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote For God\rquote s sake, Susan, do I have to tell \i you \i0 First Law? A \i robot may not harm a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm. \i0 Our entire position depends on the fact that First Law is rigidly observed by all robots of all types. If the public should hear, and they will hear, that there was an exception, even one exception, we might be forced to close down altogether. Our only chance of survival would be to announce at once that the robot involved had been destroyed, explain the circumstances, and hope that the public can be convinced that it will never happen again.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I would like to find out exactly what happened,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin. \ldblquote I was not present at the time and I would like to know exactly what the Randow boy was doing in my laboratories without my permission.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The important thing that happened,\rdblquote  said Lanning, \ldblquote is obvious. Your robot struck Randow and the damn fool flashed the \lquote Robot out of control\rquote  button and made a case of it. But your robot struck him and inflicted damage to the extent of a broken arm. The truth is your Lenny is so distorted it lacks First Law and it must be destroyed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It does \i not \i0 lack First Law. I have studied its brainpaths and know it does not lack it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then how could it strike a man?\rdblquote  Desperation turned him to sarcasm. \ldblquote Ask Lenny. Surely you have taught it to speak by now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin\rquote s cheeks Bushed a painful pink. She said, \ldblquote I prefer to interview the victim. And in my absence, Alfred, I want my offices sealed tight, with Lenny inside. I want no one to approach him. If any harm comes to him while I am gone, this company will not see me again under any circumstances.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Will you agree to its destruction, if it has broken First Law?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin, \ldblquote because I know it hasn\rquote t.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Charles Randow lay in bed with his arm set and in a cast. His major suffering was still from the shock of those few moments in which he thought a robot was advancing on him with murder in its positronic mind. No other human had ever had such reason to fear direct robotic harm as he had had just then. He had had a unique experience. \par
\tab Susan Calvin and Alfred Lanning stood beside his bed now; Peter Bogert, who had met them on the way, was with them. Doctors and nurses had been shooed out. \par
\tab Susan Calvin said, \ldblquote Now--what happened?\rdblquote  Randow was daunted. He muttered, \ldblquote The thing hit me in the arm. It was coming at me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Calvin said, \ldblquote Move further back in the story. What were you doing in my laboratory without authorization?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The young computer swallowed, and the Adam\rquote s apple in his thin neck bobbed noticeably. He was high-cheekboned and abnormally pale. He said, \ldblquote We all knew about your robot. The word is you were trying to teach it to talk like a musical instrument. There were bets going as to whether it talked or not. Some said--uh--you could teach a gatepost to talk.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I suppose,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin, freezingly, \ldblquote that is meant as a compliment. What did that have to do with you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I was supposed to go in there and settle matters--see if it would talk, you know. We swiped a key to your place and I waited till you were gone and went in. We had a lottery on who was to do it. I lost.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I tried to get it to talk and it hit me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What do you mean, you tried to get it to talk? How did you try?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I--I asked it questions, but it wouldn\rquote t say anything, and I had to give the thing a fair shake, so I kind of--yelled at it, and--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And?\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was a long pause. Under Susan Calvin\rquote s unwavering stare, Randow finally said, \ldblquote I tried to scare it into saying something.\rdblquote  He added defensively, \ldblquote I had to give the thing a fair shake.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How did you try to scare it?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I pretended to take a punch at it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And it brushed your arm aside?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It \i hit \i0 my arm.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Very well. That\rquote s all.\rdblquote  To Lanning and Bogert, she said, \ldblquote Come, gentlemen.\rdblquote  \par
\tab At the doorway, she turned back to Randow. \ldblquote I can settle the bets going around, if you are still interested. Lenny can speak a few words quite well.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab They said nothing until they were in Susan Calvin\rquote s office. Its walls were lined with her books, some of which she had written herself. It retained the patina of her own frigid, carefully ordered personality. It had only one chair in it and she sat down. Lanning and Bogert remained standing. \par
\tab She said, \ldblquote Lenny only defended itself. That is the Third Law: A \i robot must protect its own existence.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Except,\rdblquote  \i0 said Lanning forcefully, \i\ldblquote when this conflicts with the First \i0 or \i Second Laws. \i0 Complete the statement! Lenny had no right to defend itself in any way at the cost of harm, however minor, to a human being.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nor did it,\rdblquote  shot back Calvin, \i\ldblquote knowingly. \i0 Lenny has an aborted brain. It had no way of knowing its own strength or the weakness of humans. In brushing aside the threatening arm of a human being it could not know the bone would break. In human terms, no moral blame can be attached to an individual who honestly cannot differentiate good and evil.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bogert interrupted, soothingly, \ldblquote Now, Susan, \i we \i0 don\rquote t blame. \i We \i0 understand that Lenny is the equivalent of a baby, humanly speaking, and we don\rquote t blame it. But the public will. U. S. Robots will be closed down.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Quite the opposite. If you had the brains of a flea, Peter, you would see that this is the opportunity U. S. Robots is waiting for. That this will solve its problems.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lanning hunched his white eyebrows low. He said, softly, \ldblquote What problems, Susan?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Isn\rquote t the corporation concerned about maintaining our research personnel at the present--Heaven help us--high level?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We certainly are.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, what are you offering prospective researchers? Excitement? Novelty? The thrill of piercing the unknown? No! You offer them salaries and the assurance of no problems.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bogert said, \ldblquote How do you mean, no problems?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are there problems?\rdblquote  shot back Susan Calvin. \ldblquote What kind of robots do we turn out? Fully developed robots, fit for their tasks. An industry tells us what it needs; a computer designs the brain; machinery forms the robot; and there it is, complete and done. Peter, some time ago, you asked me with reference to Lenny what its use was. What\rquote s the use, you said, of a robot that was not designed for any job? Now I ask you--what\rquote s the use of a robot designed for only one job? It begins and ends in the same place. The LNE models mine boron. If beryllium is needed, they are useless. If boron technology enters a new phase, they become useless. A human being so designed would be sub-human. A robot so designed is sub-robotic.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you want a versatile robot?\rdblquote  asked Lanning, incredulously. \ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  demanded the robopsychologist. \ldblquote Why not? I\rquote ve been handed a robot with a brain almost completely stultified. I\rquote ve been teaching it, and you, Alfred, asked me what was the use of that. Perhaps very little as far as Lenny itself is concerned, since it will never progress beyond the five-year-old level on a human scale. But what\rquote s the use in general? A very great deal, if you consider it as a study in the abstract problem of \i learning how \i0 to \i teach robots. \i0 I have learned ways to short-circuit neighboring pathways in order to create new ones. More study will yield better, more subtle and more efficient techniques of doing so.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose you started with a positronic brain that had all the basic pathways carefully outlined but none of the secondaries. Suppose you then started creating secondaries. You could sell basic robots designed for instruction; robots that could be modeled to a job, and then modeled to another, if necessary. Robots would become as versatile as human beings. \i Robots could learn!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0 They stared at her. She said, impatiently, \ldblquote You still don\rquote t understand, do you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I understand what you are saying,\rdblquote  said Lanning. \par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t you understand that with a completely new field of research and completely new techniques to be developed, with a completely new area of the unknown to be penetrated, youngsters will feel a new urge to enter robotics? Try it and see.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote May I point out,\rdblquote  said Bogert, smoothly, \ldblquote that this is dangerous. Beginning with ignorant robots such as Lenny will mean that one could never trust First Law--exactly as turned out in Lenny\rquote s case.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly. Advertise the fact.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A\i dvertise it!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote Of course. Broadcast the danger. Explain that you will set up a new research institute on the moon, if Earth\rquote s population chooses not to allow this sort of thing to go on upon Earth, but stress the danger to the possible applicants by all means.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lanning said, \ldblquote For God\rquote s sake, why?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Because the spice of danger will add to the lure. Do you think nuclear technology involves no danger and spationautics no peril? Has your lure of absolute security been doing the trick for you? Has it helped you to cater to the Frankenstein complex you all despise so? Try something else then, something that has worked in other fields.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was a sound from beyond the door that led to Calvin\rquote s personal laboratories. It was the chiming sound of Lenny. \par
\tab The robopsychologist broke off instantly, listening. She said, \ldblquote Excuse me. I think Lenny is calling me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Can it call you?\rdblquote  said Lanning. \par
\tab\ldblquote I said I\rquote ve managed to teach it a few words.\rdblquote  She stepped toward the door, a little flustered. \ldblquote If you will wait for me--\rdblquote  \par
\tab They watched her leave and were silent for a moment. Then Lanning said, \ldblquote Do you think there\rquote s anything to what she says, Peter?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Just possibly, Alfred,\rdblquote  said Bogert. \ldblquote Just possibly. Enough for US to bring the matter up at the directors\rquote  meeting and see what they say. After all, the fat \i is \i0 in the fire. A robot has harmed a human being and knowledge of it is public. As Susan says, we might as well try to turn the matter to our advantage. Of course, I distrust her motives in all this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How do you mean?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Even if all she has said is perfectly true, it is only rationalization as far as she is concerned. Her motive in all this is her desire to hold on to this robot. If we pressed her\rdblquote  (and the mathematician smiled at the incongruous literal meaning of the phrase) \ldblquote she would say it was to continue learning techniques of teaching robots, but I think she has found another use for Lenny. A rather unique one that would fit only Susan of all women.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t get your drift.\rdblquote  Bogert said, \ldblquote Did you hear what the robot was calling?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, no, I didn\rquote t quite--\rdblquote  began Lanning, when the door opened suddenly, and both men stopped talking at once. \par
\tab Susan Calvin stepped in again, looking about uncertainly. \ldblquote Have either of you seen--I\rquote m positive I had it somewhere about--Oh, there it is.\rdblquote  \par
\tab She ran to a corner of one bookcase and picked up an object of intricate metal webbery, dumbbell shaped and hollow, with variously shaped metal pieces inside each hollow, just too large to be able to fallout of the webbing. \par
\tab As she picked it up, the metal pieces within moved and struck together, clicking pleasantly. It struck Lanning that the object was a kind of robotic version of a baby rattle. \par
\tab As Susan Calvin opened the door again to pass through, Lenny\rquote s voice chimed again from within. This time, Lanning heard it clearly as it spoke the words Susan Calvin had taught it. \par
\tab In heavenly celeste-like sounds, it called out, \ldblquote Mommie, I want you. I want you, Mommie.\rdblquote  \par
\tab And the footsteps of Susan Calvin could be heard hurrying eagerly across the laboratory floor toward the only kind of baby she could ever have or love. \par
