\tab\ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  said Defense, in annoyance. \i\ldblquote You \i0 can do that. The only witnesses capable of testifying to Easy\rquote s condition and to the nature of Easy\rquote s state of mind are employees of U. S. Robots. The judge can\rquote t possibly accept their testimony as unprejudiced.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How can he deny expert testimony?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote By refusing to be convinced by it. That\rquote s his right as the judge. Against the alternative that a man like Professor Ninheimer deliberately set about ruining his own reputation, even for a sizable sum of money, the judge isn\rquote t going to accept the technicalities of your engineers. The judge is a man, after all. If he has to choose between a man doing an impossible thing and a robot doing an impossible thing, he\rquote s quite likely to decide in favor of the man.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A man \i can \i0 do an impossible thing,\rdblquote  said Lanning, \ldblquote because we don\rquote t know all the complexities of the human mind and we don\rquote t know what, in a given human mind, is impossible and what is not. We do know what is really impossible to a robot.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, we\rquote ll see if we can\rquote t convince the judge of that,\rdblquote  Defense replied wearily. \par
\tab\ldblquote If all you say is so,\rdblquote  rumbled Robertson, \ldblquote I don\rquote t see how you can.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ll see. It\rquote s good to know and be aware of the difficulties involved, but let\rquote s not be \i too \i0 downhearted. I\rquote ve tried to look ahead a few moves in the chess game, too.\rdblquote  With a stately nod in the direction of the robopsychologist, he added, \i\ldblquote With \i0 the help of the good lady here.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Lanning looked from one to the other and said, \ldblquote What the devil is this?\rdblquote  \par
\tab But the bailiff thrust his head into the room and announced somewhat breathlessly that the trial was about to resume. \par
\tab They took their seats, examining the man who had started all the trouble. \par
\tab Simon Ninheimer owned a fluffy head of sandy hair, a face that narrowed past a beaked nose toward a pointed chin, and a habit of sometimes hesitating before key words in his conversation that gave him an air of a seeker after an almost unbearable precision. When he said, \ldblquote The Sun rises in the--uh--east, 11 one was certain he had given due consideration to the possibility that it might at some time rise in the west. \par
\tab Prosecution said, \ldblquote Did you oppose employment of Robot EZ-27 by the university?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I did, sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why was that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I did not feel that we understood the--uh--motives of U. S. Robots thoroughly. I mistrusted their anxiety to place the robot with us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Did you feel that it was capable of doing the work that it was allegedly designed to do?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I know for a fact that it was not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Would you state your reasons?\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Simon Ninheimer\rquote s book, entitled \i Social Tensions Involved in Space-Flight and Their Resolution, \i0 had been eight years in the making. Ninheimer\rquote s search for precision was not confined to his habits of speech, and in a subject like sociology, almost inherently imprecise, it left him breathless. \par
\tab Even with the material in galley proofs, he felt no sense of completion. Rather the reverse, in fact. Staring at the long strips of print, he felt only the itch to tear the lines of type apart and rearrange them differently. \par
\tab Jim Baker, Instructor and soon to be Assistant Professor of Sociology, found Ninheimer, three days after the first batch of galleys had arrived from the printer, staring at the handful of paper in abstraction. The galleys came in three copies: one for Ninheimer to proofread, one for Baker to proofread independently, and a third, marked \ldblquote Original,\rdblquote  which was to receive the final corrections, a combination of those made by Ninheimer and by Baker, after a conference at which possible conflicts and disagreements were ironed out. This had been their policy on the several papers on which they had collaborated in the past three years and it worked well. \par
\tab Baker, young and ingratiatingly soft-voiced, had his own copies of the galleys in his hand. He said eagerly, \ldblquote I\rquote ve done the first chapter and it contains some typographical beauts.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The first chapter always has them,\rdblquote  said Ninheimer distantly. \ldblquote Do you want to go over it now?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer brought his eyes to grave focus on Baker. \ldblquote I haven\rquote t done anything on the galleys, Jim. I don\rquote t think I\rquote ll bother.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Baker looked confused. \ldblquote Not bother?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer pursed his lips. \ldblquote I\rquote ve asked about the--uh--workload of the machine. After all, he was originally--uh--promoted as a proofreader. They\rquote ve set a schedule.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The \i machine? \i0 You mean Easy?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I believe that is the foolish name they gave it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But, Dr. Ninheimer, I thought you were staying clear of it\rdblquote\lquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I seem to be the only one doing so. Perhaps I ought to take my share of the--uh--advantage.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh. Well, I seem to have wasted time on this first chapter, then,\rdblquote  said the younger man ruefully. \par
\tab\ldblquote Not wasted. We can compare the machine\rquote s result with yours as a check.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If you want to, but--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I doubt that we\rquote ll find anything wrong with Easy\rquote s work. It\rquote s supposed never to have made a mistake.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I dare say,\rdblquote  said Ninheimer dryly. \par
\par
\tab The first chapter was brought in again by Baker four days later. This time it was Ninheimer\rquote s copy, fresh from the special annex that had been built to house Easy and the equipment it used. \par
\tab Baker was jubilant. \ldblquote Dr. Ninheimer, it not only caught everything I caught--it found a dozen errors I missed! The whole thing took it twelve minutes!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer looked over the sheaf, with the neatly printed marks and symbols in the margins. He said, \ldblquote It is not as complete as you and I would have made it. We would have entered an insert on Suzuki\rquote s work on the neurological effects of low gravity.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You mean his paper in \i Sociological Reviews?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote Well, you can\rquote t expect impossibilities of Easy. It can\rquote t read the literature for us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I realize that. As a matter of fact, I have prepared the insert. I will see the machine and make certain it knows how to--uh--handle inserts.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It will know.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I prefer to make certain.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer had to make an appointment to see Easy, and then could get nothing better than fifteen minutes in the late evening. \par
\tab But the fifteen minutes turned out to be ample. Robot EZ-27 understood the matter of inserts at once. \par
\tab Ninheimer found himself uncomfortable at close quarters with the robot for the first time. Almost automatically, as though it were human, he found himself asking, \ldblquote Are you happy with your work?\rquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Most happy, Professor Ninheimer,\rdblquote  said Easy solemnly, the photocells that were its eyes gleaming their normal deep red. \par
\tab\ldblquote You know me?\rdblquote\i\par
\tab\i0\ldblquote From the fact that you present me with additional material to include in the galleys, it follows that you are the author. The author\rquote s name, of course, is at the head of each sheet of galley proof.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I see. You make--uh--deductions, then. Tell me\rdblquote --he couldn\rquote t resist the question--\rdblquote what do you think of the book so far?\rquote  \par
\tab Easy said, \ldblquote I find it very pleasant to work with.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Pleasant? That is an odd word for a--uh--a mechanism without emotion. I\rquote ve been told you have no emotion.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The words of your book go in accordance with my circuits,\rdblquote  Easy explained. \ldblquote They set up little or no counterpotentials. It is in my brain paths to translate this mechanical fact into a word such as \lquote pleasant.\rquote  The emotional context is fortuitous.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I see. Why do you find the book pleasant?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It deals with human beings, Professor, and not with inorganic materials or mathematical symbols. Your book attempts to understand human beings and to help increase human happiness.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And this is what you try to do and so my book goes in accordance with your circuits? Is that it?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is it, Professor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The fifteen minutes were up. Ninheimer left and went to the university library, which was on the point of closing. He kept them open long enough to find an elementary text on robotics. He took it home with him. \par
\tab Except for occasional insertion of late material, the galleys went to Easy and from him to the publishers with little intervention from Ninheimer at first--and none at all later. \par
\tab Baker said, a little uneasily, \ldblquote It almost gives me a feeling of uselessness.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It should give you a feeling of having time to begin a new project,\rdblquote  said Ninheimer, without looking up from the notations he was making in the current issue of \i Social Science Abstracts. \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote I\rquote m just not used to it. I keep worrying about the galleys. It\rquote s silly, I know.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It is.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The other day I got a couple of sheets before Easy sent them off to--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What!\rdblquote  Ninheimer looked up, scowling. The copy of \i Abstracts \i0 slid shut. \ldblquote Did you disturb the machine at its work?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Only for a minute. Everything was all right. Oh, it changed one word. You referred to something as \lquote criminal\rquote ; it changed the word to \lquote reckless.\rquote  It thought the second adjective fit in better with the context.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer grew thoughtful. \ldblquote What did you think?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You know, I agreed with it. I let it stand.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer turned in his swivel-chair to face his young associate. \ldblquote See here, I wish you wouldn\rquote t do this again. If I am to use the machine, I wish the--uh--full advantage of it. If I am to use it and lose your--uh--services anyway because you supervise it when the whole point is that it requires no supervision, I gain nothing. Do you \i see?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote Yes, Dr. Ninheimer,\rdblquote  said Baker, subdued. The advance copies of \i Social Tensions \i0 arrived in Dr. Ninheimer\rquote s office on the eighth of May. He looked through it briefly, flipping pages and pausing to read a paragraph here and there. Then he put his copies away. \par
\tab As he explained later, he forgot about it. For eight years, he had worked at it, but now, and for months in the past, other interests had engaged him while Easy had taken the load of the book off his shoulders. He did not even think to donate the usual complimentary copy to the university library. Even Baker, who had thrown himself into work and had steered clear of the department head since receiving his rebuke at their last meeting, received no copy. \par
\tab On the sixteenth of June that stage ended. Ninheimer received a phone call and stared at the image in the \lquote plate with surprise. \par
\tab\ldblquote Speidell! Are you in town?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir. I\rquote m in Cleveland.\rdblquote  Speidell\rquote s voice trembled with emotion. \par
\tab\ldblquote Then why the call?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Because I\rquote ve just been looking through your new book! Ninheimer, are you \i mad? \i0 Have you gone \i insane?\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab\i0 Ninheimer stiffened. \ldblquote Is something--uh--wrong?\rdblquote  he asked in alarm. \par
\tab\ldblquote Wrong? I refer you to page 562. What in blazes do you mean by interpreting my work as you do? Where in the paper cited do I make the claim that the criminal personality is nonexistent and that it is the law-enforcement agencies that are the \i true \i0 criminals? Here, let me quote--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Wait! Wait!\rdblquote  cried Ninheimer, trying to find the page. \ldblquote Let me see. Let me see...Good God!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Speidell, I don\rquote t see how this could have happened. I never wrote this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But that\rquote s what\rquote s printed! And that distortion isn\rquote t the worst. You look at page 690 and imagine what Ipatiev is going to do to you when he sees the hash you\rquote ve made of his findings! Look, Ninheimer, the book is \i riddled \i0 with this sort of thing. I don\rquote t know what you were thinking of--but there\rquote s nothing to do but get the book off the market. And you\rquote d better be prepared for extensive apologies at the next Association meeting!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Speidell, listen to me--\rdblquote  But Speidell had flashed off with a force that had the \lquote plate glowing with after-images for fifteen seconds. \par
\tab It was then that Ninheimer went through the book and began marking off passages with red ink. \par
\tab He kept his temper remarkably well when he faced Easy again, but his lips were pale. He passed the book to Easy and said, \ldblquote Will you read the marked passages on pages 562, 631, 664 and 690?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Easy did so in four glances. \ldblquote Yes, Professor Ninheimer.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This is not as I had it in the original galleys.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir. It is not.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Did you change it to read as it now does?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Sir, the passages as they read in your version were most uncomplimentary to certain groups of human beings. I felt it advisable to change the wording to avoid doing them harm.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How \i dared \i0 you do such a thing?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The First Law, Professor, does not let me, through any inaction, allow harm to come to human beings. Certainly, considering your reputation in the world of sociology and the wide circulation your book would receive among scholars, considerable harm would come to a number of the human beings you speak of.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But do you realize the harm that will come to me now?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It was necessary to choose the alternative with less harm.\rdblquote  Professor Ninheimer, shaking with fury, staggered away. It was clear to him that U. S. Robots would have to account to him for this. \par
\par
\tab There was some excitement at the defendants\rquote  table, which increased as Prosecution drove the point home. \par
\tab\ldblquote Then Robot EZ-27 informed you that the reason for its action was based on the First Law of Robotics?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is correct, sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That, in effect, it had no choice?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It follows then that U. S. Robots designed a robot that would of necessity rewrite books to accord with its own conceptions of what was right. And yet they palmed it off as simple proofreader. Would you say that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Defense objected firmly at once, pointing out that the witness was being asked for a decision on a matter in which he had no competence. The judged admonished Prosecution in the usual terms, but there was no doubt that the exchange had sunk home--not least upon the attorney for the Defense. \par
\tab Defense asked for a short recess before beginning cross-examination, using a legal technicality for the purpose that got him five minutes. \par
\tab He leaned over toward Susan Calvin. \ldblquote Is it possible, Dr. Calvin, that Professor Ninheimer is telling the truth and that Easy was motivated by the First Law?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Calvin pressed her lips together, then said, \ldblquote No. It \i isn\rquote t \i0 possible. The last part of Ninheimer\rquote s testimony is deliberate perjury. Easy is not designed to be able to judge matters at the stage of abstraction represented by an advanced textbook on sociology. It would never be able to tell that certain groups of humans would be harmed by a phrase in such a book. Its mind is simply not built for that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I suppose, though, that we can\rquote t prove this to a layman,\rdblquote  said Defense pessimistically. \par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  Admitted Calvin. \ldblquote The proof would be highly complex. Our way out is still what it was. We must prove Ninheimer is lying, and nothing he has said need change our plan of attack.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Very well, Dr. Calvin,\rdblquote  said Defense, \ldblquote I must accept your word in this. We\rquote ll go on as planned.\rdblquote  \par
\tab In the courtroom, the judge\rquote s gavel rose and fell and Dr. Ninheimer took the stand once more. He smiled a little as one who feels his position to be impregnable and rather enjoys the prospect of countering a useless attack. \par
\tab Defense approached warily and began softly. \ldblquote Dr. Ninheimer, do you mean to say that you were completely unaware of these alleged changes in your manuscript until such time as Dr. Speidell called you on the sixteenth of June?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is correct, sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Did you never look at the galleys after Robot EZ-27 had proofread them?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote At first I did, but it seemed to me a useless task. I relied on the claims of U. S. Robots. The absurd--uh--changes were made only in the last quarter of the book after the robot, I presume, had learned enough about sociology--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind your presumptions!\rdblquote  said Defense. \ldblquote I understood your colleague, Dr. Baker, saw the later galleys on at least one occasion. Do you remember testifying to that effect?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir. As I said, he told me about seeing one page, and even there, the robot had changed a word.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Again Defense broke in. \ldblquote Don\rquote t you find it strange, sir, that after over a year of implacable hostility to the robot, after having voted against it in the first place and having refused to put it to any use whatever, you suddenly decided to put your book, your \i magnum opus, \i0 into its hands?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t find that strange. I simply decided that I might as well use the machine.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And you were so confident of Robot EZ-27--all of a sudden--that you didn\rquote t even bother to check your galleys?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I told you I was--uh--persuaded by U. S. Robots\rquote  propaganda.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So persuaded that when your colleague, Dr. Baker, attempted to check on the robot, you berated him soundly?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I didn\rquote t berate him. I merely did not wish to have him--uh--waste his time. At least, I thought then it was a waste of time. I did not see the significance of that change in a word at the--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Defense said with heavy sarcasm, \ldblquote I have no doubt you were instructed to bring up that point in order that the word-change be entered in the record--\rdblquote  He altered his line to forestall objection and said, \ldblquote The point is that you were extremely angry with Dr. Baker.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir. Not angry.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You didn\rquote t give him a copy of your book when you received it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Simple forgetfulness. I didn\rquote t give the library its copy, either.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer smiled cautiously. \ldblquote Professors are notoriously absentminded.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Defense said, \ldblquote Do you find it strange that, after more than a year of perfect work, Robot EZ-27 should go wrong on your book? On a book, that is, which was written by you, who was, of all people, the most implacably hostile to the robot?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote My book was the only sizable work dealing with mankind that it had to face. The Three Laws of Robotics took hold then.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Several times, Dr. Ninheimer,\rdblquote  said Defense, \ldblquote you have tried to sound like an expert on robotics. Apparently you suddenly grew interested in robotics and took out books on the subject from the library. You testified to that effect, did you not?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote One book, sir. That was the result of what seems to me to have been--uh--natural curiosity.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And it enabled you to explain why the robot should, as you allege, have distorted your book?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Very convenient. But are you sure your interest in robotics was not intended to enable you to manipulate the robot for your own purposes?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer flushed. \ldblquote Certainly not, sir!\rdblquote  Defense\rquote s voice rose. \ldblquote In fact, are you sure the alleged altered passages were not as you had them in the first place?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The sociologist half-rose. \ldblquote That\rquote s--uh--uh--ridiculous! I have the galleys--\rdblquote  \par
\tab He had difficulty speaking and Prosecution rose to insert smoothly, \ldblquote With your permission, Your Honor, I intend to introduce as evidence the set of galleys given by Dr. Ninheimer to Robot EZ-27 and the set of galleys mailed by Robot EZ-27 to the publishers. I will do so now if my esteemed colleague so desires, and will be willing to allow a recess in order that the two sets of galleys may be compared.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Defense waved his hand impatiently. \ldblquote That is not necessary. My honored opponent can introduce those galleys whenever he chooses. I\rquote m sure they will show whatever discrepancies are claimed by the plaintiff to exist. What I would like to know of the witness, however, is whether he also has in his possession \i Dr. Baker\rquote s \i0 galleys.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Dr. Baker\rquote s galleys?\rdblquote  Ninheimer frowned. He was not yet quite master of himself. \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Professor! I mean Dr. Baker\rquote s galleys. You testified to the effect that Dr. Baker had received a separate copy of the galleys. I will have the clerk read your testimony if you are suddenly a selective type of amnesiac. Or is it just that professors are, as you say, notoriously absent-minded?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer said, \ldblquote I remember Dr. Baker\rquote s galleys. They weren\rquote t necessary once the job was placed in the care of the proofreading machine--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So you burned them?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No. I put them in the waste basket.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Burned them, dumped them--what\rquote s the difference? The point is you got rid of them.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote There\rquote s nothing wrong--\rdblquote  began Ninheimer weakly. \par
\tab\ldblquote Nothing wrong?\rdblquote  thundered Defense. \ldblquote Nothing wrong except that there is now no way we can check to see if, on certain crucial galley sheets, you might not have substituted a harmless blank one from Dr. Baker\rquote s copy for a sheet in your own copy which you had deliberately mangled in such a way as to force the robot to--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Prosecution shouted a furious objection. Justice Shane leaned forward, his round face doing its best to assume an expression of anger equivalent to the intensity of the emotion felt by the man. \par
\tab The judge said, \ldblquote Do you have any evidence, Counselor, for the extraordinary statement you have just made?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Defense said quietly, \ldblquote No direct evidence, Your Honor. But I would like to point out that, viewed properly, the sudden conversion of the plaintiff from anti-roboticism, his sudden interest in robotics, his refusal to check the galleys or to allow anyone else to check them, his careful neglect to allow anyone to see the book immediately after publication, all very clearly point--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Counselor,\rdblquote  interrupted the judge impatiently, \ldblquote this is not the place for esoteric deductions. The plaintiff is not on trial. Neither are you prosecuting him. I forbid this line of attack and I can only point out that the desperation that must have induced you to do this cannot help but weaken your case. If you have legitimate questions to ask, Counselor, you may continue with your cross-examination. But I warn you against another such exhibition in this courtroom.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I have no further questions, Your Honor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Robertson whispered heatedly as counsel for the Defense returned to his table, \ldblquote What good did that do, for God\rquote s sake? The judge is dead-set against you now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Defense replied calmly, \ldblquote But Ninheimer is good and rattled. And we\rquote ve set him up for tomorrow\rquote s move. He\rquote ll be ripe.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin nodded gravely. \par
\par
\tab The rest of Prosecution\rquote s case was mild in comparison. Dr. Baker was called and bore out most of Ninheimer\rquote s testimony. Drs. Speidell and Ipatiev were called, and they expounded most movingly on their shock and dismay at certain quoted passages in Dr. Ninheimer\rquote s book. Both gave their professional opinion that Dr. Ninheimer\rquote s professional reputation had been seriously impaired. \par
\tab The galleys were introduced in evidence, as were copies of the finished book. \par
\tab Defense cross-examined no more that day. Prosecution rested and the trial was recessed till the next morning. \par
\tab Defense made his first motion at the beginning of the proceedings on the second day. He requested that Robot EZ-27 be admitted as a spectator to the proceedings. \par
\tab Prosecution objected at once and Justice Shane called both to the bench. \par
\tab Prosecution said hotly, \ldblquote This is obviously illegal. A robot may not be in any edifice used by the general public.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote This courtroom,\rdblquote  pointed out Defense, \ldblquote is closed to all but those having an immediate connection with the case.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A large machine of \i known \i0 erratic behavior would disturb my clients and my witnesses by its very presence! It would make hash out of the proceedings.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The judge seemed inclined to agree. He turned to Defense and said rather unsympathetically, \ldblquote What are the reasons for your request?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Defense said, \ldblquote It will be our contention that Robot EZ-27 could not possibly, by the nature of its construction, have behaved as it has been described as behaving. It will be necessary to present a few demonstrations.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Prosecution said, \ldblquote I don\rquote t see the point, Your Honor. Demonstrations conducted by men employed at U. S. Robots are worth little as evidence when U. S. Robots is the defendant.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Your Honor,\rdblquote  said Defense, \ldblquote the validity of any evidence is for you to decide, not for the Prosecuting Attorney. At least, that is my understanding.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Justice Shane, his prerogatives encroached upon, said, \ldblquote Your understanding is correct. Nevertheless, the presence of a robot here does raise important legal questions.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Surely, Your Honor, nothing that should be allowed to override the requirements of justice. If the robot is not present, we are prevented from presenting our only defense.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The judge considered. \ldblquote There would be the question of transporting the robot here.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is a problem with which U. S. Robots has frequently been faced. We have a truck parked outside the courtroom, constructed according to the laws governing the transportation of robots. Robot EZ-27 is in a packing case inside with two men guarding it. The doors to the truck are properly secured and all other necessary precautions have been taken.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You seem certain,\rdblquote  said Justice Shane, in renewed ill-temper, \ldblquote that judgment on this point will be in your favor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all, Your Honor. If it is not, we simply turn the truck about. I have made no presumptions concerning your decision.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The judge nodded. \ldblquote The request on the part of the Defense is granted.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The crate was carried in on a large dolly and the two men who handled it opened it. The courtroom was immersed in a dead silence. \par
\par
\tab Susan Calvin waited as the thick slabs of celluform went down, then held out one hand. \ldblquote Come, Easy.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The robot looked in her direction and held out its large metal arm. It towered over her by two feet but followed meekly, like a child in the clasp of its mother. Someone giggled nervously and choked it off at a hard glare from Dr. Calvin. \par
\tab Easy seated itself carefully in a large chair brought by the bailiff, which creaked but held. \par
\tab Defense said, \ldblquote When it becomes necessary, Your Honor, we will prove that this is actually Robot EZ-27, the specific robot in the employ of Northeastern University during the period of time with which we are concerned.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  His Honor said. \ldblquote That will be necessary. I, for one, have no idea how you can tell one robot from another.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And now,\rdblquote  said Defense, \ldblquote I would like to call my first witness to the stand. Professor Simon Ninheimer, please.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The clerk hesitated, looked at the judge. Justice Shane asked, with visible surprise, \ldblquote You are calling the \i plaintiff \i0 as your witness?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Your Honor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I hope that you\rquote re aware that as long as he\rquote s your witness, you will be allowed none of the latitude you might exercise if you were cross-examining an opposing witness.\rdblquote\par
\tab Defense said smoothly, \ldblquote My only purpose in all this is to arrive at the truth. It will not be necessary to do more than ask a few polite questions.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said the judge dubiously, \ldblquote you\rquote re the one handling the case. Call the witness.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer took the stand and was informed that he was still under oath. He looked more nervous than he had the day before, almost apprehensive. \par
\tab But Defense looked at him benignly. \par
\tab\ldblquote Now, Professor Ninheimer, you are suing my clients in the amount of $750,000.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is the--uh--sum. Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That is a great deal of money.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I have suffered a great deal of harm.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Surely not that much. The material in question involves only a few passages in a book. Perhaps these were unfortunate passages, but after all, books sometimes appear with curious mistakes in them.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer\rquote s nostrils flared. \ldblquote Sir, this book was to have been the climax of my professional career! Instead, it makes me look like an incompetent scholar, a perverter of the views held by my honored friends and associates, and a believer of ridiculous and--uh--outmoded viewpoints. My reputation is irretrievably shattered! I can never hold up my head in any--uh--assemblage of scholars, regardless of the outcome of this trial. I certainly cannot continue in my career, which has been the whole of my life. The very purpose of my life has been--uh--aborted and destroyed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Defense made no attempt to interrupt the speech, but stared abstractedly at his fingernails as it went on. \par
\tab He said very soothingly, \ldblquote But surely, Professor Ninheimer, at your present age, you could not hope to earn more than--let us be generous--$l5O,OOO during the remainder of your life. Yet you are asking the court to award you five times as much.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Ninheimer said, with an even greater burst of emotion, \ldblquote It is not in my lifetime alone that I am ruined. I do not know for how many generations I shall be pointed at by sociologists as a--uh--a fool or maniac. My real achievements will be buried and ignored. I am ruined not only until the day of my death, but for all time to come, because there will always be people who will not believe that a robot made those insertions--\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was at this point that Robot EZ-27 rose to his feet. Susan Calvin made no move to stop him. She sat motionless, staring straight ahead. Defense sighed softly. \par
\tab Easy\rquote s melodious voice carried clearly. It said, \ldblquote I would like to explain to everyone that I did insert certain passages in the galley proofs that seemed directly opposed to what had been there at first--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Even the Prosecuting Attorney was too startled at the spectacle of a seven-foot robot rising to address the court to be able to demand the stopping of what was obviously a most irregular procedure. \par
\tab When he could collect his wits, it was too late. For Ninheimer rose in the witness chair, his face working. \par
\tab He shouted wildly, \ldblquote Damn you, you were instructed to keep your mouth shut about--\rdblquote  \par
\tab He ground to a choking halt, and Easy was silent, too. Prosecution was on his feet now, demanding that a mistrial be declared. \par
\tab Justice Shane banged his gavel desperately. \ldblquote Silence! Silence! Certainly there is every reason here to declare a mistrial, except that in the interests of justice I would like to have Professor Ninheimer complete his statement. I distinctly heard him say to the robot that the robot had been instructed to keep its mouth shut about something. There was no mention in your testimony, Professor Ninheimer, as to any instructions to the robot to keep silent about anything!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer stared wordlessly at the judge. Justice Shane said, \ldblquote Did you instruct Robot EZ-27 to keep silent about something? And if so, about what?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Your Honor--\rdblquote  began Ninheimer hoarsely, and couldn\rquote t continue. \par
\tab The judge\rquote s voice grew sharp. \ldblquote Did you, in fact, order the inserts in question to be made in the galleys and then order the robot to keep quiet about your part in this?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Prosecution objected vigorously, but Ninheimer shouted, \ldblquote Oh, what\rquote s the use? Yes! Yes!\rdblquote And he ran from the witness stand. He was stopped at the door by the bailiff and sank hopelessly into one of the last rows of seats, head buried in both hands. \par
\tab Justice Shane said, \ldblquote It is evident to me that Robot EZ-27 was brought here as a trick. Except for the fact that the trick served to prevent a serious miscarriage of justice, I would certainly hold attorney for the Defense in contempt. It is clear now, beyond any doubt, that the plaintiff has committed what is to me a completely inexplicable fraud since, apparently, he was knowingly ruining his career in the process--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Judgment, of course, was for the defendant. \par
\par
\tab Dr. Susan Calvin had herself announced at Dr. Ninheimer\rquote s bachelor quarters in University Hall. The young engineer who had driven the car offered to go up with her, but she looked at him scornfully. \par
\tab\ldblquote Do you think he\rquote ll assault me? Wait down here.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer was in no mood to assault anyone. He was packing, wasting no time, anxious to be away before the adverse conclusion of the trial became general knowledge. \par
\tab He looked at Calvin with a queerly defiant air and said, \ldblquote Are you coming to warn me of a countersuit? If so, it will get you nothing. I have no money, no job, no future. I can\rquote t even meet the costs of the trial.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If you\rquote re looking for sympathy,\rdblquote  said Calvin coldly, \ldblquote don\rquote t look for it here. This was your doing. However, there will be no countersuit, neither of you nor of the university. We will even do what we can to keep you from going to prison for perjury. We aren\rquote t vindictive.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, is that why I\rquote m not already in custody for forswearing myself? I had wondered. But then,\rdblquote  he added bitterly, \ldblquote why \i should \i0 you be vindictive? You have what you want now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Some of what we want, yes,\rdblquote  said Calvin. \ldblquote The university will keep Easy in its employ at a considerably higher rental fee. Furthermore, certain underground publicity concerning the trial will make it possible to place a few more of the EZ models in other institutions without danger of a repetition of this trouble.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then why have you come to see me?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Because I don\rquote t have all of what I want yet. I want to know why you hate robots as you do. Even if you had won the case, your reputation would have been ruined. The money you might have obtained could not have compensated for that. Would the satisfaction of your hatred for robots have done so?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Are you interested in \i human \i0 minds, Dr. Calvin?\rdblquote  asked Ninheimer, with acid mockery. \par
\tab\ldblquote Insofar as their reactions concern the welfare of robots, yes. For that reason, I have learned a little of human psychology.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Enough of it to be able to trick met\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That wasn\rquote t hard,\rdblquote  said Calvin, without pomposity. \ldblquote The difficult thing was doing it in such a way as not to damage Easy.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It is like you to be more concerned for a machine than for a man.\rdblquote  He looked at her with savage contempt. \par
\tab It left her unmoved. \ldblquote It merely seems so, Professor Ninheimer. It is only by being concerned for robots that one can truly be concerned for twenty-first-century man. You would understand this if you were a roboticist.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I have read enough robotics to know I don\rquote t \i want \i0 to be a roboticist!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Pardon me, you have read \i a book \i0 on robotics. It has taught you nothing. You learned enough to know that you could order a robot to do many things, even to falsify a book, if you went about it properly. You learned enough to know that you could not order him to forget something entirely without risking detection, but you thought you could order him into simple silence more safely. You were wrong.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You guessed the truth from his silencer\rquote  \ldblquote It wasn\rquote t guessing. You were an amateur and didn\rquote t know enough to cover your tracks completely. My only problem was to prove the matter to the judge and you were kind enough to help us there, in your ignorance of the robotics you claim to despise.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab\ldblquote Is there any purpose in this discussion?\rdblquote  asked Ninheimer wearily. \par
\tab\ldblquote For me, yes,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin, \ldblquote because I want you to understand how completely you have misjudged robots. You silenced Easy by telling him that if he told anyone about your own distortion of the book, you would lose your job. That set up a certain potential within Easy toward silence, one that was strong enough to resist our efforts to break it down. We would have damaged the brain if we had persisted. \par
\tab\ldblquote On the witness stand, however, you yourself put up a higher counterpotential. You said that because people would think that you, not a robot, had written the disputed passages in the book, you would lose far more than just your job. You would lose your reputation, your standing, your respect, your reason for living. You would lose the memory of you after death. A new and higher potential was set up by you--and Easy talked.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, God,\rdblquote  said Ninheimer, turning his head away. Calvin was inexorable. She said, \ldblquote Do you understand \i why \i0 he talked? It was not to accuse you, but to \i defend \i0 you! It can be mathematically shown that he was about to assume full blame for your crime, to deny that you had anything to do with it. The First Law required that. He was going to lie--to damage himself--to bring monetary harm to a corporation. All that meant less to him than did the saving of you. If you really understood robots and robotics, you would have let him talk. But you did not understand, as I was sure you wouldn\rquote t, as I guaranteed to the defense attorney that you wouldn\rquote t. You were certain, in your hatred of robots, that Easy would act as a human being would act and defend itself at your expense. So you flared out at him in panic--and destroyed yourself.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer said with feeling, \ldblquote I hope some day your robots turn on you and kill you!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t be foolish,\rdblquote  said Calvin. \ldblquote Now I want you to explain why you\rquote ve done all this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ninheimer grinned a distorted, humorless grin. \ldblquote I am to dissect my mind, am I, for your intellectual curiosity, in return for immunity from a charge of perjury?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Put it that way if you like,\rdblquote  said Calvin emotionlessly. \ldblquote But explain.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So that you can counter future anti-robot attempts more efficiently? With greater understanding?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I accept that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You know,\rdblquote  said Ninheimer, \ldblquote I\rquote ll tell you--just to watch it do you no good at all. You can\rquote t understand human motivation. You can only understand your damned machines because you\rquote re a machine yourself, with skin on.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab He was breathing hard and there was no hesitation in his speech, no searching for precision. It was as though he had no further use for precision. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote For two hundred and fifty years, the machine has been replacing Man and destroying the handcraftsman. Pottery is spewed out of molds and presses. Works of art have been replaced by identical gimcracks stamped out on a die. Call it progress, if you wish! The artist is restricted to abstractions, confined to the world of ideas. He must design something in mind--and then the machine does the rest. \par
\tab\ldblquote Do you suppose the potter is content with mental creation? Do you suppose the idea is enough? That there is nothing in the feel of the clay itself, in watching the thing grow as hand and mind work \i together? \i0 Do you suppose the actual growth doesn\rquote t act as a feedback to modify and improve the idea?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You are not a potter,\rdblquote  said Dr. Calvin. \ldblquote I am a creative artist! I design and build articles and books. There is more to it than the mere thinking of words and of putting them in the right order. If that were all, there would be no pleasure in it, no return. \par
\tab\ldblquote A book should take shape in the hands of the writer. One must actually see the chapters grow and develop. One must work and rework and watch the changes take place beyond the original concept even. There is taking the galleys in hand and seeing how the sentences look in print and molding them again. There are a hundred contacts between a man and his work at every stage of the game and the contact itself is pleasurable and repays a man for the work he puts into his creation more than anything else could. \i Your robot would take all that away.\i0\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So does a typewriter. So does a printing press. Do you propose to return to the hand illumination of manuscripts?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Typewriters and printing presses take away some, but your robot would deprive us of all. Your robot takes over the galleys. Soon it, or other robots, would take over the original writing, the searching of the sources, the checking and cross-checking of passages, perhaps even the deduction of conclusions. What would that leave the scholar? One thing only--the barren decisions concerning what orders to give the robot next! I want to save the future generations of the world of scholarship from such a final hell. That meant more to me than even my own reputation and so I set out to destroy U. S. Robots by whatever means.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You were bound to fail,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin. \ldblquote I was bound to try,\rdblquote  said Simon Ninheimer. Calvin turned and left. She did her best to feel no pang of sympathy for the broken man. \par
\tab She did not entirely succeed. \par
