Measures on Hyper Base had been taken in a sort of rattling fury -- the muscular equivalent of a hysterical shriek.\par
\tab To itemize them in order of both chronology and desperation, they were:\par
\par
\pard\fi-720\li1080\tx1080 1.\tab All work on the Hyperatomic Drive through all the space volume occupied by the Stations of the Twenty-Seventh Asteroidal Grouping came to a halt.\par
\pard\f3\par
\pard\fi-720\li1080\tx1080\f0 2.\tab That entire volume of space was nipped out of the System, practically speaking. No one entered without permission. No one left under any conditions.\par
\pard\f3\par
\pard\fi-720\li1080\tx1080\f0 3.\tab By special government patrol ship, Drs. Susan Calvin and Peter Bogert, respectively Head Psychologist and Mathematical Director of United States Robot & Mechanical Men Corporation, were brought to Hyper Base.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Susan Calvin had never left the surface of Earth before, and had no perceptible desire to leave it this time. In an age of Atomic Power and a clearly coming Hyperatomic Drive, she remained quietly provincial. So she was dissatisfied with her trip and unconvinced of the emergency, and every line of her plain, middle-aged face showed it clearly enough during her first dinner at Hyper Base.\par
\tab Nor did Dr. Bogert\rquote s sleek paleness abandon a certain hangdog attitude. Nor did Major-general Kallner, who headed the project, even once forget to maintain a hunted expression. In short, it was a grisly episode, that meal, and the little session of three that followed began in a gray, unhappy manner.\par
\tab Kallner, with his baldness glistening, and his dress uniform oddly unsuited to the general mood, began with uneasy directness.\par
\tab\ldblquote This is a queer story to tell, sir, and madam. I want to thank you for coming on short notice and without a reason being given. We\rquote ll try to correct that now. We\rquote ve lost a robot. Work has stopped and \i must\i0  stop until such time as we locate it. So far we have failed, and we feel we need expert help.\rdblquote\par
\tab Perhaps the general felt his predicament anticlimactic. He continued with a note of desperation, \ldblquote I needn\rquote t tell you the importance of our work here. More than eighty percent of last year\rquote s appropriations for scientific research have gone to us-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why, we know that,\rdblquote  said Bogert, agreeably. \ldblquote U. S. Robots is receiving a generous rental fee for use of our robots.\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin injected a blunt, vinegary note, \ldblquote What makes a single robot so important to the project, and why hasn\rquote t it been located?\rdblquote\par
\tab The general turned his red face toward her and wet his lips quickly, \ldblquote Why, in a manner of speaking we \i have\i0  located it.\rdblquote  Then, with near anguish, \ldblquote Here, suppose I explain. As soon as the robot failed to report a state of emergency was declared, and all movement off Hyper Base stopped. A cargo vessel had landed the previous day and had delivered us two robots for our laboratories. It had sixty-two robots of the... uh... game type for shipment elsewhere. We are certain as to that figure. There is no question about it whatever.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes? And the connection?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote When our missing robot failed of location anywhere -- I assure you we would have found a missing blade of grass if it had been there to find -- we brainstormed ourselves into counting the robots left of the cargo ship. They have sixty-three now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So that the sixty-third, I take it, is the missing prodigal?\rdblquote  Dr. Calvin\rquote s eyes darkened.\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, but we have no way of telling which is the sixty-third.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a dead silence while the electric clock chimed eleven times, and then the robopsychologist said, \ldblquote Very peculiar,\rdblquote  and the corners of her lips moved downward.\par
\tab\ldblquote Peter,\rdblquote  she turned to her colleague with a trace of savagery, \ldblquote what\rquote s wrong here? What kind of robots are they, using at Hyper Base?\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Bogert hesitated and smiled feebly, \ldblquote It\rquote s been rather a matter of delicacy till now, Susan.\rdblquote\par
\tab She spoke rapidly, \ldblquote Yes, \i till\i0  now. If there are sixty-three same-type robots, one of which is wanted and the identity of which cannot be determined, why won\rquote t any of them do? What\rquote s the idea of all this? Why have we been sent for?\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert said in resigned fashion, \ldblquote If you\rquote ll give me a chance, Susan -- Hyper Base happens to be using several robots whose brains are not impressioned with the entire First Law of Robotics.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote\i Aren\rquote t\i0  impressioned?\rdblquote  Calvin slumped back in her chair, \ldblquote I see. How many were made?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A few. It was on government order and there was no way of violating the secrecy. No one was to know except the top men directly concerned. You weren\rquote t included, Susan. It was nothing I had anything to do with.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab The general interrupted with a measure of authority. \ldblquote I would like to explain that bit. I hadn\rquote t been aware that Dr. Calvin was unacquainted with the situation. I needn\rquote t tell you, Dr. Calvin, that there always has been strong opposition to robots on the Planet. The only defense the government has had against the Fundamentalist radicals in this matter was the fact that robots are always built with an unbreakable First Law -- which makes it impossible for them to harm human beings under any circumstance.\par
\tab\ldblquote But we \i had\i0  to have robots of a different nature. So just a few of the NS-2 model, the Nestors, that is, were prepared with a modified First Law. To keep it quiet, all NS-2\rquote s are manufactured without serial numbers; modified members are delivered here along with a group of normal robots; and, of course, all our kind are under the strictest impressionment never to tell of their modification to unauthorized personnel.\rdblquote  He wore an embarrassed smile; \ldblquote This has all worked out against us now.\rdblquote\par
\tab Calvin said grimly, \ldblquote Have you asked each one who it is, anyhow? Certainly, you are authorized?\rdblquote\par
\tab The general nodded, \ldblquote All sixty-three deny having worked here -- and one is lying.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Does the one you want show traces of wear? The others, I take it, are factory-fresh.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The one in question only arrived last month. It, and the two that have just arrived, were to be the last we needed. There\rquote s no perceptible wear.\rdblquote  He shook his head slowly and his eyes were haunted again, \ldblquote Dr. Calvin, we don\rquote t dare let that ship leave. If the existence of non-First Law robots becomes general knowledge-\rdblquote  There seemed no way of avoiding understatement in the conclusion.\par
\tab\ldblquote Destroy all sixty-three,\rdblquote  said the robopsychologist coldly and flatly, \ldblquote and make an end of it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert drew back a corner of his mouth. \ldblquote You mean destroy thirty thousand dollars per robot. I\rquote m afraid U. S. Robots wouldn\rquote t like that. We\rquote d better make an effort first, Susan, before we destroy anything.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In that case,\rdblquote  she said, sharply, \ldblquote I need facts. Exactly what advantage does Hyper Base derive from these modified robots? What factor made them desirable, general?\rdblquote\par
\tab Kallner ruffled his forehead and stroked it with an upward gesture of his hand. \ldblquote We had trouble with our previous robots. Our men work with hard radiations a good deal, you see. It\rquote s dangerous, of course, but reasonable precautions are taken. There have been only two accidents since we began and neither was fatal. However, it was impossible to explain that to an ordinary robot. The First Law states -- I\rquote ll quote it -- \lquote\i No robot may harm a human being, or through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm\i0 .\rquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s primary, Dr. Calvin. When it was necessary for one of our men to expose himself for a short period to a moderate gamma field, one that would have no physiological effects, the nearest robot would dash in to drag him out. If the field were exceedingly weak, it would succeed, and work could not continue till all robots were cleared out. If the field were a trifle stronger, the robot would never reach the technician concerned, since its positronic brain would collapse under gamma radiations -- and then we would be out one expensive and hard-to-replace robot.\par
\tab\ldblquote We tried arguing with them. Their point was that a human being in a gamma field was endangering his life and that it didn\rquote t matter that he could remain there half an hour safely. Supposing, they would say, he forgot and remained an hour. They couldn\rquote t take chances. We pointed out that they were risking their lives on a wild off-chance. But self-preservation is only the Third Law of Robotics -- and the First Law of human safety came first. We gave them orders; we ordered them strictly and harshly to remain out of gamma fields at whatever cost. But obedience is only the Second Law of Robotics -- and the First Law of human safety came first. Dr. Calvin, we either had to do without robots, or do something about the First Law -- and we made our choice.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t believe,\rdblquote  said Dr. Calvin, \ldblquote that it was found possible to remove the First Law.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t removed, it was modified,\rdblquote  explained Kallner. \ldblquote Positronic brains were constructed that contained the positive aspect only of the Law, which in them reads: \lquote\i No robot may harm a human being\i0 .\rquote  That is all. They have no compulsion to prevent one coming to harm through an extraneous agency such as gamma rays. I state the matter correctly, Dr. Bogert?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Quite,\rdblquote  assented the mathematician.\par
\tab\ldblquote And that is the only difference of your robots from the ordinary NS2 model? The \i only\i0  difference? Peter?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The \i only\i0  difference, Susan.\rdblquote\par
\tab She rose and spoke with finality, \ldblquote I intend sleeping now, and in about eight hours, I want to speak to whomever saw the robot last. And from now on, General Kallner, if I\rquote m to take any responsibility at all for events, I want full and unquestioned control of this investigation.\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin, except for two hours of resentful lassitude, experienced nothing approaching sleep. She signaled at Bogert\rquote s door at the local time of 0700 and found him also awake. He had apparently taken the trouble of transporting a dressing gown to Hyper Base with him, for he was sitting in it. He put his nail scissors down when Calvin entered.\par
\tab He said softly, \ldblquote I\rquote ve been expecting you more or less. I suppose you feel sick about all this.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I do.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well -- I\rquote m sorry. There was no way of preventing it. When the call came out from Hyper Base for us, I knew that something must have gone wrong with the modified Nestors. But what was there to do? I couldn\rquote t break the matter to you on the trip here, as I would have liked to, because I had to be sure. The matter of the modification is top secret.\rdblquote\par
\tab The psychologist muttered, \ldblquote I should have been told. U. S. Robots had no right to modify positronic brains this way without the approval of a psychologist.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert lifted his eyebrows and sighed. \ldblquote Be reasonable, Susan. You couldn\rquote t have influenced them. In this matter, the government was bound to have its way. They want the Hyperatomic Drive and the etheric physicists want robots that won\rquote t interfere with them. They were going to get them even if it did mean twisting the First Law. We had to admit it was possible from a construction standpoint and they swore a mighty oath that they wanted only twelve, that they would be used only at Hyper Base, that they would be destroyed once the Drive was perfected, and that full precautions would be taken. And they insisted on secrecy -- and that\rquote s the situation.\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Calvin spoke through her teeth, \ldblquote I would have resigned.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It wouldn\rquote t have helped. The government was offering the company a fortune, and threatening it with antirobot legislation in case of a refusal. We were stuck then, and we\rquote re badly stuck now. If this leaks out, it might hurt Kallner and the government, but it would hurt U. S. Robots a devil of a lot more.\rdblquote\par
\tab The psychologist stared at him. \ldblquote Peter, don\rquote t you realize what all this is about? Can\rquote t you understand what the removal of the First Law means? It isn\rquote t just a matter of secrecy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know what removal would mean. I\rquote m not a child. It would mean complete instability, with no nonimaginary solutions to the positronic Field Equations.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, mathematically. But can you translate that into crude psychological thought. All normal life, Peter, consciously or otherwise, resents domination. If the domination is by an inferior, or by a supposed inferior, the resentment becomes stronger. Physically, and, to an extent, mentally, a robot -- any robot -- is superior to human beings. What makes him slavish, then? \i Only the First Law!\i0  Why, without it, the first order you tried to give a robot would result in your death. Unstable? What do you think?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Susan,\rdblquote  said Bogert, with an air of sympathetic amusement. \ldblquote I\rquote ll admit that this Frankenstein Complex you\rquote re exhibiting has a certain justification -- hence the First Law in the first place. But the Law, I repeat and repeat, has not been removed -- merely modified.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And what about the stability of the brain?\rdblquote\par
