\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve worked with other robots we have here -- the simple ones. Nothing different about the Nestors except that they\rquote re a good deal cleverer -- and more annoying.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Annoying? In what way?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well -- perhaps it\rquote s not their fault. The work here is rough and most of us get a little jagged. Fooling around with hyper-space isn\rquote t fun.\rdblquote  He smiled feebly, finding pleasure in confession. \ldblquote We run the risk continually of blowing a hole in normal space-time fabric and dropping right out of the universe, asteroid and all. Sounds screwy, doesn\rquote t it? Naturally, you\rquote re on edge sometimes. But these Nestors aren\rquote t. They\rquote re curious, they\rquote re calm, they don\rquote t worry. It\rquote s enough to drive you nuts at times. When you want something done in a tearing hurry, they seem to take their time. Sometimes I\rquote d rather do without.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You say they take their time? Have they ever refused an order?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, no,\rdblquote  hastily. \ldblquote They do it all right. They tell you when they think you\rquote re wrong, though. They don\rquote t know anything about the subject but what we taught them, but that doesn\rquote t stop them. Maybe I imagine it, but the other fellows have the same trouble with their Nestors.\rdblquote\par
\tab General Kallner cleared his throat ominously, \ldblquote Why have no complaints reached me on the matter, Black?\rdblquote\par
\tab The young physicist reddened, \ldblquote We didn\rquote t \i really\i0  want to do without the robots, sir, and besides we weren\rquote t certain exactly how such... uh... minor complaints might be received.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert interrupted softly, \ldblquote Anything in particular happen the morning you last saw it?\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a silence. With a quiet motion, Calvin repressed the comment that was about to emerge from Kallner, and waited patiently.\par
\tab Then Black spoke in blurting anger, \ldblquote I had a little trouble with it. I\rquote d broken a Kimball tube that morning and was out five days of work; my entire program was behind schedule; I hadn\rquote t received any mail from home for a couple of weeks. And \i he\i0  came around wanting me to repeat an experiment I had abandoned a month ago. He was always annoying me on that subject and I was tired of it. I told him to go away -- and that\rquote s all I saw of him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You told him to go away?\rdblquote  asked Dr. Calvin with sharp interest. \ldblquote In just those words? Did you say \lquote Go away\rquote ? Try to remember the exact words.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was apparently an internal struggle in progress. Black cradled his forehead in a broad palm for a moment, then tore it away and said defiantly, \ldblquote I said, \lquote Go lose yourself.\rquote  \ldblquote\par
\tab Bogert laughed for a short moment. \ldblquote And he did, eh?\rdblquote\par
\tab But Calvin wasn\rquote t finished. She spoke cajolingly, \ldblquote Now we\rquote re getting somewhere, Mr. Black. But exact details are important. In understanding the robot\rquote s actions, a word, a gesture, an emphasis may be everything. You couldn\rquote t have said just those three words, for instance, could you? By your own description you must have been in a hasty mood. Perhaps you strengthened your speech a little.\rdblquote\par
\tab The young man reddened, \ldblquote Well... I may have called it a... a few things.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly what things?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh -- I wouldn\rquote t remember exactly. Besides I couldn\rquote t repeat it. You know how you get when you\rquote re excited.\rdblquote  His embarrassed laugh was almost a giggle, \ldblquote I sort of have a tendency to strong language.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s quite all right,\rdblquote  she replied, with prim severity. \ldblquote At the moment, I\rquote m a psychologist. I would like to have you repeat exactly what you said as nearly as you remember, and, even more important, the exact tone of voice you used.\rdblquote\par
\tab Black looked at his commanding officer for support, found none. His eyes grew round and appalled, \ldblquote But I can\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You must.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose,\rdblquote  said Bogert, with ill-hidden amusement, \ldblquote you address me. You may find it easier.\rdblquote\par
\tab The young man\rquote s scarlet face turned to Bogert. He swallowed. \ldblquote I said\rdblquote  His voice faded out. He tried again, \ldblquote I said-\rdblquote\par
\tab And he drew a deep breath and spewed it out hastily in one long succession of syllables. Then, in the charged air that lingered, he concluded almost in tears, \ldblquote ... more or less. I don\rquote t remember the exact order of what I called him, and maybe I left out something or put in something, but that was about it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Only the slightest flush betrayed any feeling on the part of the robopsychologist. She said, \ldblquote I am aware of the meaning of most of the terms used. The others, I suppose, are equally derogatory.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid so,\rdblquote  agreed the tormented Black.\par
\tab\ldblquote And in among it, you told him to lose himself.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I meant it only figuratively.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I realize that. No disciplinary action is intended, I am sure.\rdblquote  And at her glance, the general, who, five seconds earlier, had seemed not sure at all, nodded angrily.\par
\tab\ldblquote You may leave, Mr. Black. Thank you for your cooperation.\rdblquote\par
