\tab It took five hours for Susan Calvin to interview the sixty-three robots. It was five hours of multi-repetition; of replacement after replacement of identical robot; of Questions A, B, C, D; and Answers A, B, C, D; of a carefully bland expression, a carefully neutral tone, a carefully friendly atmosphere; and a hidden wire recorder.\par
\tab The psychologist felt drained of vitality when she was finished.\par
\tab Bogert was waiting for her and looked expectant as she dropped the recording spool with a clang upon the plastic of the desk.\par
\tab She shook her head, \ldblquote All sixty-three seemed the same to me. I couldn\rquote t tell-\rdblquote\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote You couldn\rquote t expect to tell by ear, Susan. Suppose we analyze the recordings.\rdblquote\par
\tab Ordinarily, the mathematical interpretation of verbal reactions of robots is one of the more intricate branches of robotic analysis. It requires a staff of trained technicians and the help of complicated computing machines. Bogert knew that. Bogert stated as much, in an extreme of unshown annoyance after having listened to each set of replies, made lists of word deviations, and graphs of the intervals of responses.\par
\tab\ldblquote There are no anomalies present, Susan. The variations in wording and the time reactions are within the limits of ordinary frequency groupings. We need finer methods. They must have computers here. No.\rdblquote  He frowned and nibbled delicately at a thumbnail. \ldblquote We can\rquote t use computers. Too much danger of leakage. Or maybe if we-\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Calvin stopped him with an impatient gesture, \ldblquote Please, Peter. This isn\rquote t one of your petty laboratory problems. If we can\rquote t determine the modified Nestor by some gross difference that we can see with the naked eye, one that there is no mistake about, we\rquote re out of luck. The danger of being wrong, and of letting him escape is otherwise too great. It\rquote s not enough to point out a minute irregularity in a graph. I tell you, if that\rquote s all I\rquote ve got to go on, I\rquote d destroy them all just to be certain. Have you spoken to the other modified Nestors?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I have,\rdblquote  snapped back Bogert, \ldblquote and there\rquote s nothing wrong with them. They\rquote re above normal in friendliness if anything. They answered my questions, displayed pride in their knowledge -- except the two new ones that haven\rquote t had time to learn their etheric physics. They laughed rather good-naturedly at my ignorance in some of the specializations here.\rdblquote  He shrugged, \ldblquote I suppose that forms some of the basis for resentment toward them on the part of the technicians here. The robots are perhaps too willing to impress you with their greater knowledge.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can you try a few Planar Reactions to see if there has been any change, any deterioration, in their mental set-up since manufacture?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I haven\rquote t yet, but I will.\rdblquote  He shook a slim finger at her, \ldblquote You\rquote re losing your nerve, Susan. I don\rquote t see what it is you\rquote re dramatizing. They\rquote re essentially harmless.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They are?\rdblquote  Calvin took fire. \ldblquote They are? Do you realize one of them is lying? One of the sixty-three robots I have just interviewed has deliberately lied to me after the strictest injunction to tell the truth. The abnormality indicated is horribly deep-seated, and horribly frightening.\rdblquote\par
\tab Peter Bogert felt his teeth harden against each other. He said, \ldblquote Not at all. Look! Nestor 10 was given orders to lose himself. Those orders were expressed in maximum urgency by the person most authorized to command him. You can\rquote t counteract that order either by superior urgency or superior right of command. Naturally, the robot will attempt to defend the carrying out of his orders. In fact, objectively, I admire his ingenuity. How better can a robot lose himself than to hide himself among a group of similar robots?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, you would admire it. I\rquote ve detected amusement in you, Peter -- amusement and an appalling lack of understanding. Are you a roboticist, Peter? Those robots attach importance to what they consider superiority. You\rquote ve just said as much yourself. Subconsciously they feel humans to be inferior and the First Law which protects us from them is imperfect. They are unstable. And here we have a young man ordering a robot to leave him, to lose himself, with every verbal appearance of revulsion, disdain, and disgust. Granted, that robot must follow orders, but subconsciously, there is resentment. It will become more important than ever for it to prove that it is superior despite the horrible names it was called. It may become so important that what\rquote s left of the First Law won\rquote t be enough.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How on Earth, or anywhere in the Solar System, Susan, is a robot going to know the meaning of the assorted strong language used upon him? Obscenity is not one of the things impressioned upon his brain.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Original impressionment is not everything,\rdblquote  Calvin snarled at him. \ldblquote Robots have learning capacity, you... you fool-\rdblquote  And Bogert knew that she had really lost her temper. She continued hastily, \ldblquote Don\rquote t you suppose he could tell from the tone used that the words weren\rquote t complimentary? Don\rquote t yon suppose he\rquote s heard the words used before and noted upon what occasions?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, then,\rdblquote  shouted Bogert, \ldblquote will you kindly tell me one way in which a modified robot can harm a human being, no matter how offended it is, no matter how sick with desire to prove superiority?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If I tell you one way, will you keep quiet?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab They were leaning across the table at each other, angry eyes nailed together.\par
\tab The psychologist said, \ldblquote If a modified robot were to drop a heavy weight upon a human being, he would not be breaking the First Law, if he did so with the knowledge that his strength and reaction speed would be sufficient to snatch the weight away before it struck the man. However once the weight left his fingers, he would be no longer the active medium. Only the blind force of gravity would be that. The robot could then change his mind and merely by inaction, allow the weight to strike. The modified First Law allows that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s an awful stretch of imagination.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s what my profession requires sometimes. Peter, let\rquote s not quarrel, let\rquote s work. You know the exact nature of the stimulus that caused the robot to lose himself. You have the records of his original mental make-up. I want you to tell me how possible it is for our robot to do the sort of thing I just talked about. Not the specific instance, mind you, but that whole class of response. And I want it done quickly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And meanwhile-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And meanwhile, we\rquote ll have to try performance tests directly on the response to First Law.\rdblquote\par
