\tab Major-general Kallner had not worn his uniform in its entirety since the first dinner with the U. S. Robot representatives. He wore nothing over his blue-gray shirt now, the collar was open, and the black tie was pulled loose.\par
\tab He looked hopefully at Bogert, who was still blandly neat and whose inner tension was perhaps betrayed only by the trace of glister at his temples.\par
\tab The general said, \ldblquote How does it look? What is it you\rquote re trying to see?\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert replied, \ldblquote A difference which may turn out to be a little too subtle for our purposes, I\rquote m afraid. For sixty-two of those robots the necessity of jumping toward the apparently threatened human was what we call, in robotics, a forced reaction. You see, even when the robots knew that the human in question would not come to harm -- and after the third or fourth time they must have known it -- they could not prevent reacting as they did. First Law requires it\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But the sixty-third robot, the modified Nestor, had no such compulsion. He was under free action. If he had wished, he could have remained in his seat. Unfortunately,\rdblquote  said his voice was mildly regretful, \ldblquote he didn\rquote t so wish.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why do you suppose?\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert shrugged, \ldblquote I suppose Dr. Calvin will tell us when she gets here. Probably with a horribly pessimistic interpretation, too. She is sometimes a bit annoying.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote She\rquote s qualified, isn\rquote t she?\rdblquote  demanded the general with a sudden frown of uneasiness.\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  Bogert seemed amused. \ldblquote She\rquote s qualified all right. She understands robots like a sister -- comes from hating human beings so much, I think. It\rquote s just that, psychologist or not, she\rquote s an extreme neurotic. Has paranoid tendencies. Don\rquote t take her too seriously.\rdblquote\par
\tab He spread the long row of broken-line graphs out in front of him. \ldblquote You see, general, in the case of each robot the time interval from moment of drop to the completion of a five-foot movement tends to decrease as the tests are repeated. There\rquote s a definite mathematical relationship that governs such things and failure to conform would indicate marked abnormality in the positronic brain. Unfortunately, all here appear normal.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But if our Nestor 10 was not responding with a forced action, why isn\rquote t his curve different? I don\rquote t understand that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s simple enough. Robotic responses are not perfectly analogous to human responses, more\rquote s the pity. In human beings, voluntary action is much slower than reflex action. But that\rquote s not the case with robots; with them it is merely a question of freedom of choice, otherwise the speeds of free and forced action are much the same. What I \i had\i0  been expecting, though, was that Nestor 10 would be caught by surprise the first time and allow too great an interval to elapse before responding.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And he didn\rquote t?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then we haven\rquote t gotten anywhere.\rdblquote  The general sat back with an expression of pain. \ldblquote It\rquote s five days since you\rquote ve come.\rdblquote\par
\tab At this point, Susan Calvin entered and slammed the door behind her. \ldblquote Put your graphs away, Peter,\rdblquote  she cried, \ldblquote you know they don\rquote t show anything.\rdblquote\par
\tab She mumbled something impatiently as Kallner half-rose to greet her, and went on, \ldblquote We\rquote ll have to try something else quickly. I don\rquote t like what\rquote s happening.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert exchanged a resigned glance with the general. \ldblquote Is anything wrong?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean specifically? No. But I don\rquote t like to have Nestor 10 continue to elude us. It\rquote s bad. It \i must\i0  be gratifying his swollen sense of superiority. I\rquote m afraid that his motivation is no longer simply one of following orders. I think it\rquote s becoming more a matter of sheer neurotic necessity to outthink humans. That\rquote s a dangerously unhealthy situation. Peter, have you done what I asked? Have you worked out the instability factors of the modified NS-2 along the lines I want?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s in progress,\rdblquote  said the mathematician, without interest.\par
\tab She stared at him angrily for a moment, then turned to Kallner. \ldblquote Nester 10 is decidedly aware of what we\rquote re doing, general. He had no reason to jump for the bait in this experiment, especially after the first time, when he must have seen that there was no real danger to our subject. The others couldn\rquote t help it; but \i he\i0  was deliberately falsifying a reaction.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What do you think we ought to do now, then, Dr. Calvin?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Make it impossible for him to fake an action the next time. We will repeat the experiment, but with an addition. High-tension cables, capable of electrocuting the Nestor models will be placed between subject and robot -- enough of them to avoid the possibility of jumping over -- and the robot will be made perfectly aware in advance that touching the cables will mean death.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hold on,\rdblquote  spat out Bogert with sudden viciousness. \ldblquote I rule that out. We are not electrocuting two million dollars worth of robots to locate Nestor 10. There are other ways.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re certain? You\rquote ve found none. In any case, it\rquote s not a question of electrocution. We can arrange a relay which will break the current at the instant of application of weight. If the robot should place his weight on it, he won\rquote t die. \i But he won\rquote t know that\i0 , you see.\rdblquote\par
\tab The general\rquote s eyes gleamed into hope. \ldblquote Will that work?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It should. Under those conditions, Nestor 10 would have to remain in his seat. He could be \i ordered\i0  to touch the cables and die, for the Second Law of obedience is superior to the Third Law of self-preservation. But \i he won\rquote t\i0  be ordered to; he will merely be left to his own devices, as will all the robots. In the case of the normal robots, the First Law of human safety will drive them to their death even without orders. But not our Nestor 10. Without the entire First Law, and without having received any orders on the matter, the Third Law, self-preservation, will be the highest operating, and he will have no choice but to remain in his seat. It would be a forced action.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Will it be done tonight, then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Tonight,\rdblquote  said the psychologist, \ldblquote if the cables can be laid in time. I\rquote ll tell the robots now what they\rquote re to be up against.\rdblquote\par
