\tab Major-general Kallner, too, was angry. For one week all of Hyper Base had stopped dead, barring some paper work on the subsidiary asteroids of the group. For nearly one week, the two top experts in the field had aggravated the situation with useless tests. And now they -- or the woman, at any rate -- made impossible propositions.\par
\tab Fortunately for the general situation, Kallner felt it impolitic to display his anger openly.\par
\tab Susan Calvin was insisting, \ldblquote Why not, sir? It\rquote s obvious that the present situation is unfortunate. The only way we may reach results in the future -- or what future is left us in this matter -- is to separate the robots. We can\rquote t keep them together any longer.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote My dear Dr. Calvin,\rdblquote  rumbled the general, his voice sinking into the lower baritone registers. \ldblquote I don\rquote t see how I can quarter sixty-three robots all over the place-\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Calvin raised her arms helplessly. \ldblquote I can do nothing then. Nestor 10 will either imitate what the other robots would do, or else argue them plausibly into not doing what he himself cannot do. And in any case, this is bad business. We\rquote re in actual combat with this little lost robot of ours and he\rquote s winning out. Every victory of his aggravates his abnormality.\rdblquote\par
\tab She rose to her feet in determination. \ldblquote General Kallner, if you do not separate the robots as I ask, then I can only demand that all sixty-three be destroyed immediately.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You demand it, do you?\rdblquote  Bogert looked up suddenly, and with real anger. \ldblquote What gives you the right to demand any such thing? Those robots remain as they are. \i I\rquote m \i0 responsible to the management, not you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And I,\rdblquote  added Major-general Kallner, \ldblquote am responsible to the World Co-ordinator -- and I must have this settled.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In that case,\rdblquote  flashed back Calvin, \ldblquote there is nothing for me to do but resign. If necessary to force you to the necessary destruction, I\rquote ll make this whole matter public. It was not I that approved the manufacture of modified robots.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote One word from you, Dr. Calvin,\rdblquote  said the general, deliberately, \ldblquote in violation of security measures, and you would be certainly imprisoned instantly.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert felt the matter to be getting out of hand. His voice grew syrupy, \ldblquote Well, now, we\rquote re beginning to act like children, all of us. We need only a little more time. Surely we can outwit a robot without resigning, or imprisoning people, or destroying two millions.\rdblquote\par
\tab The psychologist turned on him with quiet fury, \ldblquote I don\rquote t want any unbalanced robots in existence. We have one Nestor that\rquote s definitely unbalanced, eleven more that are potentially so, and sixty-two normal robots that are being subjected to an unbalanced environment. The only absolute safe method is complete destruction.\rdblquote\par
\tab The signal-burr brought all three to a halt, and the angry tumult of growingly unrestrained emotion froze.\par
\tab\ldblquote Come in,\rdblquote  growled Kallner.\par
\tab It was Gerald Black, looking perturbed. He had heard angry voices. He said, \ldblquote I thought I\rquote d come myself... didn\rquote t like to ask anyone else-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What is it? Don\rquote t orate-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The locks of Compartment C in the trading ship have been played with. There are fresh scratches on them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Compartment C?\rdblquote  explained Calvin quickly. \ldblquote That\rquote s the one that holds the robots, isn\rquote t it? Who did it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote From the inside,\rdblquote  said Black, laconically.\par
\tab\ldblquote The lock isn\rquote t out of order, is it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. It\rquote s all right. I\rquote ve been staying on the ship now for four days and none of them have tried to get out. But I thought you ought to know, and I didn\rquote t like to spread the news. I noticed the matter myself.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is anyone there now?\rdblquote  demanded the general.\par
\tab\ldblquote I left Robbins and McAdams there.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a thoughtful silence, and then Dr. Calvin said, ironically, \ldblquote Well?\rdblquote\par
\tab Kallner rubbed his nose uncertainly, \ldblquote What\rquote s it all about?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Isn\rquote t it obvious? Nester 10 is planning to leave. That order to lose himself is dominating his abnormality past anything we can do. I wouldn\rquote t be surprised if what\rquote s left of his First Law would scarcely be powerful enough to override it. He is perfectly capable of seizing the ship and leaving with it. Then we\rquote d have a mad robot on a spaceship. What would he do next? Any idea? Do you still want to leave them all together, general?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nonsense,\rdblquote  interrupted Bogert. He had regained his smoothness. \ldblquote All that from a few scratch marks on a lock.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Have you, Dr. Bogert, completed the analysis I\rquote ve required, since you volunteer opinions?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote May I see it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not? Or mayn\rquote t I ask that, either?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because there\rquote s no point in it, Susan. I told you in advance that these modified robots are less stable than the normal variety, and my analysis shows it. There\rquote s a certain very small chance of breakdown under extreme circumstances that are not likely to occur. Let it go at that. I won\rquote t give you ammunition for your absurd claim that sixty-two perfectly good robots be destroyed just because so far you lack the ability to detect Nestor 10 among them.\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin stared him down and let disgust fill her eyes. \ldblquote You won\rquote t let anything stand in the way of the permanent directorship, will you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Please,\rdblquote  begged Kallner, half in irritation. \ldblquote Do you insist that nothing further can be done, Dr. Calvin?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t think of anything, sir,\rdblquote  she replied, wearily. \ldblquote If there were only other differences between Nestor 10 and the normal robots, differences that didn\rquote t involve the First Law. Even one other difference. Something in impressionment, environment, specification-\rdblquote  And she stopped suddenly.\par
\tab\ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve thought of something... I think-\rdblquote  Her eyes grew distant and hard, \ldblquote These modified Nestors, Peter. They get the same impressioning the normal ones get, don\rquote t they?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Exactly the same.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And what was it you were saying, Mr. Black,\rdblquote  she turned to the young man, who through the storms that had followed his news had maintained a discreet silence. \ldblquote Once when complaining of the Nestors\rquote  attitude of superiority, you said the technicians had taught them all they knew.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, in etheric physics. They\rquote re not acquainted with the subject when they come here.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Bogert, in surprise. \ldblquote I told you, Susan, when I spoke to the other Nestors here that the two new arrivals hadn\rquote t learned etheric physics yet.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And why is that?\rdblquote  Dr. Calvin was speaking in mounting excitement. \ldblquote Why aren\rquote t NS-2 models impressioned with etheric physics to start with?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I can tell you that,\rdblquote  said Kallner. \ldblquote It\rquote s all of a piece with the secrecy. We thought that if we made a special model with knowledge of etheric physics, used twelve of them and put the others to work in an unrelated field, there might be suspicion. Men working with normal Nestors might wonder why they knew etheric physics. So there was merely an impressionment with a capacity for training in the field. Only the ones that come here, naturally, receive such a training. It\rquote s that simple.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I understand. Please get out of here, the lot of you. Let me have an hour or so.\rdblquote\par
