\tab Calvin felt she could not face the ordeal for a third time. Her mind had contemplated it and rejected it with an intensity that left her nauseated. She could face that unending file of repetitious robots no more.\par
\tab So Bogert asked the question now, while she sat aside, eyes and mind half closed.\par
\tab Number Fourteen came in -- forty-nine to go.\par
\tab Bogert looked up from the guide sheet and said, \ldblquote What is your number in line?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Fourteen, sir.\rdblquote  The robot presented his numbered ticket.\par
\tab\ldblquote Sit down, boy.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert asked, \ldblquote You haven\rquote t been here before on this day?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, boy, we are going to have another man in danger of harm soon after we\rquote re through here. In fact, when you leave this room, you will be led to a stall where you will wait quietly, till you are needed. Do you understand?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Now, naturally, if a man is in danger of harm, you will try to save him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Naturally, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Unfortunately, between the man and yourself, there will be a gamma ray field.\rdblquote\par
\tab Silence.\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you know what gamma rays are?\rdblquote  asked Bogert sharply.\par
\tab\ldblquote Energy radiation, sir?\rdblquote\par
\tab The next question came in a friendly, offhand manner, \ldblquote Ever work with gamma rays?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir.\rdblquote  The answer was definite.\par
\tab\ldblquote Mm-m. Well, boy, gamma rays will kill you instantly. They\rquote ll destroy your brain. That is a fact you must know and remember. Naturally, you don\rquote t want to destroy yourself.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Naturally.\rdblquote  Again the robot seemed shocked. Then, slowly, \ldblquote But, sir, if the gamma rays are between myself and the master that may be harmed, how can I save him? I would be destroying myself to no purpose.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, there is that,\rdblquote  Bogert seemed concerned about the matter. \ldblquote The only thing I can advise, boy, is that if you detect the gamma radiation between yourself and the man, you may as well sit where you are.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robot was openly relieved. \ldblquote Thank you, sir. There wouldn\rquote t be any use, would there?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course not. But if there \i weren\rquote t\i0  any dangerous radiation, that would be a different matter.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Naturally, sir. No question of that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You may leave now. The man on the other side of the door will lead you to your stall. Please wait there.\rdblquote\par
\tab He turned to Susan Calvin when the robot left. \ldblquote How did that go, Susan?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Very well,\rdblquote  she said, dully.\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you think we could catch Nestor 10 by quick questioning on etheric physics?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps, but it\rquote s not sure enough.\rdblquote  Her hands lay loosely in her lap. \ldblquote Remember, he\rquote s fighting us. He\rquote s on his guard. The only way we can catch him is to outsmart him -- and, within his limitations, he can think much more quickly than a human being.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, just for fun -- suppose I ask the robots from now on a few questions on gamma rays. Wave length limits, for instance.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  Dr. Calvin\rquote s eyes sparked to life. \ldblquote It would be too easy for him to deny knowledge and then he\rquote d be warned against the test that\rquote s coming up -- which is our real chance. Please follow the questions I\rquote ve indicated, Peter, and don\rquote t improvise. It\rquote s just within the bounds of risk to ask them if they\rquote ve ever worked with gamma rays. And try to sound even less interested than you do when you ask it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert shrugged, and pressed the buzzer that would allow the entrance of Number Fifteen.\par
\tab The large Radiation Room was in readiness once more. The robots waited patiently in their wooden cells, all open to the center but closed off from each other.\par
\tab Major-general Kallner mopped his brow slowly with a large handkerchief while Dr. Calvin checked the last details with Black.\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re sure now,\rdblquote  she demanded, \ldblquote that none of the robots have had a chance to talk with each other after leaving the Orientation Room?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Absolutely sure,\rdblquote  insisted Black. \ldblquote There\rquote s not been a word exchanged.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And the robots are put in the proper stalls?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Here\rquote s the plan.\rdblquote\par
\tab The psychologist looked at it thoughtfully, \ldblquote Um-m-m.\rdblquote\par
\tab The general peered over her shoulder. \ldblquote What\rquote s the idea of the arrangement, Dr. Calvin?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve asked to have those robots that appeared even slightly out of true in the previous tests concentrated on one side of the circle. I\rquote m going to be sitting in the center myself this time, and I wanted to watch those particularly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote\i You\rquote re\i0  going to be sitting there-,\rdblquote  exclaimed Bogert.\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  she demanded coldly. \ldblquote What I expect to see may be something quite momentary. I can\rquote t risk having anyone else as main observer. Peter, you\rquote ll be in the observing booth, and I want you to keep your eye on the opposite side of the circle. General Kallner, I\rquote ve arranged for motion pictures to be taken of each robot, in case visual observation isn\rquote t enough. If these are required, the robots are to remain exactly where they are until the pictures are developed and studied. None must leave, none must change place. Is that clear?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Perfectly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then let\rquote s try it this one last time.\rdblquote\par
