\i\tab\i0 Hyper Base had lived for this day. Spaced about the gallery of the viewing room, in order and precedence strictly dictated by protocol, was a group of officials, scientists, technicians and others who could only be lumped under the general classification of \ldblquote personnel.\rdblquote  In accordance with their separate temperaments they waited hopefully, uneasily, breathlessly, eagerly, or fearfully for this culmination of their efforts. \par
\tab The hollowed interior of the asteroid known as Hyper Base had become for this day the center of a sphere of iron security that extended out for ten thousand miles. No ship might enter that sphere and live. No message might leave without scrutiny. \par
\tab A hundred miles away, more or less, a small asteroid moved neatly in the orbit into which it had been urged a year before, an orbit that ringed Hyper Base in as perfect a circle as could be managed. The asteroidlet\rquote s identity number was H937, but no one on Hyper Base called it anything but It. (\ldblquote Have you been out on it today?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The general\rquote s on it, blowing his top,\rdblquote  and eventually the impersonal pronoun achieved the dignity of capitalization.) \par
\tab On It, unoccupied now as zero second approached, was the \i Parsec, \i0 the only ship of its kind ever built in the history of man. It lay, unmanned, ready for its takeoff into the inconceivable. \par
\tab Gerald Black, who, as one of the bright young men in etherics engineering, rated a front-row view, cracked his large knuckles, then wiped his sweating palms on his stained white smock and said sourly, \ldblquote Why don\rquote t you bother the general, or Her Ladyship there?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Nigel Ronson, of Interplanetary Press, looked briefly across the gallery toward the glitter of Major-general Richard Kallner and the unremarkable woman at his side, scarcely visible in the glare of his dress uniform. He said, \ldblquote I would. except that I\rquote m interested in news.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ronson was short and plump. He painstakingly wore his hair in a quarter-inch bristle, his shirt collar open and his trouser leg ankle-short, in faithful imitation of the newsmen who were stock characters on TV shows. He was a capable reporter nevertheless. \par
\tab Black was stocky, and his dark hairline left little room for forehead, but his mind was as keen as his strong fingers were blunt. He said, \ldblquote They\rquote ve got all the news.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nuts,\rdblquote  said Ronson. \ldblquote Kallner\rquote s got no body under that gold braid. Strip him and you\rquote ll find only a conveyer belt dribbling orders downward and shooting responsibility upward.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black found himself at the point of a grin but squeezed it down. He said. \ldblquote What about the Madam Doctor?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Dr. Susan Calvin of U. S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation.\rdblquote  intoned the reporter. \ldblquote The lady with hyperspace where her heart ought to be and liquid helium in her eyes. She\rquote d pass through the sun and come out the other end encased in frozen flame.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black came even closer to a grin. \ldblquote How about Director Schloss, then?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ronson said glibly, \ldblquote He knows too much. Between spending his time fanning the feeble flicker of intelligence in his listener and dimming his own brains for fear of blinding said listener permanently by sheer force of brilliance, he ends up saying nothing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black showed his teeth this time. \ldblquote Now suppose you tell me why you pick on me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Easy, doctor. I looked at you and figured you\rquote re too ugly to be stupid and too smart to miss a possible opportunity at some good personal publicity.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Remind me to knock you down someday.\rdblquote  said Black. \ldblquote What do you want to know?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The man from Interplanetary Press pointed into the pit and said, \ldblquote Is that thing going to work?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black looked downward too, and felt a vague chill riffle over him like the thin night wind of Mars. The pit was one large television screen, divided in two. One half was an over-all view of It. On It\rquote s pitted gray surface was the \i Parse, \i0 glowing mutedly in the feeble sunlight. The other half showed the control room of the \i Parsec. \i0 There was no life in that control room. In the pilot\rquote s seat was an object the vague humanity of which did not for a moment obscure the fact that it was only a positronic robot. \par
\tab Black said, \ldblquote Physically, mister, this will work. That robot will leave and come back. Space! how we succeeded with that part of it. I watched it all. I came here two weeks after I took my degree in etheric physics and I\rquote ve been here, barring leave and furloughs, ever since. I was here when we sent the first piece of iron wire to Jupiter\rquote s orbit and back through hyperspace--and got back iron filings. I was here when we sent white mice there and back and ended up with mincemeat. \par
\tab\ldblquote We spent six months establishing an even hyperfield after that. We had to wipe out lags of as little as tenths of thousandths of seconds from point to point in matter being subjected to hypertravel. After that, the white mice started coming back intact. I remember when we celebrated for a week because one white mouse came back alive and lived ten minutes before dying. Now they live as long as we can take proper care of them.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ronson said, \ldblquote Great!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black looked at him obliquely. \ldblquote I said, \i physically \i0 it will work. Those white mice that come back--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No minds. Not even little white mice-type minds. They won\rquote t eat. They have to be force-fed. They won\rquote t mate. They won\rquote t run. They sit. They sit. They sit. That\rquote s all. We finally worked up to sending a chimpanzee. It was pitiful. It was too close to a man to make watching it bearable. It came back a hunk of meat that could make crawling motions. It could move its eyes and sometimes it would scrabble. It whined and sat in its own wastes without the sense to move. Somebody shot it one day, and we were all grateful for that. I tell you this, fella, nothing that ever went into hyperspace has come back with a mind.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Is this for publication?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote  After this experiment, maybe. They expect great things of it.\rdblquote  A comer of Black\rquote s mouth lifted. \par
\tab\ldblquote You don\rquote t?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote With a robot at the controls? No.\rdblquote  Almost automatically Black\rquote s mind went back to that interlude, some years back, in which he had been unwittingly responsible for the near loss of a robot. He thought of the Nestor robots that filled Hyper Base with smooth, ingrained knowledge and perfectionist shortcomings. Mat was the use of talking about robots? He was not, by nature, a missionary. \par
\tab But then Ronson, filling the continuing silence with a bit of small talk, said, as he replaced the wad of gum in his mouth with a fresh piece, \ldblquote Don\rquote t tell me \i you\rquote re \i0 anti-robot. I\rquote ve always heard that scientists are the one group that aren\rquote t anti-robot.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black\rquote s patience snapped. He said, \ldblquote That\rquote s true, and that\rquote s the trouble. Technology\rquote s gone robot-happy. Any job has to have a robot, or the engineer in charge feels cheated. You want a doorstop; buy a robot with a thick foot. That\rquote s a serious thing.\rdblquote  He was speaking in a low, intense voice, shoving the words directly into Ronson\rquote s ear. \par
\tab Ronson managed to extricate his arm. He said, \ldblquote Hey, I\rquote m no robot. Don\rquote t take it out on me. I\rquote m a man. \i Homo sapiens. \i0 You just broke an arm bone of mine. Isn\rquote t that proof?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Having started, however, it took more than frivolity to stop Black. He said, \ldblquote Do you know how much time was wasted on this setup? We\rquote ve had a perfectly generalized robot built and we\rquote ve given it one order. Period. I heard the order given. I\rquote ve memorized it. Short and sweet. \lquote Seize the bar with a firm grip. Pull it toward you firmly. \i Firmly! \i0 Maintain your hold until the control board informs you that you have passed through hyperspace twice.\rquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So at zero time, the robot will grab the control bar and pull it firmly toward himself. His hands are heated to blood temperature. Once the control bar is in position, heat expansion completes contact and hyperfield is initiated. If anything happens to his brain during the first trip through hyperspace, it doesn\rquote t matter. All he needs to do is maintain position one microinstant and the ship will come back and the hyperfield will flip off. Nothing can go wrong. Then we study all its generalized reactions and see what, if anything, has gone wrong.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ronson looked blank. \ldblquote This all makes sense to me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Does it?\rdblquote  asked Black bitterly. \ldblquote And what will you learn from a robot brain? It\rquote s positronic, ours is cellular. It\rquote s metal, ours is protein. They\rquote re not the same. There\rquote s no comparison. Yet I\rquote m convinced that on the basis of what they learn, or think they learn, from the robot, they\rquote ll send men into hyperspace. Poor devils! Look, it\rquote s not a question of dying. It\rquote s coming back mindless. If you\rquote d seen the chimpanzee, you\rquote d know what I mean. Death is clean and final. The other thing--\rdblquote  \par
\tab The reporter said, \ldblquote Have you talked about this to anyone?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black said, \ldblquote Yes. They say what you said. They say I\rquote m anti-robot and that settles everything. --Look at Susan Calvin there. You can bet \i she \i0 isn\rquote t anti-robot. She came all the way from Earth to watch this experiment. If it had been a man at the controls, she wouldn\rquote t have bothered. But what\rquote s the use!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Hey,\rdblquote  said Ronson, \ldblquote don\rquote t stop now. There\rquote s more.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote More what?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote More problems. You\rquote ve explained the robot. But why the security provisions all of a sudden?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Huh?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Come \i on. \i0 Suddenly I can\rquote t send dispatches. Suddenly ships can\rquote t come into the area. What\rquote s going on? This is just another experiment. The public knows about hyperspace and what you boys are trying to do, so what\rquote s the big secret?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The backwash of anger was still seeping over Black, anger against the robots, anger against Susan Calvin, anger at the memory of that little lost robot in his past. There was some to spare, he found, for the irritating little newsman and his irritating little questions. \par
\tab He said to himself, Let\rquote s see how he takes it. He said, \ldblquote You really want to know?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You bet.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote All right. We\rquote ve never initiated a hyperfield for any object a millionth as large as that ship, or to send anything a millionth as far. That means that the hyperfield that will soon be initiated is some million million times as energetic as any we\rquote ve ever handled. We\rquote re not sure what it can do.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What do you mean?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Theory tells us that the ship will be neatly deposited out near Sirius and neatly brought back here. But how large a volume of space about the \i Parsec \i0 will be carried with it? It\rquote s hard to tell. We don\rquote t know enough about hyperspace. The asteroid on which the ship sits may go with it and, you know, if our calculations are even a little off, it may never be brought back here. It may return, say, twenty billion miles away. And there\rquote s a chance that more of space than just the asteroid may be shifted.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How much more?\rdblquote  demanded Ronson. \par
\tab\ldblquote We can\rquote t say. There\rquote s an element of statistical uncertainty. That\rquote s why no ships must approach too closely. That\rquote s why we\rquote re keeping things quiet till the experiment is safely over.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ronson swallowed audibly. \ldblquote Supposing it reaches to Hyper Base?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There\rquote s a chance of it,\rdblquote  said Black with composure. \ldblquote Not much of a chance or Director Schloss wouldn\rquote t be here, I assure you. Still, there\rquote s a mathematical chance.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The newsman looked at his watch. \ldblquote When does this all happen?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In about five minutes. You\rquote re not nervous, are you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Ronson, but he sat down blankly and asked no more questions. \par
\tab Black leaned outward over the railing. The final minutes were ticking off. \par
\tab\i The robot moved! \par
\tab\i0 There was a mass sway of humanity forward at that sign of motion and the lights dimmed in order to sharpen and heighten the brightness of the scene below. But so far it was only the first motion. The hands of the robot approached the starting bar. \par
\tab Black waited for the final second when the robot would pull the bar toward himself. Black could imagine a number of possibilities, and all sprang nearly simultaneously to mind. \par
\tab There would first be the short flicker that would indicate the departure through hyperspace and return. Even though the time interval was exceedingly short, return would not be to the \i precise \i0 starting position and there would be a flicker. There always was. \par
\tab Then, when the ship returned, it might be found, perhaps, that the devices to even the field over the huge volume of the ship had proved inadequate. The robot might be scrap steel. The ship might be scrap steel. \par
\tab Or their calculations might be somewhat off and the ship might never return. Or worse still, Hyper Base might go with the ship and never return. \par
\tab Or, of course, all might be well. The ship might flicker and be there in perfect shape. The robot, with mind untouched, would get out of his seat and signal a successful completion of the first voyage of a man-made object beyond the gravitational control of the sun. \par
\tab The last minute was ticking off. \par
\tab The last second came and the robot seized the starting bar and pulled it firmly toward himself--\par
\tab Nothing! \par
\tab No flicker. Nothing! \par
\tab The \i Parsec \i0 never left normal space. \par
\par
\tab Major-general Kallner took off his officer\rquote s cap to mop his glistening forehead and in doing so exposed a bald head that would have aged him ten years in appearance if his drawn expression had not already done so. Nearly an hour had passed since the \i Parsec\rquote s \i0 failure and nothing had been done. \par
\tab\ldblquote How did it happen? How did it happen? I don\rquote t understand it.\rdblquote  Dr. Mayer Schloss, who at forty was the \ldblquote grand old man\rdblquote  of the young science of hyperfield matrices, said hopelessly, \ldblquote There is nothing wrong with the basic theory. I\rquote ll swear my life away on that. There\rquote s a mechanical failure on the ship somewhere. Nothing more.\rdblquote  He had said that a dozen times. \par
\tab\ldblquote I thought everything was tested.\rdblquote  That had been said too. \ldblquote It was, sir, it was. Just the same--\rdblquote  And that. \par
\tab They sat staring at each other in Kallner\rquote s office, which was now out of bounds for all personnel. Neither quite dared to look at the third person present. \par
\tab Susan Calvin\rquote s thin lips and pale cheeks bore no expression. She said coolly, \ldblquote You may console yourself with what I have told you before. It is doubtful whether anything useful would have resulted.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote This is not the time for the old argument,\rdblquote  groaned Schloss. \ldblquote I am not arguing. U. S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation will supply robots made up to specification to any legal purchaser for any legal use. We did our part, however. We informed you that we could not guarantee being able to draw conclusions with regard to the human brain from anything that happened to the positronic brain. Our responsibility ends there. There is no argument.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Great space,\rdblquote  said General Kallner, in a tone that made the expletive feeble indeed. \ldblquote Let\rquote s not discuss that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What else was there to do?\rdblquote  muttered Schloss, driven to the subject nevertheless. \ldblquote Until we know exactly what\rquote s happening to the mind in hyperspace we can\rquote t progress. The robot\rquote s mind is at least capable of mathematical analysis. It\rquote s a start, a beginning. And until we try--\rdblquote  He looked up wildly, \ldblquote But your robot isn\rquote t the point, Dr. Calvin. We\rquote re not worried about him or his positronic brain. Damn it, woman--\rdblquote  His voice rose nearly to a scream. \par
\tab The robopsychologist cut him to silence with a voice that scarcely raised itself from its level monotone. \ldblquote No hysteria, man. In my lifetime I have witnessed many crises and I have never seen one solved by hysteria. I want answers to some questions.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Schloss\rquote s full lips trembled and his deep-set eyes seemed to retreat into their sockets and leave pits of shadow in their places. He said harshly, \ldblquote Are you trained in etheric engineering?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is an irrelevant question. I am Chief Robopsychologist of the United States Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation. That is a positronic robot sitting at the controls of the \i Parsec. \i0 Like all such robots, it is leased and not sold. I have a right to demand information concerning any experiment in which such a robot is involved.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Talk to her, Schloss,\rdblquote  barked General Kallner. \ldblquote She\rquote s--she\rquote s all right.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Dr. Calvin turned her pale eyes on the general, who had been present at the time of the affair of the lost robot and who therefore could be expected not to make the mistake of underestimating her. (Schloss had been out on sick leave at the time, and hearsay is not as effective as personal experience.) \ldblquote Thank you, general,\rdblquote  she said. \par
\tab Schloss looked helplessly from one to the other and muttered, \ldblquote What do you want to know?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Obviously my first question is, What \i is \i0 your problem if the robot is not?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But the problem is an obvious one. The ship hasn\rquote t moved. Can\rquote t you see that? Are you blind?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I see quite well. What I don\rquote t see is your obvious panic over some mechanical failure. Don\rquote t you people expect failure sometimes?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The general muttered, \ldblquote It\rquote s the expense. The ship was hellishly expensive. The World Congress--appropriations--\rdblquote  He bogged down. \par
\tab\ldblquote The ship\rquote s still there. A slight overhaul and correction would involve no great trouble.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Schloss had taken hold of himself. The expression on his face was one of a man who had caught his soul in both hands, shaken it hard and set it on its feet. His voice had even achieved a kind of patience. \ldblquote Dr. Calvin, when I say a mechanical failure, I mean something like a relay jammed by a speck of dust, a connection inhibited by a spot of grease, a transistor balked by a momentary heat expansion. A dozen other things. A hundred other things. Any of them can be quite temporary. They can stop taking effect at any moment.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Which means that at any moment the \i Parsec \i0 may flash through hyperspace and back after all.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly. Now do you understand?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all. Wouldn\rquote t that be just what you want?\rdblquote  Schloss made a motion that looked like the start of an effort to seize a double handful of hair and yank. He said, \ldblquote You are not an etherics engineer.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Does that tongue-tie you, doctor?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We had the ship set,\rdblquote  said Schloss despairingly, \ldblquote to make a jump from a definite point in space relative to the center of gravity of the galaxy to another point. The return was to be to the original point corrected for the motion of the solar system. In the hour that has passed since the \i Parsec \i0 should have moved, the solar system has shifted position. The original parameters to which the hyperfield is adjusted no longer apply. The ordinary laws of motion do not apply to hyperspace and it would take us a week of computation to calculate a new set of parameters.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You mean that if the ship moves now it will return to some unpredictable point thousands of miles away?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Unpredictable?\rdblquote  Schloss smiled hollowly. \ldblquote Yes, I should call it that. The \i Parsec \i0 might end up in the Andromeda nebula or in the center of the sun. In any case the odds are against our ever seeing it again.\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin nodded. \ldblquote The situation then is that if the ship disappears, as it may do at any moment, a few billion dollars of the taxpayers\rquote  money may be irretrievably gone, and--it will be said--through bungling.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Major-general Kallner could not have winced more noticeably if he had been poked with a sharp pin in the fundament. \par
\tab The robopsychologist went on, \ldblquote Somehow, then, the ship\rquote s hyperfield mechanism must be put out of action, and that as soon as possible. Something will have to be unplugged or jerked loose or flicked off.\rdblquote  She was speaking half to herself. \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s not that simple,\rdblquote  said Schloss. \ldblquote I can\rquote t explain it completely, since you\rquote re not an etherics expert. It\rquote s like trying to break an ordinary electric circuit by slicing through high-tension wire with garden shears. It could be disastrous. It \i would \i0 be disastrous.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Do you mean that any attempt to shut off the mechanism would hurl the ship into hyperspace?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Any \i random \i0 attempt would \i probably \i0 do so. Hyper-forces are not limited by the speed of light. It is very probable that they have no limit of velocity at all. It makes things extremely difficult. The only reasonable solution is to discover the nature of the failure and learn from that a safe way of disconnecting the field.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And how do you propose to do that, Dr. Schloss?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Schloss said, \ldblquote It seems to me that the only thing to do is to send one of our Nestor robots--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No! Don\rquote t be foolish,\rdblquote  broke in Susan Calvin. \par
\tab Schloss said, freezingly, \ldblquote The Nestors are acquainted with the problems of etherics engineering. They will be ideally--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Out of the question. You cannot use one of our positronic robots for such a purpose without my permission. You do not have it and you shall not get it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What is the alternative?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You must send one of your engineers.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Schloss shook his head violently, \ldblquote Impossible. The risk involved is too great. If we lose a ship \i and \i0 man--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nevertheless, you may not use a Nestor robot, or any robot.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The general said, \ldblquote I--I must get in touch with Earth. This whole problem has to go to a higher level.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin said with asperity, \ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t just yet if I were you, general. You will be throwing yourself on the government\rquote s mercy without a suggestion or plan of action of your own. You will not come out very well, I am certain.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But what is there to do?\rdblquote  The general was using his handkerchief again. \par
\tab\ldblquote Send a man. There is no alternative.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Schloss had paled to a pasty gray. \ldblquote It\rquote s easy to say, send a man. But whom?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve been considering that problem. Isn\rquote t there a young man--his name is Black--whom I met on the occasion of my previous visit to Hyper Base?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Dr. Gerald Black?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I think so. Yes. He was a bachelor then. Is he still?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I believe so.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I would suggest then that he be brought here, say, in fifteen minutes, and that meanwhile I have access to his records.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Smoothly she had assumed authority in this situation, and neither Kallner nor Schloss made any attempt to dispute that authority with her. \par
\par
\tab Black had seen Susan Calvin from a distance on this, her second visit to Hyper Base. He had made no move to cut down the distance. Now that he had been called into her presence, he found himself staring at her with revulsion and distaste. He scarcely noticed Dr. Schloss and General Kallner standing behind her. \par
\tab He remembered the last time he had faced her thus, undergoing a cold dissection for the sake of a lost robot. \par
\tab Dr. Calvin\rquote s cool gray eyes were fixed steadily on his hot brown ones. \par
\tab\ldblquote Dr. Black,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote I believe you understand the situation.\rdblquote  Black said, \ldblquote I do.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Something will have to be done. The ship is too expensive to lose. The bad publicity will probably mean the end of the project.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black nodded. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been thinking that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I hope you\rquote ve also thought that it will be necessary for someone to board the \i Parsec, \i0 find out what\rquote s wrong, and--uh--deactivate it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was a moment\rquote s pause. Black said harshly, \ldblquote What fool would go?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Kallner frowned and looked at Schloss, who bit his lip and looked nowhere. \par
\tab Susan Calvin said, \ldblquote There is, of course, the possibility of accidental activation of the hyperfield, in which case the ship may drive beyond all possible reach. On the other hand, it may return somewhere within the solar system. If so, no expense or effort will be spared to recover man and ship.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black said, \ldblquote Idiot and ship! Just a correction.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin disregarded the comment. She said, \ldblquote I have asked General Kallner\rquote s permission to put it to you. It is you who must go.\rdblquote  \par
\tab No pause at all here. Black said, in the flattest possible way, \ldblquote Lady, I\rquote m not volunteering.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote There are not a dozen men on Hyper Base with sufficient knowledge to have any chance at all of carrying this thing through successfully. Of those who have the knowledge, I\rquote ve selected you on the basis of our previous acquaintanceship. You will bring to this task an understanding--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Look, I\rquote m \i not \i0 volunteering.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You have no choice. Surely you will face your responsibility?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote\i My \i0 responsibility? What makes it mine?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The fact that you are best fitted for the job.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you know the risk?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I think I do,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin. \par
\tab\ldblquote I know you don\rquote t. You never saw that chimpanzee. Look, when I said \lquote idiot and ship\rquote  I wasn\rquote t expressing an opinion. I was telling you a fact. I\rquote d risk my life if I had to. Not with pleasure, maybe, but I\rquote d risk it. Risking idiocy, a lifetime of animal mindlessness, is something I won\rquote t risk, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin glanced thoughtfully at the young engineer\rquote s sweating, angry face. \par
\tab Black shouted, \ldblquote Send one of your robots, one of your NS-2 jobs.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The psychologist\rquote s eye reflected a kind of cold glitter. She said with deliberation, \ldblquote Yes, Dr. Schloss suggested that. But the NS-2 robots are leased by our firm, not sold. They cost millions of dollars apiece, you know. I represent the company and I have decided that they are too expensive to be risked in a matter such as this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black lifted his hands. They clenched and trembled close to his chest as though he were forcibly restraining them. \ldblquote You\rquote re telling me--you\rquote re saying you want me to go instead of a robot because I\rquote m more expendable.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It comes to that, yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Dr. Calvin,\rdblquote  said Black, \ldblquote I\rquote d see you in hell first.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That statement might be almost literally true, Dr. Black. As General Kallner will confirm, you are ordered to take this assignment. You are under quasi-military law here, I understand, and if you refuse an assignment, you can be court-martialed. A case like this will mean Mercury prison and I believe that will be close enough to hell to make your statement uncomfortably accurate were I to visit you, though I probably would not. On the other hand, if you agree to board the \i Parsec \i0 and carry through this job, it will mean a great deal for your career.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black glared, red-eyed, at her. \par
\tab Susan Calvin said, \ldblquote Give the man five minutes to think about this, General Kallner, and get a ship ready.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Two security guards escorted Black out of the room. \par
