\tab Gerald Black felt cold. His limbs moved as though they were not part of him. It was as though he were watching himself from some remote, safe place, watching himself board a ship and make ready to leave for It and for the \i Parsec. \par
\tab\i0 He couldn\rquote t quite believe it. He had bowed his head suddenly and said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll go.\rdblquote  \par
\tab But why? \par
\tab He had never thought of himself as the hero type. Then why? Partly, of course, there was the threat of Mercury prison. Partly it was the awful reluctance to appear a coward in the eyes of those who knew him, that deeper cowardice that was behind half the bravery in the world. \par
\tab Mostly, though, it was something else. \par
\tab Ronson of Interplanetary Press had stopped Black momentarily as he was on his way to the ship. Black looked at Ronson\rquote s Bushed face and said. \ldblquote What do you want?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Ronson babbled. \ldblquote Listen! When you get back, I want it exclusive. I\rquote ll arrange any payment you want--anything you want--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black pushed him aside, sent him sprawling, and walked on. \par
\tab The ship had a crew of two. Neither spoke to him. Their glances slid over and under and around him. Black didn\rquote t mind that. They were scared spitless themselves and their ship was approaching the \i Parsec \i0 like a kitten skittering sideways toward the first dog it had ever seen. He could do without \i them. \par
\tab\i0 There was only one face that he kept seeing. The anxious expression of General Kallner and the look of synthetic determination on Schloss\rquote s face were momentary punctures on his consciousness. They healed almost at once. It was Susan Calvin\rquote s unruffled face that he saw. Her calm expressionlessness as he boarded the ship. \par
\tab He stared into the blackness where Hyper Base had already disappeared into space--\par
\tab Susan Calvin! Doctor Susan Calvin! Robopsychologist Susan Calvin! The robot that walks like a woman! \par
\tab What were her three laws, he wondered. First Law: Thou shalt protect the robot with all thy might and all thy heart and all thy soul. Second Law: Thou shalt hold the interests of U. S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation holy provided it interfereth not with the First Law. Third Law: Thou shalt give passing consideration to a human being provided it interfereth not with the First and Second laws. \par
\tab Had she ever been young, he wondered savagely? Had she ever felt one honest emotion? \par
\tab Space! How he wanted to do something--something that would take that frozen look of nothing off her face. \par
\tab And he would! \par
\tab By the stars, he would. Let him but get out of this sane and he would see her smashed and her company with her and all the vile brood of robots with them. It was that thought that was driving him more than fear of prison or desire for social prestige. It was that thought that almost robbed him of fear altogether. Almost. \par
\tab One of the pilots muttered at him, without looking, \ldblquote You can drop down from here. It\rquote s half a mile under.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black said bitterly, \ldblquote Aren\rquote t you landing?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Strict orders not to. The vibration of the landing might--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What about the vibration of my landing?\rdblquote  The pilot said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve got my orders.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black said no more but climbed into his suit and waited for the inner lock to open. A tool kit was welded firmly to the metal of the suit about his right thigh. \par
\tab Just as he stepped into the lock, the earpieces inside his helmet rumbled at him. \ldblquote Wish you luck, doctor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab It took a moment for him to realize that it came from the two men aboard ship, pausing in their eagerness to get out of that haunted volume of space to give him that much, anyway. \par
\tab\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Black awkwardly, half resentfully. \par
\tab And then he was out in space, tumbling slowly as the result of the slightly off-center thrust of feet against outer lock. \par
\tab He could see the \i Parsec \i0 waiting for him, and by looking between his legs at the right moment of the tumble he could see the long hiss of the lateral jets of the ship that had brought him, as it turned to leave. \par
\tab He was alone! Space, he was alone! \par
\tab Could any man in history ever have felt so alone? \par
\tab Would he know, he wondered sickly, if--if anything happened? Would there be any moments of realization? Would he feel his mind fade and the light of reason and thought dim and blank out? \par
\tab Or would it happen suddenly, like the cut of a force knife? In either case\par
\tab The thought of the chimpanzee, blank-eyed, shivering with mindless terrors, was fresh within him. \par
\par
\tab The asteroid was twenty feet below him now. It swam through space with an absolutely even motion. Barring human agency, no grain of sand upon it had as much as stirred through astronomical periods of time. \par
\tab In the ultimate jarlessness of It, some small particle of grit encumbered a delicate working unit on board the \i Parsec, \i0 or a speck of impure sludge in the fine oil that bathed some moving part had stopped it. \par
\tab Perhaps it required only a small vibration, a tiny tremor originating from the collision of mass and mass to unencumber that moving part, bringing it down along its appointed path, creating the hyperfield, blossoming it outward like an incredibly ripening rose. \par
\tab His body was going to touch It and he drew his limbs together in his anxiety to \ldblquote hit easy.\rdblquote  He did not want to touch the asteroid. His skin crawled with intense aversion. \par
\tab It came closer. Now--now--\par
\par
\tab Nothing! \par
\tab There was only the continuing touch of the asteroid, the uncanny moments of slowly mounting pressure that resulted from a mass of 250 pounds (himself plus suit) possessing full inertia but no weight to speak of. \par
\tab Black opened his eyes slowly and let the sight of stars enter. The sun was a glowing marble, its brilliance muted by the polarizing shield over his faceplate. The stars were correspondingly feeble but they made up the familiar arrangement. With sun and constellations normal, he was still in the solar system. He could even see Hyper Base, a small, dim crescent. \par
\tab He stiffened in shock at the sudden voice in his ear. It was Schloss. \par
\tab Schloss said, \ldblquote We\rquote ve got you in view, Dr. Black. You are not alone!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black could have laughed at the phraseology, but he only said in a low, clear voice, \ldblquote Clear off. If you\rquote ll do that, you won\rquote t be distracting me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab A pause. Schloss\rquote s voice, more cajoling, \ldblquote If you care to report as you go along, it may relieve the tension.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ll get information from me when I get back. Not before.\rdblquote  He said it bitterly, and bitterly his metal-encased fingers moved to the control panel in his chest and blanked out the suit\rquote s radio. They could talk into a vacuum now. He had his own plans. If he got out of this sane, it would be \i his \i0 show. \par
\tab He got to his feet with infinite caution and stood on It. He swayed a bit as involuntary muscular motions, tricked by the almost total lack of gravity into an endless series of overbalancings, pulled him this way and that. On Hyper Base there was a pseudo-gravitic field to hold them down. Black found that a portion of his mind was sufficiently detached to remember that and appreciate it in \i absentia. \par
\tab\i0 The sun had disappeared behind a crag. The stars wheeled visibly in time to the asteroid\rquote s one-hour rotation period. \par
\tab He could see the \i Parsec \i0 from where he stood and now he moved toward it slowly, carefully--tippy-toe almost. (No vibration. No vibration. The words ran pleadingly through his mind.) \par
\tab Before he was completely aware of the distance he had crossed, he was at the ship. He was at the foot of the line of hand grips that led to the outer lock. \par
\tab There he paused. \par
\tab The ship looked quite normal. Or at least it looked normal except for the circle of steely knobs that girdled it one third of the way up, and a second circle two thirds of the way up. At the moment, they must be straining to become the source poles of the hyperfield. \par
\tab A strange desire to reach up and fondle one of them came over Black. It was one of those irrational impulses, like the momentary thought, \ldblquote What if I jumped?\rdblquote  that is almost inevitable when one stares down from a high building. \par
\tab Black took a deep breath and felt himself go clammy as he spread the fingers of both hands and then lightly, so lightly, put each hand flat against the side of the ship. \par
\par
\tab Nothing! He seized the lowest hand grip and pulled himself up, carefully. He longed to be as experienced at null-gravity manipulation as were the construction men. You had to exert enough force to overcome inertia and then stop. Continue the pull a second too long and you would overbalance, careen into the side of the ship. \par
\tab He climbed slowly, tippy-fingers, his legs and hips swaying to the right as his left arm reached upward, to the left as his right arm reached upward. \par
\tab A dozen rungs, and his fingers hovered over the contact that would open the outer lock. The safety marker was a tiny green smear. \par
\tab Once again he hesitated. This was the first use he would make of the ship\rquote s power. His mind ran over the wiring diagrams and the force distributions. If he pressed the contact, power would be siphoned off the micropile to pull open the massive slab of metal that was the outer lock. \par
\tab Well? What was the use? Unless he had some idea as to what was wrong, there was no way of telling the effect of the power diversion. He sighed and touched contact. \par
\tab Smoothly, with neither jar nor sound, a segment of the ship curled open. Black took one more look at the friendly constellations (they had not changed) and stepped into the softly illuminated cavity. The outer lock closed behind him. \par
\tab Another contact now. The inner lock had to be opened. Again he paused to consider. Air pressure within the ship would drop ever so slightly as the inner lock opened, and seconds would pass before the ship\rquote s electrolyzers could make up the loss. \par
\tab Well? The Bosch posterior-plate, to name one item, was sensitive to pressure, but surely not \i this \i0 sensitive. \par
\tab He sighed again, more softly (the skin of his fear was growing calloused) and touched the contact. The inner lock opened. \par
\tab He stepped into the pilot room of the \i Parsec, \i0 and his heart jumped oddly when the first thing he saw was the visiplate, set for reception and powdered with stars. He forced himself to look at them. \par
\par
\tab Nothing! \par
\tab Cassiopeia was visible. The constellations were normal and he was inside the \i Parsec. \i0 Somehow he could feel the worst was over. Having come so far and remained within the solar system, having kept his mind so far, he felt something that was faintly like confidence begin to seep back. \par
\tab There was an almost supernatural stillness about the \i Parsec. \i0 Black had been in many ships in his life and there had always been the sounds of life, even if only the scuffing of a shoe or a cabin boy humming in the corridor. Here the very beating of his own heart seemed muffled to soundlessness. \par
\tab The robot in the pilot\rquote s seat had its back to him. It indicated by no response that it was aware of his having entered. \par
\tab Black bared his teeth in a savage grin and said sharply, \ldblquote Release the bar! Stand up!\rdblquote  The sound of his voice was thunderous in the close quarters. \par
\tab Too late he dreaded the air vibrations his voice set up, but the stars on the visiplate remained unchanged. \par
\tab The robot, of course, did not stir. It could receive no sensations of any sort. It could not even respond to the First Law. It was frozen in the unending middle of what should have been almost instantaneous process. \par
\tab He remembered the orders it had been given. They were open to no misunderstanding: \ldblquote Seize the bar with a firm grip. Pull it toward you firmly. Firmly! Maintain your hold until the control board informs you that you have passed through hyperspace twice.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Well, it had not yet passed through hyperspace once. Carefully, he moved closer to the robot. It sat there with the bar pulled firmly back between its knees. That brought the trigger mechanism almost into place. The temperature of his metal hands then curled that trigger, thermocouple fashion, just sufficiently for contact to be made. Automatically Black glanced at the thermometer reading set into the control board. The robot\rquote s hands were at 37 Centigrade, as they should be. \par
\tab He thought sardonically, Fine thing. I\rquote m alone with this machine and I can\rquote t do anything about it. \par
\tab What he would have liked to do was take a crowbar to it and smash it to filings. He enjoyed the flavor of that thought. He could see the horror on Susan Calvin\rquote s face (if any horror could creep through the ice, the horror of a smashed robot was it). Like all positronic robots, this one-shot was owned by U. S. Robots, had been made there, had been tested there. \par
\tab And having extracted what juice he could out of imaginary revenge, he sobered and looked about the ship. \par
\tab After all, progress so far had been zero. \par
\par
\tab Slowly, he removed his suit. Gently, he laid it on the rack. Gingerly, he walked from room to room, studying the large interlocking surfaces of the hyperatomic motor, following the cables, inspecting the field relays. \par
\tab He touched nothing. There were a dozen ways of deactivating the hyperfield, but each one would be ruinous unless he knew at least approximately where the error lay and let his exact course of procedure be guided by that. \par
\tab He found himself back at the control panel and cried in exasperation at the grave stolidity of the robot\rquote s broad back, \ldblquote Tell me, will you? What\rquote s wrong?\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was the urge to attack the ship\rquote s machinery at random. Tear at it and get it over with. He repressed the impulse firmly. If it took him a week, he would deduce, somehow, the proper point of attack. He owed that much to Dr. Susan Calvin and his plans for her. \par
\tab He turned slowly on his heel and considered. Every part of the ship, from the engine itself to each individual two-way toggle switch. had been exhaustively checked and tested on Hyper Base. It was almost impossible to believe that anything could go wrong. There wasn\rquote t a thing on board ship\par
\tab Well, yes, there was, of course. The robot! That had been tested at U. S. Robots and they, blast their devils\rquote  hides, could be assumed to be competent. \par
\tab What was it everyone always said: A robot can just naturally do a better job. \par
\tab It was the normal assumption, based in part on U. S. Robots\rquote  own advertising campaigns. They could make a robot that would be better than a man for a given purpose. Not \ldblquote as good as a man.\rdblquote  but \ldblquote better than a man.\rdblquote  \par
\tab And as Gerald Black stared at the robot and thought that, his brows contracted under his low forehead and his look became compounded of astonishment and a wild hope. \par
\tab He approached and circled the robot. He stared at its arms holding the control bar in trigger position, holding it forever so, unless the ship jumped or the robot\rquote s own power supply gave out. \par
\tab Black breathed. \ldblquote I bet. I \i bet.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0 He stepped away, considered deeply, He said. \ldblquote It\rquote s \i got \i0 to be.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He turned on ship\rquote s radio. Its carrier beam was already focused on Hyper Base. He barked into the mouthpiece. \ldblquote Hey, Schloss.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Schloss was prompt in his answer. \ldblquote Great Space. Black--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind,\rdblquote  said Black crisply. \ldblquote No speeches. I just want to make sure you\rquote re watching.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, of course. We all are. Look--\rdblquote  \par
\tab But Black turned off the radio. He grinned with tight one-sidedness at the TV camera inside the pilot room and chose a portion of the hyperfield mechanism that would be in view. He didn\rquote t know how many people would be in the viewing room. There might be only Kallner, Schloss and Susan Calvin. There might be all personnel. In any case, he would give them something to watch. \par
\tab Relay Box # 3 was adequate for the purpose, he decided. It was located in a wall recess, coated over with a smooth cold-seamed panel. Black reached into his tool kit and removed the splayed, blunt-edged seamer. He pushed his space suit farther back on the rack (having turned it to bring the tool kit in reach) and turned to the relay box. \par
\tab Ignoring a last tingle of uneasiness, Black brought up the seamer, made contact at three separated points along the cold seam. The tool\rquote s force field worked deftly and quickly, the handle growing a trifle warm in his hand as the surge of energy came and left. The panel swung free. \par
\tab He glanced quickly, almost involuntarily, at the ship\rquote s visiplate. The stars were normal. He, himself, felt normal. \par
\tab That was the last bit of encouragement he needed. He raised his foot and smashed his shoe down on the feather-delicate mechanism within the recess. \par
\tab There was a splinter of glass, a twisting of metal, and a tiny spray of mercury droplets\par
\tab Black breathed heavily. He turned on the radio once more. \ldblquote Still there, Schloss?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, but--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then I report the hyperfield on board the \i Parsec \i0 to be deactivated. Come and get me.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Gerald Black felt no more the hero than when he had left for the \i Parsec, \i0 but he found himself one just the same. The men who had brought him to the small asteroid came to take him off. They landed this time. They clapped his back. \par
\tab Hyper Base was a crowded mass of waiting personnel when the ship arrived, and Black was cheered. He waved at the throng and grinned, as was a hero\rquote s obligation, but he felt no triumph inside. Not yet. Only anticipation. Triumph would come later, when he met Susan Calvin. \par
\tab He paused before descending from the ship. He looked for her and did not see her. General Kallner was there, waiting, with all his soldierly stiffness restored and a bluff look of approval firmly plastered on his face. Mayer Schloss smiled nervously at him. Ronson of Interplanetary Press waved frantically. Susan Calvin was nowhere. \par
\tab He brushed Kallner and Schloss aside when he landed. \ldblquote I\rquote m going to wash and eat first.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He had no doubts but that, for the moment at least, he could dictate terms to the general or to anybody. \par
\tab The security guards made a way for him. He bathed and ate leisurely in enforced isolation, he himself being solely responsible for the enforcement. Then he called Ronson of Interplanetary and talked to him briefly. He waited for the return call before he felt he could relax thoroughly. It had all worked out so much better than he had expected. The very failure of the ship had conspired perfectly with him. \par
\tab Finally he called the general\rquote s office and ordered a conference. It was what it amounted to--orders. Major-general Kallner all but said, \ldblquote Yes, Sir.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab They were together again. Gerald Black, Kallner, Schloss--even Susan Calvin. But it was Black who was dominant now. The robopsychologist, graven-faced as ever, as unimpressed by triumph as by disaster, had nevertheless seemed by some subtle change of attitude to have relinquished the spotlight. \par
\tab Dr. Schloss nibbled a thumbnail and began by saying, cautiously, \ldblquote Dr. Black, we are all very grateful for your bravery and success.\rdblquote  Then, as though to institute a healthy deflation at once, he added, \ldblquote Still, smashing the relay box with your heel was imprudent and--well, it was an action that scarcely deserved success.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black said, \ldblquote It was an action that could scarcely have avoided success. You see\rdblquote  (this was bomb number one) \ldblquote by that time I knew what had gone wrong.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Schloss rose to his feet. \ldblquote You did? Are you sure?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Go there yourself. It\rquote s safe now. I\rquote ll tell you what to look for.\rdblquote  Schloss sat down again, slowly. General Kallner was enthusiastic. \ldblquote Why, this is the best yet, if true.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s true,\rdblquote  said Black. His eyes slid to Susan Calvin, who said nothing. \par
\tab Black was enjoying the sensation of power. He released bomb number two by saying, \ldblquote It was the robot, of course. Did you hear that, Dr. Calvin?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin spoke for the first time. \ldblquote I hear it. I rather expected it, as a matter of fact. It was the only piece of equipment on board ship that had not been tested at Hyper Base.\rdblquote  \par
\tab For a moment Black felt dashed. He said, \ldblquote You said nothing of that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Dr. Calvin said, \ldblquote As Dr. Schloss said several times, I am not an etherics expert. My guess, and it was no more than that, might easily have been wrong. I felt I had no right to prejudice you in advance of your mission.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black said, \ldblquote All right, did you happen to guess \i how \i0 it went wrong?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why, it was made better than a man. That\rquote s what the trouble was. Isn\rquote t it strange that the trouble should rest with the very specialty of U. S. Robots? They make robots better than men, I understand.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He was slashing at her with words now but she did not rise to his bait. \par
\tab Instead, she sighed. \ldblquote My dear Dr. Black. I am not responsible for the slogans of our sales-promotion department.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black felt dashed again. She wasn\rquote t an easy woman to handle, this Calvin. He said, \ldblquote Your people built a robot to replace a man at the controls of the \i Parsec. \i0 He had to pull the control bar toward himself, place it in position and let the heat of his hands twist the trigger to make final contact. Simple enough, Dr. Calvin?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Simple enough, Dr. Black.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote  And if the robot had been made no better than a man, he would have succeeded. Unfortunately, U. S. Robots felt compelled to make it better than a man. The robot was told to pull back the control bar firmly. \i Firmly. \i0 The word was repeated, strengthened, emphasized. So the robot did what it was told. It pulled it back firmly. There was only one trouble. He was easily ten times stronger than the ordinary human being for whom the control bar was designed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote  Are you implying--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m \i saying \i0 the bar bent. It bent back just enough to misplace the trigger. When the heat of the robot\rquote s hand twisted the thermocouple\rquote  it did \i not \i0 make contact.\rdblquote  He grinned. \ldblquote This isn\rquote t the failure of just one robot, Dr. Calvin. It\rquote s symbolic of the failure of the robot idea.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Come now, Dr. Black,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin icily, \ldblquote you\rquote re drowning logic in missionary psychology. The robot was equipped with adequate understanding as well as with brute force. Had the men who gave it its orders used quantitative terms rather than the foolish adverb \lquote firmly,\rquote  this would not have happened. Had they said, \lquote apply a pull of fifty-five pounds,\rquote  all would have been well.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What you are saying,\rdblquote  said Black, \ldblquote is that the inadequacy of a robot must be made up for by the ingenuity and intelligence of a man. I assure you that the people back on Earth will look at it in that way and will not be in the mood to excuse U. S. Robots for this fiasco.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Major-general Kallner said quickly, with a return of authority to his voice, \ldblquote Now wait, Black, all that has happened is obviously classified information.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In fact,\rdblquote  said Schloss suddenly, \ldblquote your theory hasn\rquote t been checked yet. We\rquote ll send a party to the ship and find out. It may not be the robot at all.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ll take care to make that discovery, will you? I wonder if the people will believe an interested party. Besides which, I have one more thing to tell you.\rdblquote  He readied bomb number three and said, \ldblquote As of this moment, I\rquote m resigning from this man\rquote s project. I\rquote m quitting.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  asked Susan Calvin. \par
\tab\ldblquote Because, as you said, Dr. Calvin, I am a missionary,\rdblquote  said Black, smiling. \ldblquote I have a mission. I feel I owe it to the people of Earth to tell them that the age of the robots has reached the point where human life is valued less than robot life. It is now possible to order a man into danger because a robot is too precious to risk. I believe Earthmen should hear that. Many men have many reservations about robots as is. U. S. Robots has not yet succeeded in making it legally permissible to use robots on the planet Earth itself. I believe what I have to say, Dr. Calvin, will complete the matter. For this day\rquote s work, Dr. Calvin, you and your company and your robots will be wiped off the face of the solar system.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He was forewarning her, Black knew; he was forearming her, but he could not forego this scene. He had lived for this very moment ever since he had first left for the \i Parsec, \i0 and he could not give it up. \par
\tab He all but gloated at the momentary glitter in Susan Calvin\rquote s pale eyes and at the faintest flush in her cheeks. He thought, How do you feel now, madam scientist? \par
\tab Kallner said, \ldblquote You will not be permitted to resign, Black, nor will you be permitted--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How can you stop me, general? I\rquote m a hero, haven\rquote t you heard? And old Mother Earth \i will \i0 make much of its heroes. It always has. They\rquote ll want to hear from me and they\rquote ll believe anything I say. And they won\rquote t like it if I\rquote m interfered with, at least not while I\rquote m a fresh, brand-new hero. I\rquote ve already talked to Ronson of Interplanetary Press and told him I had something big for them, something that would rock every government official and science director right out of the chair plush, so Interplanetary will be first in line, waiting to hear from me. So what can you do except to have me shot? And I think you\rquote d be worse off after that if you tried it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black\rquote s revenge was complete. He had spared no word. He had hampered himself not in the least. He rose to go. \par
\par
\tab\ldblquote One moment, Dr. Black,\rdblquote  said Susan Calvin. Her low voice carried authority. \par
\tab Black turned involuntarily, like a schoolboy at his teacher\rquote s voice, but he counteracted that gesture by a deliberately mocking, \ldblquote You have an explanation to make, I suppose?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  she said primly. \ldblquote You have explained for me, and quite well. I chose you because I knew you would understand, though I thought you would understand sooner. I had had contact with you before. I knew you disliked robots and would, therefore, be under no illusions concerning them. From your records, which I asked to see before you were given your assignment, I saw that you had expressed disapproval of this robot-through-hyperspace experiment. Your superiors held that against you, but I thought it a point in your favor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What are you talking about, doctor, if you\rquote ll excuse my rudeness?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The fact that you should have understood why no robot could have been sent on this mission. What was it you yourself said? Something about a robot\rquote s inadequacies having to be balanced by the ingenuity and intelligence of a man. Exactly so, young man, exactly so. Robots have no ingenuity. Their minds are finite and can be calculated to the last decimal. That, in fact, is my job. \par
\tab\ldblquote Now if a robot is given an order, a \i precise \i0 order, he can follow it. If the order is not precise, he cannot correct his own mistake without further orders. Isn\rquote t that what you reported concerning the robot on the ship? How then can we send a robot to find a flaw in a mechanism when we cannot possibly give precise orders, since we know nothing about the flaw ourselves? \lquote Find out what\rquote s wrong\rquote  is not an order you can give to a robot; only to a man. The human brain, so far at least, is beyond calculation.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Black sat down abruptly and stared at the psychologist in dismay. Her words struck sharply on a substratum of understanding that had been larded over with emotion. He found himself unable to refute her. Worse than that, a feeling of defeat encompassed him. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote You might have said this before I left.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I might have,\rdblquote  agreed Dr. Calvin, \ldblquote but I noticed your very natural fear for your sanity. Such an overwhelming concern would easily have hampered your efficiency as an investigator, and it occurred to me to let you think that my only motive in sending you was that I valued a robot more. That, I thought, would make you angry, and anger, my dear Dr. Black, is sometimes a very useful emotion. At least, an angry man is never quite as afraid as he would be otherwise. It worked out nicely, I think.\rdblquote  She folded her hands loosely in her lap and came as near a smile as she ever had in her life. \par
\tab Black said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll be damned.\rdblquote  Susan Calvin said, \ldblquote So now, if you\rquote ll take my advice, return to your job, accept your status as hero, and tell your reporter friend the details of your brave deed. Let that be the big news you promised him.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Slowly, reluctantly, Black nodded. \par
\tab Schloss looked relieved; Kallner burst into a toothy smile. They held out hands, not having said a word in all the time that Susan Calvin had spoken, and not saying a word now. \par
\tab Black took their hands and shook them with some reserve. He said, \ldblquote It\rquote s your part that should be publicized, Dr. Calvin.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Susan Calvin said icily, \ldblquote Don\rquote t be a fool, young man. This is my job.\rdblquote\par
