\scaps When Susan Calvin returned from hyper base\scaps0 , Alfred Tanning was waiting for her. The old man never spoke about his age, but everyone knew it to be over seventy-five. Yet his mind was keen, and if he had finally allowed himself to be made Director-Emeritus of Research with Bogert as acting Director, it did not prevent him from appearing in his office daily.\par
\tab\ldblquote How close are they to the Hyperatomic Drive?\rdblquote  he asked.\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  she replied irritably, \ldblquote I didn\rquote t ask.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hmm. I wish they\rquote d hurry. Because if they don\rquote t, Consolidated might beat them to it, and beat \i us\i0  to it as well.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote\i Consolidated\i0 . What have they got to do with it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, we\rquote re not the only ones with calculating machines. Ours may be positronic, but that doesn\rquote t mean they\rquote re better. Robertson is calling a big meeting about it tomorrow. He\rquote s been waiting for you to come back.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Robertson of U. S. Robot & Mechanical Men Corporation, son of the founder, pointed his lean nose at his general manager and his Adam\rquote s apple jumped as he said, \ldblquote You start now. Let\rquote s get this straight.\rdblquote\par
\tab The general manager did so with alacrity, \ldblquote Here\rquote s the deal now, chief. Consolidated Robots approached us a month ago with a funny sort of proposition. They brought about five tons of figures, equations, all that sort of stuff. It was a problem, see, and they wanted an answer from The Brain. The terms were as follows-\rdblquote\par
\tab He ticked them off on thick fingers: \ldblquote A hundred thousand for us if there is no solution and we can tell them the missing factors. Two hundred thousand if there is a solution, plus costs of construction of the machine involved, plus quarter interest in all profits derived therefrom. The problem concerns the development of an interstellar engine-\rdblquote\par
\tab Robertson frowned and his lean figure stiffened, \ldblquote Despite the fact that they have a thinking machine of their own. Right?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly what makes the whole proposition a foul ball, chief? Levver, take it from there.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abe Levver looked up from the far end of the conference table and smoothed his stubbled chin with a faint rasping sound. He smiled:\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s this way, sir. Consolidated \i had\i0  a thinking machine. It\rquote s broken.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  Robertson half rose.\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right. Broken! It\rquote s \i kaput\i0 . Nobody knows why, but I got hold of some pretty interesting guesses -- like, for instance, that they asked it to give them an interstellar engine with the same set of information they came to us with, and that it cracked their machine wide open. It\rquote s scrap -- just scrap now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You get it, chief?\rdblquote  The general manager was wildly jubilant. \ldblquote You get it? There isn\rquote t any industrial research group of any size that isn\rquote t trying to develop a space-warp engine, and Consolidated and U. S. Robots have the lead on the field with our super robot-brains. Now that they\rquote ve managed to foul theirs up, we have a clear field. That\rquote s the nub, the... uh... motivation. It will take them six years at least to build another and they\rquote re sunk, unless they can break ours, too, with the same problem.\rdblquote\par
\tab The president of U. S. Robots bulged his eyes, \ldblquote Why, the dirty rats-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hold on, chief. There\rquote s more to this.\rdblquote  He pointed a finger with a wide sweep, \ldblquote Lanning, take it!\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Alfred Lanning viewed the proceedings with faint scorn -- his usual reaction to the doings of the vastly better-paid business and sales divisions. His unbelievable gray eyebrows hunched low and his voice was dry:\par
\tab\ldblquote From a scientific standpoint the situation, while not entirely clear, is subject to intelligent analysis. The question of interstellar travel under present conditions of physical theory is... uh... vague. The matter is wide open -- and the information given by Consolidated to its thinking machine, assuming these we have to be the same, was similarly wide open. Our mathematical department has given it a thorough analysis, and it seems Consolidated has included everything. Its material for submission contains all known developments of Franciacci\rquote s space-warp theory, and, apparently, all pertinent astrophysical and electronic data. It\rquote s quite a mouthful.\rdblquote\par
\tab Robertson followed anxiously. He interrupted, \ldblquote Too much for The Brain to handle?\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning shook his head decisively, \ldblquote No. There are no known limits to The Brain\rquote s capacity. It\rquote s a different matter. It\rquote s a question of the Robotic Laws. The Brain, for instance, could never supply a solution to a problem set to it if that solution, would involve the death or injury of humans. As far as it would be concerned, a problem with only such a solution would be insoluble. If such a problem is combined with an extremely urgent demand that it be answered, it is just possible that The Brain, only a robot after all, would be presented with a dilemma, where it could neither answer nor refuse to answer. Something of the sort must have happened to Consolidated\rquote s machine.\rdblquote\par
\tab He paused, but the general manager urged on, \ldblquote Go ahead, Dr. Tanning. Explain it the way you explained it to me.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning set his lips and raised his eyebrows in the direction of Dr. Susan Calvin who lifted her eyes from her precisely folded hands for the first time. Her voice was low and colorless.\par
\tab\ldblquote The nature of a robot reaction to a dilemma is startling,\rdblquote  she began. \ldblquote Robot psychology is far from perfect -- as a specialist, I can assure you of that but it can be discussed in qualitative terms, because with all the complications introduced into a robot\rquote s positronic brain, it is built by humans and is therefore built according to human values.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now a human caught in an impossibility often responds by a retreat from reality: by entry into a world of delusion, or by taking to drink, going off into hysteria, or jumping off a bridge. It all comes to the same thing -- a refusal or inability to face the situation squarely. And so, the robot, a dilemma at its mildest will disorder half its relays; and at its worst it will burn out every positronic brain path past repair.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I see,\rdblquote  said Robertson, who didn\rquote t. \ldblquote Now what about this information Consolidated\rquote s wishing on us?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It undoubtedly involves,\rdblquote  said Dr. Calvin, \ldblquote a problem of a forbidden sort. But The Brain is considerably different from Consolidated\rquote s robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right, chief. That\rquote s right.\rdblquote  The general manager was energetically interruptive. \ldblquote I want you to get this, because it\rquote s the whole point of the situation.\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin\rquote s eyes glittered behind the spectacles, and she continued patiently, \ldblquote You see, sir, Consolidated\rquote s machines, their Super-Thinker among them, are built without personality. They go in for functionalism, you know -- they have to, without U. S. Robot\rquote s basic patents for the emotional brain paths. Their Thinker is merely a calculating machine on a grand scale, and a dilemma ruins it instantly.\par
\tab\ldblquote However, The Brain, our own machine, has a personality -- a child\rquote s personality. It is a supremely deductive brain, but it resembles an \i idiot savant\i0 . It doesn\rquote t really understand what it does -- it just does it. And because it is really a child, it is more resilient. Life isn\rquote t so serious, you might say.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robopsychologist continued: \ldblquote Here is what we\rquote re going to do. We have divided all of Consolidated\rquote s information into logical units. We are going to feed the units to The Brain singly and cautiously. When \i the\i0  factor enters -- the one that creates the dilemma -- The Brain\rquote s child personality will hesitate. Its sense of judgment is not mature. There will be a perceptible interval before it will recognize a dilemma as such. And in that interval, it will reject the unit automatically -- before its brainpaths can be set in motion and ruined.\rdblquote\par
\tab Robertson\rquote s Adam\rquote s apple squirmed, \ldblquote Are you sure, now?\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Calvin masked impatience, \ldblquote It doesn\rquote t make much sense, I admit, in lay language; but there is no conceivable use in presenting the mathematics of this. I assure you, it is as I say.\rdblquote\par
\tab The general manager was in the breach instantly and fluently, \ldblquote So here\rquote s the situation, chief. If we take the deal, we can put it through like this. The Brain will tell us which unit of information involves the dilemma. From there, we can figure \i why\i0  the dilemma. Isn\rquote t that right, Dr. Bogert? There you are, chief, and Dr. Bogert is the best mathematician you\rquote ll find anywhere. We give Consolidated a \lquote No Solution\rquote  answer, with the reason, and collect a hundred thousand. They\rquote re left with a broken machine; we\rquote re left with a whole one. In a year, two maybe, we\rquote ll have a space-warp engine or a hyper-atomic motor some people call it. Whatever you name it, it will be the biggest thing in the world.\rdblquote\par
\tab Robertson chuckled and reached out, \ldblquote Let\rquote s see the contract. I\rquote ll sign it.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab When Susan Calvin entered the fantastically guarded vault that held The Brain, one of the current shift of technicians had just asked it: \ldblquote If one and a half chickens lay one and a half eggs in one and a half days, how many eggs will nine chickens lay in nine days?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Brain had just answered, \ldblquote Fifty-four.\rdblquote\par
\tab And the technician had just said to another, \ldblquote See, you dope!\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Calvin coughed and there was a sudden impossible flurry of directionless energy. The psychologist motioned briefly, and she was alone with The Brain.\par
\tab The Brain was a two-foot globe merely -- one which contained within it a thoroughly conditioned helium atmosphere, a volume of space completely vibration-absent and radiation-free -- and within that was that unheard-of complexity of positronic brain-paths that was The Brain. The rest of the room was crowded with the attachments that were the intermediaries between The Brain and the outside world -- its voice, its arms, its sense organs.\par
\tab Dr. Calvin said softly, \ldblquote How are you, Brain?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Brain\rquote s voice was high-pitched and enthusiastic, \ldblquote Swell, Miss Susan. You\rquote re going to ask me something. I can tell. You always have a book in your hand when you\rquote re going to ask me something.\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Calvin smiled mildly, \ldblquote Well, you\rquote re right, but not just yet. This is going to be a question. It will be so complicated we\rquote re going to give it to you in writing. But not just yet; I think I\rquote ll talk to you first.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. I don\rquote t mind talking.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Now, Brain, in a little while, Dr. Lanning and Dr. Bogert will be here with this complicated question. We\rquote ll give it to you a very little at a time and very slowly, because we want you to be careful. We\rquote re going to ask you to build something, if you can, out of the information, but I\rquote m going to warn you now that the solution might involve... uh... damage to human beings.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Gosh!\rdblquote  The exclamation was hushed, drawn-out.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now you watch for that. When we come to a sheet which means damage, even maybe death, don\rquote t get excited. You see, Brain, in this case, we don\rquote t mind -- not even about death; we don\rquote t mind at all. So when you come to that sheet, just stop, give it back -- and that\rquote ll be all. You understand?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, sure. By golly, the death of humans! Oh, my!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Now, Brain, I hear Dr. Lanning and Dr. Bogert coming. They\rquote ll tell you what the problem is all about and then we\rquote ll start. Be a good boy, now-\rdblquote\par
\tab Slowly the sheets were fed in. After each one came the interval of the queerly whispery chuckling noise that was The Brain in action. Then the silence that meant readiness for another sheet. It was a matter of hours -- during which the equivalent of something like seventeen fat volumes of mathematical physics were fed into The Brain.\par
\tab As the process went on, frowns appeared and deepened. Lanning muttered ferociously under his breath. Bogert first gazed speculatively at his fingernails, and then bit at them in abstracted fashion. It was when the last of the thick pile of sheets disappeared that Calvin, white-faced, said:\par
\tab\ldblquote Something\rquote s wrong.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning barely got the words out, \ldblquote It can\rquote t be. Is it -- dead?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Brain?\rdblquote  Susan Calvin was trembling. \ldblquote Do you hear me, Brain?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Huh?\rdblquote  came the abstracted rejoinder. \ldblquote Do you want me?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The solution-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, that! I can do it. I\rquote ll build you a whole ship, just as easy -- if you let me have the robots. A nice ship, it\rquote ll take two months maybe.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There was -- no difficulty?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It took long to figure,\rdblquote  said The Brain.\par
\tab Dr. Calvin backed away. The color had not returned to her thin cheeks. She motioned the others away.\par
\par
\tab In her office, she said, \ldblquote I can\rquote t understand it. The information, as given, must involve a dilemma -- probably involves death. If something has gone wrong-\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert said quietly, \ldblquote The machine talks and makes sense. It can\rquote t be a dilemma.\rdblquote\par
\tab But the psychologist replied urgently, \ldblquote There are dilemmas \i and\i0  dilemmas. There are different forms of escape. Suppose The Brain is only mildly caught; just badly enough, say, to be suffering from the delusion that he can solve the problem, when he can\rquote t. Or suppose it\rquote s teetering on the brink of something really bad, so that any small push shoves it over.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose,\rdblquote  said Lanning, \ldblquote there is no dilemma. Suppose Consolidated\rquote s machine broke down over a different question, or broke down for purely mechanical reasons.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But even so,\rdblquote  insisted Calvin, \ldblquote we couldn\rquote t take chances. Listen, from now on, no one is to as much as breathe to The Brain. I\rquote m taking over.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  sighed Lanning, \ldblquote take over, then. And meanwhile we\rquote ll let The Brain build its ship. And if it \i does\i0  build it, we\rquote ll have to test it.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was ruminating, \ldblquote We\rquote ll need our top field men for \i that\i0 .\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Michael Donovan brushed down his red hair with a violent motion of his hand and a total indifference to the fact that the unruly mass sprang to attention again immediately.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Call the turn now, Greg. They say the ship is finished. They don\rquote t know what it is, but it\rquote s finished. Let\rquote s go, Greg. Let\rquote s grab the controls right now.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell said wearily, \ldblquote Cut it, Mike. There\rquote s a peculiar overripe flavor to your humor at its freshest, and the confined atmosphere here isn\rquote t helping it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, listen,\rdblquote  Donovan took another ineffectual swipe at his hair, \ldblquote I\rquote m not worried so much about our cast-iron genius and his tin ship. There\rquote s the matter of my lost leave. And the monotony! There\rquote s nothing here but whiskers and figures -- the wrong kind of figures. Oh, why do they \i give\i0  us these jobs?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because,\rdblquote  replied Powell, gently, \ldblquote we\rquote re no loss, if they lose us. O.K., relax! -- Doc Lanning\rquote s coming this way.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning was coming, his gray eyebrows as lavish as ever, his aged figure unbent as yet and full of life. He walked silently up the ramp with the two men and out into the open field, where, obeying no human master, silent robots were building a ship.\par
\tab Wrong tense. \i Had\i0  built a ship!\par
\tab For Lanning said, \ldblquote The robots have stopped. Not one has moved today.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s completed then? Definitely?\rdblquote  asked Powell.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now how can I tell?\rdblquote  Lanning was peevish, and his eyebrows curled down in an eye-hiding frown. \ldblquote It \i seems\i0  done. There are no spare pieces about, and the interior is down to a gleaming finish.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ve been inside?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Just in, then out. I\rquote m no space-pilot. Either of you two know much about engine theory?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan looked at Powell, who looked at Donovan.\par
\tab Donovan said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve got my license, sir, but at last reading it didn\rquote t say anything about hyper-engines or warp-navigation. Just the usual child\rquote s play in three dimensions.\rdblquote\par
\tab Alfred Lanning looked up with sharp disapproval and snorted the length of his prominent nose.\par
\tab He said frigidly, \ldblquote Well, we have our engine men.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell caught at his elbow as he walked away, \ldblquote Sir, is the ship still restricted ground?\rdblquote\par
\tab The old director hesitated, then rubbed the bridge of his nose, \ldblquote I suppose not. For you two anyway.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan looked after him as he left and muttered a short, expressive phrase at his back. He turned to Powell, \ldblquote I\rquote d like to give him a literary description of himself, Greg.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose you come along, Mike.\rdblquote\par
\tab The inside of the ship was finished, as finished as a ship ever was; that could be told in a single eye-blinking glance. No martinet in the system could have put as much spit-and-polish into a surface as those robots had. The walls were of a gleaming silvery finish that retained no fingerprints.\par
\tab There were no angles; walls, floors, and ceiling faded gently into each other and in the cold, metallic glittering of the hidden lights, one was surrounded by six chilly reflections of one\rquote s bewildered self.\par
\tab The main corridor was a narrow tunnel that led in a hard, clatter-footed stretch along a line of rooms of no interdistinguishing features.\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote I suppose furniture is built into the wall. Or maybe we\rquote re not supposed to sit or sleep.\rdblquote\par
\tab It was in the last room, the one nearest the nose, that the monotony broke. A curving window of non-reflecting glass was the first break in the universal metal, and below it was a single large dial, with a single motionless needle hard against the zero mark.\par
\tab Donovan said, \ldblquote Look at that!\rdblquote  and pointed to the single word on the finely-marked scale.\par
\tab It said, \ldblquote Parsecs\rdblquote  and the tiny figure at the right end of the curving, graduated meter said \ldblquote 1,000,000.\rdblquote\par
\tab There were two chairs; heavy, wide-flaring, uncushioned. Powell seated himself gingerly, and found it molded to the body\rquote s curves, and comfortable.\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote What do you think of it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For my money, The Brain has brain-fever. Let\rquote s get out.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure you don\rquote t want to look it over a bit?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I have looked it over. I came, I saw, I\rquote m through!\rdblquote  Donovan\rquote s red hair bristled into separate wires, \ldblquote Greg, let\rquote s get out of here. I quit my job five seconds ago, and this is a restricted area for non-personnel.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell smiled in an oily self-satisfied manner and smoothed his mustache, \ldblquote O.K., Mike, turn off that adrenalin tap you\rquote ve got draining into your bloodstream. I was worried, too, but no more.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No more, huh? How come, no more? Increased your insurance?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Mike, this ship can\rquote t fly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How do you know?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, we\rquote ve been through the entire ship, haven\rquote t we?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Seems so.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Take my word for it, we have. Did you see any pilot room except for this one port and the one gauge here in parsecs? Did you see any controls?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And did you see any engines?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Holy Joe, no!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, then! Let\rquote s break the news to Lanning, Mike.\rdblquote\par
\tab They cursed their way through the featureless corridors and finally hit-and-missed their way into the short passage to the air lock.\par
\tab Donovan stiffened, \ldblquote Did you lock this thing, Greg?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, I never touched it. Yank the lever, will you?\rdblquote\par
\tab The lever never budged, though Donovan\rquote s face twisted appallingly with exertion.\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote I didn\rquote t see any emergency exits. If something\rquote s gone wrong here, they\rquote ll have to melt us out.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, and we\rquote ve got to wait until they find out that some fool has locked us in here,\rdblquote  added Donovan, frantically.\par
\tab\ldblquote Let\rquote s get back to the room with the port. It\rquote s the only place from which we might attract attention.\rdblquote\par
\tab But they didn\rquote t.\par
\tab In that last room, the port was no longer blue and full of sky. It was black, and hard yellow pin-point stars spelled \i space\i0 .\par
\tab There was a dull, double thud, as two bodies collapsed separately into two chairs.\par
\par
\tab Alfred Lanning met Dr. Calvin just outside his office. He lit a nervous cigar and motioned her in.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Well, Susan, we\rquote ve come pretty far, and Robertson\rquote s getting jumpy. What are you doing with The Brain?\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin spread her hands, \ldblquote It\rquote s no use getting impatient. The Brain is worth more than anything we forfeit on this deal.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But you\rquote ve been questioning it for two months.\rdblquote\par
\tab The psychologist\rquote s voice was flat, but somehow dangerous, \ldblquote You would rather run this yourself?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Now you know what I meant.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, I suppose I do,\rdblquote  Dr. Calvin rubbed her hands nervously. \ldblquote It isn\rquote t easy. I\rquote ve been pampering it and probing it gently, and I haven\rquote t gotten anywhere yet. Its\rquote  reactions aren\rquote t normal. Its answers -- they\rquote re queer, somehow. But nothing I can put my finger on yet. And you see, until we know what\rquote s wrong, we must just tiptoe our way through. I can never tell what simple question or remark will just... push him over... and then -- Well, and then we\rquote ll have on our hands a completely useless Brain. Do you want to face that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, it can\rquote t break the First Law.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I would have thought so, but-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re not even sure of that?\rdblquote  Lanning was profoundly shocked.\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, I can\rquote t be sure of anything, Alfred-\rdblquote\par
\tab The alarm system raised its fearful clangor with a horrifying suddenness. Lanning clicked on communications with an almost paralytic spasm. The breathless words froze him.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Susan... you heard that... the ship\rquote s gone. I sent those two field men inside half an hour ago. You\rquote ll have to see The Brain again.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Susan Calvin said with enforced calm, \ldblquote Brain, what happened to the ship?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Brain said happily, \ldblquote The ship I built, Miss Susan?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right. What has happened to it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why, nothing at all. The two men that were supposed to test it were inside, and we were all set. So I sent it off.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh -- Well, that\rquote s nice.\rdblquote  The psychologist felt some difficulty in breathing. \ldblquote Do you think they\rquote ll be all right?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Right as anything, Miss Susan. I\rquote ve taken care of it all. It\rquote s a bee-yootiful ship.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Brain, it \i is\i0  beautiful, but you think they have enough food, don\rquote t you? They\rquote ll be comfortable?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Plenty of food.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This business might be a shock to them, Brain. Unexpected, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Brain tossed it off, \ldblquote They\rquote ll be all right. It ought to be interesting for them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Interesting? How?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Just interesting,\rdblquote  said The Brain, slyly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Susan,\rdblquote  whispered Lanning in a fuming whisper, \ldblquote ask him if death comes into it. Ask him what the dangers are.\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin\rquote s expression contorted with fury, \ldblquote Keep quiet!\rdblquote  In a shaken voice, she said to The Brain, \ldblquote We can communicate with the ship, can\rquote t we Brain?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, they can hear you if you call by radio. I\rquote ve taken care of that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thanks. That\rquote s all for now.\rdblquote\par
\tab Once outside, Lanning lashed out ragingly, \ldblquote Great Galaxy, Susan, if this gets out, it will ruin all of us. We\rquote ve got to get those men back. Why didn\rquote t you ask it if there was danger of death -- straight out?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because,\rdblquote  said Calvin, with a weary frustration, \ldblquote that\rquote s just what I can\rquote t mention. If it\rquote s got a case of dilemma, it\rquote s about death. Anything that would bring it up badly might knock it completely out. Will we be better off then? Now, look, it said we could communicate with them. Let\rquote s do so, get their location, and bring them back. They probably can\rquote t use the controls themselves; The Brain is probably handling them remotely. Come!\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab It was quite a while before Powell shook himself together.\par
\tab\ldblquote Mike,\rdblquote  he said, out of cold lips, \ldblquote did you feel an acceleration?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan\rquote s eyes were blank, \ldblquote Huh? No... no.\rdblquote\par
\tab And then the redhead\rquote s fists clenched and he was out of his seat with sudden frenzied energy and up against the cold, wide-curving glass. There was nothing to see -- but stars.\par
\tab He turned, \ldblquote Greg, they must have started the machine while we were inside. Greg, it\rquote s a put-up job; they fixed it up with the robot to jerry us into being the try-out boys, in case we were thinking of backing out.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote What are you talking about? What\rquote s the good of sending us out if we don\rquote t know how to run the machine? How are we supposed to bring it back? No, this ship left by itself, and without any apparent acceleration.\rdblquote  He rose, and walked the floor slowly. The metal walls dinned back the clangor of his steps.\par
\tab He said tonelessly, \ldblquote Mike, this is the most confusing situation we\rquote ve ever been up against.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That,\rdblquote  said Donovan, bitterly, \ldblquote is news to me. I was just beginning to have a very swell time, when you told me.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell ignored that. \ldblquote No acceleration -- which means the ship works on a principle different from any known.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Different from any we know, anyway.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Different from \i any\i0  known. There are no engines within reach of manual control. Maybe they\rquote re built into the walls. Maybe that\rquote s why they\rquote re thick as they are.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What are you mumbling about?\rdblquote  demanded Donovan.\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not listen? I\rquote m saying that whatever powers this ship is enclosed, and evidently not meant to be handled. The ship is running by remote control.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Brain\rquote s control?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then you think we\rquote ll stay out here till The Brain brings us back.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It could be. If so, let\rquote s wait quietly. The Brain is a robot. It\rquote s got to follow the First Law. It can\rquote t hurt a human being.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan sat down slowly, \ldblquote You figure that?\rdblquote  Carefully, he flattened his hair, \ldblquote Listen, this junk about the space-warp knocked out Consolidated\rquote s robot, and the longhairs said it was because interstellar travel killed humans. Which robot are you going to trust? Ours had the same data, I understand.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell was yanking madly at his mustache, \ldblquote Don\rquote t pretend you don\rquote t know your robotics, Mike. Before it\rquote s physically possible in any way for a robot to even make a start to breaking the First Law, so many things have to break down that it would be a ruined mess of scrap ten times over. There\rquote s some simple explanation to this.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh sure, sure. Just have the butler call me in the morning. It\rquote s all just too, too simple for me to bother about before my beauty nap.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, Jupiter, Mike, what are you complaining about so far? The Brain is taking care of us. This place is warm. It\rquote s got light. It\rquote s got air. There wasn\rquote t even enough of an acceleration jar to muss your hair if it were smooth enough to be mussable in the first place.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yeah? Greg, you must\rquote ve taken lessons. No one could put Pollyanna that far out of the running without. What do we eat? What do we drink? Where are we? How do we get back? And in case of accident, to what exit and in what spacesuit do we run, not walk? I haven\rquote t even seen a bathroom in the place, or those little conveniences that go along with bathrooms. Sure, we\rquote re being taken care of -- but good?\rdblquote\par
\tab The voice that interrupted Donovan\rquote s tirade was not Powell\rquote s. It was nobody\rquote s. It was there, hanging in open air -- stentorian and petrifying in its effects.\par
\tab\ldblquote GREGORY POWELL! MICHAEL DONOVAN! GREGORY POWELL! MICHAEL DONOVAN! PLEASE REPORT YOUR PRESENT POSITIONS. IF YOUR SHIP ANSWERS CONTROLS, PLEASE RETURN TO BASE. GREGORY POWELL! MICHAEL DONOVAN! -\rdblquote\par
\tab The message was repetitious, mechanical, broken by regular, untiring intervals.\par
\tab Donovan said, \ldblquote Where\rquote s it coming from?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know.\rdblquote  Powell\rquote s voice was an intense whisper, \ldblquote Where do the lights come from? Where does anything come from?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, how are we going to answer?\rdblquote  They had to speak in the intervals between the loudly echoing, repeating message.\par
\tab The walls were bare -- as bare and as unbroken as smooth, curving metal can be. Powell said, \ldblquote Shout an answer.\rdblquote\par
\tab They did. They shouted, in turns, and together, \ldblquote Position unknown! Ship out of control! Condition desperate!\rdblquote\par
\tab Their voices rose and cracked. The short businesslike sentences became interlarded and adulterated with screaming and emphatic profanity, but the cold, calling voice repeated and repeated and repeated unwearyingly.\par
\tab\ldblquote They don\rquote t hear us,\rdblquote  gasped Donovan. \ldblquote There\rquote s no sending mechanism. Just a receiver.\rdblquote  His eyes focused blindly at a random spot on the wall.\par
\tab Slowly the din of the outside voice softened and receded. They called again when it was a whisper, and they called again, hoarsely, when there was silence.\par
\tab Something like fifteen minutes later, Powell said lifelessly, \ldblquote Let\rquote s go through the ship again. There must be something to eat somewheres.\rdblquote  He did not sound hopeful. It was almost an admission of defeat.\par
\tab They divided in the corridor to the right and left. They could follow one another by the hard footsteps resounding, and they met occasionally in the corridor, where they would glare at each other and pass on.\par
\tab Powell\rquote s search ended suddenly and as it did, he heard Donovan\rquote s glad voice rise boomingly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Hey, Greg,\rdblquote  it howled, \ldblquote The ship \i has\i0  got plumbing. How did we miss it?\rdblquote\par
\tab It was some five minutes later that he found Powell by hit-and-miss. He was saying, \ldblquote Still no shower baths, though,\rdblquote  but it got choked off in the middle.\par
\tab\ldblquote Food,\rdblquote  he gasped.\par
\tab The wall had dropped away, leaving a curved gap with two shelves. The upper shelf was loaded with unlabeled cans of a bewildering variety of sizes and shapes. The enameled cans on the lower shelf were uniform and Donovan felt a cold draft about his ankles. The lower half was refrigerated.\par
\tab\ldblquote How... how-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t there, before,\rdblquote  said Powell, curtly. \ldblquote That wall section dropped out of sight as I came in the door.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was eating. The can was the preheating type with enclosed spoon and the warm odor of baked beans filled the room. \ldblquote Grab a can, Mike!\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan hesitated, \ldblquote What\rquote s the menu?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How do I know! Are you finicky?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, but all I eat on ships are beans. Something else would be first choice.\rdblquote  His hand hovered and selected a shining elliptical can whose flatness seemed reminiscent of salmon or similar delicacy. It opened at the proper pressure.\par
\tab\ldblquote Beans!\rdblquote  howled Donovan, and reached for another. Powell hauled at the slack of his pants. \ldblquote Better eat that, sonny boy. Supplies are limited and we may be here a long, long time.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan drew back sulkily, \ldblquote Is that all we have? Beans?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Could be.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s on the lower shelf?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Milk.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Just milk?\rdblquote  Donovan cried in outrage.\par
\tab\ldblquote Looks it.\rdblquote\par
\tab The meal of beans and milk was carried through in silence, and as they left, the strip of hidden wall rose up and formed an unbroken surface once more.\par
\tab Powell sighed, \ldblquote Everything automatic. Everything just so. Never felt so helpless in my life. Where\rquote s your plumbing?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Right there. And that wasn\rquote t among those present when we first looked, either.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fifteen minutes later they were back in the glassed-in room, staring at each other from opposing seats.\par
\tab Powell looked gloomily at the one gauge in the room. It still said \ldblquote parsecs,\rdblquote  the figures still ended in \ldblquote 1,000,000\rdblquote  and the indicating needle was still pressed hard against the zero mark.\par
\par
\tab In the innermost offices of the U. S. Robot & Mechanical Men Corp. Alfred Lanning was saying wearily, \ldblquote They won\rquote t answer. We\rquote ve tried every wavelength, public, private, coded, straight, even this subether stuff they have now. And The Brain still won\rquote t say anything?\rdblquote  He shot this at Dr. Calvin.\par
\tab\ldblquote It won\rquote t amplify on the matter, Alfred,\rdblquote  she said, emphatically. \ldblquote It says they can hear us... and when I try to press it, it becomes... well, it becomes sullen. And it\rquote s not supposed to -- whoever heard of a sullen robot?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose you tell us what you have, Susan,\rdblquote  said Bogert.\par
\tab\ldblquote Here it is! It admits it controls the ship itself entirely. It is definitely optimistic about their safety, but without details. I don\rquote t dare press it. However, the center of disturbance seems to be about the interstellar jump itself. The Brain definitely laughed when I brought up the subject. There are other indications, but that is the closest it\rquote s come to an open abnormality.\rdblquote\par
\tab She looked at the others, \ldblquote I refer to hysteria. I dropped the subject immediately, and I hope I did no harm, but it gave me a lead. I can handle hysteria. Give me twelve hours! If I can bring it back to normal, it will bring back the ship.\rdblquote\par
\tab Bogert seemed suddenly stricken. \ldblquote The interstellar jump!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s the matter?\rdblquote  The cry was double from Calvin and Lanning.\par
\tab\ldblquote The figures for the engine The Brain gave us. Say... I just thought of something.\rdblquote\par
\tab He left hurriedly.\par
\tab Lanning gazed after him. He said brusquely to Calvin, \ldblquote You take care of your end, Susan.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Two hours later, Bogert was talking eagerly, \ldblquote I tell you, Lanning, that\rquote s it. The interstellar jump is not instantaneous not as long as the speed of light is finite. Life can\rquote t exist... \i matter and energy \i0 as such can\rquote t exist in the space warp. I don\rquote t know what it would be like -- but that\rquote s it. That\rquote s what killed Consolidated\rquote s robot.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Donovan felt as haggard as he looked. \ldblquote Only five days?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Only five days. I\rquote m sure of it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan looked about him wretchedly. The stars through the glass were familiar but infinitely indifferent. The walls were cold to the touch; the lights, which had recently flared up again, were unfeelingly bright; the needle on the gauge pointed stubbornly to zero; and Donovan could not get rid of the taste of beans.\par
\tab He said, morosely, \ldblquote I need a bath.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell looked up briefly, and said, \ldblquote So do I. You needn\rquote t feel self-conscious. But unless you want to bathe in milk and do without drinking\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ll do without drinking eventually, anyway. Greg, where does this interstellar travel come in?\rquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You tell me. Maybe we just keep on going. We\rquote d get there, eventually. At least the dust of our skeletons would -- but isn\rquote t our death the whole point of The Brain\rquote s original breakdown?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan spoke with his back to the other, \ldblquote Greg, I\rquote ve been thinking. It\rquote s pretty bad. There\rquote s not much to do -- except walk around or talk to yourself. You know those stories about guys marooned in space. They go nuts long before they starve. I don\rquote t know, Greg, but ever since the lights went on, I feel funny.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a silence, then Powell\rquote s voice came thin and small, \ldblquote So do I. What\rquote s it like?\rdblquote\par
\tab The redheaded figure turned, \ldblquote Feel funny inside. There\rquote s a pounding in me with everything tense. It\rquote s hard to breathe. I can\rquote t stand still.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Um-m-m. Do you feel vibration?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How do you mean?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sit down for a minute and listen. You don\rquote t hear it, but you feel it -- as if something\rquote s throbbing somewheres and it\rquote s throbbing the whole ship, and you, too, along with it. Listen-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yeah . . . yeah. What do you think it is, Greg? You don\rquote t suppose it\rquote s us?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It might be.\rdblquote  Powell stroked his mustache slowly. \ldblquote But it might be the ship\rquote s engines. It might be getting ready.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For what?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For the interstellar jump. It may be coming and the devil knows what it\rquote s like.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan pondered. Then he said, savagely, \ldblquote If it does, let it. But I wish we could fight. It\rquote s humiliating to have to wait for it.\rdblquote\par
\tab An hour later, perhaps, Powell looked at his hand on the metal chair-arm and said with frozen calm, \ldblquote Feel the wall, Mike.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan did, and said, \ldblquote You can feel it shake, Greg.\rdblquote\par
\tab Even the stars seemed blurred. From somewhere came the vague impression of a huge machine gathering power with the walls, storing up energy for a mighty leap, throbbing its way up the scales of strength.\par
\tab It came with a suddenness and a stab of pain. Powell stiffened, and half-jerked from his chair. His sight caught Donovan and blanked out while Donovan\rquote s thin shout whimpered and died in his ears. Something writhed within him and struggled against a growing blanket of ice, that thickened.\par
\tab Something broke loose and whirled in a blaze of flickering light and pain. It fell -- and whirled and fell headlong into silence!\par
\tab It was death!\par
\tab It was a world of no motion and no sensation. A world of dim, unsensing consciousness; a consciousness of darkness and of silence and of formless struggle.\par
\tab Most of all a consciousness of eternity.\par
\tab He was a tiny white thread of ego -- cold and afraid.\par
\tab Then the words came, unctuous and sonorous, thundering over him in a foam of sound:\par
\tab\ldblquote Does your coffin fit differently lately? Why not try Morbid M. Cadaver\rquote s extensible caskets? They are scientifically designed to fit the natural curves of the body, and are enriched with Vitamin B1. Use Cadaver\rquote s caskets for comfort. Remember - you\rquote re - going - to - be - dead - a - long - long - time!\rdblquote\par
\tab It wasn\rquote t quite sound, but whatever it was, it died away in an oily rumbling whisper.\par
\tab The white thread that might have been Powell heaved uselessly at the insubstantial eons of time that existed all about him -- and collapsed upon itself as the piercing shriek of a hundred million ghosts of a hundred million soprano voices rose to a crescendo of melody:\par
\par
\i\f3\tab\f0\ldblquote I\rquote ll be glad when you\rquote re dead, you rascal, you.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll be glad when you\rquote re dead, you rascal, you.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll be glad-\rdblquote\par
\i0\f3\par
\tab\f0 It rose up a spiral stairway of violent sound into the keening supersonics that passed hearing, and then beyond-\par
\par
\tab The white thread quivered with a pulsating pang. It strained quietly-\par
\tab The voices were ordinary -- and many. It was a crowd speaking; a swirling mob that swept through and past and over him with a rapid, headlong motion, that left drifting tatters of words behind them.\par
\tab\ldblquote What did they getcha for, boy? Y\rquote look banged up-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote --A hot fire, I guess, but I got a case-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote --I\rquote ve made Paradise, but old St. Pete-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Naaah, I got a pull with the boy. Had dealings with him-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hey, Sam, come this way-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Ja get a mouthpiece? Beelzebub says-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote --Going on, my good imp? My appointment is with Sa-\rdblquote\par
\tab And above it all the original stentorian roar, that plunged across all:\par
\tab\ldblquote HURRY! HURRY! HURRY!!! Stir your bones, and don\rquote t keep us waiting -- there are many more in line. Have your certificates ready, and make sure Peter\rquote s release is stamped across it. See if you are at the proper entrance gate. There will be plenty of fire for all. Hey, you -- YOU DOWN THERE. TAKE YOUR PLACE IN LINE OR-\rdblquote\par
\tab The white thread that was Powell groveled backward before the advancing shout, and felt the sharp stab of the pointing finger. It all exploded into a rainbow of sound that dripped its fragments onto an aching brain.\par
\tab Powell was in the chair, again. He felt himself shaking.\par
\tab Donovan\rquote s eyes were opening into two large popping bowls of glazed blue.\par
\tab\ldblquote Greg,\rdblquote  he whispered in what was almost a sob. \ldblquote Were you dead?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I... felt dead.\rdblquote  He did not recognize his own croak.\par
\tab Donovan was obviously making a bad failure of his attempt to stand up, \ldblquote Are we alive now? Or is there more?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I... feel alive.\rdblquote  It was the same hoarseness. Powell said cautiously, \ldblquote Did you... hear anything, when... when you were dead?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan paused, and then very slowly nodded his head, \ldblquote Did you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Did you hear about coffins... and females singing... and the lines forming to get into Hell? Did you?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan shook his head, \ldblquote Just one voice.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Loud?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. Soft, but rough like a file over the fingertips. It was a sermon, you know. About hell-fire. He described the tortures of... well, \i you know\i0 . I once heard a sermon like that -- almost.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was perspiring.\par
\par
\tab They were conscious of sunlight through the port. It was weak, but it was blue-white -- and the gleaming pea that was the distant source of light was not Old Sol.\par
\tab And Powell pointed a trembling finger at the single gauge. The needle stood stiff and proud at the hairline whose figure read 300,000 parsecs.\par
\tab Powell said, \ldblquote Mike if it\rquote s true, we must be out of the Galaxy altogether.\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan said, \ldblquote Blazed Greg! We\rquote d be the first men out of the Solar System.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes! That\rquote s just it. We\rquote ve escaped the sun. We\rquote ve escaped the Galaxy. Mike, this ship is the answer. It means freedom for all humanity -- freedom to spread through to every star that exists -- millions and billions and trillions of them.\rdblquote\par
\tab And then he came down with a hard thud, \ldblquote But how do we get back, Mike?\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan smiled shakily, \ldblquote Oh, that\rquote s all right. The ship brought us here. The ship will take us back. Me for more beans.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But Mike... hold on, Mike. If it takes us back the way it brought us here-\rdblquote\par
\tab Donovan stopped halfway up and sat back heavily into the chair.\par
\tab Powell went on, \ldblquote We\rquote ll have to... die again, Mike\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  sighed Donovan, \ldblquote if we have to, we have to. At least it isn\rquote t permanent, not \i very\i0  permanent.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Susan Calvin was speaking slowly now. For six hours she had been slowly prodding The Brain -- for six fruitless hours. She was weary of repetitions, weary of circumlocutions, weary of everything.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now, Brain, there\rquote s just one more thing. You must make a special effort to answer simply. Have you been entirely clear about the interstellar jump? I mean does it take them very far?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote As far as they want to go, Miss Susan. Golly, it isn\rquote t any trick through the warp.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And on the other side, what will they see?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Stars and stuff. What do you suppose?\rdblquote\par
\tab The next question slipped out, \ldblquote They\rquote ll be alive, then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And the interstellar jump won\rquote t hurt them?\rdblquote\par
\tab She froze as The Brain maintained silence. That was it! She had touched the sore spot.\par
\tab\ldblquote Brain,\rdblquote  she supplicated faintly, \ldblquote Brain, do you hear me?\rdblquote\par
\tab The answer was weak, quivering. The Brain said, \ldblquote Do I have to answer? About the jump, I mean?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not if you don\rquote t want to. But it would be interesting -- I mean if you wanted to.\rdblquote  Susan Calvin tried to be bright about it.\par
\tab\ldblquote Aw-w-w. You spoil everything.\rdblquote\par
\tab And the psychologist jumped up suddenly, with a look of flaming insight on her face.\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, my,\rdblquote  she gasped. \ldblquote Oh, my.\rdblquote\par
\tab And she felt the tension of hours and days released in a burst. It was later that she told Lanning, \ldblquote I tell you it\rquote s all right. No, you must leave me alone, now. The ship will be back safely, \i with\i0  the men, and I want to rest. I \i will\i0  rest. Now go away.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab The ship returned to Earth as silently, as unjarringly as it had left. It dropped precisely into place and the main lock gaped open. The two men who walked out felt their way carefully and scratched their rough and scrubbily-stubbled chins.\par
\tab And then, slowly and purposefully, the one with red hair knelt down and planted upon the concrete of the runway a firm, loud kiss.\par
\tab They waved aside the crowd that was gathering and made gestures of denial at the eager couple that had piled out of the down-swooping ambulance with a stretcher between them.\par
\tab Gregory Powell said, \ldblquote Where\rquote s the nearest shower?\rdblquote\par
\tab They were led away.\par
\tab They were gathered, all of them, about a table. It was a full staff meeting of the brains of U. S. Robot & Mechanical Men Corp.\par
\par
\tab Slowly and climactically, Powell and Donovan finished a graphic and resounding story.\par
\tab Susan Calvin broke the silence that followed. In the few days that had elapsed she had recovered her icy, somewhat acid, calm -- but still a trace of embarrassment broke through.\par
\tab\ldblquote Strictly speaking,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote this was my fault -- all of it. When we first presented this problem to The Brain, as I hope some of you remember, I went to great lengths to impress upon it the importance of rejecting any item of information capable of creating a dilemma. In doing so I said something like \lquote Don\rquote t get excited about the death of humans. We don\rquote t mind it at all. Just give the sheet back and forget it.\rquote\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hm-m-m,\rdblquote  said Lanning. \ldblquote What follows?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The obvious. When that item entered its calculations which yielded the equation controlling the length of minimum interval for the interstellar jump -- it meant death for humans. That\rquote s where Consolidated\rquote s machine broke down completely. But I had depressed the importance of death to The Brain -- not entirely, for the First Law can never be broken -- but just sufficiently so that The Brain could take a second look at the equation. Sufficiently to give it time to realize that after the interval was passed through, the men would return to life -- just as the matter and energy of the ship itself would return to being. This so-called \lquote death,\rquote  in other words, was a strictly temporary phenomenon. You see?\rdblquote\par
\tab She looked about her. They were all listening.\par
\tab She went on, \ldblquote So he accepted the item, but not without a certain jar. Even with death temporary and its importance depressed, it was enough to unbalance him very gently.\rdblquote\par
\tab She brought it out calmly, \ldblquote He developed a sense of humor -- it\rquote s an escape, you see, a method of partial escape from reality. He became a practical joker.\rdblquote\par
\tab Powell and Donovan were on their feet.\par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  cried Powell?\par
\tab Donovan was considerably more colorful about it.\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s so,\rdblquote  said Calvin. \ldblquote He took care of you, and kept you safe, but you couldn\rquote t handle any controls, because they weren\rquote t for you -- just for the humorous Brain. We could reach you by radio, but you couldn\rquote t answer. You had plenty of food, but all of it beans and milk. Then you died, so to speak, and were reborn, but the period of your death was made... well... interesting. I wish I knew how he did it. It was The Brain\rquote s prize joke, but he meant no harm.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No harm!\rdblquote  gasped Donovan. \ldblquote Oh, if that cute little tyke only had a neck.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning raised a quieting hand, \ldblquote All right, it\rquote s been a mess, but it\rquote s all over. What now?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Bogert, quietly, \ldblquote obviously it\rquote s up to us to improve the space-warp engine. There must be some way of getting around that interval of jump. If there is, we\rquote re the only organization left with a grand-scale super-robot, so we\rquote re bound to find it if anyone can. And then -- U. S. Robots has interstellar travel, and humanity has the opportunity for galactic empire.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What about Consolidated?\rdblquote  said Lanning?\par
\tab\ldblquote Hey,\rdblquote  interrupted Donovan suddenly, \ldblquote I want to make a suggestion there. They landed U. S. Robots into quite a mess. It wasn\rquote t as bad a mess as they expected and it turned out well, but their intentions weren\rquote t pious. And Greg and I bore the most of it.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, they wanted an answer, and they\rquote ve got one. Send them that ship, guaranteed, and U. S. Robots can collect their two hundred thou plus construction costs. And if they test it -- then suppose we let The Brain have just a little more fun before it\rquote s brought back to normal.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning said gravely, \ldblquote It sounds just and proper to me.\rdblquote\par
\tab To which Bogert added absently, \ldblquote Strictly according to contract, too.\rdblquote\par
