Francis Quinn was a politician of the new school. That, of course, is a meaningless expression, as are all expressions of the sort. Most of the \ldblquote new schools\rdblquote  we have were duplicated in the social life of ancient Greece, and perhaps, if we knew more about it, in the social life of ancient Sumeria and in the lake dwellings of prehistoric Switzerland as well.\par
\tab But, to get out from under what promises to be a dull and complicated beginning, it might be best to state hastily that Quinn neither ran for office nor canvassed for votes, made no speeches and stuffed no ballot boxes. Any more than Napoleon pulled a trigger at Austerlitz.\par
\tab And since politics makes strange bedfellows, Alfred Lanning sat at the other side of the desk with his ferocious white eyebrows bent far forward over eyes in which chronic impatience had sharpened to acuity. He was not pleased.\par
\tab The fact, if known to Quinn, would have annoyed him not the least. His voice was friendly, perhaps professionally so.\par
\tab\ldblquote I assume you know Stephen Byerley, Dr. Lanning.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I have heard of him. So have many people.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, so have I. Perhaps you intend voting for him at the next election.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I couldn\rquote t say.\rdblquote  There was an unmistakable trace of acidity here. \ldblquote I have not followed the political currents, so I\rquote m not aware that he is running for office.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He may be our next mayor. Of course, he is only a lawyer now, but great oaks-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  interrupted Lanning, \ldblquote I have heard the phrase before. But I wonder if we can get to the business at hand.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We \i are\i0  at the business at hand, Dr. Lanning.\rdblquote  Quinn\rquote s tone was very gentle, \ldblquote It is to my interest to keep Mr. Byerley a district attorney at the very most, and it is to your interest to help me do so.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To \i my\i0  interest? Come!\rdblquote  Lanning\rquote s eyebrows hunched low.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, say then to the interest of the U. S. Robot & Mechanical Men Corporation. I come to you as Director Emeritus of Research, because I know that your connection to them is that of, shall we say, \lquote elder statesman.\rquote  You are listened to with respect and yet your connection with them is no longer so tight but that you cannot possess considerable freedom of action; even if the action is somewhat unorthodox.\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Lanning was silent a moment, chewing the cud of his thoughts. He said more softly, \ldblquote I don\rquote t follow you at all, Mr. Quinn.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I am not surprised, Dr. Lanning. But it\rquote s all rather simple. Do you mind?\rdblquote  Quinn lit a slender cigarette with a lighter of tasteful simplicity and his big-boned face settled into an expression of quiet amusement. \ldblquote We have spoken of Mr. Byerley -- a strange and colorful character. He was unknown three years ago. He is very well known now. He is a man of force and ability, and certainly the most capable and intelligent prosecutor I have ever known. Unfortunately he is not a friend of mine\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I understand,\rdblquote  said Lanning, mechanically. He stared at his fingernails.\par
\tab\ldblquote I have had occasion,\rdblquote  continued Quinn, evenly, \ldblquote in the past year to investigate Mr. Byerley -- quite exhaustively. It is always useful, you see, to subject the past life of reform politicians to rather inquisitive research. If you knew how often it helped-\rdblquote  He paused to smile humorlessly at the glowing tip of his cigarette. \ldblquote But Mr. Byerley\rquote s past is unremarkable. A quiet life in a small town, a college education, a wife who died young, an auto accident with a slow recovery, law school, coming to the metropolis, an attorney.\rdblquote\par
\tab Francis Quinn shook his head slowly, then added, \ldblquote But his present life. Ah, that is remarkable. Our district attorney never eats!\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning\rquote s head snapped up, old eyes surprisingly sharp, \ldblquote Pardon me?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Our district attorney never eats.\rdblquote  The repetition thumped by syllables. \ldblquote I\rquote ll modify that slightly. He has never been seen to eat or drink. Never! Do you understand the significance of the word? Not rarely, but never!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I find that quite incredible. Can you trust your investigators?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I can trust my investigators, and I don\rquote t find it incredible at all. Further, our district attorney has never been seen to drink -- in the aqueous sense as well as the alcoholic -- nor to sleep. There are other factors, but I should think I have made my point.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Lanning leaned back in his seat, and there was the rapt silence of challenge and response between them, and then the old roboticist shook his head. \ldblquote No. There is only one thing you can be trying to imply, if I couple your statements with the fact that you present them to me, and that is impossible.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But the man is quite inhuman, Dr. Lanning.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If you told me he were Satan in masquerade, there would be a faint chance that I might believe you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I tell you he is a robot, Dr. Lanning.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I tell you it is as impossible a conception as I have ever heard, Mr. Quinn.\rdblquote\par
\tab Again the combative silence.\par
\tab\ldblquote Nevertheless,\rdblquote  and Quinn stubbed out his cigarette with elaborate care, \ldblquote you will have to investigate this impossibility with all the resources of the Corporation.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sure that I could undertake no such thing, Mr. Quinn. You don\rquote t seriously suggest that the Corporation take part in local politics.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You have no choice. Supposing I were to make my facts public without proof. The evidence is circumstantial enough.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suit yourself in that respect.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But it would not suit me. Proof would be much preferable. And it would not suit \i you\i0 , for the publicity would be very damaging to your company. You are perfectly well acquainted, I suppose, with the strict rules against the use of robots on inhabited worlds.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Certainly!\rdblquote  -- brusquely.\par
\tab\ldblquote You know that the U. S. Robot & Mechanical Men Corporation is the only manufacturer of positronic robots in the Solar System, and if Byerley is a robot, he is a \i positronic\i0  robot. You are also aware that all positronic robots are leased, and not sold; that the Corporation remains the owner and manager of each robot, and is therefore responsible for the actions of all.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It is an easy matter, Mr. Quinn, to prove the Corporation has never manufactured a robot of a humanoid character.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It can be done? To discuss merely possibilities.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. It can be done.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Secretly, I imagine, as well. Without entering it in your books.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not the positronic brain, sir. Too many factors are involved in that, and there is the tightest possible government supervision.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, but robots are worn out, break down, go out of order -- and are dismantled.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And the positronic brains re-used or destroyed.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Really?\rdblquote  Francis Quinn allowed himself a trace of sarcasm. \ldblquote And if one were, accidentally, of course, not destroyed -- and there happened to be a humanoid structure waiting for a brain.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Impossible!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You would have to prove that to the government and the public, so why not prove it to me now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But what could our purpose be?\rdblquote  demanded Lanning in exasperation. \ldblquote Where is our motivation? Credit us with a minimum of sense.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote My dear sir, please. The Corporation would be only too glad to have the various Regions permit the use of humanoid positronic robots on inhabited worlds. The profits would be enormous. But the prejudice of the public against such a practice is too great. Suppose you get them used to such robots first -- see, we have a skillful lawyer, a good mayor, and he is a robot. Won\rquote t you buy our robot butlers?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thoroughly fantastic. An almost humorous descent to the ridiculous.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I imagine so. Why not prove it? Or would you still rather try to prove it to the public?\rdblquote\par
