\tab The face of Stephen Byerley is not an easy one to describe. He was forty by birth certificate and forty by appearance -- but it was a healthy, well-nourished good-natured appearance of forty; one that automatically drew the teeth of the bromide about \ldblquote looking one\rquote s age.\rdblquote\par
\tab This was particularly true when he laughed, and he was laughing now. It came loudly and continuously, died away for a bit, then began again-\par
\tab And Alfred Lanning\rquote s face contracted into a rigidly bitter monument of disapproval. He made a half gesture to the woman who sat beside him, but her thin, bloodless lips merely pursed themselves a trifle.\par
\tab Byerley gasped himself a stage nearer normality.\par
\tab\ldblquote Really, Dr. Lanning... really -- I... \i I\i0 ... a robot?\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning bit his words off with a snap, \ldblquote It is no statement of mine, sir. I would be quite satisfied to have you a member of humanity. Since our corporation never manufactured you, I am quite certain that you are -- in a legalistic sense, at any rate. But since the contention that you are a robot has been advanced to us seriously by a man of certain standing-\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t mention his name, if it would knock a chip off your granite block of ethics, but let\rquote s pretend it was Frank Quinn, for the sake of argument, and continue.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning drew in a sharp, cutting snort at the interruption, and paused ferociously before continuing with added frigidity, \ldblquote -by a man of certain standing, with whose identity I am not interested in playing guessing games, I am bound to ask your cooperation in disproving it. The mere fact that such a contention could be advanced and publicized by the means at this man\rquote s disposal would be a bad blow to the company I represent -- even if the charge were never proven. You understand me?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, yes, your position is clear to me. The charge itself is ridiculous. The spot you find yourself in is not. I beg your pardon, if my laughter offended you. It was the first I laughed at, not the second. How can I help you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It could be very simple. You have only to sit down to a meal at a restaurant in the presence of witnesses, have your picture taken, and eat.\rdblquote  Lanning sat back in his chair, the worst of the interview over. The woman beside him watched Byerley with an apparently absorbed expression but contributed nothing of her own.\par
\tab Stephen Byerley met her eyes for an instant, was caught by them, then turned back to the roboticist. For a while his fingers were thoughtful over the bronze paperweight that was the only ornament on his desk.\par
\tab He said quietly, \ldblquote I don\rquote t think I can oblige you.\rdblquote\par
\tab He raised his hand, \ldblquote Now wait, Dr. Lanning. I appreciate the fact that this whole matter is distasteful to you, that you have been forced into it against your will, that you feel you are playing an undignified and even ridiculous part. Still, the matter is even more intimately concerned with myself, so be tolerant.\par
\tab\ldblquote First, what makes you think that Quinn -- this man of certain standing, you know -- wasn\rquote t hoodwinking you, in order to get you to do exactly what you are doing?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why it seems scarcely likely that a reputable person would endanger himself in so ridiculous a fashion, if he weren\rquote t convinced he were on safe ground.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was little humor in Byerley\rquote s eyes, \ldblquote You don\rquote t know Quinn. He could manage to make safe ground out of a ledge a mountain sheep could not handle. I suppose he showed the particulars of the investigation he claims to have made of me?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Enough to convince me that it would be too troublesome to have our corporation attempt to disprove them when you could do so more easily.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then you believe him when he says I never eat. You are a scientist, Dr. Lanning. Think of the logic required. I have not been observed to eat, therefore, I never eat Q.E.D. After all!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You are using prosecution tactics to confuse what is really a very simple situation.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote On the contrary, I am trying to clarify what you and Quinn between you are making a very complicated one. You see, I don\rquote t sleep much, that\rquote s true, and I certainly don\rquote t sleep in public. I have never cared to eat with others -- an idiosyncrasy which is unusual and probably neurotic in character, but which harms no one. Look, Dr. Lanning, let me present you with a suppositious case. Supposing we had a politician who was interested in defeating a reform candidate at any cost and while investigating his private life came across oddities such as I have just mentioned.\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose further that in order to smear the candidate effectively, he comes to your company as the ideal agent. Do you expect him to say to you, \lquote So-and-so is a robot because he hardly ever eats with people, and I have never seen him fall asleep in the middle of a case; and once when I peeped into his window in the middle of the night, there he was, sitting up with a book; and I looked in his frigidaire and there was no food in it.\rquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If he told you that, you would send for a straitjacket. But if he tells you, \lquote He \i never\i0  sleeps; he \i never\i0  eats,\rquote  then the shock of the statement blinds you to the fact that such statements are impossible to prove. You play into his hands by contributing to the to-do.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Regardless, sir,\rdblquote  began Lanning, with a threatening obstinacy, \ldblquote of whether you consider this matter serious or not, it will require only the meal I mentioned to end it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Again Byerley turned to the woman, who still regarded him expressionlessly. \ldblquote Pardon me. I\rquote ve caught your name correctly, haven\rquote t I? Dr. Susan Calvin?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Mr. Byerley.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re the U. S. Robot\rquote s psychologist, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote\i Robo\i0 psychologist, please.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, are robots so different from men, mentally?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Worlds different.\rdblquote  She allowed herself a frosty smile, \ldblquote Robots are essentially decent.\rdblquote\par
\tab Humor tugged at the corners of the lawyer\rquote s mouth, \ldblquote Well, that\rquote s a hard blow. But what I wanted to say was this. Since you\rquote re a psycho -- a robopsychologist, \i and\i0  a woman, I\rquote ll bet that you\rquote ve done something that Dr. Lanning hasn\rquote t thought of.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And what is that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ve got something to eat in your purse.\rdblquote\par
\tab Something caught in the schooled indifference of Susan Calvin\rquote s eyes. She said, \ldblquote You surprise me, Mr. Byerley.\rdblquote\par
\tab And opening her purse, she produced an apple. Quietly, she handed it to him. Dr. Lanning, after an initial start, followed the slow movement from one hand to the other with sharply alert eyes.\par
\tab Calmly, Stephen Byerley bit into it, and calmly he swallowed it\par
\tab\ldblquote You see, Dr. Lanning?\rdblquote\par
\tab Dr. Lanning smiled in a relief tangible enough to make even his eyebrows appear benevolent A relief that survived for one fragile second.\par
\tab Susan Calvin said, \ldblquote I was curious to see if you would eat it, but, of course, in the present case, it proves nothing.\rdblquote\par
\tab Byerley grinned, \ldblquote It doesn\rquote t?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course not. It is obvious, Dr. Lanning, that if this man were a humanoid robot, he would be a perfect imitation. He is almost too human to be credible. After all, we have been seeing and observing human beings all our lives; it would be impossible to palm something merely nearly right off on us. It would have to be \i all\i0  right. Observe the texture of the skin, the quality of the irises, the bone formation of the hand. If he\rquote s a robot, I wish U. S. Robots \i had\i0  made him, because he\rquote s a good job. Do you suppose then, that anyone capable of paying attention to such niceties would neglect a few gadgets to take care of such things as eating, sleeping, elimination? For emergency use only, perhaps; as, for instance, to prevent such situations as are arising here. So a meal won\rquote t really prove anything.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Now wait,\rdblquote  snarled Lanning, \ldblquote I am -- not quite the fool both of you make me out to be. I am not interested in the problem of Mr. Byerley\rquote s humanity or nonhumanity. I am interest in getting the corporation out of a hole. A public meal will end the matter and keep it ended no matter what Quinn does. We can leave the finer details to lawyers and robopsychologists.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But, Dr. Lanning,\rdblquote  said Byerley, \ldblquote you forget the politics of the situation. I am as anxious to be elected, as Quinn is to stop me. By the way, did you notice that you used his name? It\rquote s a cheap shyster trick of mine; I knew you would, before you were through.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning flushed, \ldblquote What has the election to do with it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Publicity works both ways, sir. If Quinn wants to call me a robot, and has the nerve to do so, I have the nerve to play the game his way.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean you-\rdblquote  Lanning was quite frankly appalled.\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly. I mean that I\rquote m going to let him go ahead, choose his rope, test its strength, cut off the right length, tie the noose, insert his head and grin. I can do what little else is required.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You are mighty confident.\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin rose to her feet, \ldblquote Come, Alfred, we won\rquote t change his mind for him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You see.\rdblquote  Byerley smiled gently. \ldblquote You\rquote re a human psychologist, too.\rdblquote\par
