\tab\ldblquote Why don\rquote t you let me use the wheel chair, Steve? This is Silly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because I\rquote d rather carry you. Do you object? You know that you\rquote re as glad to get out of that motorized buggy for a while, as I am to see you out. How do you feel today?\rdblquote  He deposited John with infinite care upon the cool grass.\par
\tab\ldblquote How should I feel? But tell me about your troubles.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Quinn\rquote s campaign will be based on the fact that he claims I\rquote m a robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab John\rquote s eyes opened wide, \ldblquote How do you know? It\rquote s impossible. I won\rquote t believe it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, come, I tell you it\rquote s so. He had one of the big-shot scientists of U. S. Robot & Mechanical Men Corporation over at the office to argue with me.\rdblquote\par
\tab Slowly John\rquote s hands tore at the grass, \ldblquote I see. I see.\rdblquote\par
\tab Byerley said, \ldblquote But we can let him choose his ground. I have an idea. Listen to me and tell me if we can do it--\rdblquote\par
