\tab The scene as it appeared in Alfred Lanning\rquote s office that night was a tableau of stares. Francis Quinn stared meditatively at Alfred Lanning. Lanning\rquote s stare was savagely set upon Susan Calvin, who stared impassively in her turn at Quinn.\par
\tab Francis Quinn broke it with a heavy attempt at lightness, \ldblquote Bluff. He\rquote s making it up as he goes along.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you going to gamble on that, Mr. Quinn?\rdblquote  asked Dr. Calvin, indifferently.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s your gamble, really.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Look here,\rdblquote  Lanning covered definite pessimism with bluster, \ldblquote we\rquote ve done what you asked. We witnessed the man eat. It\rquote s ridiculous to presume him a robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do \i you\i0  think so?\rdblquote  Quinn shot toward Calvin. \ldblquote Lanning said you were the expert.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning was almost threatening, \ldblquote Now, Susan-\rdblquote\par
\tab Quinn interrupted smoothly, \ldblquote Why not let her talk, man? She\rquote s been sitting there imitating a gatepost for half an hour.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning felt definitely harassed. From what he experienced then to incipient paranoia was but a step. He said, \ldblquote Very well. Have your say, Susan. We won\rquote t interrupt you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin glanced at him humorlessly, then fixed cold eyes on Mr. Quinn. \ldblquote There are only two ways of definitely proving Byerley to be a robot, sir. So far you are presenting circumstantial evidence, with which you can accuse, but not prove -- and I think Mr. Byerley is sufficiently clever to counter that sort of material. You probably think so yourself, or you wouldn\rquote t have come here.\par
\tab\ldblquote The two methods of \i proof\i0  are the physical and the psychological. Physically, you can dissect him or use an X-ray. How to do that would be \i your\i0  problem. Psychologically, his behavior can be studied, for if he \i is\i0  a positronic robot, he must conform to the three Rules of Robotics. A positronic brain cannot be constructed without them. You know the Rules, Mr. Quinn?\rdblquote\par
\tab She spoke them carefully, clearly, quoting word for word the famous bold print on page one of the \ldblquote Handbook of Robotics.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve heard of them,\rdblquote  said Quinn, carelessly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Then the matter is easy to follow,\rdblquote  responded the psychologist, dryly. \ldblquote If Mr. Byerley breaks any of those three rules, he is not a robot. Unfortunately, this procedure works in only one direction. If he lives up to the rules, it proves nothing one way or the other.\rdblquote\par
\tab Quinn raised polite eyebrows, \ldblquote Why not, doctor?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because, if you stop to think of it, the three Rules of Robotics are the essential guiding principles of a good many of the world\rquote s ethical systems. Of course, every human being is supposed to have the instinct of self-preservation. That\rquote s Rule Three to a robot. Also every \lquote good\rquote  human being, with a social conscience and a sense of responsibility, is supposed to defer to proper authority; to listen to his doctor, his boss, his government, his psychiatrist, his fellow man; to obey laws, to follow rules, to conform to custom -- even when they interfere with his comfort or his safety. That\rquote s Rule Two to a robot. Also, every \lquote good\rquote  human being is supposed to love others as himself, protect his fellow man, risk his life to save another. That\rquote s Rule One to a robot. To put it simply -- if Byerley follows all the Rules of Robotics, he may be a robot, and may simply be a very good man.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But,\rdblquote  said Quinn, \ldblquote you\rquote re telling me that you can never prove him a robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I may be able to prove him \i not\i0  a robot\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s not the proof I want.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ll have such proof as exists. You are the only one responsible for your own wants.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Here Lanning\rquote s mind leaped suddenly to the sting of an idea, \ldblquote Has it occurred to anyone,\rdblquote  he ground out, \ldblquote that district attorney is a rather strange occupation for a robot? The prosecution of human beings -- sentencing them to death -- bringing about their infinite harm-\rdblquote\par
\tab Quinn grew suddenly keen, \ldblquote No, you can\rquote t get out of it that way. Being district attorney doesn\rquote t make him human. Don\rquote t you know his record? Don\rquote t you know that he boasts that he has never prosecuted an innocent man; that there are scores of people left untried because the evidence against them didn\rquote t satisfy him, even though he could probably have argued a jury into atomizing them? That happens to be so.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning\rquote s thin cheeks quivered, \ldblquote No, Quinn, no. There is nothing in the Rules of Robotics that makes any allowance for human guilt. A robot may not judge whether a human being deserves death. It is not for him to decide. \i He may not harm a human\i0 --variety skunk, or variety angel.\rdblquote\par
\tab Susan Calvin sounded tired. \ldblquote Alfred,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote don\rquote t talk foolishly. What if a robot came upon a madman about to set fire to a house with people in it? He would stop the madman, wouldn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And if the only way he could stop him was to kill him-\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a faint sound in Lanning\rquote s throat. Nothing more.\par
\tab\ldblquote The answer to that, Alfred, is that he would do his best not to kill him. If the madman died, the robot would require psychotherapy because he might easily go mad at the conflict presented him --of having broken Rule One to adhere to Rule One in a higher sense. But a man would be dead and a robot would have killed him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, \i is\i0  Byerley mad?\rdblquote  demanded Lanning; with all the sarcasm he could muster.\par
\tab\ldblquote No, but he has killed no man himself. He has exposed facts which might represent a particular human being to be dangerous to the large mass of other human beings we call society. He protects the greater number and thus adheres to Rule One at maximum potential. That is as far as he goes. It is the judge who then condemns the criminal to death or imprisonment, after the jury decides on his guilt or innocence. It is the jailer who imprisons him, the executioner who kills him. And Mr. Byerley has done nothing but determine truth and aid society.\par
\tab\ldblquote As a matter of fact, Mr. Quinn, I have looked into Mr. Byerley\rquote s career since you first brought this matter to our attention. I find that he has never demanded the death sentence in his closing speeches to the jury. I also find that he has spoken on behalf of the abolition of capital punishment and contributed generously to research institutions engaged in criminal neurophysiology. He apparently believes in the cure, rather than the punishment of crime. I find that significant.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You do?\rdblquote  Quinn smiled. \ldblquote Significant of a certain odor of roboticity, perhaps?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps. Why deny it? Actions such as his could come only from a robot, or from a very honorable and decent human being. But you see, you just can\rquote t differentiate between a robot and the very best of humans.\rdblquote\par
\tab Quinn sat back in his chair. His voice quivered with impatience. \ldblquote Dr. Lanning, it\rquote s perfectly possible to create a humanoid robot that would perfectly duplicate a human in appearance, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning harrumphed and considered, \ldblquote It\rquote s been done experimentally by U. S. Robots,\rdblquote  he said reluctantly, \ldblquote without the addition of a positronic brain, of course. By using human ova and hormone control, one can grow human flesh and skin over a skeleton of porous silicone plastics that would defy external examination. The eyes, the hair, the skin would be really human, not humanoid. And if you put a positronic brain, and such other gadgets as you might desire inside, you have a humanoid robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab Quinn said shortly, \ldblquote How long would it take to make one?\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning considered, \ldblquote If you had all your equipment -- the brain, the skeleton, the ovum, the proper hormones and radiations -- say, two months.\rdblquote\par
\tab The politician straightened out of his chair. \ldblquote Then we shall see what the insides of Mr. Byerley look like. It will mean publicity for U. S. Robots -- but I gave you your chance.\rdblquote\par
\tab Lanning turned impatiently to Susan Calvin, when they were alone. \ldblquote Why do you insist-\rdblquote ?\par
\tab And with real feeling, she responded sharply and instantly, \ldblquote Which do you want -- the truth or my resignation? I won\rquote t lie for you. U. S. Robots can take care of itself. Don\rquote t turn coward.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What,\rdblquote  said Lanning, \ldblquote if he opens up Byerley, and wheels and gears fall out what then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He won\rquote t open Byerley,\rdblquote  said Calvin, disdainfully. \ldblquote Byerley is as clever as Quinn, at the very least\rdblquote\par
