\tab The news broke upon the city a week before Byerley was to have been nominated. But \ldblquote broke\rdblquote  is the wrong word. It staggered upon the city, shambled, crawled. Laughter began, and wit was free. And as the far off hand of Quinn tightened its pressure in easy stages, the laughter grew forced, an element of hollow uncertainty entered, and people broke off to wonder.\par
\tab The convention itself had the sir of a restive stallion. There had been no contest planned. Only Byerley could possibly have been nominated a week earlier. There was no substitute even now. They had to nominate him, but there was complete confusion about it.\par
\tab It would not have been so bad if the average individual were not torn between the enormity of the charge, if true, and its sensational folly, if false.\par
