\tab What broke loose is popularly and succinctly described as hell.\par
\tab It was what the Fundamentalists were waiting for. They were not a political party; they made pretense to no formal religion. Essentially they were those who had not adapted themselves to what had once been called the Atomic Age, in the days when atoms were a novelty. Actually, they were the Simple-Lifers, hungering after a life, which to those who lived it had probably appeared not so Simple, and who had been, therefore, Simple-Lifers themselves.\par
\tab The Fundamentalists required no new reason to detest robots and robot manufacturers; but a new reason such as the Quinn accusation and the Calvin analysis was sufficient to make such detestation audible.\par
\tab The huge plants of the U. S. Robot & Mechanical Men Corporation was a hive that spawned armed guards. It prepared for war.\par
\tab Within the city the house of Stephen Byerley bristled with police.\par
\tab The political campaign, of course, lost all other issues, and resembled a campaign only in that it was something filling the hiatus between nomination and election.\par
