\tab Dr. Calvin and Stephen Byerley met once again -- a week before he took the oath of office as mayor. It was late -- past midnight.\par
\tab Dr. Calvin said, \ldblquote You don\rquote t look tired.\rdblquote\par
\tab The mayor-elect smiled. \ldblquote I may stay up for a while. Don\rquote t tell Quinn.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I shan\rquote t. But that was an interesting story of Quinn\rquote s, since you mention him. It\rquote s a shame to have spoiled it. I suppose you knew his theory?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Parts of it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It was highly dramatic. Stephen Byerley was a young lawyer, a powerful speaker, a great idealist -- and with a certain flare for biophysics. Are you interested in robotics, Mr. Byerley?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Only in the legal aspects.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote\i This\i0  Stephen Byerley was. But there was an accident. Byerley\rquote s wife died, he himself, worse. His legs were gone; his face was gone; his voice was gone. Part of his mind was bent. He would not submit to plastic surgery. He retired from the world, legal career gone -- only his intelligence, and his hands left. Somehow he could obtain positronic brains, even a complex one, one which had the greatest capacity of forming judgments in ethical problems -- which is the highest robotic function so far developed.\par
\tab\ldblquote He grew a body about it. Trained it to be everything he would have been and was no longer. He sent it out into the world as Stephen Byerley, remaining behind himself as the old, crippled teacher that no one ever saw-\rdblquote\par
