\tab\ldblquote How did that happen? Do you mind telling me? It couldn\rquote t have been accidental.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t entirely. Quinn did most of the work. My men started quietly spreading the fact that I had never hit a man; that I was unable to hit a man; that to fail to do so under provocation would be sure proof that I was a robot. So I arranged for a silly speech in public, with all sorts of publicity overtones, and almost inevitably, some fool fell for it. In its essence, it was what I call a shyster trick. One in which the artificial atmosphere which has been created does all the work. Of course, the emotional effects made my election certain, as intended.\rdblquote\par
\tab The robopsychologist nodded. \ldblquote I see you intrude on my field -- as every politician must, I suppose. But I\rquote m very sorry it turned out this way. I like robots. I like them considerably better than I do human beings. If a robot can be created capable of being a civil executive, I think he\rquote d make the best one possible. By the Laws of Robotics, he\rquote d be incapable of harming humans, incapable of tyranny, of corruption, of stupidity, of prejudice. And after he had served a decent term, he would leave, even though he were immortal, because it would be impossible for him to hurt humans by letting them know that a robot had ruled them. It would be most ideal.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Except that a robot might fail due to the inherent inadequacies of his brain. The positronic brain has never equaled the complexities of the human brain.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He would have advisers. Not even a human brain is capable of governing without assistance.\rdblquote\par
\tab Byerley considered Susan Calvin with grave interest. \ldblquote Why do you smile, Dr. Calvin?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I smile because Mr. Quinn didn\rquote t think of everything.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean there could be more to that story of his.\rdblquote\par
