\tab Harriman sat alone. In the artificially lit interior of his office, there was no indication that it had grown dark outside. He had no real sense that three hours had passed since he had taken George Ten back to his cubicle and left him there with the first film references. \par
\tab He was now merely alone with the ghost of Susan Calvin, the brilliant roboticist who had, virtually single-handed, built up the positronic robot from a massive toy to man\rquote s most delicate and versatile instrument; so delicate and versatile that man dared not use it, out of envy and fear. \par
\tab It was over a century now since she had died. The problem of the Frankenstein complex had existed in \i her \i0 time, and she had never solved it. She had never tried to solve it, for there had been no need. Robotics had expanded in her day with the needs of space exploration. \par
\tab It was the very success of the robots that had lessened man\rquote s need for them and had left Harriman, in these latter times--\par
\tab But would Susan Calvin have turned to robots for help. Surely, she would have--\par
\tab And he sat there long into the night. \par
