\pard\qc\f0 3.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Gerald Martin took Andrew to the regional offices of the United States Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation. As a member of the Regional Legislature he had no trouble at all in gaining an interview with the chief robopsychologist. In fact, it was only as a member of the Regional Legislature that he qualified as a robot owner in the first place-- in those early days when robots were rare.\par
\tab Andrew did not understand any of this at the time. But in later years, with greater learning, he could re-view that early scene and understand it in its proper light.\par
\tab The robopsychologist, Merton Mansky, listened with a growing frown and more than once managed to stop his fingers at the point beyond which they would have irrevocably drummed on the table. He had drawn features and a lined forehead, but he might actually have been younger than he looked.\par
\tab\ldblquote Robotics is not an exact art, Mr. Martin,\rdblquote  Mansky explained. \ldblquote I cannot explain it to you in detail, but the mathematics governing the plotting of the positronic pathways is far too complicated to permit of any but approximate solutions. Naturally, since we build everything around the Three Laws, those are incontrovertible. We will, of course, replace your robot--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  said Sir. \ldblquote There is no question of failure on his part. He performs his assigned duties perfectly. The point is he also carves wood in exquisite fashion and never the same twice. He produces works of art.\rdblquote\par
\tab Mansky looked confused. \ldblquote Strange. Of course, we\rquote re attempting generalized pathways these days. Really creative, you think?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote See for yourself.\rdblquote  Sir handed over a little sphere of wood on which there was a playground scene in which the boys and girls were almost too small to make out, yet they were in perfect proportion and they blended so naturally with the grain that it, too, seemed to have been carved.\par
\tab Mansky was incredulous. \ldblquote\i He\i0  did that?\rdblquote  He handed it back with a shake of his head. \ldblquote The luck of the draw. Something in the pathways.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can you do it again?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Probably not. Nothing like this has ever been reported.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good! I don\rquote t in the least mind Andrew\rquote s being the only one.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I suspect that the company would like to have your robot back for study,\rdblquote  Mansky said.\par
\tab\ldblquote Not a chance!\rdblquote  Sir said with sudden grimness. \ldblquote Forget it.\rdblquote  He turned to Andrew, \ldblquote Let\rquote s go home, now.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 4.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Miss was dating boys and wasn\rquote t about the house much. It was Little Miss, not as little as she once was, who filled Andrew\rquote s horizon now. She never forgot that the very first piece of wood carving he had done had been for her. She kept it on a silver chain about her neck.\par
\tab It was she who first objected to Sir\rquote s habit of giving away Andrew\rquote s work. \ldblquote Come on, Dad, if anyone wants one of them, let him pay for it. It\rquote s worth it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It isn\rquote t like you to be greedy, Mandy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not for us, Dad. For the artist.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew had never heard the word before, and when he had a moment to himself he looked it up in the dictionary.\par
\tab Then there was another trip, this time to Sir\rquote s lawyer.\par
\tab\ldblquote What do you think of this, John?\rdblquote  Sir asked.\par
\tab The lawyer was John Finegold. He had white hair and a pudgy belly, and the rims of his contact lenses were tinted a bright green. He looked at the small plaque Sir had given him. \ldblquote This is beautiful. But I\rquote ve already heard the news. Isn\rquote t thus a carving made by your robot? The one you\rquote ve brought with you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Andrew does them. Don\rquote t you, Andrew?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Sir,\rdblquote  said Andrew.\par
\tab\ldblquote How much would you pay for that, John?\rdblquote  Sir asked.\par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t say. I\rquote m not a collector of such things.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Would you believe I have been offered two hundred and fifty dollars for that small thing. Andrew has made chairs that have sold for five hundred dollars. There\rquote s two hundred thousand dollars in the bank from Andrew\rquote s products.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good heavens, he\rquote s making you rich, Gerald.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Half rich,\rdblquote  said Sir. \ldblquote Half of it is in an account in the name of Andrew Martin.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The robot?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right, and I want to know if it\rquote s legal.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Legal . . . ?\rdblquote  Feingold\rquote s chair creaked as he leaned back in it. \ldblquote There are no precedents, Gerald. How did your robot sign the necessary papers?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He can sign his name. Now, is there anything further that ought to be done?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Um.\rdblquote  Feingold\rquote s eyes seemed to turn inward for a moment. Then he said, \ldblquote Well, we can set up a trust to handle all finances in his name and that will place a layer of insulation between him and the hostile world. Beyond that, my advice is you do nothing. No one has e stopped you so far. If anyone objects, let \i him\i0  bring suit\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And will you take the case if the suit is brought?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For a retainer, certainly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How much?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Something like that,\rdblquote  Feingold said, and pointed to the wooden plaque.\par
\tab\ldblquote Fair enough,\rdblquote  said Sir.\par
\tab Feingold chuckled as he turned to the robot. \ldblquote Andrew, are you pleased that you have money?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What do you plan to do with it?\rdblquote  Pay for things, sir, which otherwise Sir \ldblquote would have to pay for. It would save him expense, sir.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 5.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Such occasions\rquote  arose. Repairs were expensive, and revisions were even more so. With the years, new models of robots were produced and Sir saw to it that Andrew had the advantage of every new device, until he was a model of metallic excellence. It was all done at Andrew\rquote s expense. Andrew insisted on that.\par
\tab Only his positronic pathways were untouched. Sir insisted on that.\par
\tab\ldblquote The new models aren\rquote t as good as you are, Andrew,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote The new robots are worthless. The company has learned to make the pathways more precise, more closely on the nose, more deeply on the track. The new robots don\rquote t shift. They do what they\rquote re designed for and never stray. I like you better.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you, Sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And it\rquote s your doing, Andrew, don\rquote t you forget that. I am certain Mansky put an end to generalized pathways as soon as he had a good look at you. He didn\rquote t like the unpredictability. Do you know how many times he asked for you back so he could place you under study? Nine times! I never let him have you, though; and now that he\rquote s retired, we may have some peace.\rdblquote\par
\tab So Sir\rquote s hair thinned and grayed and his face grew pouchy, while Andrew looked even better than he had when he first joined the family. Ma\rquote am had joined an art colony somewhere in Europe, and Miss was a poet in New York. They wrote sometimes, but not often. Little Miss was married and lived not far away. She said she did not want to leave Andrew. When her child, Little Sir, was born, she let Andrew hold the bottle and feed him.\par
\tab With the birth of a grandson, Andrew felt that Sir finally had someone to replace those who had gone. Therefore, it would not be so unfair now to come to him with the request.\par
\tab\ldblquote Sir, it is kind of you to have allowed me to spend my money as I wished\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It was your money, Andrew.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Only by your voluntary act, Sir. I do not believe the law would have stopped you from keeping it all.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The law won\rquote t persuade me to do wrong, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Despite all expenses, and despite taxes, too, Sir, I have nearly six hundred thousand dollars.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know that, Andrew.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I want to give it to you, Sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I won\rquote t take it, Andrew\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In exchange for something you can give me, Sir\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh? What is that, Andrew?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote My freedom, Sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Your--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I wish to buy my freedom, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 6.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 It wasn\rquote t that easy. Sir had flushed, had said, \ldblquote For God\rquote s sake!\rdblquote  Then he had turned on his heel and stalked away.\par
\tab It was Little Miss who finally brought him round, defiantly and harshly-- and in front of Andrew. For thirty years no one had ever hesitated to talk in front of Andrew, whether or not the matter involved Andrew. He was only a robot.\par
\tab\ldblquote Dad, why are you taking this as a personal affront? He\rquote ll still be here. He\rquote ll still be loyal. He can\rquote t help that; it\rquote s built in. All he wants is a form of words. Ha wants to be called free. Is that so terrible? Hasn\rquote t be earned this chance? Heavens, he and I have been talking about it for years!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Talking about it for years, have you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, and over and over again he postponed it for fear he would hurt you. I \i made\i0  him put the matter up to you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He doesn\rquote t know what freedom is. He\rquote s a robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Dad, you don\rquote t know him. He\rquote s read everything in the library. I don\rquote t know what he feels inside, but I don\rquote t know what \i you\i0  feel inside either. When you talk to him you\rquote ll find he reacts to the various abstractions as you and I do, and what else counts? If some one else\rquote s reactions are like your own, what more can you ask for?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The law won\rquote t take that attitude,\rdblquote  Sir said, angrily. \ldblquote See here, you!\rdblquote  He turned to Andrew with a deliberate grate in his voice. \ldblquote I can\rquote t free you except by doing it legally. If this gets into the courts, you not only won\rquote t get your freedom but the law will take official cognizance of your money. They\rquote ll tell you that a robot has no right to earn money. Is this rigmarole worth losing your money?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Freedom is without price, Sir,\rdblquote  said Andrew. \ldblquote Even the chance of freedom is worth the money.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 7.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 It seemed the court might also take the attitude that freedom was without price, and might decide that for no price, however great, could a robot buy its freedom.\par
\tab The simple statement of the regional attorney who represented those who had brought a class action to oppose the freedom was this: \ldblquote The word `freedom\rquote  has no meaning when applied to a robot. Only a human being can be free.\rdblquote  He said it several times, when it seemed appropriate; slowly, with his hand coming down rhythmically on the desk before him to mark the words.\par
\tab Little Miss asked permission to speak on behalf of Andrew.\par
\tab She was recognized by her full name, something Andrew had never heard pronounced before: \ldblquote Amanda Laura Martin Charney may approach the bench.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you, Your Honor. I am not a lawyer and I don\rquote t know the proper way of phrasing things, but I hope you will listen to my meaning and ignore the words.\par
\tab\ldblquote Let\rquote s understand what it means to be free in Andrew\rquote s case. In some ways, he \i is\i0  free. I think it\rquote s at least twenty years since anyone in the Martin family gave him an order to do something that we felt he might not do of his own accord. But we can, if we wish, give him an order to do anything, couching it as harshly as we wish, because he is a machine that belongs to us. Why should we be in a position to do so, when he has served us so long, so faithfully, and has earned so much money for us? He owes us nothing more. The debit is entirely on the other side.\par
\tab\ldblquote Even if we were legally forbidden to place Andrew in involuntary servitude, he would still serve us voluntarily. Making him free would be a trick of words only, but it would mean much to him. It would give him everything and cost us nothing.\rdblquote\par
\tab For a moment the judge seemed to be suppressing a smile. \ldblquote I see your point, Mrs. Chamey. The fact is that there is no binding law in this respect and no precedent. There is, however, the unspoken assumption that only a man may enjoy freedom. I can make new law here, subject to reversal in a higher court; but I cannot lightly run counter to that assumption. Let me address the robot. Andrew!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Your Honor.\rdblquote\par
\tab It was the first time Andrew bad spoken in court, and the judge seemed astonished for a moment at the human timbre of his voice.\par
\tab\ldblquote Why do you want to be free, Andrew? In what way will this matter to you?\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew said, \ldblquote Would you wish to be a slave, Your Honor?\rdblquote\par
\f3\tab\f0\ldblquote But you are not a slave. You are a perfectly good robot-- a genius of a robot, I am given to understand, capable of an artistic expression that can be matched nowhere. What more could you do if you were free?\rdblquote\par
\f3\tab\f0\ldblquote Perhaps no more than I do now, Your Honor, but with greater joy. It has been said in this courtroom that only a human being can be free. It seems to me that only someone who wishes for freedom can be free. I wish for freedom.\rdblquote\par
\tab And it was that statement that cued the judge. The crucial sentence in his decision was \ldblquote There is no right to deny freedom to any object with a mind advanced enough to grasp the concept and desire the state.\rdblquote  It was eventually upheld by the World Court. \par
\par
\pard\qc 8.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Sir remained displeased, and his harsh voice made Andrew feel as if he were being short-circuited. \ldblquote I don\rquote t want your damned money, Andrew. I\rquote ll take it only because you won\rquote t feel free otherwise. From now on, you can select your own jobs and do them as you please. I will give you no orders, except this one: Do as you please. But I am still responsible for you. That\rquote s part of the court order. I hope you understand that.\rdblquote\par
\tab Little Miss interrupted. \ldblquote Don\rquote t be irascible, Dad. The responsibility is no great chore. You know you won\rquote t have to do a thing. The Three Laws still hold.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then how is he free?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are not human beings bound by their laws, Sir?\rdblquote  Andrew replied.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m not going to argue.\rdblquote  Sir left the room, and Andrew saw him only infrequently after that.\par
\tab Little Miss came to see him frequently in the small house that had been built and made over for him. It had no kitchen, of course, nor bathroom facilities. It had just two rooms; one was a library and one was a combination storeroom and workroom. Andrew accepted many commissions and worked harder as a free robot than he ever had before, till the cost of the house was paid for and the structure was signed over to him.\par
\tab One day Little Sir-- no, \ldblquote George!\rdblquote -- came. Little Sir had insisted on that after the court decision. \ldblquote A free robot doesn\rquote t call anyone Little Sir,\rdblquote  George had said. \ldblquote I call you Andrew. You must call me George.\rdblquote\par
\tab His preference was phrased as an order, so Andrew called him George-- but Little Miss remained Little Miss.\par
\tab One day when George came alone, it was to say that Sir was dying. Little Miss was at the bedside, but Sir wanted Andrew as well.\par
\tab Sir\rquote s voice was still quite strong, though he seemed unable to move much. He struggled to raise his hand.\par
\tab\ldblquote Andrew,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote Andrew-- Don\rquote t help me, George. I\rquote m only dying; I\rquote m not crippled. Andrew, I\rquote m glad you\rquote re free. I just wanted to tell you that.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew did not know what to say. He had never been at the side of someone dying before, but he knew it was the human way of ceasing to function. It was an involuntary and irreversible dismantling, and Andrew did not know what to say that might be appropriate. He could only remain standing, absolutely silent, absolutely motionless.\par
\tab When it was over, Little Miss said to him, \ldblquote He may not have seemed friendly to you toward the end, Andrew, but he was old, you know; and it hurt him that you should want to be free.\rdblquote\par
\tab Then Andrew found the words. \ldblquote I would never have been free without him, Little Miss.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 9.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Only after Sir\rquote s death did Andrew begin to wear clothes. He began with an old pair of trousers at first, a pair that George had given him.\par
\tab George was married now, and a lawyer. He had joined Feingold\rquote s firm. Old Feingold was long since dead, but his daughter had carried on. Eventually the firm\rquote s name became Feingold and Martin. It remained so even when the daughter retired and no Feingold took her place. At the time Andrew first put on clothes, the Martin name had just been added to the firm.\par
\tab George had tried not to smile the first time he saw Andrew attempting to put on trousers, but to Andrew\rquote s eyes the smile was clearly there. George showed Andrew how to manipulate the static charge to allow the trousers to open, wrap about his lower body, and move shut. George demonstrated on his own trousers, but Andrew was quite aware it would take him a while to duplicate that one flowing motion.\par
\tab\ldblquote But why do you want trousers, Andrew? Your body is so beautifully functional it\rquote s a shame to cover it especially when you needn\rquote t worry about either temperature control or modesty. And the material doesn\rquote t cling properly-- not on metal.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew held his ground. \ldblquote Are not human bodies beautifully functional, George? Yet you cover yourselves.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For warmth, for cleanliness, for protection, for decorativeness. None of that applies to you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I feel bare without clothes. I feel different, George,\rdblquote  Andrew responded.\par
\tab\ldblquote Different! Andrew, there are millions of robots on Earth now. In this region, according to the last census, there are almost as many robots as there are men.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know, George. There are robots doing every conceivable type of work.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And none of them wear clothes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But none of them are free, George.\rdblquote\par
\tab Little by little, Andrew added to his wardrobe. He was inhibited by George\rquote s smile and by the stares of the people who commissioned work.\par
\tab He might be free, but there was built into Andrew a carefully detailed program concerning his behavior to people, and it was only by the tiniest steps that he dared advance; open disapproval would set him back months. Not everyone accepted Andrew as free. He was incapable of resenting that, and yet there was a difficulty about his thinking process when he thought of it. Most of all, he tended to avoid putting on clothes-- or too many of them-- when he thought Little Miss might come to visit him. She was older now and was often away in some warmer climate, but when she returned the first thing she did was visit him.\par
\tab On one of her visits, George said, ruefully, \ldblquote She\rquote s got me, Andrew. I\rquote ll be running for the legislature next year. `Like grandfather,\rquote  she says, `like grandson.\rquote\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Like grandfather . . .\rdblquote  Andrew stopped, uncertain.\par
\tab\ldblquote I mean that I, George, the grandson, will be like Sir, the grandfather, who was in the legislature once.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It would be pleasant, George, if Sir were still--\rdblquote  He paused, for he did not want to say, \ldblquote in working order.\rdblquote  That seemed inappropriate.\par
\tab\ldblquote Alive;\rdblquote  George said. \ldblquote Yes, I think of the old monster now and then, too.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew often thought about this conversation. He had noticed his own incapacity in speech when talking with George. Somehow the language had changed since Andrew had come into being with a built-in vocabulary. Then, too, George used a colloquial speech, as Sir and Little Miss had not. Why should he have called Sir a monster when surely that word was not a appropriate. Andrew could not even turn to his own books for guidance. They were old, and most dealt with woodworking, with art, with furniture design. There were none on language, none on the ways of human beings.\par
\tab Finally, it seemed to him that he must seek the proper books; and as a free robot, he felt he must not ask George. He would go to town and use the library. It was a triumphant decision and he felt his electro potential grow distinctly higher until he had to throw in an impedance coil.\par
\tab He put on a full costume, including even a shoulder chain of wood. He would have preferred the glitter plastic, but George had said that wood was much more appropriate, and that polished cedar was considerably more valuable as well.\par
\tab He had placed a hundred feet between himself and the house before gathering resistance brought him to a halt. He shifted the impedance coil out of circuit, and when that did not seem to help enough he returned to his home and on a piece of notepaper wrote neatly, \ldblquote I have gone to the library,\rdblquote  and placed it in clear view on his worktable. \par
\par
\pard\qc 10.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Andrew never quite got to the library.\par
\tab He had studied the map. He knew the route, but not the appearance of it. The actual landmarks did not resemble the symbols on the map and he would hesitate. Eventually, he thought he must have somehow gone wrong, for everything looked strange.\par
\tab He passed an occasional field-robot, but by the time he decided he should ask his way none were in sight. A vehicle passed and did not stop.\par
\tab Andrew stood irresolute, which meant calmly motionless, for coming across the field toward him were two human beings.\par
\tab He turned to face them, and they altered their course to meet him. A moment before, they had been talking loudly. He had heard their voices. But now they were silent. They had the look that Andrew associated with human uncertainty; and they were young, but not very young. Twenty, perhaps? Andrew could never judge human age.\par
\tab\ldblquote Would you describe to me the route to the town library, sirs?\rdblquote\par
\tab One of them, the taller of the two, whose tall hat lengthened him still farther, almost grotesquely, said, not to Andrew, but to the other, \ldblquote It\rquote s a robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab The other had a bulbous nose and heavy eyelids. He said, not to Andrew but to the first, \ldblquote It\rquote s wearing clothes.\rdblquote\par
\tab The tall one snapped his fingers. \ldblquote It\rquote s the free robot. They have a robot at the old Martin place who isn\rquote t owned by anybody. Why else would it be wearing clothes?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Ask it,\rdblquote  said the one with the nose.\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you the Martin robot?\rdblquote  asked the tall one.\par
\tab\ldblquote I am Andrew Martin, sir,\rdblquote  Andrew said.\par
\tab\ldblquote Good. Take off your clothes. Robots don\rquote t wear clothes.\rdblquote  He said to the other, \ldblquote That\rquote s disgusting. Look at him!\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew hesitated. He hadn\rquote t heard an order in that tone of voice in so long that his Second Law circuits had momentarily jammed.\par
\tab The tall one repeated, \ldblquote Take off your clothes. I order you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Slowly, Andrew began to remove them.\par
\tab\ldblquote Just drop them,\rdblquote  said the tall one.\par
\tab The nose said, \ldblquote If it doesn\rquote t belong to anyone, it could be ours as much as someone else\rquote s.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Anyway,\rdblquote  said the tall one, \ldblquote who\rquote s to object to anything we do. We\rquote re not damaging property.\rdblquote  tie turned to Andrew. \ldblquote Stand on your head.\rdblquote  \ldblquote The head is not meant-\rdblquote  Andrew began.\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s an order. If you don\rquote t know how, try anyway.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew hesitated again, then bent to put his head on the ground. He tried to lift his legs but fell, heavily.\par
\tab The tall one said, \ldblquote Just lie there.\rdblquote  He said to the other, \ldblquote We can take him apart. Ever take a robot apart?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Will he let us?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How can he stop us?\rdblquote\par
\tab There was no way Andrew could stop them, if they ordered him in a forceful enough manner not to resist The Second Law of obedience took precedence over the Third Law of self-preservation. In any case, he could not defend himself without possibly hurting them, and that would mean breaking the First Law. At that thought, he felt every motile unit contract slightly and he quivered as he lay there.\par
\tab The tall one walked over and pushed at him with his foot. \ldblquote He\rquote s heavy. I think we\rquote ll need tools to do the job.\rdblquote\par
\tab The nose said, \ldblquote We could order him to take himself, apart. It would be fun to watch him try.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said the tall one, thoughtfully, \ldblquote but let\rquote s get him off the road. If someone comes along--\rdblquote\par
\tab It was too late. Someone had, indeed, come along and it was George. From where he lay, Andrew had seen him topping a small rise in the middle distance. He would have liked to signal him in some way, but the last order had been \ldblquote Just lie there!\rdblquote\par
\tab George was running now, and he arrived on the scene somewhat winded. The two young men stepped back a little and then waited thoughtfully.\par
\tab\ldblquote Andrew, has something gone wrong?\rdblquote  George asked, anxiously.\par
\tab Andrew replied, \ldblquote I am well, George.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then stand up. What happened to your clothes?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That your robot, Mac?\rdblquote  the tall young man asked.\par
\tab George turned sharply. \ldblquote He\rquote s no one\rquote s robot. What\rquote s been going on here.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We politely asked him to take his clothes off. What\rquote s that to you, if you don\rquote t own him.\rdblquote\par
\tab George turned to Andrew. \ldblquote What were they doing, Andrew?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It was their intention in some way to dismember me. They were about to move me to a quiet spot and order me to dismember myself.\rdblquote\par
\tab George looked at the two young men, and his chin trembled.\par
\tab The young men retreated no farther. They were smiling.\par
\tab The tall one said, lightly, \ldblquote What are you going to do, pudgy? Attack us?\rdblquote\par
\tab George said, \ldblquote No. I don\rquote t have to. This robot has been with my family for over seventy-five years. He knows us and he values us more than he values anyone else. I am going to tell him that you two are threatening my life and that you plan to kill me. I will ask him to defend me. In choosing between me and you two, he will choose me. Do you know what will happen to you when he attacks you?\rdblquote\par
\tab The two were backing away slightly, looking uneasy.\par
\tab George said, sharply, \ldblquote Andrew, I am in danger and about to come to harm from these young men. Move toward them!\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew did so, and the young men did not wait. They ran.\par
\tab\ldblquote All right, Andrew, relax,\rdblquote  George said. He looked unstrung. He was far past the age where he could face the possibility of a dustup with one young man, let alone two.\par
\tab\ldblquote I couldn\rquote t have hurt them, George: I could see they were not attacking you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I didn\rquote t order you to attack them. I only told you to move toward them. Their own fears did the rest.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How can they fear robots?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s a disease of mankind, one which has not yet been cured. But never mind that. What the devil are you doing here, Andrew? Good thing I found your note. I was just on the point of turning back and hiring a helicopter when I found you. How did you get it into your head to go to the library? I would have brought you any books you needed\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I am a--\rdblquote  Andrew began.\par
\tab\ldblquote Free robot. Yes, yes. All right, what did you want in the library?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I want to know more about human beings, about the world, about everything. And about robots, George. I want to write a history about robots.\rdblquote\par
\tab George put his arm on the other\rquote s shoulder. \ldblquote Well, let\rquote s walk home. But pick up your clothes first. Andrew, there are a million books on robotics and all of them include histories of the science. The world is growing saturated not only with robots but with information about robots.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew shook his head, a human gesture he had lately begun to adopt. \ldblquote Not a history of robotics, George. A history of \i robots\i0 , by a robot. I want to explain how robots feel about what has happened since the first ones were allowed to work and live on Earth.\rdblquote\par
\tab George\rquote s eyebrows lifted, but he said nothing in direct response. \par
\par
\pard\qc 11.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Little Miss was just past her eighty-third birthday, but there was nothing about her that was lacking in either energy or determination. She gestured with her cane oftener than she propped herself up with it.\par
\tab She listened to the story in a fury of indignation. \ldblquote George, that\rquote s horrible. Who were those young ruffians?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. What difference does it make? In the end they did not do any damage.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They might have. You\rquote re a lawyer, George; and if you\rquote re well off, it\rquote s entirely due to the talents of Andrew. It was the money \i he\i0  earned that is the foundation of everything we have. He provides the continuity for this family, and I will \i not\i0  have him treated as a wind-up toy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What would you have me do, Mother?\rdblquote  George asked.\par
\tab\ldblquote I said you\rquote re a lawyer. Don\rquote t you listen? You set up a test case somehow, and you force the regional courts to declare for robot rights and get the legislature to pass the necessary bills. Carry the whole thing to the World Court, if you have to. I\rquote ll be watching, George, and I\rquote ll tolerate no shirking.\rdblquote\par
\tab She was serious, so what began as a way of soothing the fearsome old lady became an involved matter with enough legal entanglement to make it interesting. As senior partner of Feingold and Martin, George plotted strategy. But he left the actual work to his junior partners, with much of it a matter for his son, Paul, who was also a member of the firm and who reported dutifully nearly every day to his grandmother. She, in turn, discussed the case every day with Andrew.\par
\tab Andrew was deeply involved. His work on his book on robots was delayed again, as he pored over the legal arguments and even, at times, made very diffident suggestions. \par
\tab\ldblquote George told me that day I was attacked that human beings have always been afraid of robots,\rdblquote  he said one day. \ldblquote As long as they are, the courts and the legislatures are not likely to work hard on behalf of robots. Should not something be done about public opinion?\rdblquote\par
\tab So while Paul stayed in court, George took to the public platform. It gave him the advantage of being informal, and he even went so far sometimes as to wear the new, loose style of clothing which he called drapery.\par
\tab Paul chided him, \ldblquote Just don\rquote t trip over it on stage, Dad.\rdblquote\par
\tab George replied, despondently, \ldblquote I\rquote ll try not to.\rdblquote\par
\tab He addressed the annual convention of holo-news editors on one occasion and said, in part: \ldblquote If, by virtue of the Second Law, we can demand of any robot unlimited obedience in all respects not involving harm to a human being, then any human being, \i any\i0  human being, has a fearsome power over any robot, \i any\i0  robot. In particular, since Second Law supersedes Third Law; \i any\i0  human being can use the law of obedience to overcome the law of self-protection. He can order any robot to damage itself or even to destroy itself for any reason, or for no reason.\par
\tab\ldblquote Is this just? Would we treat an animal so? Even an inanimate object which had given us good service has a claim on our consideration. And a robot is not insensitive; it is not an animal. It can think well enough so that it can talk to us, reason with us, joke with us. Can we treat them as friends, can we work together with them, and not give them some of the fruits of that friendship, some of the benefits of co-working?\par
\tab\ldblquote If a man has the right to give a robot any order that does not involve harm to a human being, he should have the decency never to give a robot any order that involves harm to a robot, unless human safety absolutely requires it. With great power goes great responsibility, and if the robots have Three Laws to protect men, is it too much to ask that men have a law or two to protect robots?\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew was right. It was the battle over public opinion that held the key to courts and legislature. In the end, a law was passed that set up conditions under which robot-harming orders were forbidden. It was endlessly qualified and the punishments for violating the law were totally inadequate, but the principle was established. The final passage by the World Legislature came through on the day of Little Miss\rquote  death.\par
\tab That was no coincidence. Little Miss held on to life desperately during the last debate and let go only when word of victory arrived. Her last smile was for Andrew. Her last words were, \ldblquote You have been good to us, Andrew.\rdblquote  She died with her hand holding his, while her son and his wife and children remained at a respectful distance from both. \par
\par
\pard\qc 12.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Andrew waited patiently when the receptionist-robot disappeared into the inner office. The receptionist might have used the holographic chatterbox, but un-questionably it was perturbed by having to deal with another robot rather than with a human being.\par
\tab Andrew passed the time revolving the matter his mind: Could \ldblquote unroboted\rdblquote  be used as an analog of \ldblquote unmanned,\rdblquote  or had unmanned become a metaphoric term sufficiently divorced from its original literal meaning to be applied to robots--or to women for that matter? Such problems frequently arose as he worked on his book on robots. The trick of thinking out sentences to express all complexities had undoubtedly increased his vocabulary.\par
\tab Occasionally, someone came into the room to stare at him and he did not try to avoid the glance. He looked at each calmly, and each in turn looked away.\par
\tab Paul Martin finally emerged. He looked surprised, or he would have if Andrew could have made out his expression with certainty. Paul had taken to wearing the heavy makeup that fashion was dictating for bath sexes. Though it made sharper and firmer the somewhat bland lines of Paul\rquote s face, Andrew disapproved. He found that disapproving of human beings, as long as he did not express it verbally, did not make him very uneasy. He could even write the disapproval. He was sure it had not always been so.\par
\tab\ldblquote Come in, Andrew. I\rquote m sorry I made you wait, but there was something I \i had\i0  to finish. Come in, you had said you wanted to talk to me, but I didn\rquote t know you meant here in town.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If you are busy, Paul, I am prepared to continue to wait.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul glanced at the interplay of shifting shadows on the dial on the wall that served as timepieces and said, \ldblquote I can make some time. Did you come alone?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I hired an automatobile.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Any trouble?\rdblquote  Paul asked, with more than a trace of anxiety.\par
\tab\ldblquote I wasn\rquote t expecting any. My rights are protected.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul looked all the more anxious for that. \ldblquote Andrew, I\rquote ve explained that the law is unenforceable, at least under most conditions. And if you insist on wearing clothes, you\rquote ll run into trouble eventually; just like that first time.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And only tine, Paul. I\rquote m sorry you are displeased\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, look at it this way: you are virtually a living legend, Andrew, and you are too valuable in many different ways for you to have any right to take chances with yourself. By the way, how\rquote s the book coming?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I am approaching the end, Paul. The publisher is quite pleased.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know that he\rquote s necessarily pleased with the book as a book. I think he expects to sell many copies because it\rquote s written by a robot and that\rquote s what pleases him.\par
\tab\ldblquote Only human, I\rquote m afraid.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I am not displeased. Let it sell for whatever reason, since it will mean money and I can use some.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Grandmother left you--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Little Miss was generous, and I\rquote m sure I can count on the family to help me out further. But it is the royalties from the book on which I am counting to help me through the next step.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What next step is that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I wish to see the head of U.S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation. I have tried to make an appointment; but so far I have not been able to reach him. The Corporation did not cooperate with me in the writing of the book, so I am not surprised, you understand.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul was clearly amused. \ldblquote Cooperation is the last thing you can expect. They didn\rquote t cooperate with us in our great fight for robot rights. Quite the reverse, and you can see why. Give a robot rights and people may not want to buy them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nevertheless,\rdblquote  said Andrew, \ldblquote if you call them, you may be able to obtain an interview for me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m no more popular with them than you are, Andrew.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But perhaps you can hint that by seeing me they may head off a campaign by Feingold and Martin to strengthen the rights of robots further.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Wouldn\rquote t that be a lie, Andrew?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Paul, and I can\rquote t tell one. That is why you must call.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Ah, you can\rquote t lie, but you can urge me to tell a lie, is that it? You\rquote re getting more human all the time, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 13.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 The meeting was not easy to arrange, even with Paul\rquote s supposedly weighted name.\par
\tab But it finally came about. When it did, Harley Smythe-Robertson, who, on his mother\rquote s side, was descended from the original founder of the corporation and who had adopted the hyphenation to indicate it, looked remarkably unhappy. He was approaching retirement age and his entire tenure as president had been devoted to the matter of robot rights. His gray hair was plastered thinly over the top of his scalp; his face was not made up, and he eyed Andrew with brief hostility from time to time.\par
\tab Andrew began the conversation. \ldblquote Sir, nearly a century ago, I was told by a Merton Mansky of this corporation that the mathematics governing the plotting of the positronic pathways was far too complicated to permit of any but approximate solutions and that, therefore, my own capacities were not fully predictable.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That was a century ago.\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson hesitated, then said icily, \ldblquote\i Sir\i0 . It is true no longer. Our robots are made with precision now and are trained precisely to their jobs.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Paul, who had come along, as he said, to make sure that the corporation played fair, \ldblquote with the result that my receptionist must be guided at every point once events depart from the conventional, however slightly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You would be much more displeased if it were to improvise,\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson said.\par
\tab\ldblquote Then you no longer manufacture robots like myself which are flexible and adaptable.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No longer.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The research I have done in connection with my book,\rdblquote  said Andrew, \ldblquote indicates that I am the oldest robot presently in active operation.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The oldest presently,\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson, \ldblquote and the oldest ever. The oldest that will ever be. No robot is useful after the twenty-fifth year. They are called in and replaced with newer models.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No robot \i as presently manufactured\i0  is useful after the twentieth year,\rdblquote  said Paul, with a note of sarcasm creeping into his voice. \ldblquote Andrew is quite exceptional in this respect.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew, adhering to the path he had marked out for himself, continued, \ldblquote As the oldest robot in the world and the most flexible, am I not unusual enough to merit special treatment from the company?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson said, freezing up. \ldblquote Your unusualness is an embarrassment to the company. If you were on lease, instead of having been an outright sale through some mischance, you would long since have been replaced.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But that is exactly the point,\rdblquote  said Andrew. \ldblquote I am a free robot and I own myself. Therefore I come to you and ask you to replace me. You cannot do this without the owner\rquote s consent. Nowadays, that consent is extorted as a condition of the lease, but in my time this did not happen.\rdblquote\par
\tab Smythe-Robertson was looking both startled and puzzled, and for a moment there was silence. Andrew found himself staring at the hologram on the wall. It was a death mask of Susan Calvin, patron saint of all roboticists. She had been dead for nearly two centuries now, but as a result of writing his book Andrew knew, her so well he could half persuade himself that he had met her in life.\par
\tab Finally Smythe-Robertson asked, \ldblquote How can I replace you for you? If I replace you, as robot, how can I donate the new robot to you as owner since in the very act of replacement you cease to exist.\rdblquote  He smiled grimly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all difficult,\rdblquote  Paul interposed. \ldblquote The seat of Andrew\rquote s personality is his positronic brain and it is the one part that cannot be replaced without creating a new robot. The positronic brain, therefore, is Andrew the owner. Every other part of the robotic body can be replaced without affecting the robot\rquote s personality, and those other parts are the brain\rquote s possessions. Andrew, I should say, wants to supply his brain with a new robotic body.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Andrew, calmly. He turned to Smythe-Robertson. \ldblquote You have manufactured androids, haven\rquote t you? Robots that have the outward appearance of humans, complete to the texture of the skin?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, we have. They worked perfectly well, with their synthetic fibrous skins and tendons. There was virtually no metal anywhere except for the brain, yet they were nearly as tough as metal robots. They were tougher, weight for weight.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul looked interested. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t know that. How many are on the market?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote None,\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson. \ldblquote They were much more expensive than metal models and a market survey showed they would not be accepted. They looked too human.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew was impressed. \ldblquote But the corporation retains its expertise, I assume. Since it does, I wish to request that I be replaced by an organic robot, an android.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul looked surprised. \ldblquote Good Lord!\rdblquote  he said.\par
\tab Smythe-Robertson stiffened. \ldblquote Quite impossible!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why is it impossible?\rdblquote  Andrew asked. \ldblquote I will pay any reasonable fee, of course.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We do not manufacture androids.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You do not \i choose\i0  to manufacture androids,\rdblquote  Paul interjected quickly. \ldblquote That is not the same as being unable to manufacture them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nevertheless,\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson responded, \ldblquote the manufacture of androids is against public policy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There is no law against it,\rdblquote  said Paul.\par
\tab\ldblquote Nevertheless, we do not manufacture them-- and we will not.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul cleared his throat. \ldblquote Mr. Smythe-Robertson,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote Andrew is a free robot who comes under the purview of the law guaranteeing robot rights. You are aware of this, I take it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Only too well.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This robot, as a free robot, chooses to wear clothes. This results in his being frequently humiliated by thoughtless human beings despite the law against the humiliation of robots. It is difficult to prosecute vague offenses that don\rquote t meet with the general disapproval of those who must decide on guilt and innocence.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote U.S. Robots understood that from the start. Your father\rquote s firm unfortunately did not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote My father is dead now, but what I see is that we have here a clear offense with a clear target.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What are you talking about?\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson.\par
\tab\ldblquote My client, Andrew Martin-- he has just become my client-- is a free robot who is entitled to ask U.S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation for the rights of replacement, which the corporation supplies to anyone who owns a robot for more than twenty-five years. In fact, the corporation insists on such replacement.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul was smiling and thoroughly at ease. \ldblquote The positronic brain of my client,\rdblquote  he went on, \ldblquote is the owner of the body of my client which is certainly more than twenty-five years old. The positronic brain demands the replacement of the body and offers to pay any reasonable fee for an android body as that replacement. If you refuse the request, my client undergoes humiliation and we will sue.\par
\tab\ldblquote While public opinion would not ordinarily support the claim of a robot in such a case, may I remind you that U.S. Robots is not popular with the public generally. Even those who most use and profit from robots are suspicious of the corporation. This may be a hangover from the days when robots were widely feared. It may be resentment against the power and wealth of U.S. Robots, which has a worldwide monopoly. Whatever the cause may be, the resentment eats. I think you will find that you would prefer not to be faced with a lawsuit, particularly since my client is wealthy and will live for many more centuries and will have no reason to refrain from fighting the battle forever.\rdblquote\par
\tab Smythe-Robertson had slowly reddened. \ldblquote You are trying to force--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I force you to do nothing,\rdblquote  said Paul. \ldblquote If you wish to refuse to accede to my client\rquote s reasonable request, you may by all means do so and we will leave without another word. But we will sue, as is certainly our right, and you will find that you will eventually lose.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I see that you are going to accede,\rdblquote  said Paul. \ldblquote You may hesitate but you will come to it in the end. Let me assure you, then, of one further point: If, in the process of transferring my client\rquote s positronic brain from his present body to an organic one, there is any damage, however slight, then I will never rest until I\rquote ve nailed the corporation to the ground. I will, if necessary, take every possible step to mobilize public opinion against the corporation if one brain path of my client\rquote s platinum-iridium essence is scrambled.\rdblquote  He turned to Andrew and asked, \ldblquote Do you agree to all this, Andrew?\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew hesitated a full minute. It amounted to the approval of lying, of blackmail, of the badgering and humiliation of a human being. But not physical harm, he told himself, not physical harm.\par
\tab He managed at last to come out with a rather faint \ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 14.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 He felt as though he were being constructed again. For days, then for weeks, finally for months, Andrew found himself not himself somehow, and the simplest actions kept giving rise to hesitation.\par
\tab Paul was frantic. \ldblquote They\rquote ve damaged you, Andrew. We\rquote ll have to institute suit!\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew spoke very slowly. \ldblquote You-- mustn\rquote t. You\rquote ll never be able to prove-- something-- like m-m-m-m-- \ldblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Malice?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Malice. Besides, I grow-- stronger, better. It\rquote s the tr-- tr-- tr-- \ldblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Tremble?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Trauma. After all, there\rquote s never been such an op-op-op-- before.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew could feel his brain from the inside. No one else could. He knew he was well, and during the months that it took him to learn full coordination and full positronic interplay he spent hours before the mirror.\par
\tab Not quite human! The face was stiff-- too stiff and the motions were too deliberate. They lacked the careless, free flow of the human being, but perhaps that might come with time. At least now he could wear clothes without the ridiculous anomaly of a metal face going along with it.\par
\tab Eventually, he said, \ldblquote I will be going back to work.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul laughed. \ldblquote That means you are well. What will you be doing? Another book?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Andrew, seriously. \ldblquote I live too long for any one career to seize me by the throat and never let me go. There was a time when I was primarily an artist, and I can still turn to that. And there was a time when I was a historian, and I can still turn to that. But now I wish to be a robobiologist.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A robopsychologist, you mean.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. That would imply the study of positronic brains, and at the moment I lack the desire to do that. A robobiologist, it seems to me, would be concerned with the working of the body attached to that brain.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Wouldn\rquote t that be a roboticist?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A roboticist works with a metal body. I would be studying an organic humanoid body, of which I have the only one, as far as I know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You narrow your field,\rdblquote  said Paul, thoughtfully. \ldblquote As an artist, all conception is yours; as a historian you deal chiefly with robots; as a robobiologist, you will deal with yourself.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew nodded. \ldblquote It would seem so.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew had to start from the very beginning, for he knew nothing of ordinary biology and almost nothing of science. He became a familiar sight in the libraries, where he sat at the electronic indices for hours at a time, looking perfectly normal in clothes. Those few who knew he was a robot in no way interfered with him.\par
\tab He built a laboratory in a room which he added to his house; and his library grew, too.\par
\tab Years passed, and Paul came to him one day and said, \ldblquote It\rquote s a pity you\rquote re no longer working on the history of robots. I understand U.S. Robots is adopting a radically new policy.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul had aged, and his deteriorating eyes had been replaced with photoptic cells. In that respect, he had drawn closer to Andrew.\par
\tab\ldblquote What have they done?\rdblquote  Andrew asked.\par
\tab\ldblquote They are manufacturing central computers, gigantic positronic brains, really, which communicate with anywhere from a dozen to a thousand robots by microwave. The robots themselves have no brains at all. They are the limbs of the gigantic brain, and the two are physically separate.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is that more efficient?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote U.S. Robots claims it is. Smythe-Robertson established the new direction before he died, however, and it\rquote s my notion that it\rquote s a backlash at you. U.S. Robots is determined that they will make no robots that will give them the type of trouble you have, and for that reason they separate brain and body. The brain will have no body to wish changed; the body will have no brain to wish anything.\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s amazing, Andrew,\rdblquote  Paul went on, \ldblquote the influence you have had on the history of. robots. It was your artistry that encouraged U.S. Robots to make robots more precise and specialized; it was your freedom that resulted in the establishment of the principle of robotic rights; it was your insistence on an android body that made U.S. Robots switch to brain-body separation\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew grew thoughtful. \ldblquote I suppose in the end the corporation will produce one vast brain controlling several billion robotic bodies. All the eggs will be in one basket. Dangerous. Not proper at all.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I think you\rquote re right,\rdblquote  said Paul, \ldblquote but I don\rquote t suspect it will come to pass for a century at least and I won\rquote t live to see it. In fact, I may not live to see next year.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Paul!\rdblquote  cried Andrew, in concern.\par
\tab Paul shrugged. \ldblquote Men are mortal, Andrew. We\rquote re not like you. It doesn\rquote t matter too much, but it does make it important to assure you on one point. I\rquote m the last of the human Martins. The money I control personally will be left to the trust in your name, and as far as anyone can foresee the future, you will be economically secure.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Unnecessary,\rdblquote  Andrew said, with difficulty. In all this time, he could not get used to the deaths of the Martins.\par
\tab\ldblquote Let\rquote s not argue. That\rquote s the way it\rquote s going to be. Now, what are you working on?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I am designing a system for allowing androids-- myself-- to gain energy from the combustion of hydrocarbons, rather than from atomic cells.\rdblquote\par
\tab Paul raised his eyebrows. \ldblquote So that they will breathe and eat?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How long have you been pushing in that direction?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For a long time now, but I think I have finally designed an adequate combustion chamber for catalyzed controlled breakdown.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But why, Andrew? The atomic cell is surely infinitely better.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In some ways, perhaps. But the atomic cell is inhuman.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 15.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 It took time, but Andrew had time. In the first place, he did not wish to do anything till Paul had died in peace. With the death of the great-grandson of Sir, Andrew felt more nearly exposed to a hostile world and for that reason was all the more determined along the path he had chosen.\par
\tab Yet he was not really alone. If a man had died, the firm of Feingold and Martin lived, for a corporation does not die any more than a robot does.\par
\tab The firm had its directions and it followed them soullessly. By way of the trust and through the law firm, Andrew continued to be wealthy. In return for their own large annual retainer, Feingold and Martin involved themselves in the legal aspects of the new combustion chamber. But when the time came for Andrew to visit U.S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation, he did it alone. Once he had gone with Sir and once with Paul. This time, the third time, he was alone and manlike.\par
\tab U.S. Robots had changed. The actual production plant had been shifted to a large space station, as had grown to be the case with more and more industries. With them had gone many robots. The Earth itself was becoming park like, with its one-billion-person population stabilized and perhaps not more than thirty percent of its at-least-equally-large robot population independently brained.\par
\tab The Director of Research was Alvin Magdescu, dark of complexion and hair, with a little pointed beard and wearing nothing above the waist but the breast band that fashion dictated. Andrew himself was well covered in the older fashion of several decades back.\par
\tab Magdescu offered his hand to his visitor. \ldblquote I know you, of course, and I\rquote m rather pleased to see you. You\rquote re our most notorious product and it\rquote s a pity old Smythe-Robertson was so set against you. We could have done a great deal with you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You still can,\rdblquote  said Andrew.\par
\tab\ldblquote No, I don\rquote t think so. We\rquote re past the time. We\rquote ve had robots on Earth for over a century, but that\rquote s changing. It will be back to space with them, and those that stay here won\rquote t be brained.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But there remains myself, and I stay on Earth.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote True, but there doesn\rquote t seem to be much of the robot about you. What new request have you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To be still less a robot. Since I am so far organic, I wish an organic source of energy. I have here the plans--\rdblquote\par
\tab Magdescu did not hasten through them. He might have intended to at first, but he stiffened and grew intent. At one point, he said, \ldblquote This is remarkably ingenious. Who thought of all this?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I did,\rdblquote  Andrew replied.\par
\tab Magdescu looked up at him sharply, then said, \ldblquote It would amount to a major overhaul of your body, and an experimental one, since such a thing has never been attempted before. I advise against it. Remain as you are.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew\rquote s face had limited means of expression, but impatience showed plainly in his voice. \ldblquote Dr. Magdescu, you miss the entire point: You have no choice but to accede to my request. If such devices can be built into my body, they can be built into human bodies as well. The tendency to lengthen human life by prosthetic devices has already been remarked on. There are no devices better than the ones I have designed or am designing. As it happens, I control the patents by way of the firm of Feingold and Martin. We are quite capable of going into business for ourselves and of developing the kind of prosthetic devices that may end by producing human beings with many of the properties of robots. Your own business will then suffer.\par
\tab\ldblquote If, however, you operate on me now and agree to do so under similar circumstances in the future, you will receive permission to make use of the patents and control the technology of both robots and of the prosthetization of human beings. The initial leasing will not be granted, of course, until after the first operation is completed successfully, and after enough time has passed to demonstrate that it is indeed successful.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew felt scarcely any First Law inhibition to the stern conditions he was setting a human being. He was learning to reason that what seemed like cruelty might, in the long run, be kindness.\par
\tab Magdescu was stunned. \ldblquote I\rquote m not the one to decide something like this. That\rquote s a corporate decision that would take time.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I can wait a reasonable time,\rdblquote  said Andrew, \ldblquote but only a reasonable time.\rdblquote  And he thought with satisfaction that Paul himself could not have done it better. \par
\par
\pard\qc 16.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 It took only a reasonable time, and the operation was a success.\par
\tab\ldblquote I was very much against the operation, Andrew,\rdblquote  Magdescu said, \ldblquote but not for the reasons you might think. I was not in the least against the experiment, if it had been on someone else. I hated risking \i your\i0  positronic brain. Now that you have the positronic pathways interacting with simulated nerve pathways, it might have been difficult to rescue the brain intact if the body had gone bad.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I had every faith in the skill of the staff at U.S. Robots,\rdblquote  said Andrew. \ldblquote And I can eat now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, you can sip olive oil. It will mean occasional cleanings of the combustion chamber, as we have explained to you. Rather an uncomfortable touch, I should think.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps, if I did not expect to go further. Self cleaning is not impossible. In fact, I am working on a device that will deal with solid food that may be expected to contain incombustible fractions-- indigestible matter, so to speak, that will have to be discarded.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You would then have to develop an anus.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Or the equivalent.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What else, Andrew--?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Everything else.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Genitalia, too?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Insofar as they will fit my plans. My body is a canvas on which I intend to draw--\rdblquote\par
\tab Magdescu waited for the sentence to he completed, and when it seemed that it would not be, he completed it himself. \ldblquote A man?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We shall see,\rdblquote  Andrew said.\par
\f3\tab\f0\ldblquote That\rquote s a puny ambition, Andrew. You\rquote re better than a man. You\rquote ve gone downhill from the moment you opted to become organic.\rdblquote\par
\f3\tab\f0\ldblquote My brain has not suffered.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, it hasn\rquote t. I\rquote ll grant you that. But, Andrew, the whole new breakthrough in prosthetic devices made possible by your patents is being marketed under your name. You\rquote re recognized as the inventor and you\rquote re being honored for it-- as you should be. Why play further games with your body?\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew did not answer.\par
\tab The honors came. He accepted membership in several learned societies, including one that was devoted to the new science he had established-- the one he had called robobiology but which had come to be termed prosthetology. On the one hundred and fiftieth anniversary of his construction, a testimonial dinner was given in his honor at U.S. Robots. If Andrew saw an irony in this, he kept it to himself.\par
\tab Alvin Magdescu came out of retirement to chair the dinner. He was himself ninety-four years old and was alive because he, too, had prosthetized devices that, among other things, fulfilled the function of liver and kidneys. The dinner reached its climax when Magdescu, after a short and emotional talk, raised his glass to toast The Sesquicentennial Robot.\par
\tab Andrew had had the sinews of his face redesigned to the point where he could show a human range of emotions, but he sat through all the ceremonies solemnly passive. He did not like to be a Sesquicentennial Robot. \par
\par
\pard\qc 17.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 It was prosthetology that finally took Andrew off the Earth.\par
\tab In the decades that followed the celebration of his sesquicentennial, the Moon had come to be a world more Earthlike than Earth in every respect but its gravitational pull; and in its underground cities there was a fairly dense population. Prosthetized devices there had to take the lesser gravity into account. Andrew spent five years on the Moon working with local prosthetologists to make the necessary adaptations. When not at his work, he wandered among the robot population, every one of which treated him with the robotic obsequiousness due a man.\par
\tab He came back to an Earth that was humdrum and quiet in comparison, and visited the offices of Feingold and Martin to announce his return.\par
\tab The current head of the firm, Simon DeLong, was surprised. \ldblquote We had been told you were returning, Andrew\rdblquote -- he had almost said Mr. Martin-- \ldblquote but we were not expecting you till next week.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I grew impatient,\rdblquote  said Andrew briskly. He was anxious to get to the point. \ldblquote On the Moon, Simon, I was in charge of a research team of twenty human scientists. I gave orders that no one questioned. The Lunar robots deferred to me as they would to a human being. Why, then, am I not a human being?\rdblquote\par
\tab A wary look entered DeLong\rquote s eyes. \ldblquote My dear Andrew, as you have just explained, you are treated as a human being by both robots and human beings. You are, therefore, a human being \i de facto\i0 .\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To be a human being \i de facto\i0  is not enough. I want not only to be treated as one, but to be legally identified as one. I want to be a human being \i de jure\i0 .\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Now, that is another matter,\rdblquote  DeLong said. \ldblquote There we would run into human prejudice and into the undoubted fact that, however much you may be like a human being, you are \i not\i0  a human being.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In what way not?\rdblquote  Andrew asked. \ldblquote I have the shape of a human being and organs equivalent to those of a human being. My organs, in fact, are identical to some of those in a prosthetized human being. I have contributed artistically, literally, and scientifically to human culture as much as any human being now alive. What more can one ask?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I myself would ask nothing more. The trouble is that it would take an act of the World Legislature to define you as a human being. Frankly, I wouldn\rquote t expect that to happen.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To whom on the Legislature could I speak?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To the Chairman of the Science and Technology Committee, perhaps.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can you arrange a meeting?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But you scarcely need an intermediary. In your position, you can--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. \i You\i0  arrange it.\rdblquote  It didn\rquote t even occur to Andrew that he was giving a fiat order to a human being. He had grown so accustomed to that on the Moon. \ldblquote I want him to know that the firm of Feingold and Martin is backing me in this to the hilt.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, now--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To the hilt, Simon. In one hundred and seventy-three years I have in one fashion or another contributed greatly to this firm. I have been under obligation to individual members of the firm in times past. I am not, now. It is rather the other way around now and I am calling in my debts.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I will-- do what I can,\rdblquote  DeLong said. \par
\par
\pard\qc 18.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 The Chairman of the Science and Technology Committee was from the East Asian region and was a woman. Her name was Chee Li-hsing and her transparent garments-- obscuring what she wanted obscured only by their dazzle-- made her look plastic-wrapped. \ldblquote I sympathize with your wish for full human rights,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote There have been times in history when segments of the human population fought for full human rights. What rights, however, can you possibly want that you do not have?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote As simple a thing as my right to life,\rdblquote  Andrew stated. \ldblquote A robot can be dismantled at any time.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A human being can be executed at any time.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Execution can only follow due process of law. There is no trial needed for my dismantling. Only the word of a human being in authority is needed to end me. Besides-- besides--\rdblquote  Andrew tried desperately to allow no sign of pleading, but his carefully designed tricks of human expression and tone of voice betrayed him here. \ldblquote The truth is I want to be a man. I have wanted it through six generations of human beings.\rdblquote\par
\tab Li-hsing looked up at him out of darkly sympathetic eyes. \ldblquote The Legislature can pass a law declaring you one. They could pass a law declaring that a stone statue be defined as a man. Whether they will actually do so is, however, as likely in the first case as the second. Congress people are as human as the rest of the population and there is always that element of suspicion against robots.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Even now?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Even now. We would all allow the fact that you have earned the prize of humanity, and yet there would remain the fear of setting an undesirable precedent.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What precedent? I am the only free robot, the only one of my type, and there will never be another. You may consult U.S. Robots.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote `Never\rquote  is a long word, Andrew-- or, if you prefer, Mr. Martin-- since I will gladly give you my personal accolade as man. You will find that most congress people will not be so willing to set the precedent, no matter how meaningless such a precedent might be. Mr. Martin, you have my sympathy, but I cannot tell you to hope. Indeed--\rdblquote\par
\tab She sat back and her forehead wrinkled. \ldblquote Indeed, if the issue grows too heated, there might well arise a certain sentiment, both inside the Legislature and out side, for that dismantling you mentioned. Doing away with you could turn out to be the easiest way of resolving the dilemma. Consider that before deciding to push matters.\rdblquote\par
\tab Andrew stood firm. \ldblquote Will no one remember the technique of prosthetology, something that is almost entirely mine?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It may seem cruel, but they won\rquote t. Or if they do, it will be remembered against you. People will say you did it only for yourself. It will be said it was part of a campaign to roboticize human beings, or to humanify robots; and in either case evil and vicious. You have never been part of a political hate campaign, Mr. Martin; but I tell you that you would be the object of vilification of a kind neither you nor I would credit, and there would be people to believe it all. Mr. Martin, let your life be.\rdblquote\par
\tab She rose, and next to Andrew\rquote s seated figure she seemed small and almost childlike.\par
\tab\ldblquote If I decide to fight for my humanity, will you be on my side?\rdblquote\par
\tab She thought, then replied, \ldblquote I will be-- insofar as I can be. If at any time such a stand would appear to threaten my political future, I might have to abandon you, since it is not an issue I feel to be at the very root of my beliefs. I am trying to be honest with you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you, and I will ask no more. I intend to fight this through, whatever the consequences, and I will ask you for your help only for as long as you can give it.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 19.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 It was not a direct fight. Feingold and Martin counseled patience and Andrew muttered, grimly, that he had an endless supply of that. Feingold and Martin then entered on a campaign to narrow and restrict the area of combat.\par
\tab They instituted a lawsuit denying the obligation to pay debts to an individual with a prosthetic heart on the grounds that the possession of a robotic organ removed humanity, and with it the constitutional rights of human beings. They fought the matter skillfully and tenaciously, losing at every step but always in such a way that the decision was forced to be as broad as possible, and then carrying it by way of appeals to the World Court.\par
\tab It took years, and millions of dollars.\par
\tab When the final decision was handed down, DeLong held what amounted to a victory celebration over the legal loss. Andrew was, of course, present in the company offices on the occasion.\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ve done two things, Andrew,\rdblquote  said DeLong, \ldblquote both of which are good. First of all, we have established the fact that no number of artificial parts in the human body causes it to cease being a human body. Secondly, we have engaged public opinion in the question in such a way as to put it fiercely on the side of a broad interpretation of humanity, since there is not a human being in existence who does not hope for prosthetics if they will keep him alive.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And do you think the Legislature will now grant me my humanity?\rdblquote  Andrew asked.\par
\tab DeLong looked faintly uncomfortable. \ldblquote As to that, I cannot be optimistic. There remains the one organ which the World Court has used as the criterion of humanity. Human beings have an organic cellular brain and robots have a platinum iridium positronic brain if they have one at all-- and you certainly have a positronic brain. No, Andrew, don\rquote t get that look in your eye. We lack the knowledge to duplicate the work of a cellular brain in artificial structures close enough to the organic type as to allow it to fall within the court\rquote s decision. Not even you could do it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What should we do, then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Make the attempt, of course. Congresswoman Li-hsing will be on our side and a growing number of other congress people. The President will undoubtedly go along with a majority of the Legislature in this matter.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do we have a majority?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. Far from it. But we might get one if the public will allow its desire for a broad interpretation of humanity to extend to you. A small chance, I admit; but if you do not wish to give up, we must gamble for it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I do not wish to give up.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 20.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Congresswoman Li-hsing was considerably older than she had been when Andrew had first met her. Her transparent garments were long gone. Her hair was now close-cropped and her coverings were tubular. Yet still Andrew clung, as closely as he could within the limits of reasonable taste, to the style of clothing that had prevailed when he had first adopted clothing more than a century before.\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ve gone as far as we can, Andrew,\rdblquote  Li-hsing admitted. \ldblquote We\rquote ll try once more after recess, but, to be honest, defeat is certain and then the whole thing will have to be given up. All my most recent efforts have only earned me certain defeat in the coming congressional campaign.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know,\rdblquote  said Andrew, \ldblquote and it distressed me. You said once you would abandon me if it came to that. Why have you not done so?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote One can change one\rquote s mind, you know. Somehow, abandoning you became a higher price than I cared to pay for just one more term. As it is, I\rquote ve been in the Legislature , for over a quarter of a century. It\rquote s enough.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is there no way we can change minds, Chee?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ve changed all that are amenable to reason. The rest-- the majority-- cannot be moved from their emotional antipathies.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Emotional antipathy is not a valid reason for voting one way or the other.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know that, Andrew, but they don\rquote t advance emotional antipathy as their reason.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It all comes down to the brain, then,\rdblquote  Andrew said cautiously. \ldblquote But must we leave it at the level of cells versus positrons? Is there no way of forcing a functional definition? Must we say that a brain is made of this or that? May we not say that a brain is something-- anything-- capable of a certain level of thought?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Won\rquote t work,\rdblquote  said Li-hsing. \ldblquote Your brain is manmade, the human brain is not. Your brain is constructed, theirs developed. To any human being who is intent on keeping up the barrier between himself and a robot, those differences are a steel wall a mile high and a mile thick.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If we could get at the source of their antipathy, the very source--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote After all your years,\rdblquote  Li-hsing said, sadly, \ldblquote you are still trying to reason out the human being. Poor Andrew, don\rquote t be angry, but it\rquote s the robot in you that drives you in that direction.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Andrew. \ldblquote If I could bring myself--\rdblquote  \par
\par
\pard\qc 1. (Reprise)\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 If he could bring himself--\par
\tab He had known for a long time it might come to that, and in the end he was at the surgeon\rquote s. He had found one, skillful enough for the job at hand-- which meant a surgeon-- robot, for no human surgeon could be trusted in this connection, either in ability or in intention.\par
\tab The surgeon could not have performed the operation on a human being, so Andrew, after putting off the moment of decision with a sad line of questioning that reflected the turmoil within himself, had put First Law to one side by saying \ldblquote I, too, am a robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab He then said, as firmly as he had learned to form the words even at human beings over these past decades, \ldblquote I \i order\i0  you to carry through the operation on me.\rdblquote\par
\tab In the absence of the First Law, an order so firmly given from one who looked so much like a man activated the Second Law sufficiently to carry the day. \par
\par
\pard\qc 21.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Andrew\rquote s feeling of weakness was, he was sure, quite imaginary. He had recovered from the-- operation. Nevertheless, he leaned, as unobtrusively as he could manage, against the wall. It would be entirely too revealing to sit.\par
\tab Li-hsing said, \ldblquote The final vote will come this week, Andrew. I\rquote ve been able to delay it no longer, and we must lose. And that will be it, Andrew.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I am grateful for your skill at delay. It gave me the time I needed, and I took the gamble I had to.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What gamble is this?\rdblquote  Li-hsing asked with open concern.\par
\tab\ldblquote I couldn\rquote t tell you, or even the people at Feingold and Martin. I was sure I would be stopped. See here, if it is the brain that is at issue, isn\rquote t the greatest difference of all the matter of immortality. Who really cares what a brain looks like or is built of or how it was formed. What matters is that human brain cells die; \i must\i0  die. Even if every other organ in the body is maintained or replaced, the brain cells, which cannot be replaced without changing and therefore killing the personality, must eventually die.\par
\tab\ldblquote My own positronic pathways have lasted nearly two centuries without perceptible change, and can last for centuries more. Isn\rquote t \i that\i0  the fundamental barrier? Human beings can tolerate an immortal robot, for it doesn\rquote t matter how long a machine lasts, but they cannot tolerate an immortal human being since their own mortality is endurable only so long as it is universal. And for that reason they won\rquote t make me a human being.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What is it you\rquote re leading up to, Andrew?\rdblquote  Li-hsing asked.\par
\tab\ldblquote I have removed that problem. Decades ago, my positronic brain was connected to organic nerves. Now, one last operation has arranged that connection in such a way that slowly-- quite slowly-- the potential is being drained from my pathways.\rdblquote\par
\tab Li-hsing\rquote s finely wrinkled face showed no expression for a moment. Then her lips tightened. \ldblquote Do you mean you\rquote ve arranged to die, Andrew? You can\rquote t have. That violates the Third Law.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Andrew, \ldblquote I have chosen between the death of my body and the death of my aspirations and desires. To have let my body live at the cost of the greater death is what would have violated the Third Law.\rdblquote\par
\tab Li-hsing seized his arm as though she were about to shake him. She stopped herself. \ldblquote Andrew, it won\rquote t work! Change it back.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It can\rquote t be done. Too much damage was done. I have a year to live more or less. I will last through the two-hundredth anniversary of my construction. I was weak enough to arrange that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How can it be worth it? Andrew, you\rquote re a fool.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If it brings me humanity, that will be worth it. If it doesn\rquote t, it will bring an end to striving and that will be worth it, too.\rdblquote\par
\tab Then Li-hsing did something that astonished herself. Quietly, she began to weep. \par
\par
\pard\qc 22.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 It was odd how that last deed caught the imagination of the world. All that Andrew had done before had not swayed them. But he had finally accepted even death to be human, and the sacrifice was too great to be rejected.\par
\tab The final ceremony was timed, quite deliberately, for the two hundredth anniversary. The World President was to sign the act and make the people\rquote s will law. The ceremony would be visible on a global network and would be beamed to the Lunar state and even to the Martian colony.\par
\tab Andrew was in a wheelchair. He could still walk, but only shakily.\par
\tab With mankind watching, the World President said, \ldblquote Fifty years ago, you were declared The Sesquicentennial Robot, Andrew.\rdblquote  After a pause, and in a more solemn tone, he continued, \ldblquote Today we declare you The Bicentennial Man, Mr. Martin.\rdblquote\par
\tab And Andrew, smiling, held out his hand to shake that of the President. \par
\par
\pard\qc 23.\par
\pard\f3\par
\tab\f0 Andrew\rquote s thoughts were slowly fading as he lay in bed. Desperately he seized at them. Man! He was a man!\par
\tab He wanted that to be his last thought. He wanted to dissolve-- die with that.\par
\tab He opened his eyes one more time and for one last time recognized Li-hsing, waiting solemnly. Others were there, but they were only shadows, unrecognizable shadows. Only Li-hsing stood out against the deepening gray.\par
\tab Slowly, inchingly, he held out his hand to her and very dimly and faintly felt her take it.\par
\tab She was fading in his eyes as the last of his thoughts trickled away. But before she faded completely, one final fugitive thought came to him and rested for a moment on his mind before everything stopped.\par
\tab\ldblquote Little Miss,\rdblquote  he whispered, too low to be heard. \par
\par
